1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ This variation, after  3...Nf6  , is called the 'Berlin Defense' or the 'Berlin Wall', due to its super solid nature. Rooted in the family of the Ruy Lopez opening, the Berlin Defense was first seen in the practice in 1801, and examined by @@StartBracket@@it's in the name - who else?@@EndBracket@@ Berliners, as recorded in history.  The opening enjoyed a solid reputation throughout chess history. Already in the year 1901, Mr. Pillsbury said in a lecture on chess openings in Chicago @@StartBracket@@The Literary Digest, 2 February 1901@@EndBracket@@ that among the great masters the Ruy López is considered to retain the advantage of the first move for any length of time and that the Berlin Defense @@StartBracket@@3...Nf6@@EndBracket@@ was the best response to it.  After a period of @@StartBracket@@relatively@@EndBracket@@ little activity in this line, the variation underwent its revival once Kramnik used it with great success in his World Championship Match in 2000 against Kasparov.  Kramnik declared that: 'The Berlin Defense suited my strategy for the match. I had a defensive strategy - actually, I had in my pocket some other sharper stuff to fall back on - but first I wanted to try the defensive strategy with Black and it worked so well. This was all new to Kasparov - he probably expected me to fight for equality with Black.'  Well, dear reader, we are warned: this stable variation is anything but an easy nut to crack and contains toxic radiation levels too! }
4. d3
{ This line is called the 'Anti-Berlin'. We are keeping the queens on the board for the moment, sidestepping the forced lines arising after 4...Nxe4, amongst others the super solid ending, the 'Berlin Wall', deployed 4 times by Kramnik with great success in the World Championship Match @@StartBracket@@London, 2000@@EndBracket@@.   The creme-de-la-creme of this opening and considered to be the main line, is the following line:  4.O-O  Nxe4  Black accepts the gift of White. As the following lines illustrate, Black's greediness goes unpunished even though his king is in the center and he is down on development.  5.d4   5.Re1  is another main option for White, and popular these days.  5...Nd6  6.Nxe5  Be7  Closing the e-file, while preparing for short-castling.  7.Bf1  after which we reach the starting point of loads of dazzling variations, like what happened in my game against 'The Beast':  7...Nxe5  8.Rxe5  O-O  9.d4  Bf6  10.Re1  Re8  11.Bf4  Rxe1  12.Qxe1  Ne8  13.Nc3  Bxd4  14.Nd5  d6  15.Bg5=∞  with double-edged play in Adhiban,B @@StartBracket@@2654@@EndBracket@@ - Werle,J @@StartBracket@@2545@@EndBracket@@ Caleta 2020, ½-½ @@StartBracket@@31@@EndBracket@@.  5...Nd6  Black gains a tempo because of the assault on the bishop.  6.Bxc6   6.dxe5  is another line, but not dangerous for Black if he knows what he is doing!  6...Nxb5  7.a4  Funnily enough, the Knight is trapped here. Black can fight his way out by  7...Nbd4  when the line resumes. For instance,  8.Nxd4  d5  9.exd6  Nxd4  10.Qxd4  Qxd6  11.Qe4+  Qe6  12.Qd4  with a repetition of moves.  dxc6  7.dxe5  The pawn structure obtains its definite shape.  7...Nf5  8.Qxd8+  Kxd8  Likewise in the Ruy Lopez Exchange @@StartBracket@@Volume 1@@EndBracket@@, White obtained a 4 vs 3 pawn majority on the kingside, while Black is stuck with a doubled pawn on the queenside.  In contrast with the RLE, as a consequence of the e-pawn being far pushed to e5 @@StartBracket@@instead of being placed on e4@@EndBracket@@ Black has full control over the light squares @@StartBracket@@e4 and f5@@EndBracket@@. This blockade makes it hard to make use of the pawn majority.   Kramnik had great results with Black and White has an everlasting issue finding an advantage here. That's why I choose the lines arising after  4.d3  , leading to completely different positions. }
4... Bc5
{ Part 3: The typical Anti-Berlin type of positions. The bishop is placed actively on c5 and renders conquering the pawn on e5 less attractive for White.  Part 1: The Sidelines.   4...Ne7!?  This is the Mortimer Defense.  5.Nxe5??  White fell around 30 times for this trick, firstly in 1887 and most recently in October 2021!  5...c6   4...Bd6!?  Often tried in practice by Aronian.   4...a6?!  5.Bxc6  dxc6  6.Nxe5  a razor-sharp gambit.  Part 2: The Ruy-Lopez type of positions.   4...d6  5.O-O  Be7  6.c3  O-O  7.Re1  a6  8.Ba4  b5  9.Bc2  Bb7  10.Nbd2  Re8  11.Nf1  g6  12.d4  Bf8  13.Ng3  Bg7  14.d5  Nb8  This move has been mostly seen in tournament practice.  15.b3!  Likewise, anticipating on c7-c6..  15...c6  16.c4!  The French GM maintains a firm grasp on the center by keeping his pawn chain intact. Moreover, the black bishop is biting on granite. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@9@@EndBracket@@ Fressinet,L  @@StartBracket@@2654@@EndBracket@@-Johannessen,L @@StartBracket@@2536@@EndBracket@@ Germany 2008 CBM 123. }
5. Bxc6
{ It's a recurring story: likewise in the Ruy Lopez Exchange @@StartBracket@@Part 1@@EndBracket@@, we trade off the bishop for the knight in an early phase of the game, inflicting damages to Black's pawn structure whereas we avoid the old but currently relevant variation after  5.O-O  Nd4!?  Without hesitation, the troops were sent forward into battle. Back in the old and romantic days of chess, withdrawal was not an option.   The first high-level game in this line, between Loewenthal and Anderssen @@StartBracket@@London, 1851@@EndBracket@@, went:  5.O-O  Nd4!?  6.Nxd4  Bxd4  7.c3  Bb6  8.Bg5  h6  9.Bh4  c6  10.Bc4  g5  11.Bg3  d6  12.h3  h5  13.d4  h4   13...Nxe4!?  14.Bh2  with unclear play.  14.Bh2  Qe7  15.Nd2  g4!  White is in serious trouble here. Black has no peaceful intentions, opening the g-file.  16.dxe5  dxe5  17.hxg4  Nxg4  18.Be2  Rg8!  Aiming for Nxh2 and Qg5, threatening mate on g2.  19.Nc4  Bc7  20.Qd2  b5  21.Ne3  Where else? When taken on its own merits, the knight is not badly placed on e3, however, it allows the next move...  21...Qg5!  White is helpless against all the impending threats on his king.  22.Bxg4  Bxg4  23.f3  Bb6  24.Rae1  Rd8  25.Qf2  Bh3  26.f4  Qxg2+  27.Qxg2  Bxe3+  28.Rxe3  Rxg2+  29.Kh1  Rxh2+  30.Kxh2  Bxf1  0-1 @@StartBracket@@30@@EndBracket@@ Loewenthal, J-Anderssen, A London 1851. }
5... dxc6
{ The e5-pawn is poisoned, since after taking Black will strike back on f2 by 6..Qd4. Therefore, White brings his king in safety, whereafter he is ready to take on e5. Moreover, the bishop is not ideally placed on c5 now and often it goes back to d6 - losing one move. }
6. O-O
{ Another popular option for White is  6.Nbd2  but like in the Ruy Lopez Exchange, I prefer a quick short castling. Why? We kind of finalize our development, keeping our options open for different set-ups such as c3-d4, Bg5 or Be3, and Nbd2-f1-g3, Na3-c4 or Nc3.   6.Nxe5??  Qd4! }
6... Nd7
{ This move has a solid reputation. It has been played by Ding Liren, Anand, Nakamura, and Ivanchuk, and - last but definetely not least @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ - your very own and favorite author!   6...Qe7  7.Nbd2   7.h3?!  Rg8!!  0-1 @@StartBracket@@27@@EndBracket@@ Aronian,L @@StartBracket@@2794@@EndBracket@@-Kramnik,V @@StartBracket@@2800@@EndBracket@@ Berlin 2018  Bg4 }
7. c3
{ Mostly played is  7.Nbd2  .  However, by this move  7.c3  , White seizes immediately the initiative in the center.   For instance,  7.Nbd2  O-O  8.Nc4  f6  9.Kh1!?  a5  10.a4  Nb6  11.Be3  Bxe3  12.Nxe3  Be6  13.Ng1!  1-0 @@StartBracket@@108@@EndBracket@@ Giri, A @@StartBracket@@2764@@EndBracket@@-Lysyj, I @@StartBracket@@2593@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2020. }
7... O-O 8. d4 Bd6 9. Bg5 f6 10. Bh4 Qe8 11. Nbd2 Qf7
{ Black prepares for Re8 and Nf8, meanwhile hindering Nc4.  This is the starting position of chapter 4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Nd7 Main Line. }
*

