[Black "Creating a pawn weakness on d6, Warmerdam − Werle, Netherlands 2020"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. O-O Nd7 7. c3 O-O 8.
d4 Bd6 9. Bg5
{ Played instantly and with confidence by my young opponent. Although I was the older player here, I felt like being the 'green' one and besides far from comfortable in this position. In my morning preparation my engines couldn't come with fully equalizing answers to White's strategy. }
9... f6
{ Black is limited in his options. First, he wants to move the queen from the diagonal of the bishop, then he overprotects e5 with rook e8, while creating space for the knight-regrouping via f8 to g6. }
10. Bh4 Qe8 11. Nbd2 Qf7
{ Black prepares for Re8 and Nf8, meanwhile hindering Nc4. } 12. Bg3 Re8 13.
Qc2 Nf8
{ This essential rerouting of the knight to g6, is indispensable in Black's operations.   13...b6  14.Rfe1  a5  15.Nf1  Nf8  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@33@@EndBracket@@ Lagno,K @@StartBracket@@2549@@EndBracket@@ -Lei,T @@StartBracket@@2483@@EndBracket@@ China 2019  16.dxe5!  The e5-pawn is about to be isolated.  16...fxe5  17.Ne3 }
14. dxe5 fxe5 15. Ng5 Qf6 16. Qb3+ Ne6 17. Nxe6
{ Ideally, I would take back with the bishop, keeping the queens on the board. }
17... Qxe6 18. Nc4
{ Max doesn't waive his right to swap the queens. However, first he intends to take off my bishop   @@StartBracket@@pair@@EndBracket@@.   18.Qxe6+?!  Bxe6  19.Nf3  Bc4⇆ }
18... a5 19. Nxd6 cxd6 20. Rfd1 Qxb3 21. axb3 Be6 22. c4 Red8
{ or 23.Rd2, to double the rooks. } 23. f4
{ My young opponent didn't exploit all his potential.   23.Rd3!  a4!  The best move to stay in the game.  24.h4!   24.Rxa4  Rxa4  25.bxa4  Bxc4  26.Rd2  White wants to take now on e5.  26...Kf7  27.Bxe5  Re8!  Black remains a pawn down, but he activates the rook and is intending to enter a drawish-like opposite-colored bishop ending.  28.Bxd6  Rxe4⇆   24.f3  Kf7  25.Rad1  axb3  26.Bxe5  Kf7   24...axb3  25.Rxa8  Rxa8  26.Rxd6±  25.Rad1  axb3  26.Bxe5  Bxc4  27.Rxd6 }
23... exf4 24. Bxf4 d5
{ By the many exchanges which are about to follow, the remaining position with uneven bishops is a draw. }
25. exd5 cxd5 26. Bc7 Rd7 27. Rxa5 Rxa5
{ 27...Rc8  also 27..Rc8 should be sufficient for a draw, but why entering a rook ending with a pawn down?  28.cxd5  Rcxc7  29.Ra8+  Kf7  30.dxe6+  Kxe6 }
28. Bxa5 dxc4 29. Rxd7 Bxd7 30. bxc4 b5 31. cxb5
{ 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@31@@EndBracket@@ Warmerdam,M @@StartBracket@@2497@@EndBracket@@-Werle,J   @@StartBracket@@2540@@EndBracket@@ Netherlands 2020   31.cxb5  is a dead draw.  31...Bxb5  32.Kf2  Kf7  The king will try to oppose the enemy king.  33.Ke3  Bc6  34.g3  Ke6  The light squares are Black's, the dark squares are White's.  35.Kd4  Bg2  36.Kc5  Kd7  Black will easily manage to block the b-pawn on the light squares.   31.c5  Bc6  32.Kf2  Kf7  33.g3  Ke6  34.Bc3  g6  also here, Black will not allow the white king to invade. }
*

