[Black "Creating a pawn weakness on d6, Eljanov − Radjabov, Shamkir 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. O-O Nd7 7. c3 O-O 8.
d4 Bd6 9. Bg5 f6 10. Qb3+
{ 10.Bh4  this was the move I faced against countryman and the second of Jorden van Foreest, Max Warmerdam. }
10... Kh8 11. Bh4 b6 12. Nbd2 Ba6 13. Rfe1 Qe7 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Qxe5 16.
Bg3 Qe7 17. Bxd6 cxd6 18. Rad1
{ 18.Qa3  Bb7  19.Nc4  c5  20.Rad1  Rfd8  21.Qa4!  h6  22.f3  Qe6  23.Ne3  Black is stuck with a backward d-pawn. White gets the much better odds after doubling on the d-file. }
18... Bc8 19. Qa4 { Tying Black's pieces down to the defence of a7 and c6. }
19... b5
{ White is much better, in case of   19...Bd7  20.Nf1!  Moving the knight to or f5 or c4, hitting the weak d6-point.  20...Rfd8   20...Rfe8  is simply losing a pawn, after  21.Qd4  21.Ne3  Be8  22.Rd2± }
20. Qa5 Bg4 21. f3 Be6 22. Nf1 d5
{ A sample line could be:   22...Rad8  23.Ne3  Rd7  24.Qa6  Rc7  25.Nd5!  showing the deficiencies of Black's position. }
23. exd5 Qc5+ 24. Ne3 Bxd5
{ Black got himself rid of the backward d6-pawn. Nonetheless hasn't all the danger been averted yet. }
25. a3
{ Dealing with any future Bxa2, meanwhile preparing for the exchange of the heavy pieces with Qb4. }
25... Rfe8 { So close to a draw, but no cigar. .   25...Be6!?  26.Qc7⩲ } 26.
Qb4 { In the ensuing ending Black is slightly worse. } 26... Qb6 27. Qd4 Qxd4
28. Rxd4
{ When Black moves the bishop, Rd4-d6 would take the c6-pawn under siege. }
28... Re7 29. Kf2 Rae8 30. Rdd1
{ Unpinning the rook and heading for the exchange of the rooks. } 30... Bb3 31.
Nf5
{ White's cunning idea is revealed. In the knight vs bishop ending White's king will be moved to d4 and c5. }
31... Rxe1 32. Rxe1 Rxe1 33. Kxe1
{ After the exchange of rooks, it becomes manifest that the c6- and a7-pawn are very weak. }
33... Be6 34. Nd4 Bd5
{ 34...Bd7  was better, but he would not be in the safe zone yet.  35.b4  Kg8  36.Kd2  Kf7  37.c4!?  bxc4  38.Kc3  Ke7  39.Kxc4  Kd6  40.Ne2  Be6+  41.Kd4  and in this ending, Black is balancing on a chord. }
35. Kd2 a6 36. Ke3 Kg8 37. Nf5
{ Radjabov is lost here, as he is defenceless against the king's march to c5 @@StartBracket@@and b6@@EndBracket@@. }
37... Kf7 38. Kd4
{ What should Black do here? It strikes me that the black king is too late for the invasion of the king, because after Ke6 @@StartBracket@@with the idea to stop Kd4-c5 with Ke6-d6@@EndBracket@@ White can take on g7. }
38... Be6 39. Ne3 Ke7 40. Kc5
{ White is winning here. The a6-pawn can no longer be protected. } 40... Kd7
41. Kb6
{ Game over. These endings are revealing the soft spots in our opponent's position, which become manifest by limited number of defending pieces of our opponent. It's crucial that we recognize from an early point in the middlegame the hidden chances which are implied in the ending. }
41... f5 42. f4 g5 43. g3 gxf4 44. gxf4 Kd6 45. Kxa6 Kc7 46. Ka5 *

