[Black "Pressurizing e5, Firouzja − Le Quang Liem, Moscow 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. O-O Bd6 7. Bg5 h6 8.
Bh4 Be6 9. Nbd2 g5 10. Bg3 Nd7 11. d4 Qf6 12. Re1 O-O-O 13. c4 g4 14. c5 Bxc5
15. dxc5 gxf3 16. Qxf3 Qe7 17. b4 h5 18. h4 Rhg8 19. Qc3 Rg4 20. a4 Rdg8 21.
Nf3
{ 21.Rac1!?  may have been a very interesting attempt to get the better position. White is preparing for b4-b5.  21...f6  22.b5  looks very promising for us. }
21... Rxg3
{ Black goes all-in.  After   21...f6  White could go for the same plan as in the 21.Rac1-line.  22.Nh2  R4g7  23.Nf1  proceeding with Rac1 and b5. }
22. fxg3 Rxg3
{ Funny enough, also in this position we should not be too worried and apply the same attacking plan as before. }
23. Qe3 f6 24. Kh2 Rg4 25. Rac1 Qg7 26. Re2
{ The best practical chance here for Black was to play energetically, activating his knight and bishop. }
26... Nf8
{ 26...f5!  27.exf5  Bd5!  when the character of the position becomes very sharp. Black will follow up with Nf6 and - if he is allowed - Ng4 or Ne4. }
27. Rd2
{ 27.b5  Ng6  28.Rd2  Nf4  29.Rg1  and after g3, White would be on top. } 27...
Qh7 28. Qd3 Bd7 29. Re1 Ne6 30. Red1
{ We don't let our opponent's knight come to f4. } 30... Nf8 31. Qb3
{ The young superstar builds in a treacherous tactic. } 31... Rxe4
{ 31...Rg8  32.b5!  Besides holding his position together on the kingside, he never forgot about his own chances.  32...cxb5  33.axb5  After c6 on the next move, Black's position collapses. }
32. Rxd7 Nxd7 33. Qe6
{ What can Black do against Qe8 mate? The rook on e4 can't come back in the house. }
33... Kd8 34. Qxf6+ { Whoops, that was threatening too. } 34... Ke8 35. Qe6+
Kd8 36. Nxe5 { The position has fallen apart like a cardhouse. } *

