[SetUp "1"]

20... b5
{ White's assailt on the kingside came to a standstill, while Black is putting his forces in motion on the queenside. }
21. Ng1 Bb6
{ The once ugly c-pawns will play a major role in the upcoming and last part of the game. }
22. Ne2 c5 23. Rf1 Bb7 24. Nc1
{ In the so familiar positional style of the former world champion, he first mobilizes alle his action before he undertakes action with c5-c4. }
24... Rd7 25. Nh4 Red8 26. Be3 c4 27. Bxb6
{ 27.dxc4  bxc4  28.Bxb6  axb6  29.Rc3  Nd4-+  when it transpires that Black has close to a winning position. }
27... axb6 28. Ng6 Nc5 29. Qe2 cxd3 30. cxd3
{ White' knight is lost on g6 and he is saddled with a backward pawn on d3. }
30... Rd4 31. f4 exf4 32. Nxf4 b4
{ The pressure for White is insurmountable. Next on black's agenda? Bb7-a6! }
33. Re3 Qd7 34. Qf3 Qa4 35. Nfe2 Rxd3
{ In the so characteristic style of Capablanca, with a 'petit combinaison', he concludes the game. }
36. Nxd3 Rxd3 37. Ng3 { 37.Rxd3  is losing, because of  37...Bxe4! } 37... Ba6
38. b3 Qa3 39. Rd1 Na4 { 39...Na4  40.bxa4  Rxe3-+ } *

