[Black "Space advantage, Firouzja − Xiong, Wijk aan Zee 2020"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. O-O Nd7 7. c3 O-O 8.
d4 Bd6 9. Bg5 f6 10. Bh4 Qe8 11. Re1 Nb6 12. Bg3 Bg4 13. Nbd2 Kh8 14. Qc2 Rd8
15. h3 Bh5 16. Nh4 { 16.c4!?  exd4  17.Bxd6  cxd6  18.Nxd4⩲ } 16... exd4 17.
Bxd6 d3
{ 17...cxd6  18.cxd4  also here White would be slightly better due to his space advantage. }
18. Qxd3 cxd6 19. f4
{ Firouzja grabs the space and builds up an initiative on the kingside. } 19...
Bf7 20. Ndf3 { White's position is just easier to play. } 20... Bg8 { 20...g6 }
21. Nd4 c5 22. Ndf5
{ Now White's advantage is taking shape. The knight on f5 is dominant and hampering Black's free movement of pieces. }
22... Qd7 23. b3 d5
{ 23...g6  would only weaken the dark squares around the king. } 24. e5
{ White obtains a dangerous passed pawn. } 24... Be6 25. Ng3 f5 26. Nf3
{ The bishop is a bad blockading piece. When White will manage to open lines on the queenside, the blockade would be difficult to sustain. }
26... h6 27. b4 { Taking control of square d4. } 27... d4
{ 27...cxb4  28.cxb4  Now White wants to 'establish' a knight on d4. Black should act. }
28. bxc5 dxc3 29. Qxc3 Nd5 30. Qd2 Qa4
{ So we reached a position in which Black liberated himself from the 'positional squeeze' he found himself in. But against a high price: one pawn. }
31. Ne2
{ The exclamation mark is for switching the roles from attacking to defending. Firouzja grits on his teeth and holds his position together. By playing Ne2 he avoids the loss of the pawn on f4. }
31... Nb4 32. Ned4 Nc6
{ Black tries to undermine the strong d4-knight. But in vain, this square is firmly in White's hands. }
33. Rad1 Bxa2
{ So, Black won the pawn back, but against what price? White needs one more move to consolidate, and then he strikes back.   33...Bd5  interesting, but White stays on top.  34.Nxc6  Bxc6  35.Qxd8  Rxd8  36.Rxd8+  Kh7  The position purely assessed on its static merits would be unclear. But that is beside the pawn rush.  37.e6!  Bxf3  38.gxf3  Qxf4  39.Rd3  and White win based on his e-pawn. }
34. Qc3 { Unpinning himself and preparing for playing e6. } 34... Rd5 35. e6
Re8 36. Rd2 Qc4 37. Qxc4 Bxc4 38. Nxc6 bxc6 39. Rd4
{ Black doesn't want to allow the knight to d4 after the exchange of rooks. But by doing so, he allows the rooks to occupy preferable positions. }
39... Bb3 40. Re3 Ba2 41. e7
{ Without the instant loss of the @@StartBracket@@e6, now e7@@EndBracket@@ pawn, White will move his rook to a3. }
41... Kg8 42. Ra3
{ Black is forced to take on d4, under inferior circumstances. } 42... Rxd4 43.
Nxd4 Bd5 44. Nxf5 g6
{ 44...Be6  45.Nd4  Rxe7  46.Re3  Pinning the bishop keep the hostile pieces 'in the box', all with the aim to grasp 2 pawns.  46...Kf7  47.Nxc6  Re8  48.Ra3  is winning for White. }
45. Nxh6+ Kg7 46. Ng4 Rxe7 47. Ne3
{ White utilizes the time he gets to play the knight to a better place. } 47...
Be4 48. Kf2 Rd7 49. Nc4
{ A rule of thumb is that the knight needs outpost. And there are plenty of them here. }
49... Rb7 50. g4 { When you have the majority of pawns, then use them! } 50...
Bd5 51. Ne3 Rb2+ 52. Kg3 Rb3 53. Rxa7+ Kf6 54. Kf2
{ Game over for Black. He is just too much material behind. } 54... Rb2+ 55.
Kf1 Be4 56. Rd7 Rh2 57. Rd4 Bf3 58. Rd6+ Kg7 59. f5 gxf5 60. Nxf5+ Kf7 61. g5
{ The g-pawn supported by the knight and rook determine the outcome of the game. }
61... Bh5 62. Rf6+ Kg8 63. g6 Rxh3 64. Ne7+ Kh8 65. Rf8+ Kg7 66. Rf7+ Kh6 67.
Rh7+ Kg5 68. g7 *

