[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Anderssen Variation: 4...Bd6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ This variation - after  3...Nf6  - is called the 'Berlin Defense' or the 'Berlin Wall', due to its super solid nature. Rooted in the family of the Ruy Lopez opening, the Berlin Defense was first seen in practice in 1801, and examined by @@StartBracket@@it's in the name - who else?@@EndBracket@@ Berliners, as recorded in history. }
4. d3
{ After this move, we set foot into the 'Anti-Berlin'. We are keeping the queens on the board for the moment, sidestepping the forced lines arising after 4..Nxe4, amongst others the supersolid ending c.q. the 'Berlin Wall', deployed 4 times by Kramnik against Kasparov with great success in the World Championship Match @@StartBracket@@London, 2000@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Bd6
{ This is a strange move, the black bishop blocks the d-pawn! Black plans to castle short, move his rook to e8 and move the bishop back to f8, whereafter all the circumstances are set for the pushing of the d-pawn. }
5. Nc3 h6
{ This is all still part of Black's set-up. At all costs, he wants to prevent the pin after Bg5. }
6. a3 a6 7. Ba4 O-O 8. g4
{ a wonderful move, coming out of the blue! It's well known that the defender should react in the center when his opponent launches a kingside attack. }
8... Nd4 9. g5
{ White is conducting demolition work. Without any compassion for the opponent, the king's castle is torn down. }
9... hxg5 10. Bxg5 Be7 11. Rg1
{ White slowly but surely moves his pieces towards Black's king. } 11... d6 12.
Nxd4 exd4 13. Ne2
{ The knight is happy to be forced to e2, as it wanted to go in the direction of the black king anyway. }
13... Nd7 14. Bh6 { Time to hit Black's weakest point. } 14... Bf6 15. Nf4
{ The g7-pawn will be once more taken under siege after Nh5. } 15... Ne5 16.
Nh5
{ Hitting g7, the knight move should do the job. In fact, also the position arising  16.Qh5  was also way beyond a big advantage for White. He follows up with 17.O-O-O, mounting the pressure on g7. }
16... Kh7 17. Bxg7 { There is no need to hesitate. } 17... Bxg7 18. Rxg7+
{ The following lines are a piece of cake.   18...Kh8  19.Qc1  Nf3+  20.Ke2  1-0 @@StartBracket@@20@@EndBracket@@ Naiditsch, A @@StartBracket@@2698@@EndBracket@@ -Gundavaa, B @@StartBracket@@2506@@EndBracket@@ Zuerich 2015   18...Kh6  19.Qd2+  Kxh5  20.Rh7+  Kg4  21.Ke2!  The king takes the f3-square from Black. Next is Rg1 mate.  21...Nf3  22.h3# }
