[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "4...d6 Fianchetto Variation: 5.O-O g6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ This variation - after  3...Nf6  - is called the 'Berlin Defense' or the 'Berlin Wall', due to its super solid nature. Rooted in the family of the Ruy Lopez opening, the Berlin Defense was first seen in practice in 1801, and examined by @@StartBracket@@it's in the name - who else?@@EndBracket@@ Berliners, as recorded in history. }
4. d3 d6
{ Making this course, at first, it merely was my intention to give you a Bxc6-repertoire against the Ruy Lopez and the Berlin Wall and it went beyond the beyond the scope to cover all the sidelines after 4. d3 d6 5.0-0. Nevertheless, along the way I got inspired by all the astonishing plans and variations available for White here. Resulting in the fact that I would like to give you an instrument against all of Black's main responses here. }
5. O-O
{ Here our plan of taking on c6 will not offer us salvation: Black can just take back with the b-pawn. Therefore, we take in the Ruy Lopez set-up with c3 and d4. }
5... g6
{ Naturally, now that White chose for a 'timid' set-up with d3. Black is striving for moving the bishop on g7 where it is better placed than on e7. }
6. d4
{ Again pushing the d-pawn forward?? Hold your horses! Albeit, on the one hand, we spend precious time in the opening moving twice with the same piece, the time is ripe to attack Black in the center as he is undeveloped. }
6... Bd7 7. d5
{ This is part of White's plan, exchanging the d7-bishop and gaining space on the queenside. In the resulting positions, Black has to play King's Indian alike positions, but without his light-squared bishop; we took the sting out of his play. }
7... Nb8
{ Black clearly intends to take the bishop back by the b8-knight. On d7 the knight stops the c-pawn advance. }
8. Bxd7+ Nbxd7
{ Can we say that the knight is better placed on d7 than on e7? Probably, although it takes time for Black. }
9. Re1
{ The central pawn needs protection, and, ideally, we take in the position with c2-c4 and only then Nc3. }
9... Bg7
{ In case of  9...Be7  we can quite easily get the upper hand by  10.c4  O-O  11.Bh6  Re8  12.Nc3  a5  13.h3  Nc5  14.b3  leaves White with the preferable position.  White is about to gain space on the queenside by a3 and b4.0-1 @@StartBracket@@43@@EndBracket@@ Szabo,K @@StartBracket@@2540@@EndBracket@@-Dumitrache,D  @@StartBracket@@2446@@EndBracket@@ Baia Sprie 2012. }
10. c4 Nc5
{ My feeling remains the same: Black is missing his light-squared bishop sincerely! }
11. Nc3 { The following move has to be played to keep the knight on c5. } 11...
a5 12. b3
{ Losing a move, but a necessary evil in order to drive off the c5-knight with b4.   12.a3?!  this is too hasty, as Black can fix our b-pawn.  12...a4⩱  . }
12... O-O 13. a3
{ Nothing can stop us now: after Rb1 we finally come to our beloved b3-b4. }
13... Nh5
{ This move was tried by German IM Christian Seel against Dutch GM Jan Smeets. }
14. Rb1 { Ready for action! b3-b4 will certainly be good for us! } 14... Nf4
15. Be3 { A useful move while defusing Nd3. } 15... Qd7
{ 15...Ncd3  won't do any harm, because of  16.Rf1!  Black can't keep his knights on these active squares.  16...Qd7  17.g3  Qg4  18.Kh1  Our strategy pays off now:  Black has to retreat to h5 after we can enjoy our structural edge. }
16. Bxc5
{ Smeets is shifting gears, no longer trying to push the pawns on the queenside but pointing his arrows on the kingside. }
16... dxc5 17. Ne2
{ The knight on f4 is on White's to-do list. In other words, it has to be expelled. }
17... Rfe8 18. Qc2 { Preparing for Nxf4 and - eventually - e4-e5. } 18... Nh5
{ Black retreats, but } 19. Nc1
{ Here, gradually, in King's Indian style, White starts operating in a strategic fashion. The white knight is best placed on d3 - keeping an eye on e5 and eventually preparing for the pawn break with b3-b4. }
