1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ This variation - after  3...Nf6  - is called the 'Berlin Defense' or the 'Berlin Wall', due to its super solid nature. Rooted in the family of the Ruy Lopez opening, the Berlin Defense was first seen in practice in 1801, and examined by @@StartBracket@@it's in the name - who else?@@EndBracket@@ Berliners, as recorded in history. }
4. d3 d6
{ Making this course, at first, it merely was my intention to give you a Bxc6-repertoire against the Ruy Lopez and the Berlin Wall and it went beyond the beyond the scope to cover all the sidelines after 4. d3 d6 5.0-0. Nevertheless, along the way I got inspired by all the astonishing plans and variations available for White here. Resulting in the fact that I would like to give you an instrument against all of Black's main responses here. }
5. O-O
{ Here our plan of taking on c6 will not offer us salvation: Black can just take back with the b-pawn. Therefore, we take in the Ruy Lopez set-up with c3 and d4. }
5... a6 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. d4 exd4 8. Nxd4
{ Recently our standard-bearer Magnus played two games here. With Black he got worse against Nakamura after 8.Qxd4, while with the white pieces one year later Carlsen tried with success 8.Nxd4, followed by 9.Qf3.   8.Qxd4!?  A sound alternative.  8...Be7  9.e5  c5  10.Qf4  Nh5!  would guarantee Black an equal game.   10...dxe5  11.Nxe5  O-O  12.Nc6  Qd6  13.Nxe7+  Qxe7  14.Nc3  Bb7  White was slightly better here because of his better pawn structure. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@51@@EndBracket@@ Nakamura, H @@StartBracket@@2736@@EndBracket@@-Carlsen, M @@StartBracket@@2863@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020  11.Qe4  d5  12.Qe2  O-O∞  Black's two bishops and strong center compensate for the misplaced knight on h5. }
8... c5 9. Nc6
{ This move lifts a tip of the veil in regard to our intentions. } 9... Qd7 10.
Na5
{ This, at first sight, a bit strange knight manoeuvre, has a lot of followers. More than 60 games could be retrieved in the database while amongst the elite players Carlsen, Grischuk, Svidler and Yu Yanghi have chosen this line.  The knight is not at all badly placed here, as it puts Black in a squeeze. Moreover, in most of the @@StartBracket@@top@@EndBracket@@ games, I saw White gets the opportunity to jump the knight back to c6. }
10... Qa4
{ Played by the best players and contains the strong idea of freeing the pieces. }
11. Bd2 Be7
{ This move can be considered the main line. Black is aiming to castle short. }
12. Re1 O-O 13. Nc3
{ Only played after short castling leaving the e7-bishop unprotected, White is enabled to play this move leaving the knight on a5 'en prise'... }
13... Qe8 14. Bf4 { Preparing to demolish Black's pawn structure. } 14... Be6
15. e5
{ We have witnessed the same idea in Part 1 of this series about the Smart Ruy Lopez in the Model Games and theoretical section. White blows up Black's structure leaving him behind with plenty of weaknesses. }
