[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ This variation - after  3...Nf6  - is called the 'Berlin Defense' or the 'Berlin Wall', due to its super solid nature. Rooted in the family of the Ruy Lopez opening, the Berlin Defense was first seen in practice in 1801, and examined by @@StartBracket@@it's in the name - who else?@@EndBracket@@ Berliners, as recorded in history. }
4. d3 d6
{ Making this course, at first, it merely was my intention to give you a Bxc6-repertoire against the Ruy Lopez and the Berlin Wall and it went beyond the beyond the scope to cover all the sidelines after 4. d3 d6 5.0-0. Nevertheless, along the way I got inspired by all the astonishing plans and variations available for White here. Resulting in the fact that I would like to give you an instrument against all of Black's main responses here. }
5. O-O Bg4
{ Pinning the knight. Like in many Ruy Lopez positions, Black plays this move after d2-d4, putting pressure on this central square. In contrast to these positions, here Black lacks this central pressure and we will try to play the bishop out of the game. Adhiban's game against Ubilava is very instructive for us on how to conduct this plan. }
6. c3 Be7
{ Following the main line. Please note that many alterations in the set up at the early stage of the game will finally return to the main line. }
7. Re1 { Good position for the rook, making way for the knight to f1. } 7...
O-O 8. h3
{ As we have seen in Part 1 of this series, the h3-move is the main part of our strategy. The bishop has to make a decision now: does he stay on the h3-c8 diagonal or does he remain the pin? }
8... Bh5
{ By far the most popular.   8...Bd7  makes no sense, as implementing h2-h3 only benefits White. }
9. Nbd2 { Please note that when reaching g3, we hit the bishop. } 9... a6 10.
Ba4 { In the Ruy Lopez we usually always preserve our light-squared bishop. }
10... b5 11. Bc2
{ This move seems rather passive, but scores excellently. It contains the clear plan of Nf1, g4 and Ng3, isolating the bishop on h5 and grabbing the initiative on the kingside.   This can be considered another main line here:  11.Bb3  Na5  12.Bc2  c5  13.Nf1  Nc6  14.Ng3  Bg6  15.Nh4  with the better chances for White, 1-0  @@StartBracket@@62@@EndBracket@@ Onischuk,A @@StartBracket@@2580@@EndBracket@@-Alvarez,F @@StartBracket@@2255@@EndBracket@@ New York 1997. }
11... d5
{ 11...Re8?!  can't be taken too seriously, after  12.Nf1  d5  13.Ng3  Bg6  14.Qe2  dxe4  15.dxe4  Nd7  16.b4  Nb6  17.Bb3±  1-0 @@StartBracket@@49@@EndBracket@@ Markovic,M @@StartBracket@@2458@@EndBracket@@-Tadjerbashi,A @@StartBracket@@2181@@EndBracket@@ Sweden 2010. }
12. Qe2 { A consolidating move, before playing g2-g4. } 12... d4 13. g4
{ Another road was  13.Nf1  dxc3  14.bxc3  with the slightly better position for White too. }
13... Bg6 14. cxd4
{ Black is in dire straits since he is kind of forced to take back on d4 with the pawn after which he has to encounter a pawn avalanche. }
14... exd4 15. Nh2 Bd6 16. Ndf1
{ White is ready for f2-f4, in which case Black is overrun on the kingside.   The next game illustrates the helplessness of Black.  16...Nd7  17.f4  f6  18.Bb3+  Bf7  19.Bxf7+  Rxf7  20.Ng3  Nc5  21.Bd2  Na4  22.Rab1  Not giving anything away, but all roads lead to Rome.   For instance,  22.Rac1  Qd7  23.Qg2  Re8  24.e5  winning a piece.  22...Qd7  23.Nf3  Re8  24.Kh1  Bf8  25.Rg1  Nd8  26.f5  Black is led to the slaughterhouse.  26...Bd6  27.Qf1  h6  28.Nh5  c5  29.h4  Bf8  30.g5  fxg5  31.hxg5  hxg5  32.Nxg5  c4  33.Qh3  Qc6  34.Nf6+  gxf6  35.Nxf7+  1-0 @@StartBracket@@35@@EndBracket@@ Neelotpal, D @@StartBracket@@2446@@EndBracket@@ -Karpatchev, A @@StartBracket@@2506@@EndBracket@@ Liffre 2017. }
