1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ This variation - after  3...Nf6  - is called the 'Berlin Defense' or the 'Berlin Wall', due to its super solid nature. Rooted in the family of the Ruy Lopez opening, the Berlin Defense was first seen in practice in 1801, and examined by @@StartBracket@@it's in the name - who else?@@EndBracket@@ Berliners, as recorded in history. }
4. d3 d6
{ Making this course, at first, it merely was my intention to give you a Bxc6-repertoire against the Ruy Lopez and the Berlin Wall and it went beyond the beyond the scope to cover all the sidelines after 4. d3 d6 5.0-0. Nevertheless, along the way I got inspired by all the astonishing plans and variations available for White here. Resulting in the fact that I would like to give you an instrument against all of Black's main responses here. }
5. O-O Bg4
{ Pinning the knight. Like in many Ruy Lopez positions, Black plays this move after d2-d4, putting pressure on this central square. In contrast to these positions, here Black lacks this central pressure and we will try to play the bishop out of the game. Adhiban's game against Ubilava is very instructive for us on how to conduct this plan. }
6. c3 Be7
{ Following the main line. Please note that many alterations in the set up at the early stage of the game will finally return to the main line. }
7. Re1 { Good position for the rook, making way for the knight to f1. } 7... a6
{ This line is very topical and can be reached via different move orders, such as @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/2np1n2/1B2p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Be7  6.c3  O-O  7.Re1  a6  - chapter 4...d6 5.O-O Be7 Main Line 8...b5. }
8. Ba4
{ Please remember that we only take on c6 after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/2np1n2/1B2p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  - chapter 4...d6 5.O-O a6. }
8... Nd7
{ This early rerouting of the knight, postponing castling, contains some poison of which we should be aware.   The next line leads to a transposition:  8...O-O  9.h3  Bh5  10.Nbd2  b5  11.Bc2  - please see the variation 7...O-O with 9...a6. }
9. Nbd2
{ Don't forget about this typical knight regrouping on the kingside. It functions excellently from there, as it can hop to f5 and it controls the central square e4. }
9... Nc5 10. Bc2
{ Naturally, our strong Ruy Lopez bishop should be preserved. } 10... Ne6 11.
h3
{ This move is in almost all cases useful to include. We control g4 without the loss of a tempo and are set under specific circumstances for g2-g4. }
11... Bh5 12. Nf1
{ In case of making progress, we are dependent on the knight manoeuvre to g3. }
12... Ng5
{ The point behind the long rerouting becomes manifest: Black uses the pin for some mass exchanges. }
13. Bxg5 Bxg5 14. Ng3
{ After this move, Black cannot maintain his bishop pair. } 14... Bxf3 15. Qxf3
{ Black has to seal the perimeter @@StartBracket@@i.e., f5 and h5@@EndBracket@@ in order to limit the scope of the knight. }
15... g6
{ In the notes of Nigel Short, this position can be considered equal. However, I think that White can quite easily obtain the slightly preferable odds. }
16. Rad1
{ Seen before, was  16.Ba4  O-O  17.Bxc6?!  Too early, giving Black counter chances along the b-file.  17...bxc6  18.d4  Qe7  19.Rad1  Rfb8⇆  @@StartBracket@@1-0 @@StartBracket@@72@@EndBracket@@ Czarnota, P @@StartBracket@@2547@@EndBracket@@ -Maiorov, N @@StartBracket@@2490@@EndBracket@@ Pardubice 2006. }
16... Qf6 17. Qe2
{ Not only avoiding the exchange of queens but at the same time preparing for the rerouting of the knight to f3. }
17... O-O 18. Nf1
{ The knight is on its way to f3. From there it guides the pawn push d3-d4. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Anti-Berliner Gambit 6...O-O"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ This variation - after  3...Nf6  - is called the 'Berlin Defense' or the 'Berlin Wall', due to its super solid nature. Rooted in the family of the Ruy Lopez opening, the Berlin Defense was first seen in practice in 1801, and examined by @@StartBracket@@it's in the name - who else?@@EndBracket@@ Berliners, as recorded in history. }
4. d3 Bc5
{ The bishop is placed actively on c5 and renders conquering the pawn on e5 less attractive for White. }
5. Bxc6
{ It's a recurring story: likewise in the Ruy Lopez Exchange @@StartBracket@@Part 1@@EndBracket@@, we trade off the bishop for the knight in an early phase of the game, inflicting damages to Black's pawn structure, whereas we avoid - amongst others - the old but currently relevant variation after  5.O-O  Nd4!?  . }
5... dxc6 6. O-O
{ Now that the e5-pawn is poisoned @@StartBracket@@  6.Nxe5??  Qd4-+  @@EndBracket@@,  White brings his king to safety, breathing new life in taking on e5.  Moreover, the bishop is not ideally placed on c5 now and often it goes back to d6 - with Black losing one move.   Another popular option for White is  6.Nbd2  , but like in the Ruy Lopez Exchange, I prefer a quick short castling.  Why? We kind of finalize our development, keeping our options open for different set-ups such as c3-d4, Bg5 or Be3, and Nbd2-f1-g3, Na3-c4 or Nc3. }
6... O-O
{ This move introduces a gambit; Black sacrifices a pawn in return for smooth developments and active play. }
7. Nxe5
{ Our opponent leaves a pawn 'en prise'. Be courageous and snatch the pawn, apply the greed-and-grit strategy and defend well... for you are destined for a great reward! }
7... Re8
{ By winning the pawn, White spent time on taking on e5, and retreat. As a result, Black's strategy comprises of a quick development of the pieces to gain supremacy. One of the key elements here is that when White succeeds to disentangle from the pin after Bg4, our prospects are bright. }
8. Nf3
{ The best move, guarding the king. The fact that we are susceptible for the pin by 8...Bg4, is something we have to bear with. }
8... Bg4
{ Without any doubt, this pin encompasses the most danger for White. Now it's our turn to find the right answer to our adversary's aggressivity. }
9. h3
{ It's a continuing story @@StartBracket@@as so often seen in the first course of this series about the Ruy Lopez Exchange@@EndBracket@@: the implementation of h2-h3 is for positional reasons in our favour. }
9... Bh5 10. Be3
{ We will proceed with Nbd2 on the next move when the harmony is back between White's pieces. }
10... Bb6
{ In an attempt to maintain the tension, Black avoids the exchange of bishops. }
11. Nbd2
{ The knights are well-coordinated, and the queen can step out of the pin. }
11... Re6 12. Qe1
{ White got the better chances as well after  12.Re1  Qe7  13.Nf1  Re5  14.g4  followed by Ng3, when the game didn't last much longer in Kane,S @@StartBracket@@1825@@EndBracket@@-Daniel,A @@StartBracket@@671@@EndBracket@@ Parsippany 2001, 1-0 @@StartBracket@@26@@EndBracket@@. }
12... Qd7 13. a4 a5 14. Nh2
{ White obtained a massive advantage here, the pawn phalanx c2-d3-e4 is of granite. Moreover, Black's counterplay is hard to find and I don't see how he is going to face f2-f4. }
*

