[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ This variation - after  3...Nf6  - is called the 'Berlin Defense' or the 'Berlin Wall', due to its super solid nature. Rooted in the family of the Ruy Lopez opening, the Berlin Defense was first seen in practice in 1801, and examined by @@StartBracket@@it's in the name - who else?@@EndBracket@@ Berliners, as recorded in history. }
4. d3 Bc5
{ The bishop is placed actively on c5 and renders conquering the pawn on e5 less attractive for White. }
5. Bxc6
{ It's a recurring story: likewise in the Ruy Lopez Exchange @@StartBracket@@Part 1@@EndBracket@@, we trade off the bishop for the knight in an early phase of the game, inflicting damages to Black's pawn structure, whereas we avoid - amongst others - the old but currently relevant variation after  5.O-O  Nd4!?  . }
5... dxc6 6. O-O
{ Now that the e5-pawn is poisoned @@StartBracket@@  6.Nxe5??  Qd4-+  @@EndBracket@@,  White brings his king to safety, breathing new life in taking on e5.  Moreover, the bishop is not ideally placed on c5 now and often it goes back to d6 - with Black losing one move.   Another popular option for White is  6.Nbd2  , but like in the Ruy Lopez Exchange, I prefer a quick short castling.  Why? We kind of finalize our development, keeping our options open for different set-ups such as c3-d4, Bg5 or Be3, and Nbd2-f1-g3, Na3-c4 or Nc3. }
6... Bd6
{ Black has to defend the e5-pawn and by this move, the pawn is protected. As a result, Black is losing valuable time. }
7. Bg5
{ Before Black can regroup his knight @@StartBracket@@e.g. Nd7, and then possibly to f8 and e6@@EndBracket@@ he is facing a difficult choice. Should he unpin his knight with his king still in the center? }
7... h6 8. Bh4 { Maintaining the pin. } 8... Bg4
{ 8...g5  9.Bg3  Bg4  leads to a transposition of moves. } 9. Nbd2
{ The knights on d2 and f3 are rock solid! On top of that White is flexible in moving the d2-knight to c4 or f1.   On top level  9.h3  appeared, which tempted Black to take on f3. Presumably,  9...Bh5  is better, maintaining the pin.   9.h3!?  Bxf3  10.Qxf3  Be7  11.Bg3  Nd7  12.Nd2  O-O  13.Nc4  when White is in charge, due to the promising continuation of Qg4 and f2-f4, Firouzja,A @@StartBracket@@2723@@EndBracket@@ -Wang,H @@StartBracket@@2756@@EndBracket@@ Moscow 2019. }
9... g5
{ This position can be reached after @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp2pp1/2pb1n1p/4p3/4P2B/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RN1Q1RK1 b kq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Bg4  9.Nbd2  Qe7  .  This is a transposition to Firouzja-Nakamura @@StartBracket@@2020@@EndBracket@@. }
10. Bg3
{ The bishop is not at all passively placed on g3, as it engages on the e5-pawn. }
10... Nh5 { After  10...Qe7  White simply follows his plan by  11.Nc4  . } 11.
Nc4 { Again, the weak link on e5 needs guidance. } 11... Nxg3
{ Nakamura's choice, but not the best. } 12. fxg3
{ Came this a surprise for Nakamura? White opens the f-file and a knight manoeuvre to f5 is in the air. }
12... Qe7 13. h3
{ This is a strong novelty over Aronian's game against Nakamura and comprises the entirely different concept of playing on the kingside.   13.c3  O-O-O  14.b4  Kb8  15.a3  h5⇆  leads to unclear play.  0-1 @@StartBracket@@28@@EndBracket@@ Aronian,L @@StartBracket@@2773@@EndBracket@@-Nakamura,H @@StartBracket@@2736@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020. }
13... Bd7 14. Nxd6+
{ Black's main strength of the bishop pair has vanished and his pawn structure is worse than White's. }
14... cxd6 15. Nd2 { The knight is on its quest for his most natural square. }
15... Be6 16. Qh5 { Preventing h5, and preparing Rf1 or Re1. } 16... O-O-O 17.
Rf2
{ Black has to make a difficult choice. Should he strive for counterplay with d6-d5, or wait in order not to create any new weaknesses? }
17... Kb8 18. Raf1 { White will try to establish a rook on f6 to take on h6. }
