4. d3 Bc5
{ The bishop is placed actively on c5 and renders conquering the pawn on e5 less attractive for White. }
5. Bxc6
{ It's a recurring story: likewise in the Ruy Lopez Exchange @@StartBracket@@Part 1@@EndBracket@@, we trade off the bishop for the knight in an early phase of the game, inflicting damages to Black's pawn structure, whereas we avoid - amongst others - the old but currently relevant variation after  5.O-O  Nd4!?  . }
5... dxc6 6. O-O
{ Now that the e5-pawn is poisoned @@StartBracket@@  6.Nxe5??  Qd4-+  @@EndBracket@@,  White brings his king to safety, breathing new life in taking on e5.  Moreover, the bishop is not ideally placed on c5 now and often it goes back to d6 - with Black losing one move.   Another popular option for White is  6.Nbd2  , but like in the Ruy Lopez Exchange, I prefer a quick short castling.  Why? We kind of finalize our development, keeping our options open for different set-ups such as c3-d4, Bg5 or Be3, and Nbd2-f1-g3, Na3-c4 or Nc3. }
6... Nd7
{ This move has a solid reputation. It has been played by Ding Liren, Anand, Nakamura, and Ivanchuk, and - last but definitely not least @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ - your very own and favourite author! }
7. c3
{ Mostly played is  7.Nbd2  .  However, by this move  7.c3  , White seizes immediately the initiative in the center.   For instance,  7.Nbd2  O-O  8.Nc4  f6  9.Kh1!?  a5  10.a4  Nb6  11.Be3  Bxe3  12.Nxe3  Be6  13.Ng1!  1-0 @@StartBracket@@108@@EndBracket@@ Giri, A @@StartBracket@@2764@@EndBracket@@-Lysyj, I @@StartBracket@@2593@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2020. }
7... h6
{ An extremely clever positional move. Black stops White from the manoeuvre Bc1-g5-h3-g3, from where it hits the central pawn on e5.   7...a5  This move was tried with success by Wesley So against Anish Giri, played in a recent online rapid game.  8.d4  Bd6  9.Bg5  We are aiming for similar ideas and to reach positions alike as in our main line, though with a different move order.  9...f6  10.Bh4  O-O  11.Nbd2  would transpose to our main line after 10...a5.   @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1ppn1ppp/2pb4/p3p3/3PP3/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Re1  a4  10.Nbd2  exd4  11.cxd4   11.Nc4!?  dxc3  12.Nxd6+  cxd6  13.Qxd6  Qe7  14.Qd4  with compensation for the sacrificed pawn in: Pavlov, V @@StartBracket@@2430@@EndBracket@@-Panitevsky, I @@StartBracket@@2489@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2016 ½-½ @@StartBracket@@30@@EndBracket@@.  11...Nb6  12.Nf1  O-O  13.Bg5  f6  14.Bh4  Bg4  15.h3  Bh5  16.Qd3  Qd7  17.g4  Bg6  Black was better in Giri, A @@StartBracket@@2776@@EndBracket@@-So, W @@StartBracket@@2770@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2021 1-0 @@StartBracket@@50@@EndBracket@@. }
8. d4
{ 8.Nbd2  O-O  9.b4  Bd6  10.Nc4  Re8!  A prophylaxis for the following knight manoeuvre...  11.Be3  This whole line looks impressive for White, grabbing the initiative on the queenside. Nonetheless, Black can launch a counterattack on the kingside, starting with the knight manoeuvre ...Nd7-f8-g6.  11...Nf8  12.h3  Ng6  13.a4  Bf8  14.Qc2  Qf6!  Black obtained here sufficient counterplay: h3 is weak and Nf4 or h4 is about to follow. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@35@@EndBracket@@ Anton Guijarro,D @@StartBracket@@2703@@EndBracket@@ -Salgado Lopez,I @@StartBracket@@2584@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020. }
8... Bd6 { We are still following the game between Firouzja and Ding. } 9. Nbd2
exd4 10. Nxd4
{ This is my recommendation to get our opponent off track. Instead of playing the obvious  10.cxd4  , we prepare for the advance of the f-pawn while improving our knight.   10.cxd4  O-O  11.h3  Nb6!  preparing for the counterpunch in the center.  12.Nb3  f5!  Ding sets up a blockade on the light squares.  13.e5  Be7  the squares on d5 and e6 are in his pocket now.  14.Qc2  f4!  By this move, Ding provides his bishop sufficient strong squares to go to @@StartBracket@@e6 and f5@@EndBracket@@. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@47@@EndBracket@@ Firouzja,A @@StartBracket@@2728@@EndBracket@@-Ding,L @@StartBracket@@2791@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020. }
10... O-O 11. f4
{ In the struggle for the center we can say: in for a penny, in for a pound! }
11... Bc5 12. Nf3
{ It's too early to say that White is better, albeit he is building up a serious initiative in the center. Black must watch his steps! }
12... Re8 13. Qc2 Nf6
{ Attacking the center is a sound plan, but Black is not yet fully prepared. }
14. e5 Nd5 15. f5 { When the avalanche of pawns seems threatening. } *

