{ Mostly played is  7.Nbd2  .  However, by this move  7.c3  , White seizes immediately the initiative in the center.   For instance,  7.Nbd2  O-O  8.Nc4  f6  9.Kh1!?  a5  10.a4  Nb6  11.Be3  Bxe3  12.Nxe3  Be6  13.Ng1!  1-0 @@StartBracket@@108@@EndBracket@@ Giri, A @@StartBracket@@2764@@EndBracket@@-Lysyj, I @@StartBracket@@2593@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2020. }
7... O-O
{ An extremely clever positional move. Black stops White from the manoeuvre Bc1-g5-h3-g3, from where it hits the central pawn on e5.   7...a5  This move was tried with success by Wesley So against Anish Giri, played in a recent online rapid game.  8.d4  Bd6  9.Bg5  We are aiming for similar ideas and to reach positions alike as in our main line, though with a different move order.  9...f6  10.Bh4  O-O  11.Nbd2  would transpose to our main line after 10...a5.   @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1ppn1ppp/2pb4/p3p3/3PP3/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Re1  a4  10.Nbd2  exd4  11.cxd4   11.Nc4!?  dxc3  12.Nxd6+  cxd6  13.Qxd6  Qe7  14.Qd4  with compensation for the sacrificed pawn in: Pavlov, V @@StartBracket@@2430@@EndBracket@@-Panitevsky, I @@StartBracket@@2489@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2016 ½-½ @@StartBracket@@30@@EndBracket@@.  11...Nb6  12.Nf1  O-O  13.Bg5  f6  14.Bh4  Bg4  15.h3  Bh5  16.Qd3  Qd7  17.g4  Bg6  Black was better in Giri, A @@StartBracket@@2776@@EndBracket@@-So, W @@StartBracket@@2770@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2021 1-0 @@StartBracket@@50@@EndBracket@@. }
8. d4
{ In order not to be overrun, Black refuses to give up on the central point e5. }
8... Bd6 9. Bg5
{ In this kind of positions, would anyway go Qe8 and f6, so why would White give Black a nudge in that direction and help him on his way? The answer is that the bishop is excellently placed on g3, hitting e5. }
9... f6 10. Bh4
{ Black is limited in his options. First, he wants to move the queen from the diagonal of the bishop, then he overprotects e5 with rook e8, while creating space for the knight-regrouping via f8 to g6.   10.Qb3+!?  Kh8  11.Bh4  b6  12.Nbd2  Ba6  13.Rfe1  Qe7  14.dxe5  Nxe5  15.Nxe5  Qxe5  16.Bg3  followed by taking on d6, left White slightly for choice in Eljanov,P @@StartBracket@@2751@@EndBracket@@-Radjabov,T @@StartBracket@@2710@@EndBracket@@ Shamkir 2017, 1-0 @@StartBracket@@46@@EndBracket@@. Please have a look at the Model Games section how to play such a position. }
10... Qe8 11. Nbd2
{ White doesn't stand still obviously, postponing the move Re1 for the moment. Now Black must reckon with Nc4 and - evt. - Nxd6.   Recently Grischuk played  11.Re1  in a blitz game with success:  11...Nb6  12.Nbd2  a5  13.Bg3  a4  14.Qc2  c5  15.dxe5  fxe5  16.Nf1  Rxf3!?  A drastic decision, burning all the bridges, but interesting.   In case of  16...Bg4  , White could follow up with  17.Nh4  ,  and, 18.Ne3, 19.Nhf5 etc.  17.gxf3  Qh5?!   17...Qf7!  would have been stronger, e.g.  18.Ne3  Be6  19.Nf5  Bxa2  with a double-edged position.  18.Qe2⩲  Grischuk, A @@StartBracket@@2777@@EndBracket@@-Maghsoodloo, P @@StartBracket@@2676@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 1-0 @@StartBracket@@60@@EndBracket@@. }
11... Qf7 { Black prepares for Re8 and Nf8, meanwhile hindering Nc4. } 12. Bg3
{ The bishop reached his destiny. Black must take precautionary measures to face the increasing pressure on e5. }
12... Re8 13. Qc2 Nf8
{ This essential rerouting of the knight to g6, is indispensable in Black's operations.   The move  13...a5  leads to a transposition to the variation 12...a5 13. Qc2 Re8. }
14. dxe5
{ Good timing to take at this time on e5. When the black knight reaches g6, he wouldn't have taken back with the pawn on e5. }
14... fxe5 15. Ng5
{ We enter a forcing line with a lot of exchanges. As a result of this chasing away of the black queen of the a2-diagonal, White paves the way for Qb3+. }
15... Qf6 16. Qb3+ Ne6
{ Blocking the diagonal, whereas the major drawback for Black here is that after  17.Nxe6  he can't take back with the bishop.   The idea behind the move  16...Be6  would miserably fail, due to  17.Nxe6  Qxe6  18.Qxb7  Rab8  19.Qxc6  Rxb2  longing in vain for compensation  20.Nc4  White is clearly better, being a pawn up in connection with the better structure and pieces.   16...Kh8??  Please don't force me to explicate this simple but nice mate 😆  17.Nf7+  Kg8  18.Nh6+  Kh8  19.Qg8# }
17. Nxe6
{ This rather odd-looking move taking back the piece with the rook, possibly allows a trick for us on which we ought to be alert. }
17... Rxe6 18. Nc4
{ It is a recurring theme in most of the lines: the knight manoeuvre Nb1-d2-c4, and then Nxd6, causing a backward pawn on d6. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Rosenthaler Gambit: 4...a6"]
[Black "Introduction: Rosenthaler Gambit"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 a6 5. Bxc6 dxc6
{ 5...bxc6  Taking towards the center and preparing d5. Nonetheless, our hunger for the e5-pawn is not stilled..  6.Nxe5!  Of course, a simplistic chess saying goes: 'A pawn is a pawn.'  6...Bd6  7.Nc4 }
6. Nxe5
{ Black's main idea is to initiate a quick development now that the diagonals and the center are open and he will castle long. }
6... Bc5
{ 6...Bd6  This move is by far the most popular here, but it doesn't make much sense to me.  7.Nc4!  White wanted to leave the e5-square anyhow. On the next move he can take the bishop.  7...Bc5  8.Be3±  and after the exchange of the c5-bishop, black's compensation is non-existent. }
7. O-O Qe7
{ 7...O-O  When one offers a pawn, one ought to go 'all-in'.  8.Nd2  Re8  9.Nef3  Bg4  10.Re1  Nd7  11.h3  Bh5  12.Nf1  White will unpin himself after Ng3.  12...Ne5  will not give Black the so-desired attack, as we can unpin ourselves with:  13.g4!  White is a healthy pawn up here. }
8. Nf3 { The knight retreats as an important defender of our king. } 8... Bg4
9. h3 Bh5 10. Be3
{ Being material up, it's convenient to develop our bishop and offer the exchange of pieces at the same time. }
10... O-O-O 11. Nbd2
{ would have been an interesting alternative. It's instructive to see with the help of this line, where Black's chances lie. }
11... Bxe3
{ 11...g5  The hidden clue behind the previous move 11. Nbd2 is disclosed now.  12.e5!  Nd5  13.Bxg5  Switching on your engine here will give you comfort. But please realize in a f2f-game, events can turn out less favorable.  13...Qd7  14.Ne4!  Even stronger than B:d8, as it allows counterplay after Rg8.   14.Bxd8  Rg8⇆  is at least dangerous. For example, }
12. fxe3 Qc5
{ White cannot defend the e3-pawn easily. For instance, after Qe2 the c2-pawn is hanging.   12...g5!?  13.Qe1!  Unpinning.  13...g4  In for a penny, in for a pound.. is that what we hear Black murmur?  14.Nh2!  White threatens Qh4, whereas Black cannot move the knight to d7 because of 15. hxg4.  14...gxh3  15.Qh4!  Don't forget that Black's position contains a lot of flaws. }
13. d4 Qe7
{ 13...Qb6  That's pretty out of the way!  14.b3  Not allowing our opponent to win material @@StartBracket@@b2@@EndBracket@@ back. }
14. e5
{ Black is losing valuable time since he has to move his knight. We use this time to defend the pawn on e3, as Black will attempt to break up our impressive central pawn formation by means of f7-f6. }
14... Nd7
{ This withdrawing movement can be considered the best. On d5 the knight's strong position won't last. Black is preparing to use the 'battering ram' f7-f6.   14...Nd5  15.Qe2  f6  The knight seems invincible on d5..but we don't stand for any superstitious nonsense..  16.c4!  Taking the lead chasing the knight, while Black has insufficient compensation for the pawn. }
15. Qe2 f6
{ Naturally, our opponent is does everything he's capable of, to generate active play on the @@StartBracket@@g- and e-@@EndBracket@@ files. }
16. exf6 { Not fearing ghosts.. } 16... gxf6
{ Opening the g-file as well.   16...Nxf6  17.Rae1  As my old trainer Babak would comment on a lazy but strong move Rae1: 'easy chess'.  17...g5  What else? White was ready to disentangle by Qe2-d3.  18.Qf2  intending Nxg5 and Ne5, as e3-e4.  18...Rhg8  19.Ne5!  follow up with e3-e4: White is on top. }
17. e4 { White is a pawn up, as simple as that. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Rosenthaler Gambit: 4...a6"]
[Black "Rosenthaler Gambit: 4...a6 5.Bxc6 bxc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ This variation - after 3..Nf6 - is called the 'Berlin Defense' or the 'Berlin Wall', due to its supersolid nature. Rooted in the family of the Ruy Lopez opening @@StartBracket@@i.e. 3.Bb5@@EndBracket@@, the Berlin Defense was first seen in practice anno 1801, and examined by @@StartBracket@@it's in the name - who else?@@EndBracket@@ Berliners, as recorded in history. }
4. d3
{ After this move, we set foot into the 'Anti-Berlin'. We are keeping the queens on the board for the moment, sidestepping the forced lines arising after 4..Nxe4, amongst others the supersolid ending c.q. the 'Berlin Wall', deployed 4 times by Kramnik against Kasparov with great success in the World Championship Match @@StartBracket@@London, 2000@@EndBracket@@. }
4... a6
{ A highly peculiar decision from Black, we are provoked to take the knight on c6. We would do this anyway, also after  4...Bc5  , let alone after the worthless  4...a6  . On top of that, we can win a pawn - served on a platter by our friendly opponent! Nonetheless, there are some dangerous ideas and pitfalls to overcome. }
5. Bxc6 { We accept the gift - hopefully not a Greek one. } 5... bxc6
{ Taking towards the center and preparing d5. Nonetheless, our hunger for the e5-pawn is not stilled.. }
6. Nxe5 { Of course, a simplistic chess saying goes: 'A pawn is a pawn.' } 6...
Bd6
{ 6...Bb7  7.O-O  d6  8.Nf3  we are just a full pawn up.   6...d5  7.O-O !  White relies upon his quick development.  7...dxe4  8.dxe4  Qxd1  9.Rxd1  Nxe4  A pyrrhic victory for Black.  10.Re1+-  Since this small rook move inflicts such a devastating toll on Black's 4...a6 and 9...Nxe4. A terrible discovered check @@StartBracket@@g6@@EndBracket@@ is following. }
7. Nc4 Bc5 8. Be3
{ Black's compensation must be hidden somewhere under the chess board, but I can't find it. }
*

