{ After this move, we set foot into the 'Anti-Berlin'. We are keeping the queens on the board for the moment, sidestepping the forced lines arising after 4..Nxe4, amongst others the supersolid ending c.q. the 'Berlin Wall', deployed 4 times by Kramnik against Kasparov with great success in the World Championship Match @@StartBracket@@London, 2000@@EndBracket@@. }
4... a6
{ A highly peculiar decision from Black, we are provoked to take the knight on c6. We would do this anyway, also after  4...Bc5  , let alone after the worthless  4...a6  . On top of that, we can win a pawn - served on a platter by our friendly opponent! Nonetheless, there are some dangerous ideas and pitfalls to overcome. }
5. Bxc6 { We accept the gift - hopefully not a Greek one. } 5... dxc6 6. Nxe5
{ Black's main idea is to initiate a quick development now that the diagonals and the center are open and he will castle long. }
6... Bc5
{ This system was 3 times applied by the strong 2600-rated correspondence player Gil. Worth having a look at and not to be underestimated! }
7. O-O Qe7 { 7...Qd6?  8.Nf3  and White has a huge advantage. } 8. Nf3
{ The knight retreats as an important defender of our king. } 8... Bg4
{ An annoying pin, and the gambit players are licking their fingers. Black castles long and has active pieces. }
9. h3 { When in dire straits, we always can fall back on h2-h3. } 9... Bh5 10.
Be3
{ Being material up, it's convenient to develop our bishop and offer the exchange of pieces at the same time. }
10... O-O-O { Black can take on e4 now. } 11. Nbd2
{ White is fully developed now and can start thinking of how to escape the pin. }
11... Bd6
{ As seen in Popov,I @@StartBracket@@2140@@EndBracket@@ -Stamenov,I Sofia 2004 1-0 @@StartBracket@@22@@EndBracket@@, White could simply follow up with }
12. Qe1 { A novelty. } 12... Rhg8 13. Nd4
{ White is everything up here, not just a pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Rosenthaler Gambit: 4...a6"]
[Black "Rosenthaler Gambit: 4...a6 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.Ne5 Bc5 7.O-O Qe7 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ This variation - after 3..Nf6 - is called the 'Berlin Defense' or the 'Berlin Wall', due to its supersolid nature. Rooted in the family of the Ruy Lopez opening @@StartBracket@@i.e. 3.Bb5@@EndBracket@@, the Berlin Defense was first seen in practice anno 1801, and examined by @@StartBracket@@it's in the name - who else?@@EndBracket@@ Berliners, as recorded in history. }
4. d3
{ After this move, we set foot into the 'Anti-Berlin'. We are keeping the queens on the board for the moment, sidestepping the forced lines arising after 4..Nxe4, amongst others the supersolid ending c.q. the 'Berlin Wall', deployed 4 times by Kramnik against Kasparov with great success in the World Championship Match @@StartBracket@@London, 2000@@EndBracket@@. }
4... a6
{ A highly peculiar decision from Black, we are provoked to take the knight on c6. We would do this anyway, also after  4...Bc5  , let alone after the worthless  4...a6  . On top of that, we can win a pawn - served on a platter by our friendly opponent! Nonetheless, there are some dangerous ideas and pitfalls to overcome. }
5. Bxc6 { We accept the gift - hopefully not a Greek one. } 5... dxc6 6. Nxe5
{ Black's main idea is to initiate a quick development now that the diagonals and the center are open and he will castle long. }
6... Bc5
{ This system was 3 times applied by the strong 2600-rated correspondence player Gil. Worth having a look at and not to be underestimated! }
7. O-O Qe7 { 7...Qd6?  8.Nf3  and White has a huge advantage. } 8. Nf3
{ The knight retreats as an important defender of our king. } 8... Bg4
{ An annoying pin, and the gambit players are licking their fingers. Black castles long and has active pieces. }
9. h3 { When in dire straits, we always can fall back on h2-h3. } 9... Bh5 10.
Be3
{ Being material up, it's convenient to develop our bishop and offer the exchange of pieces at the same time. }
10... O-O-O { Black can take on e4 now. } 11. Nbd2
{ White is fully developed now and can start thinking of how to escape the pin. }
11... Bxe3 12. fxe3
{ I tend to believe that Black has two main options here after taking on e3. Obviously, he should come up with something, as - for example - the dull Rhe8 is a lost move. He can entice us to move our central pawns, subsequently hitting them. Or he can bluntly start his offense by g7-g5-g4. }
12... g5 13. Qe1 { Unpinning. } 13... g4
{ 'In for a penny, in for a pound', is that what we hear Black mumble? } 14.
Nh2
{ White threatens Qh4, whereas Black cannot move the knight to d7 because of 15. hxg4. }
14... gxh3 { 14...Rhg8  15.Qh4  gxh3  is a transposition to our main line. }
15. Qh4 { Don't forget that Black's position contains a lot of flaws. } 15...
Rhg8 16. Qxh3+
{ The 'mole' is kicked out of our house.   Please abstain from  16.g3  because of  16...Rxg3+  17.Qxg3  Rg8  18.Qxg8+  Nxg8  19.Kh1  Qc5  when surprisingly, Black is winning here. Our king is too weak and the black queen is unstoppable. }
16... Kb8 17. Nc4 { With the aim of e4-e5, winning a minor piece. The move }
17... Rg5
{ 17...Rg6  has its drawbacks too:  18.e5  Nd5  19.Qxh5  b5  20.Na5  Rdg8  21.Rf2  Nxe3  22.Qf3+-  Rxg2+  23.Rxg2  Rxg2+  24.Qxg2!   Of course not  24.Kh1?  Qh4!  ⇆  24...Nxg2  25.Nxc6+  simply winning for White. }
18. Rf5 { This exchange extinguishes the fire. } 18... Rdg8 19. Rxg5
{ With only one pair of rooks remaining on the board, we are out of danger. }
19... Rxg5 20. Rf1
{ White is simply better here: a pawn up, a weakened black pawn structure, and nothing to be afraid of.   20...Nd7  21.Nf3  Bxf3  22.Qxf3  ways went smoothly for White. Black's compensation for the pawn faded. }
*

