{ The move  13.Re1  is less convincing, due to Black's energetic response of  13...Bxf3!  White can't keep his material edge, neither after  14.Nxf3  Nxe4  , nor after @@StartFEN@@2kr3r/1pp2ppp/p1p2n2/2q5/4P3/3PPb1P/PPPN2P1/R2QR1K1 w - - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Qxf3  Qxc2  . And let's keep the hideous @@StartFEN@@2kr3r/1pp2ppp/p1p2n2/2q5/4P3/3PPb1P/PPPN2P1/R2QR1K1 w - - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14.gxf3  out of the consideration... although... a pawn is a pawn. Nevertheless, it's not to my taste due to Black's aggressive  h5, g5 and g4. }
13... Qe7 14. e5
{ Black is losing valuable time since he has to move his knight. We use this time to defend the pawn on e3, as Black will attempt to break up our impressive central pawn formation by means of f7-f6. }
14... Nd7
{ This withdrawing movement can be considered the best. On d5 the knight's strong position won't last. Black is preparing to use the 'battering ram' f7-f6. }
15. Qe2 { 15.Qe1!?  To unpin ourselves, also leads to a better position. }
15... f6
{ Naturally, our opponent does everything he can to generate active play on the @@StartBracket@@g- and e-@@EndBracket@@ files. }
16. exf6
{ Using 'Realpolitik' by grabbing the pawn, White is not fearing any ghosts. }
16... gxf6 { Opening the g-file as well. } 17. e4
{ There exist more moves that guide us to a favourable position. Notwithstanding, this move can be considered best as it takes initiative. }
17... Rhg8 { seems logical, but White will try to establish his knight on f5. }
18. Qf2 Bxf3
{ Here White has two interesting options. One of them simply keeping the pawn by Qxf3. Or }
19. Nxf3
{ An interesting positional sacrifice, with the aim to bring the knight to f5. }
19... Qxe4 20. Nh4
{ whereafter White acquires the superior position. If you have any doubts, please compare the knights' positions. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Rosenthaler Gambit: 4...a6"]
[Black "Rosenthaler Gambit: 4...a6 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.Ne5 Bc5 7.O-O Qe7 #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ This variation - after 3..Nf6 - is called the 'Berlin Defense' or the 'Berlin Wall', due to its supersolid nature. Rooted in the family of the Ruy Lopez opening @@StartBracket@@i.e. 3.Bb5@@EndBracket@@, the Berlin Defense was first seen in practice anno 1801, and examined by @@StartBracket@@it's in the name - who else?@@EndBracket@@ Berliners, as recorded in history. }
4. d3
{ After this move, we set foot into the 'Anti-Berlin'. We are keeping the queens on the board for the moment, sidestepping the forced lines arising after 4..Nxe4, amongst others the supersolid ending c.q. the 'Berlin Wall', deployed 4 times by Kramnik against Kasparov with great success in the World Championship Match @@StartBracket@@London, 2000@@EndBracket@@. }
4... a6
{ A highly peculiar decision from Black, we are provoked to take the knight on c6. We would do this anyway, also after  4...Bc5  , let alone after the worthless  4...a6  . On top of that, we can win a pawn - served on a platter by our friendly opponent! Nonetheless, there are some dangerous ideas and pitfalls to overcome. }
5. Bxc6 { We accept the gift - hopefully not a Greek one. } 5... dxc6 6. Nxe5
{ Black's main idea is to initiate a quick development now that the diagonals and the center are open and he will castle long. }
6... Bc5
{ This system was 3 times applied by the strong 2600-rated correspondence player Gil. Worth having a look at and not to be underestimated! }
7. O-O Qe7 { 7...Qd6?  8.Nf3  and White has a huge advantage. } 8. Nf3
{ The knight retreats as an important defender of our king. } 8... Bg4
{ An annoying pin, and the gambit players are licking their fingers. Black castles long and has active pieces. }
9. h3 { When in dire straits, we always can fall back on h2-h3. } 9... Bh5 10.
Be3
{ Being material up, it's convenient to develop our bishop and offer the exchange of pieces at the same time. }
10... O-O-O { Black can take on e4 now. } 11. Nbd2
{ White is fully developed now and can start thinking of how to escape the pin. }
11... Bxe3 12. fxe3
{ I tend to believe that Black has two main options here after taking on e3. Obviously, he should come up with something, as - for example - the dull Rhe8 is a lost move. He can entice us to move our central pawns, subsequently hitting them. Or he can bluntly start his offense by g7-g5-g4. }
12... Qc5
{ White cannot defend the e3-pawn easily. For instance, after Qe2 the c2-pawn is hanging. }
13. d4
{ The move  13.Re1  is less convincing, due to Black's energetic response of  13...Bxf3!  White can't keep his material edge, neither after  14.Nxf3  Nxe4  , nor after @@StartFEN@@2kr3r/1pp2ppp/p1p2n2/2q5/4P3/3PPb1P/PPPN2P1/R2QR1K1 w - - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14.Qxf3  Qxc2  . And let's keep the hideous @@StartFEN@@2kr3r/1pp2ppp/p1p2n2/2q5/4P3/3PPb1P/PPPN2P1/R2QR1K1 w - - 0 14@@EndFEN@@  14.gxf3  out of the consideration... although... a pawn is a pawn. Nevertheless, it's not to my taste due to Black's aggressive  h5, g5 and g4. }
13... Qe7 14. e5
{ Black is losing valuable time since he has to move his knight. We use this time to defend the pawn on e3, as Black will attempt to break up our impressive central pawn formation by means of f7-f6. }
14... Nd7
{ This withdrawing movement can be considered the best. On d5 the knight's strong position won't last. Black is preparing to use the 'battering ram' f7-f6. }
15. Qe2 { 15.Qe1!?  To unpin ourselves, also leads to a better position. }
15... f6
{ Naturally, our opponent does everything he can to generate active play on the @@StartBracket@@g- and e-@@EndBracket@@ files. }
16. exf6
{ Using 'Realpolitik' by grabbing the pawn, White is not fearing any ghosts. }
16... gxf6 { Opening the g-file as well. } 17. e4
{ There exist more moves that guide us to a favourable position. Notwithstanding, this move can be considered best as it takes initiative. }
17... c5 { Black is about to create a square for his pieces on e5. } 18. d5
{ We should be on our qui vive since Black can create an outpost for his knight now.   18.c3  cxd4  19.cxd4  f5!  20.e5  Nb6  .  The powerful knight can jump to f4 in conjunction with Rg8, hitting g2. Or after f5-f4 hop to e3. We should definitely avoid this stuff! - }
18... Rdg8
{ Black obtained compensation for the pawn, but we shouldn't be unhappy with the outcome of the opening. After Kh1, Qf2 and Nh4, Nf5 we have every right to hope for an advantage. }
19. Kh1
{ Nice prophylaxis. Once we stabilize we can enjoy the fruits of our extra material. }
19... Rg7 20. Qe3 { Just unpinning ourselves, preparing for Nh4. } 20... Rhg8
21. Nh4 { Our position is totally bulletproof; White is much better here. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Mortimer Defense: 4...Ne7"]
[Black "Introduction: Mortimer Defense"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Ne7
{ You may be astounded because of this peculiar move, or - even worse - it gives you the creeps! But.. we shouldn't be too greedy here. In fact, Black set a trap by leaving his e5-pawn 'en prise'. This trap and line is named after James Mortimer, resp. the Mortimer Defense and the Mortimer-trap. }
5. d4
{ Can you believe your eyes? White 'wastes' another move with his d-pawn in this so important phase of the game where each move counts, leaving his e4-pawn en prise. If we didn't know any better, we'd say that we witness two amateurs playing.   5.Nxe5?  The pawn can't be taken, as Black will come up with the next astonishing tactical shot.  5...c6!  Suddenly, two of White's pieces are hanging. White is losing a piece after Qxa5 check. }
5... Nxe4
{ This is the best move and the positions arising resemble slightly the classical Berlin after 4.. Nxe4. Nonetheless, the knight on e7 can cause Black the biggest headache.  White can easily grab the initiative after   5...exd4  6.e5! }
6. dxe5 c6
{ Black is preparing for d7-d5, while the unwelcome guest on b5 is chased off.   6...a6!?  7.Bd3  Now that the Bishop abandoned its post, Black can choose for d7-d5. The other main option is 7.. Nc5, as played by Antipov.  7...Nc5   7...d5!?  8.exd6  Nxd6  9.Qe2!  The pin is a pain in black's neck.  9...g6  Aesthetically speaking, it looks quite nice for Black to move his bishop to the long diagonal meaning keeping the knights on the central squares d6 and e7.  10.Qe5!  Forcing Black to waive his right on castling.  8.O-O  d5  9.exd6  Taking on d6 opens up the entire center, which will turn out favorably for us if we stop the black king from castling.  9...Qxd6  10.Bc4!  We should play here as concrete as possible..  10...Qxd1  11.Rxd1  Never mind that the queens have been swapped, there remains sufficient play in the position as the black king should find his way out of the center.  11...b5  12.Be2  Bb7  In the aforementioned game, White showed a waiting attitude after 13.b3. I'd rather put a knife to his throat while he is still underdeveloped.  13.c4!  This is a strong novelty! Black is more or less forced to move the pawn to b4, leaving weaknesses behind.  13...b4  In case of taking on c4, White doesn't fear the doubling of his pawns after Bxf3.   13...bxc4  White continues his active play.  14.Bxc4  Ng6  15.Nc3!  With the idea of Nc3-d5 in conjunction with Re1+.  14.Nbd2  Planning to move the knight to b3 and evt. a5.  14...Ng6  Trying to bring out the f8-bishop first.  15.Nb3!  Black cannot afford to ignore the knight, since 16.Na5 can't be allowed.  15...Nxb3  16.axb3  This exchange is beneficial for our pawn structure. Black is left with some serious weak pawns on the queenside. }
7. Bd3
{ White is calling the knight to account, and an important decision has to be made. }
7... Nc5
{ 7...d5?!  is an inaccuracy, since after  8.exd6  Nxd6  The comparison to the quite similar line 6..a6 7.Bd3, d5 8.exd6 Nxd6 is substantial. The d6-knight is on thin ice now that the c-pawn - one moved to c6 - can't offer any protection.  9.Qe2!  Our adversary is in huge trouble: it's a huge task for him to unpin!  9...g6  10.Qe5! }
8. O-O
{ We allow Black to take our bishop, relying on our lead in development. } 8...
d5
{ A move which should be played in order to give the black pieces some space.   8...Nxd3  9.Qxd3  Ng6  10.Re1!  Strong prophylaxis! Black is impeded in playing d7-d5 now. }
9. exd6 Qxd6 10. Re1 { The Black pieces are congested in the center. } 10...
Nxd3 11. Nc3
{ The Black knight is pinned and White intends to create a dangerous initiative by bringing his pieces as soon as possible into play. }
11... Bf5 12. cxd3 O-O-O
{ Now that the king cannot castle east, he goes west. But here it will come under crossfire too.   12...Qxd3?  13.Qb3!  The black queen is suddenly a prey to all of white's pieces. Black must encounter several imminent threats, such as 13.Ne5 and Qxb7. }
13. Qa4 a6
{ What else? After  13...Kb8  we could force our opponent to sign the scoresheet by  14.Bf4! }
14. Bf4 { The king should give up any hopes on finding a shelter. } 14... Qg6
15. Qa5
{ With two lethal threats: @@StartBracket@@1@@EndBracket@@ 16.Qc7 mate, and @@StartBracket@@2@@EndBracket@@ 16.Na4 and 17.Nb6 mate. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Mortimer Defense: 4...Ne7"]
[Black "The Mortimer Defense 4...Ne7 5.O-O (Informational)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ This variation - after 3..Nf6 - is called the 'Berlin Defense' or the 'Berlin Wall', due to its supersolid nature. Rooted in the family of the Ruy Lopez opening @@StartBracket@@i.e. 3.Bb5@@EndBracket@@, the Berlin Defense was first seen in practice anno 1801, and examined by @@StartBracket@@it's in the name - who else?@@EndBracket@@ Berliners, as recorded in history. }
4. d3
{ After this move, we set foot into the 'Anti-Berlin'. We are keeping the queens on the board for the moment, sidestepping the forced lines arising after 4..Nxe4, amongst others the supersolid ending c.q. the 'Berlin Wall', deployed 4 times by Kramnik against Kasparov with great success in the World Championship Match @@StartBracket@@London, 2000@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Ne7
{ You may be astounded because of this peculiar move, or - even worse - it gives you the creeps! But.. we shouldn't be too greedy here. In fact, Black set a trap by leaving his e5-pawn 'en prise'. This trap and line is named after James Mortimer, resp. the Mortimer Defense and the Mortimer-trap. }
5. O-O
{ This move is most frequently played.   5.Nxe5?  The pawn can't be taken, as Black will come up with the next astonishing tactical shot.  5...c6!  Suddenly, two of White's pieces are hanging. White loses a piece after ...Qa5+. }
5... c6 6. Ba4 Ng6
{ A beautiful concept, in an artificial way the knight has been transferred to a better place near the king @@StartBracket@@s@@EndBracket@@. }
7. Re1 Bc5
{ Black is doing fine here. I couldn't find any advantage. Beyond any doubt, this line is very well playable for White. To give you an idea: please go with me through the game of Caruana.   7...Be7  Playable, but a bit more passive than Bc5.  8.d4  d6  9.c3  O-O  10.Nbd2  exd4   10...Re8  11.Nf1  exd4  12.cxd4  d5  13.e5  Ne4  1-0 @@StartBracket@@65@@EndBracket@@ Castellanos Rodriguez, R @@StartBracket@@2481@@EndBracket@@-Van Dael,S @@StartBracket@@2257@@EndBracket@@ Kragero 2020  14.Ng3  I believe that White is slightly better here, as he owns more space.  11.Nxd4  Re8  12.Nf1  Bd7  13.Ng3  White enjoys more space and the better position. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@32@@EndBracket@@ Leko,P @@StartBracket@@2690@@EndBracket@@-Hess, R @@StartBracket@@2574@@EndBracket@@ Douglas 2018 }
8. c3 d6 9. Nbd2 O-O 10. Nf1 Bb6 11. Ng3
{ The position is very symmetrical and in balance. Black has a lot of plausible options: one of them is d5. }
11... h6 { 11...d5= } 12. d4
{ Thus, it's White who is the first to act in the center. Black will try all what lies within his power to undermine it. }
12... exd4 13. cxd4 Bg4
{ White finds it hard to defend his d4-pawn without allowing a doubled pawn. }
14. h3 Bxf3 15. gxf3
{ White turns a weakness into a strength. Svidler uses the doubled f-pawn in the best possible way. }
15... Nh7 16. f4
{ Black was ready for the blockade on f4, after Qh4. White acts powerfully in the fight for the initiative. }
16... Qf6 17. f5 Nh4 18. e5
{ Please find this game in the Model Games section. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@47@@EndBracket@@ Svidler,P @@StartBracket@@2753@@EndBracket@@-Fressinet, L @@StartBracket@@2717@@EndBracket@@ Dubai 2014 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Mortimer Defense: 4...Ne7"]
[Black "The Mortimer Defense 4...Ne7 5.d4 exd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ This variation - after 3..Nf6 - is called the 'Berlin Defense' or the 'Berlin Wall', due to its supersolid nature. Rooted in the family of the Ruy Lopez opening @@StartBracket@@i.e. 3.Bb5@@EndBracket@@, the Berlin Defense was first seen in practice anno 1801, and examined by @@StartBracket@@it's in the name - who else?@@EndBracket@@ Berliners, as recorded in history. }
4. d3
{ After this move, we set foot into the 'Anti-Berlin'. We are keeping the queens on the board for the moment, sidestepping the forced lines arising after 4..Nxe4, amongst others the supersolid ending c.q. the 'Berlin Wall', deployed 4 times by Kramnik against Kasparov with great success in the World Championship Match @@StartBracket@@London, 2000@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Ne7
{ You may be astounded because of this peculiar move, or - even worse - it gives you the creeps! But.. we shouldn't be too greedy here. In fact, Black set a trap by leaving his e5-pawn 'en prise'. This trap and line is named after James Mortimer, resp. the Mortimer Defense and the Mortimer-trap. }
5. d4 { White can easily grab the initiative after } 5... exd4 6. e5 Nfd5 7.
Qxd4
{ in order not to be pushed back entirely, Black should keep his knight on d5 momentarily. }
7... c6 8. Bd3 Qb6 9. Qe4
{ Keeping the queens on the board.   White should refrain from  9.Qxb6?!  as after  9...axb6  10.O-O  Nb4  the position is far from clear. }
9... Qb4+
{ Our opponent can be understood for his desire of swapping of the queens. But it is against our favourable conditions! }
10. Nbd2 Ng6 11. O-O Qxe4 12. Nxe4
{ Black is suffering from his lack of space. } 12... Nb4 13. Rd1 Nxd3 14. Rxd3
{ The backward d-pawn makes Black's life miserable. } 14... b6 15. h4
{ Resuming our quest for total dominance. } 15... h5 16. Bg5
{ White is much better here. White follows up with Rad1 and eventually Nd6. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Mortimer Defense: 4...Ne7"]
[Black "The Mortimer Defense 4...Ne7 5.d4 Nxe4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ This variation - after 3..Nf6 - is called the 'Berlin Defense' or the 'Berlin Wall', due to its supersolid nature. Rooted in the family of the Ruy Lopez opening @@StartBracket@@i.e. 3.Bb5@@EndBracket@@, the Berlin Defense was first seen in practice anno 1801, and examined by @@StartBracket@@it's in the name - who else?@@EndBracket@@ Berliners, as recorded in history. }
4. d3
{ After this move, we set foot into the 'Anti-Berlin'. We are keeping the queens on the board for the moment, sidestepping the forced lines arising after 4..Nxe4, amongst others the supersolid ending c.q. the 'Berlin Wall', deployed 4 times by Kramnik against Kasparov with great success in the World Championship Match @@StartBracket@@London, 2000@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Ne7
{ You may be astounded because of this peculiar move, or - even worse - it gives you the creeps! But.. we shouldn't be too greedy here. In fact, Black set a trap by leaving his e5-pawn 'en prise'. This trap and line is named after James Mortimer, resp. the Mortimer Defense and the Mortimer-trap. }
5. d4
{ Can you believe your eyes? White 'wastes' another move with his d-pawn in this so important phase of the game where each move counts, leaving his e4-pawn en prise. If we didn't know any better, we'd say that we witness two amateurs playing.   5.Nxe5?  The pawn can't be taken, as Black will come up with the next astonishing tactical shot.  5...c6!  Suddenly, two of White's pieces are hanging. White loses a piece after ...Qa5+. }
5... Nxe4
{ This is the best move and the positions arising resemble slightly the classical Berlin after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.O-O  Nxe4  . Nonetheless, the knight on e7 can cause Black the biggest headache.   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppppnppp/5n2/1B2p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c6  6.dxe5  Nxe4  7.Bd3  is a transposition to the main line. }
6. dxe5 a6
{ A very logical move as Black wants one way or another to chase the bishop in order to be able to move his d-pawn c.q. develop his pieces. This move was tried in a 2020 online game by the Russian GM Antipov.   Contrary to  6...c6  , it doesn't weaken the d6-square and d7-pawn. However, it doesn't solve the lack of space issue. }
7. Bd3
{ Now that the bishop abandoned its post, Black can choose for  7...d5  .  The other main option is  7...Nc5  , as played by Antipov. }
7... d5 8. exd6
{ After  8.Bxe4  dxe4  9.Qxd8+  Kxd8  10.Ng5  Black gets sufficient compensation for the loss of the pawn.  10...Ke8  11.Nxe4  Nc6  The e5-pawn is weak and White should reckon with Nd4 and Bf5.  12.Bf4?!  Nd4!  Black is out of the woods. }
8... Nxd6 9. Qe2 { The pin is a pain in Black's neck. } 9... g6
{ Aesthetically speaking, it looks quite nice for Black to move his bishop to the long diagonal meaning keeping the knights on the central squares d6 and e7.   9...Be6  Doesn't come to the rescue of Black's king, as after  10.Nd4!  Black can't still move his knight on e7 out in a convenient way. }
10. Qe5 { Forcing Black to waive his right on castling. } 10... Rg8 11. O-O Bg7
{ Yeah, yeah, your bishop looks impressive. But hey, more important is what you are gonna do with your king.. }
12. Qe2 Bf5 13. Nc3 Bxd3 14. cxd3 Qd7
{ Our enemy is desperately trying to shelter his king. } 15. Re1
{ This is a line which is unlikely to be seen in practice, unless Black has prepared on this sideline. It contains a cunning plan, Baldrick! }
15... Nf5 16. g4 O-O-O
{ Beyond this simple move is a marvellous idea concealed. } 17. Kf1
{ A subtlety to walk out of the pin.   17.gxf5?!  This move can be considered as highly risky for us.  17...gxf5!  Suddenly, as by a miracle, everything falls in place for Black.  18.Kh1  Bxc3  19.bxc3  Qc6  Black has developed a dangerous attack, while White's dodgy knight is about to be pinned after Ne7-g6-h4.  20.Bf4?  This bad move is only helping Black's case.  20...Ng6!  21.Bg3  Rge8!   This is even stronger than  21...f4  .  22.Qd1  Rxe1+  is winning for Black. }
17... Rge8
{ White managed to take the knight now that he won a crucial tempo. } 18. gxf5
Nxf5 19. Qd1 Rxe1+ 20. Kxe1
{ White's king can still make up his mind which way to choose and not to forget he is a piece up!   For instance, after  20.Kxe1  Nd4  21.Nxd4  Bxd4  22.Be3  Qh3  23.Bxd4  Black is running out of attacking forces.  23...Rxd4  24.Qe2  Qxh2  25.Kd2  White's king has been brought into safety, obtaining a winning position. }
*

