{ Aesthetically speaking, it looks quite nice for Black to move his bishop to the long diagonal meaning keeping the knights on the central squares d6 and e7.   9...Be6  Doesn't come to the rescue of Black's king, as after  10.Nd4!  Black can't still move his knight on e7 out in a convenient way. }
10. Qe5 { Forcing Black to waive his right on castling. } 10... Rg8 11. O-O Bg7
{ Yeah, yeah, your bishop looks impressive. But hey, more important is what you are gonna do with your king.. }
12. Qe2 Bf5 13. Nc3 Bxd3 14. cxd3 Qd7
{ Our enemy is desperately trying to shelter his king. } 15. Re1
{ Of course, we don't lend him a hand.. } 15... Kf8 16. Ne5
{ White is more than fine here. Black will be reticent giving up his bishop since the dark squares around his king are to be occupied by the white pieces. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Mortimer Defense: 4...Ne7"]
[Black "The Mortimer Defense 4...Ne7 5.d4 Nxe4 #3 (Alternative 13.Bxf5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ This variation - after 3..Nf6 - is called the 'Berlin Defense' or the 'Berlin Wall', due to its supersolid nature. Rooted in the family of the Ruy Lopez opening @@StartBracket@@i.e. 3.Bb5@@EndBracket@@, the Berlin Defense was first seen in practice anno 1801, and examined by @@StartBracket@@it's in the name - who else?@@EndBracket@@ Berliners, as recorded in history. }
4. d3
{ After this move, we set foot into the 'Anti-Berlin'. We are keeping the queens on the board for the moment, sidestepping the forced lines arising after 4..Nxe4, amongst others the supersolid ending c.q. the 'Berlin Wall', deployed 4 times by Kramnik against Kasparov with great success in the World Championship Match @@StartBracket@@London, 2000@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Ne7
{ You may be astounded because of this peculiar move, or - even worse - it gives you the creeps! But.. we shouldn't be too greedy here. In fact, Black set a trap by leaving his e5-pawn 'en prise'. This trap and line is named after James Mortimer, resp. the Mortimer Defense and the Mortimer-trap. }
5. d4
{ Can you believe your eyes? White 'wastes' another move with his d-pawn in this so important phase of the game where each move counts, leaving his e4-pawn en prise. If we didn't know any better, we'd say that we witness two amateurs playing.   5.Nxe5?  The pawn can't be taken, as Black will come up with the next astonishing tactical shot.  5...c6!  Suddenly, two of White's pieces are hanging. White loses a piece after ...Qa5+. }
5... Nxe4
{ This is the best move and the positions arising resemble slightly the classical Berlin after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.O-O  Nxe4  . Nonetheless, the knight on e7 can cause Black the biggest headache.   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppppnppp/5n2/1B2p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 5@@EndFEN@@  5...c6  6.dxe5  Nxe4  7.Bd3  is a transposition to the main line. }
6. dxe5 a6
{ A very logical move as Black wants one way or another to chase the bishop in order to be able to move his d-pawn c.q. develop his pieces. This move was tried in a 2020 online game by the Russian GM Antipov.   Contrary to  6...c6  , it doesn't weaken the d6-square and d7-pawn. However, it doesn't solve the lack of space issue. }
7. Bd3
{ Now that the bishop abandoned its post, Black can choose for  7...d5  .  The other main option is  7...Nc5  , as played by Antipov. }
7... d5 8. exd6
{ After  8.Bxe4  dxe4  9.Qxd8+  Kxd8  10.Ng5  Black gets sufficient compensation for the loss of the pawn.  10...Ke8  11.Nxe4  Nc6  The e5-pawn is weak and White should reckon with Nd4 and Bf5.  12.Bf4?!  Nd4!  Black is out of the woods. }
8... Nxd6 9. Qe2 { The pin is a pain in Black's neck. } 9... g6
{ Aesthetically speaking, it looks quite nice for Black to move his bishop to the long diagonal meaning keeping the knights on the central squares d6 and e7.   9...Be6  Doesn't come to the rescue of Black's king, as after  10.Nd4!  Black can't still move his knight on e7 out in a convenient way. }
10. Qe5 { Forcing Black to waive his right on castling. } 10... Rg8 11. O-O Bg7
{ Yeah, yeah, your bishop looks impressive. But hey, more important is what you are gonna do with your king.. }
12. Qe2 Bf5 { It may well be that the direct } 13. Bxf5 gxf5 14. Re1
{ may be much stronger here. } 14... Bh8 15. Nc3 Rg6
{ With the intention of bringing the rook to e6. } 16. Qd3 Re6 17. Bg5
{ Black is under heavy fire here. The only plausible way to continue the game may be to press for the exchange of queens. }
17... Ne4 { nonetheless, it doesn't solve all of our opponent's problems. } 18.
Nxe4 Qxd3 19. cxd3 fxe4 20. Rxe4
{ although the d3-pawn needs protection, White is better here. } *

