[Black "Introduction: Anderssen Variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bd6
{ This is a strange move, the Black bishop blocks the d-pawn! Black plans to castle short, move his rook to e8 and move the bishop back to f8, whereafter all the circumstances are set for the pushing of the d-pawn. }
5. Nc3 h6
{ This is all still part of Blacks set-up. At all costs, he wants to prevent the pin after Bg5. }
6. a3 a6 7. Ba4 b5
{ 7...O-O  8.g4!  a wonderful move, coming out of the blue! It's well known that the defender should react in the center when his opponent launches a kingside attack.  8...Nxg4?  Is losing on the spot.  9.Rg1+-  There is no defense against all the threats along the g-file. Please note as well that the h6-pawn is White's target. }
8. Bb3 Bb7
{ At least the bad bishop is developed now. But the problems are from over yet.. }
9. Be3 Na5
{ 9...Rc8  10.h3  10.g4 looks also terribly dangerous for Black, but why should White hurry?  10...Ne7  11.g4!  11...c5  12.g5  hxg5  13.Nxg5  The pawn on f7 can be considered as Black's Achilles heel. But as a matter of fact, that goes as well for g7 now that the g-file has been opened.  13...Rf8  1/2-1/2  @@StartBracket@@21@@EndBracket@@ Nandhidhaa, P @@StartBracket@@2312@@EndBracket@@ -Ter Sahakyan,S @@StartBracket@@2617@@EndBracket@@ Montebelluna 2019  14.Rg1→ }
10. Ba2 { Of course, we are preserving our strongest minor piece. } 10... c5
11. O-O
{ Our king is safe. Next part of our plan is to open the f-file and or move our knight via h4 to f5, as was seen in: Vaibhav,S @@StartBracket@@2430@@EndBracket@@-Ledger,D @@StartBracket@@2245@@EndBracket@@ London 2011 1-0 @@StartBracket@@34@@EndBracket@@. }
