Nh5
{ Hitting g7, the knight move should do the job.   In fact, the position arising  16.Qh5  was also way beyond a big advantage for White.  He follows up with 17. O-O-O, mounting the pressure on g7. }
16... g6
{ is an insidious continuation. Behold, because White should NOT take on f8 as the initiative will slip into the opponent's hands. Instead, we should involve new attacking forces. }
17. Qe2
{ 17.Bxf8?  is bad, because of  17...Kxf8!  White should move his knight.  18.Nxf6  Qxf6  Black develops while White's king is stuck on e1.  19.Rg3  c5  20.Qe2  Qf4=∞  planning to play Bg4 as b5 and c4. White for the moment does not find a secure place for the king. }
17... c5 18. O-O-O
{ Black will be overrun with f4 and f5. His position collapses. } *

