1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 d6 5. O-O a6 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. d4 exd4 8.
Nxd4
{ Recently our standard-bearer Magnus played two games here. With Black, he got worse against Nakamura after  8.Qxd4  , while with the white pieces one year later Carlsen tried with success  8.Nxd4  , followed by 9.Qf3 }
8... c5
{ 8...Bd7  9.Qf3!  The most aggressive continuation.  9...c5  10.Nf5  Bxf5  11.exf5!  The e-file is opened with black's king on the draft.  11...Rb8  The game took a very sharp turn in Karjakin-Aronian.   11...Be7  12.Nc3  It's clear that white's pieces will occupy the more active positions.  12...O-O  13.Bg5!  As can be seen in the game of Perunovic, this novelty is more accurate, keeping the edge.  13...h6  14.Bh4  Re8  15.Rae1  Rb8  16.b3  Qd7  17.h3!  White has a simple plan of doubling the rooks on the e-file, increasing the pressure. Simply put, Black is facing a difficult position.  17...Nh7  18.Rxe7  Rxe7  19.Bxe7  Qxe7  20.Nd5⩲  White is better because of his 'octopus' on d5. The black queen has to keep an eye on both c7 as f6 @@StartBracket@@stopping f5-f6@@EndBracket@@.  12.Qg3!  A very strong novelty, which gives White the upper hand. Black is defenseless against the pressure on g7.   12.g4!?  The pawn push to g5 is very dangerous for Black. Having said that, we have also exposed our own king while being undeveloped. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@42@@EndBracket@@ Karjakin,S @@StartBracket@@2725@@EndBracket@@-Aronian,L @@StartBracket@@2782@@EndBracket@@ Nice 2010  12...Be7  13.Qxg7  Rg8  14.Qh6±  when the Black king will never ever find a shelter. }
9. Nc6 { This move lifts a tip of the veil in regards to our intentions. } 9...
Qd7 10. Na5
{ This , at first sight, a bit strange knight maneuver, has a lot of followers. More than 60 games could be retrieved in the database while amongst the elite players Carlsen, Grischuk, Svidler and Yu Yanghi have chosen this line. The knight is not at all badly placed here, as it puts Black in a squeeze. Moreover, in most of the @@StartBracket@@top@@EndBracket@@ games I saw White gets the opportunity to jump the knight back to c6. }
10... Qa4
{ Played by the best players and contains the strong idea of freeing the pieces.   10...Be7  This move has been tried a lot in practice and shouldn't be neglected.  11.Nc3  O-O  12.Re1  Re8  13.h3!  This novelty takes away the g4-square from Black. In many lines Black tries to bring the queen to g4 and evt. g6, far off from the badly placed d7.  13...Bf8  14.Bg5  It becomes obvious that Black can hardly do anything here. In case of Re6, we follow up with f2-f4. }
11. Bd2 Bg4
{ This interesting move was tried in Magnus' game.   11...Be7  This move can be considered the main line. Black is aiming for castling short.  12.Re1  O-O  13.Nc3  Only after short castling leaving the e7-bishop unprotected, White is enabled to play this move leaving the knight on a5 'en prise'..  13...Qe8  another option is   13...Qd7  but the French GM Maze shows in characteristic Berliner fashion how to get the advantage.  14.Bf4  Qg4  15.Qxg4  Nxg4  16.h3  Nf6  17.Nc6  17...Re8  18.e5  dxe5  19.Nxe7+  Rxe7  20.Bxe5  when White was everything up, in Maze,S @@StartBracket@@2628@@EndBracket@@-Lin, C @@StartBracket@@2508@@EndBracket@@ Helsingor 2018 1-0 @@StartBracket@@39@@EndBracket@@.   13...Qxa5  14.Nd5!  14.Bf4  Preparing for the demolition of the black structure.  14...Be6  15.e5!  we have witnessed the same idea in part 1 of this series about the Smart Ruy Lopez in the model games and theoretical section. White blows up black's structure leaving him behind with plenty of weaknesses.  15...dxe5  16.Bxe5  Rd8  17.Qf3  Nd5  1/2 @@StartBracket@@53@@EndBracket@@-1/2 @@StartBracket@@53@@EndBracket@@ Svidler,P @@StartBracket@@2723@@EndBracket@@-Karthikeyan, M @@StartBracket@@2606@@EndBracket@@ Chess. com INT 2020  18.Nb7  a fascinating novelty, cutting to the chase. White is up for c5!  18...Rd7  19.Ne4  with a large advantage for White. Black may temporarily avoid material losses after c5-c4, but that doesn't mean we refrain from using this weak square for our knights.   11...Nxe4  12.Nc3  Nxc3  13.Bxc3  Be6  1/2-1/2  @@StartBracket@@75@@EndBracket@@ Grischuk,A @@StartBracket@@2766@@EndBracket@@-Kramnik,V @@StartBracket@@2792@@EndBracket@@ Paris 2018  14.f4!  With this novelty we bring heat on our opponent. The king is stuck on e8 and f4-f5 is coming.  14...Be7  15.f5  Bd7  16.b3  Qe4  17.Qd2  Black is in deep trouble, since Rae1 is coming and he cannot castle. }
12. f3 Be6
{ Was provoking a smart thing to do? Maybe, due to the extra option of Qd4 with a check. }
13. Qe1
{ 13.Bc3  13...Be7  14.b3  Not only chasing away the queen, but in the meantime putting the pawns on white, the 'extra' bishop of black, restricting its scope.  14...Qd7  15.Nd2  d5  16.Qe1!  Good piece play by the champ.  16...O-O  17.Rd1  Rad8  18.Ndc4↑  Everywhere in black's camp weaknesses are being divulged. Where should the black queen go: not to c8 because of Nc6. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@62@@EndBracket@@. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@62@@EndBracket@@ Carlsen,M @@StartBracket@@2847@@EndBracket@@-Esipenko,A @@StartBracket@@2716@@EndBracket@@ Krasnaya Polyana 2021 }
13... Be7 14. c4
{ I like the configuration of the pieces a lot. Black is pulled back after b3 and is suffering from a lack of space. }
14... O-O 15. Nc3 Qxa5 { 15...Qd7  16.f4!  with a very promising attack. } 16.
Nd5 { This discovered attack promises White a much better position. } 16... Qa4
17. Nxe7+ Kh8 18. b3 { The queen is being pulled back. } 18... Qd7 19. Nd5
{ White is much better, due to his powerful bishop on c3 and the better pawn structure. }
