[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4...d6 Pin Variation: 5.O-O Bg4"]
[Black "Introduction: 4...d6 Pin Variation: 5.O-O Bg4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 d6 5. O-O Bg4
{ Pinning the knight. Like in many Ruy Lopez positions, Black plays this move after d2-d4, putting pressure on this central square. In contrast to these positions, here Black lacks this central pressure and we will try to play the bishop out of the game. }
6. c3 Be7
{ Following the main line. Please note that many alterations in the setup at the early stage of the game will finally return to the main line. }
7. Re1 { A good position for the rook, making way for the knight to f1. } 7...
a6
{ This line is very topical and can be reached by different move orders, such as 5... Be7.   7...O-O  8.h3!  As we have seen in part 1 of this series, the h3-move is the main part of our strategy. The bishop has to choose a color: does he stay on the h3-c8 diagonal or does he remain the pin.  8...Bh5  By far the most popular.   8...Bd7  makes no sense, as implementing h2-h3 only benefits White.  9.Nbd2  Please note that when reaching g3, we hit the bishop.  9...a6   9...Nd7  10.Nf1  The typical Ruy Lopez knight maneuver: Nb1-d2-f1-g3.  10...a6  11.Ba4  b5  12.Bc2  After Bb3, we are chased away by Nc5. Naturally, we are not allowed to give up our strong bishop.  12...Bg6   12...f5?  This move is losing a pawn since Black cannot take back because of a fork.  13.exf5!  d5  14.a4±  White remains a pawn up and will besiege the black weak spots, such as b5 and d5.  13.Ng3  Arrived at the destination.  13...Nb6  14.Be3  Rb8  15.Qe2!  Adhiban, aka 'the beast', prepares the d3-d4 advance.  15...b4  16.Rad1  All pieces are mobilized and it's time for a pawn move..  16...bxc3  17.bxc3  a5  18.d4↑  White obtained the initiative and thus, the better position. 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@66@@EndBracket@@ Adhiban,B @@StartBracket@@2689@@EndBracket@@-Ubilava,E @@StartBracket@@2495@@EndBracket@@ Caleta 2019  10.Ba4  In the Ruy Lopez we are expected to preserve our bishop on the light squares.  10...Nd7  With the idea of Nc5 and evt. Ne6. Another point is to play under certain circumstances f7-f5 to the f-file and to strengthen the center by moving the bishop to f6.   10...b5  11.Bc2!?  This move seems rather passive but scores excellent. It contains the clear plan of Nf1, g4, and Ng3, isolating the bishop on h5 and grabbing the initiative on the kingside.  11...d5  12.Qe2  A consolidating move, before playing g2-g4.  12...d4   12...dxe4  13.Nxe4!?  An interesting move, stepping off from the main paths.  13...Bg6  14.Nh4!  White maintains her advantage, now that - after Nxg6 - the light square bishop is the best piece on the board.  14...Qd7  15.Nxg6  hxg6  16.Ng5!  In conjunction with Bb3, White provided herself with easy play. The pressure on black's king is immense. The game went on with  13.g4  Bg6  14.cxd4!  Black is in dire straits since he kind of forced to take back on d4 with the pawn after which he has to encounter a pawn avalanche.  14...exd4   14...Nxd4  this move can't be recommended, because of  15.Nxd4  exd4  This gives White free play on the kingside.   15...Qxd4  16.Nf3!  Black has trouble defending e5.  16...Qd6  17.d4!  Using tactics to achieve our goal. White clearly took the lead, now that Black can't take on d4.  16.f4±  The advantage on the kingside is so overwhelming, that the sequel doesn't need any comments.  15.Nh2!  15...Bd6  16.Ndf1±  White is ready for f2-f4, in which case Black is overrun on the kingside. The next game illustrates the helplessness of Black. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@35@@EndBracket@@ Neelotpal, D @@StartBracket@@2446@@EndBracket@@-Karpatchev,A @@StartBracket@@2506@@EndBracket@@ Liffre 2017  11.Nf1  Almost there, at the final destination..  11...Nc5  12.Bc2  Evidently, preserving our strong bishop. White is very flexible, as he can choose between different plans, amongst those: @@StartBracket@@1@@EndBracket@@ g2-g4 followed by Ng3, or  @@StartBracket@@2@@EndBracket@@ undertaking action in the center with d3-d4.  12...Ne6   12...d5  This move appeared dozens of times in practice, though one may argue whether Black is fully organized for this pawn push.  13.exd5  Qxd5  14.Ne3  Qd8  Probably the best, however it strikes me that such a passive move is an ill omen.   14...Qd6  15.Nf5!  with the idea of d3-d4.  15...Qd7  16.d4  and black's position collapses.  15.Ng4!  An artificial placement of the knight, though not without effect. Hitting the central point on e5 and unpinning, and paving the way for d3-d4.  15...Nd7   15...Bd6  16.Bg5!  Provoking the weakening of the light squares after f7-f6.  16...f6  17.Bh4  and on the next move White takes the initiative in the center with d3-d4.  16.d4→  The time is ripe for such an energetic move in the center, due to white's strong pieces.  13.Ng3  In connection to the aforementioned, White can as well conduct his plan without the inclusion of g2-g4.  13...Bxf3  handing over the bishop, which can be deposited in the wooden box of chess pieces. White should start conducting to press on the light squares.  14.Qxf3  The inevitable consequence will be that White will be superior on the light squares.  14...Bg5  15.Ne2  This is a novelty. The idea is to prepare for d3-d4 and evt. stop Nf4 with g2-g3.  15...Bxc1  16.Raxc1  Qg5  17.Rcd1⩲  We are ready for the pawn push. }
8. Ba4 { Please remember that we only take on c6 after 5... a6 } 8... Nd7
{ this early rerouting of the knight, postponing castling, contains some poison of which we should be aware.  The next line is leading to a transposition:   8...O-O  9.h3  Bh5  10.Nbd2  b5  11.Bc2  @@StartBracket@@ Please see 7... O-O and 9... a6@@EndBracket@@. }
9. Nbd2
{ Don't forget about this typical knight regrouping on the kingside. From there it is functioning excellently, as it can hop to f5 and it controls the central square e4. }
9... Nc5 10. Bc2
{ Naturally, our strong Ruy-Lopez bishop should be preserved. } 10... Ne6 11.
h3
{ This move is in almost all cases useful to include. We control g4 without the loss of a tempo and are set under specific circumstances for g2-g4. }
11... Bh5 12. Nf1
{ In case of making progress, we are dependent on the knight maneuver to g3. }
12... Ng5
{ The point behind the long rerouting becomes manifest: Black uses the pin for some mass exchanges. }
13. Bxg5 Bxg5 14. Ng3
{ After this move, Black cannot maintain his bishop pair. } 14... Bxf3
{ 14...Bg6  is definitely not black's first choice, and leads inevitably to a worse position.  15.Ba4  O-O  16.d4  This is a novelty.  16...Bf6  17.Bxc6  bxc6  18.dxe5  dxe5  From the books we know that it's a privilege to possess the bishop pair. In this closed position they are of no value, while the knights prevail. }
15. Qxf3
{ Black has to seal the perimeter  @@StartBracket@@i.e. f5 and h5@@EndBracket@@ in order to limit the scope of the knight. }
15... g6
{ In the notes of Nigel Short, this position can be considered as equal. However, I think that White can quite easily obtain the slightly preferable odds. }
16. Rad1
{ Seen before, was   16.Ba4  O-O  17.Bxc6?!  Too early, giving Black counter chances along the b-file.  17...bxc6  18.d4  Qe7  19.Rad1  Rfb8⇆  1-0 @@StartBracket@@72@@EndBracket@@ Czarnota,P @@StartBracket@@2547@@EndBracket@@ -Maiorov,N @@StartBracket@@2490@@EndBracket@@ Pardubice 2006 }
16... Qf6
{ Not only avoiding the queen's exchange, but at the same time preparing for the rerouting of the knight to f3. }
17. Qe2 O-O 18. Nf1
{ The knight is on its way to f3. From there it guides the pawn push d3-d4. } *

