12... Bg6 13. Ng3 { Arrived at the destination. } 13... Nb6 14. Be3 Rb8 15. Qe2
{ Adhiban, aka 'the beast', prepares the d3-d4 advance. } 15... b4 16. Rad1
{ All pieces are mobilized and it's time for a pawn move.. } 16... bxc3 17.
bxc3 a5 18. d4 { White obtained the initiative and thus, the better position. }
18... exd4 19. Nxd4 Nxd4 20. Bxd4
{ Energetic play of the beast, something of which we are familiar with watching his games. The bishop attacks the king and we plan to follow up with f2-f4.   Less clear is  20.cxd4  d5!  21.e5  Nc4!  with counterplay. }
20... Re8 21. f4
{ Please take notice of the fact that we were able to get the bishop on g6 out of the game. }
21... Bh4
{ 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@66@@EndBracket@@ Adhiban,B @@StartBracket@@2689@@EndBracket@@-Ubilava,E  @@StartBracket@@2495@@EndBracket@@ Caleta 2019 }
22. Qg4
{ This move should have been played, when the beast would have definitely devoured his prey. The queen hits indirectly g7, threatening f4-f5. }
22... Bxg3 23. Qxg3 { f4-f5 is in the air... } 23... f6
{ Trying to seal off the perimeter around the king, setting a block against the strong d4-bishop. }
24. Bb3+ Kh8 25. e5
{ Opening the dark squares. Black is on the verge of defeat. For instance, }
25... fxe5
{ 25...c5  will not help Black because of  26.exf6  cxd4  27.fxg7+  Kxg7  28.f5+-  . }
26. fxe5 { Black's defenses crumble. } 26... Qd7
{ 26...dxe5  loses on the spot:  27.Bxb6+-  . } 27. exd6
{ The bishop on d4 decides the game. } 27... cxd6 28. Rxe8+ Bxe8 29. Rf1
{ White is winning, since  29...Bg6  30.Bxb6  wins a piece due to the back-rank mate. }
