[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4...d6 Pin Variation: 5.O-O Bg4"]
[Black "4...d6 Pin Variation: 5.O-O Bg4 − 7...O-O With 9...a6 10.Ba4 Nd7 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 d6 5. O-O Bg4
{ Pinning the knight. Like in many Ruy Lopez positions, Black plays this move after d2-d4, putting pressure on this central square. In contrast to these positions, here Black lacks this central pressure and we will try to play the bishop out of the game. Adhiban's game against Ubilava is very instructive for us how to conduct this plan. }
6. c3 Be7
{ Following the main line. Please note that many alterations in the set up at the early stage of the game will finally return to the main line. }
7. Re1 { Good position for the rook, making way for the knight to f1. } 7...
O-O 8. h3
{ As we have seen in part 1 of this series, the h3-move is the main part of our strategy. The bishop has to make a decision now: does he stay on the h3-c8 diagonal or does he remain the pin? }
8... Bh5
{ By far the most popular.   8...Bd7  makes no sense, as implementing h2-h3 only benefits White. }
9. Nbd2 { Please note that when reaching g3, we hit the bishop. } 9... a6 10.
Ba4 { In the Ruy Lopez we usually always preserve our light-squared bishop. }
10... Nd7
{ With the idea of Nc5 and eventually Ne6. Another point is to play under certain circumstances f7-f5 to the f-file and to strengthen the center by moving the bishop to f6. }
11. Nf1 { Almost there, at the final destination.. } 11... Nc5 12. Bc2
{ Evidently, preserving our strong bishop. White is very flexible, as he can choose between different plans, amongst those: @@StartBracket@@1@@EndBracket@@ g2-g4 followed by Ng3, or @@StartBracket@@2@@EndBracket@@ undertaking action in the center with d3-d4. }
12... d5
{ This move appeared dozens of times in practice, though one may argue whether Black is fully organized for this pawn push. }
13. exd5 Qxd5 14. Ne3 Qd8
{ Probably the best, however it strikes me that such a passive move is an ill omen. }
15. Ng4
{ An artificial placement of the knight, though not without effect. Hitting the central point on e5 and unpinning, and this, paving the way for d3-d4. }
15... Bd6 16. Bg5 { Provoking the weakening of the light squares after f7-f6. }
16... Qd7 17. d4 { with the initiative. } *

