{ This line is very topical and can be reached via different move orders, such as @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/2np1n2/1B2p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Be7  6.c3  O-O  7.Re1  a6  - chapter 4...d6 5.O-O Be7 Main Line 8...b5. }
8. Ba4
{ Please remember that we only take on c6 after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/2np1n2/1B2p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  - chapter 4...d6 5.O-O a6. }
8... Nd7
{ This early rerouting of the knight, postponing castling, contains some poison of which we should be aware.   The next line leads to a transposition:  8...O-O  9.h3  Bh5  10.Nbd2  b5  11.Bc2  - please see the variation 7...O-O with 9...a6. }
9. Nbd2
{ Don't forget about this typical knight regrouping on the kingside. It functions excellently from there, as it can hop to f5 and it controls the central square e4. }
9... Nc5 10. Bc2
{ Naturally, our strong Ruy Lopez bishop should be preserved. } 10... Ne6 11.
h3
{ This move is in almost all cases useful to include. We control g4 without the loss of a tempo and are set under specific circumstances for g2-g4. }
11... Bh5 12. Nf1
{ In case of making progress, we are dependent on the knight manoeuvre to g3. }
12... Ng5
{ The point behind the long rerouting becomes manifest: Black uses the pin for some mass exchanges. }
13. Bxg5 Bxg5 14. Ng3
{ After this move, Black cannot maintain his bishop pair. } 14... Bg6
{ Is definitely not Black's first choice and inevitably leads to a worse position. }
15. Ba4 O-O 16. d4
{ This is a novelty.   I wasn't thrilled by the following sequence of events:  16.Bxc6  bxc6  17.Nxg5  Qxg5  18.d4  Rab8  19.b3  Rfe8  20.Re3  h5⇆  with serious counterplay for Black, in Kokarev, D @@StartBracket@@2579@@EndBracket@@-Rodin, D @@StartBracket@@2426@@EndBracket@@ Voronezh 2008. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@39@@EndBracket@@. }
16... Bf6
{ 16...b5  leads to a solid advantage for White after  17.Bb3  Bf6  18.Bd5  Qd7  19.a4⩲  Black is under serious pressure. }
17. Bxc6 bxc6 18. dxe5 dxe5
{ From the books we know that it's a privilege to possess the bishop pair. In this closed position they are of no value, while the knights prevail. }
19. Qc2 a5 20. Rad1 Qc8
{ Also after  20...Qe7  21.Nf5  Qc5  22.Rd7  White is much better. } 21. Qa4
{ Black has some serious weaknesses in his position to deal with. } 21... Qe6
22. Nf5 Bxf5 23. exf5 Qxf5 24. Qxc6
{ White has every chance of winning because of the weak pawns and better piece placement. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4...d6 Pin Variation: 5.O-O Bg4"]
[Black "4...d6 Pin Variation: 5.O-O Bg4 − 7...a6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 d6 5. O-O Bg4
{ Pinning the knight. Like in many Ruy Lopez positions, Black plays this move after d2-d4, putting pressure on this central square. In contrast to these positions, here Black lacks this central pressure and we will try to play the bishop out of the game. Adhiban's game against Ubilava is very instructive for us how to conduct this plan. }
6. c3 Be7
{ Following the main line. Please note that many alterations in the set up at the early stage of the game will finally return to the main line. }
7. Re1 { Good position for the rook, making way for the knight to f1. } 7... a6
{ This line is very topical and can be reached via different move orders, such as @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/2np1n2/1B2p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Be7  6.c3  O-O  7.Re1  a6  - chapter 4...d6 5.O-O Be7 Main Line 8...b5. }
8. Ba4
{ Please remember that we only take on c6 after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/2np1n2/1B2p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...a6  - chapter 4...d6 5.O-O a6. }
8... Nd7
{ This early rerouting of the knight, postponing castling, contains some poison of which we should be aware.   The next line leads to a transposition:  8...O-O  9.h3  Bh5  10.Nbd2  b5  11.Bc2  - please see the variation 7...O-O with 9...a6. }
9. Nbd2
{ Don't forget about this typical knight regrouping on the kingside. It functions excellently from there, as it can hop to f5 and it controls the central square e4. }
9... Nc5 10. Bc2
{ Naturally, our strong Ruy Lopez bishop should be preserved. } 10... Ne6 11.
h3
{ This move is in almost all cases useful to include. We control g4 without the loss of a tempo and are set under specific circumstances for g2-g4. }
11... Bh5 12. Nf1
{ In case of making progress, we are dependent on the knight manoeuvre to g3. }
12... Ng5
{ The point behind the long rerouting becomes manifest: Black uses the pin for some mass exchanges. }
13. Bxg5 Bxg5 14. Ng3
{ After this move, Black cannot maintain his bishop pair. } 14... Bxf3 15. Qxf3
{ Black has to seal the perimeter @@StartBracket@@i.e., f5 and h5@@EndBracket@@ in order to limit the scope of the knight. }
15... g6
{ In the notes of Nigel Short, this position can be considered as equal. However, I think that White can quite easily obtain the slightly preferable odds. }
16. Rad1
{ Seen before, was  16.Ba4  O-O  17.Bxc6?!  Too early, giving Black counter chances along the b-file.  17...bxc6  18.d4  Qe7  19.Rad1  Rfb8⇆  @@StartBracket@@1-0 @@StartBracket@@72@@EndBracket@@ Czarnota, P @@StartBracket@@2547@@EndBracket@@ -Maiorov, N @@StartBracket@@2490@@EndBracket@@ Pardubice 2006. }
16... Qf6 17. Qe2
{ Not only avoiding the exchange of queens but at the same time preparing for the rerouting of the knight to f3. }
17... O-O 18. Nf1
{ The knight is on its way to f3. From there it guides the pawn push d3-d4. }
18... Qg7 19. Nh2 f5 20. Nf3
{ The knight is perfectly placed on f3, from where it hits the squares d4 and e5. }
20... Bf6 21. Ba4
{ This is a novelty, with the aim to be able to take on c6 on a suitable moment @@StartBracket@@i.e., after d4, exd4@@EndBracket@@ }
21... Kh8 22. d4
{ Black is facing now the choice between  22...exd4  and  22...b5  , a 'Cornelian dilemma', as he must choose between two courses of action that either of which will have a harmful effect. }
22... b5 23. Bb3
{ The consequences of this pawn move immediately manifest themselves: Bd5 has become a serious threat. Please note how much stronger our bishop is than Black's! }
23... Rae8 24. Bd5
{ Unmistakably, Black's early ...b7-b5 led eventually to a serious weakening of the queenside pawns and squares. }
24... Ne7 25. Bb7
{ Harassing Black's queenside pawns.   Please note that after  25...c6?  our bishop isn't getting trapped: we can play  26.dxe5  dxe5  27.c4  Rb8  28.Rd7  the rook is very strong on d7 and White is going to win material. }
