[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4...d6 Fianchetto Variation: 5.O-O g6"]
[Black "Introduction: 4...d6 Fianchetto Variation: 5.O-O g6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 d6 5. O-O g6
{ Naturally, now that White chose for a 'timid' set-up with d3. Black is striving for moving the bishop on g7 where it is better placed than on e7. }
6. d4
{ Again pushing the d-pawn forward??Hold your horses! Albeit, on the one hand we spend precious time in the opening moving twice with the same piece, the time is ripe to attack Black in the center as he is undeveloped. }
6... Bd7
{ 6...exd4  The character of the positions arising, changes drastically. Especially after the next move..  7.e5!  With force we open the way towards the black king.  7...dxe5  8.Nxe5  Our opponent is on the verge of defeat. We intend to take on c6, and or piling up the pressure at this point. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@32@@EndBracket@@ Morozevich,A @@StartBracket@@2659@@EndBracket@@-Moiseenko,V @@StartBracket@@2526@@EndBracket@@ Khanty-Mansiysk 2019 }
7. d5
{ This is part of White's plan, exchanging the d7-bishop and gaining space on the queenside. In the resulting positions, Black has to play King's Indian alike positions, but without his light squared bishop..we took the sting out of his play. }
7... Nb8
{ Black clearly intends to take the bishop back by the b8-knight. On d7 the knight stops the c-pawn advance.   7...Ne7  8.Bxd7+!?  The core idea of white's strategy. The strongest minor black piece is swapped.  8...Nxd7  The knight on d7 is usefully placed as it stops the c2-c4-c5 advance of White.   8...Qxd7  9.Re1  h5  10.c4  Black's 9th move was seen in grandmaster practice in a pandemic online blitz game. With 9.. h5 Black is aiming to gain ground on the kingside, and, besides, swap his bad bishop off on h6.  10...Bh6  11.Bxh6  Rxh6  12.Nc3  White is just much faster on the queenside, than Black on the kingside.  12...Kf8  13.c5!  Now that Black is not yet mobilized, we strike hard: files ought to be opened!: 0-1 @@StartBracket@@46@@EndBracket@@ Sjugirov,S  @@StartBracket@@2675@@EndBracket@@ -Khanin,S @@StartBracket@@2584@@EndBracket@@ Lichess.org INT 2020  9.c4!  Bg7  10.Be3  Likewise as in the King's Indian Defense, White will try to push c4-c5 to get a plus on the queenside.  10...h6  Black should prepare f7-f5 with this move, otherwise he could be surprised by Ng5 and Ne6.  11.Nfd2  f5  12.f3⩲  White reached a favorable Kings-Indian position, now that Black strong c8-bishop is off the board. See for typical plans how to play these kind of positions: 1-0 @@StartBracket@@52@@EndBracket@@ So,W @@StartBracket@@2776@@EndBracket@@-L'Ami,E @@StartBracket@@2639@@EndBracket@@ Batumi 2018 }
8. Bxd7+ Nbxd7
{ Can we say that the knight is better placed on d7 than on e7? Probably, although it takes time for Black as Nfxd7 or Qxd7 are useful moves. }
9. Re1
{ The central pawn needs protection, and, ideally, we take in the position with c2-c4 and only then Nc3. }
9... Bg7
{ In case of   9...Be7  we can quite easily get the upper hand by  10.c4  O-O  11.Bh6  Re8  12.Nc3  a5  13.h3  Nc5  14.b3  leaves White with the preferable position. White is about to gain space on the queenside by a3 and b4.0-1 @@StartBracket@@43@@EndBracket@@ Szabo,K @@StartBracket@@2540@@EndBracket@@-Dumitrache,D @@StartBracket@@2446@@EndBracket@@ Baia Sprie 2012. }
10. c4 Nc5
{ 10...O-O  11.Nc3  Nh5  12.Be3  Keeping an eye on c5, endorsing the break c4-c5, at the same time helping the defense.  12...h6  13.Nd2⩲  1/2-1/2  @@StartBracket@@13@@EndBracket@@ Parligras,M @@StartBracket@@2581@@EndBracket@@-Lupulescu,C @@StartBracket@@2635@@EndBracket@@ Iasi 2015 }
11. Nc3 { The following move has to be played to keep the knight on c5. } 11...
a5 12. b3
{ Losing a move, but a necessary evil in order to drive off the c5-knight by b4.   12.a3?!  this is too hasty, as Black can fix our b-pawn.  12...a4⩱ }
12... O-O 13. a3
{ Nothing can stop us now: after Rb1 we finally come to our beloved b3-b4. }
13... Nh5
{ 13...a4  14.b4!  Nb3  15.Rb1  True, Black can capture the c1-bishop, but this advantage will soon be forgotten due to the superior White pawn structure on the queenside.  15...Nxc1  16.Rxc1⩲ }
14. Rb1 { Ready for action! b3-b4 will certainly be good for us! } 14... Nf4
{ 14...f5?  15.exf5  gxf5  16.b4!  Before steering our knight to Black's Achilles-heel e6, we have to drive off the defender of that square.  16...axb4  17.axb4  Nd7  18.Ng5  White is winning here as there aren't any convenient ways to halt the intruder. }
15. Be3 { An useful move while defusing Nd3. } 15... Qd7
{ 15...Ncd3  won't do any harm, because of  16.Rf1!  Black can't keep his knights on these active squares.  16...Qd7  17.g3  Qg4  18.Kh1  Our strategy pays out now: Black has to retreat to h5, after we can enjoy our structural edge.  18...Nh5 }
16. Bxc5
{ Smeets is shifting gears, no longer trying to push the pawns on the queenside but pointing his arrows on the kingside. }
16... dxc5 17. Ne2
{ Evidently, the knight on f4 is on white's to-do-list. In other words, it has to be expelled. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@83@@EndBracket@@ Smeets,J @@StartBracket@@2609@@EndBracket@@ -Seel,C @@StartBracket@@2472@@EndBracket@@ Netherlands 2013 }
