[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4...d6 Fianchetto Variation: 5.O-O g6"]
[Black "4...d6 Fianchetto Variation: 5.O-O g6 6.d4 exd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 d6
{ Making this course, at first, it merely was my intention to give you a B: c6-repertoire against the Ruy Lopez and the Berlin Wall and it went beyond the beyond the scope to cover all the sidelines after 4. d3 d6 5.0-0. Nevertheless, along the way I got inspired by all the astonishing plans and variations available for White here. Resulting in the fact that I would like to give you an instrument against all of Black's main responses here. }
5. O-O
{ Here our plan of taking on c6 will not offer us salvation: Black can just take back with the b-pawn. Therefore, we take in the Ruy Lopez set-up with c3 and d4. }
5... g6
{ Naturally, now that White chose for a 'timid' set-up with d3. Black is striving for moving the bishop on g7 where it is better placed than on e7. }
6. d4
{ Again pushing the d-pawn forward?? Hold your horses! Albeit, on the one hand, we spend precious time in the opening moving twice with the same piece, the time is ripe to attack Black in the center as he is undeveloped. }
6... exd4
{ The character of the positions arising, changes drastically. Especially after the next move.. }
7. e5 { With force we open the way towards the black king. } 7... dxe5 8. Nxe5
{ Our opponent is on the verge of defeat. We intend to take on c6, and/or pile up the pressure at this point. }
8... Qd5
{ Black is playing with fire, and his royal highness won't be too glad now that her majesty left his side. }
9. Re1 Qxb5
{ Now there is a pretty knight hop in the position. Can you find it? } 10.
Nxc6+ { The knight is heading to d4. } 10... Be6 11. Nxd4
{ White obtained a huge advantage as the King is stuck in the center. } *

