1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 d6 5. O-O
{ Here our plan of taking on c6 will not offer us salvation: Black can just take back with the b-pawn. Therefore, we take in the Ruy Lopez set-up with c3 and d4. TRAINABLE }
5... g6
{ Naturally, now that White chose for a 'timid' set-up with d3. Black is striving for moving the bishop on g7 where it is better placed than on e7. }
6. d4
{ Again pushing the d-pawn forward??Hold your horses! Albeit, on the one hand we spend precious time in the opening moving twice with the same piece, the time is ripe to attack Black in the center as he is undeveloped. }
6... exd4
{ The character of the positions arising, changes drastically. Especially after the next move.. }
7. e5 { With force we open the way towards the black king. } 7... dxe5 8. Nxe5
{ Our opponent is on the verge of defeat. We intend to take on c6, and/or pile up the pressure at this point. }
8... Bd7 9. Bxc6
{ Demolishing the pawn structure of Black. Please note that we are targeting the king and we won't matter being a futile pawn down. }
9... Bxc6
{ Black doesn't solve his problems with 9...bxc6 as after 10. Re1 Be6 11. Nxc6 Qd5 12. Qxd4! White is much better. }
10. Nxc6
{ With a different move order we can reach a similar position as in the Caruana game: 10. Re1 Be7 11. Bh6 Rg8 12. Bg5 Qd6 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Nd2 1-0 @@StartBracket@@39@@EndBracket@@ Kosakowski,J @@StartBracket@@2363@@EndBracket@@-Varney, Z @@StartBracket@@2005@@EndBracket@@ Rymanow Zdroj 2017. }
10... bxc6 11. Re1+ { For better or worse, we should play this natural move.. }
11... Be7 12. Bh6 { Castling short is prevented. } 12... Qd6 13. Nd2
{ Despite the fact he is a pawn up, he is in a pickle as the black king will not find any shelter on the board. }
13... O-O-O 14. Nc4
{ Black would get in even bigger trouble when he wouldn't leave the d5-square vacant. }
14... Qd5 15. Qd3
{ Black is deadly lost against the threat of Re5. In case of Bd6, he is losing material after Bg7. }
15... Rhe8 16. Re5
{ With the idea to bring the rook via a5 to Black's king. White is winning. } *

