11... Be7 12. Bh6 { Castling short is prevented. } 12... Qd6 13. Nd2
{ Despite the fact he is a pawn up, he is in a pickle as the black king will not find any shelter on the board. }
13... O-O-O 14. Nc4
{ White spoiled his promising attacking chances after 14. Qe2? d3!! 15. cxd3 - The line missed by the black player, must have been 15. Qxe7 Qxe7 16. Rxe7 Ng8!! with equal chances. - 15... Rhe8! 16. d4 1-0 @@StartBracket@@41@@EndBracket@@ Yemelin, V-Aleksandrov,A @@StartBracket@@2340@@EndBracket@@ Ashkhabad 1990. 16...Qb4 when Black can resist the upcoming assault on his king. }
14... Qc5 15. Ne5
{ Compared to the previous variation, we choose a different plan. By deploying our knight on e5, we engage on two weaknesses: c6 and f7. }
15... Qd5 16. c4
{ White's position overall is so promising that there are more promising continuations.  One of them is 16.Qd3 heading towards the poor black king. }
16... dxc3 17. Qa4
{ Another route than via d3, and maybe even more effective. Black is helpless against the threat Qa6+ and Nxc6+. }
17... Qb5 18. Qxa7
{ The game is over. With such a weak king one is bound to forfeit. } 18... Qb7
19. Qxb7+ Kxb7 20. Nxf7
{ and rest was a matter of some extra moves.. Caruana,F @@StartBracket@@2801@@EndBracket@@ -Berend,E @@StartBracket@@2330@@EndBracket@@ Tromsoe 2014 1-0 @@StartBracket@@54@@EndBracket@@. }
