[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4...d6 Fianchetto Variation: 5.O-O g6"]
[Black "4...d6 Fianchetto Variation: 5.O-O g6 6.d4 Bd7 7.d5 Ne7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 d6
{ Making this course, at first, it merely was my intention to give you a B: c6-repertoire against the Ruy Lopez and the Berlin Wall and it went beyond the beyond the scope to cover all the sidelines after 4. d3 d6 5.0-0. Nevertheless, along the way I got inspired by all the astonishing plans and variations available for White here. Resulting in the fact that I would like to give you an instrument against all of Black's main responses here. }
5. O-O
{ Here our plan of taking on c6 will not offer us salvation: Black can just take back with the b-pawn. Therefore, we take in the Ruy Lopez set-up with c3 and d4. }
5... g6
{ Naturally, now that White chose for a 'timid' set-up with d3. Black is striving for moving the bishop on g7 where it is better placed than on e7. }
6. d4
{ Again pushing the d-pawn forward?? Hold your horses! Albeit, on the one hand, we spend precious time in the opening moving twice with the same piece, the time is ripe to attack Black in the center as he is undeveloped. }
6... Bd7 7. d5
{ This is part of White's plan, exchanging the d7-bishop and gaining space on the queenside. In the resulting positions, Black has to play King's Indian alike positions, but without his light-squared bishop; we took the sting out of his play. }
7... Ne7 8. Bxd7+
{ The core idea of White's strategy: the strongest minor black piece is swapped. }
8... Qxd7
{ The advantage over 8..Nxd7 can be defined as that the e4-pawn needs protection resulting in a loss of time for White after 9.Re1. White needs to push his c-pawn forward to create an initiative on the queenside, and for that reason he cannot afford 9.Nc3. }
9. Re1 h5 10. c4
{ Black's 9th move was seen in grandmaster practice in a pandemic online blitz game. With 9.. h5 Black is aiming to gain ground on the kingside, and, besides, swap his bad bishop off on h6. }
10... Bh6 11. Bxh6 Rxh6 12. Nc3
{ White is just much faster on the queenside, than Black on the kingside. }
12... Kf8 13. c5
{ Now that Black is not yet mobilized, we strike hard: files ought to be opened! }
13... Kg7 { 13...dxc5?  14.Nxe5+-  when White is winning after Qf3. } 14. Qb3
{ We are hitting the weak points in our enemy's camp. That's the pawn on b7. }
14... b6
{ 14...Rb8  15.c6!  The b-pawn is pinned now, and after cxb7 the a- and c-pawn become irrevocably fragile. }
15. c6 Qc8 16. a4
{ 0-1 @@StartBracket@@46@@EndBracket@@ Sjugirov,S @@StartBracket@@2675@@EndBracket@@ -Khanin,S @@StartBracket@@2584@@EndBracket@@ Lichess.org INT 2020.   16.a4  a5  17.Qa3  Trying to open the position further after axb4, Qxb4 and a4-a5. }
