[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 d6
{ Making this course, at first, it merely was my intention to give you a B: c6-repertoire against the Ruy Lopez and the Berlin Wall and it went beyond the beyond the scope to cover all the sidelines after 4. d3 d6 5.0-0. Nevertheless, along the way I got inspired by all the astonishing plans and variations available for White here. Resulting in the fact that I would like to give you an instrument against all of Black's main responses here. }
5. O-O
{ Here our plan of taking on c6 will not offer us salvation: Black can just take back with the b-pawn. Therefore, we take in the Ruy Lopez set-up with c3 and d4. }
5... g6
{ Naturally, now that White chose for a 'timid' set-up with d3. Black is striving for moving the bishop on g7 where it is better placed than on e7. }
6. d4
{ Again pushing the d-pawn forward?? Hold your horses! Albeit, on the one hand, we spend precious time in the opening moving twice with the same piece, the time is ripe to attack Black in the center as he is undeveloped. }
6... Bd7 7. d5
{ This is part of White's plan, exchanging the d7-bishop and gaining space on the queenside. In the resulting positions, Black has to play King's Indian alike positions, but without his light-squared bishop; we took the sting out of his play. }
7... Nb8
{ Black clearly intends to take the bishop back by the b8-knight. On d7 the knight stops the c-pawn advance. }
8. Bxd7+ Nbxd7
{ Can we say that the knight is better placed on d7 than on e7? Probably, although it takes time for Black. }
9. Re1
{ The central pawn needs protection, and, ideally, we take in the position with c2-c4 and only then Nc3. }
9... Bg7
{ In case of  9...Be7  we can quite easily get the upper hand by  10.c4  O-O  11.Bh6  Re8  12.Nc3  a5  13.h3  Nc5  14.b3  leaves White with the preferable position.  White is about to gain space on the queenside by a3 and b4.0-1 @@StartBracket@@43@@EndBracket@@ Szabo,K @@StartBracket@@2540@@EndBracket@@-Dumitrache,D  @@StartBracket@@2446@@EndBracket@@ Baia Sprie 2012. }
10. c4 O-O 11. Nc3
{ Both sides develop aiming to enhance their initiative on the side on which they are better. }
11... Nh5 12. Be3
{ Keeping an eye on c5, endorsing the break c4-c5, at the same time helping the defense. }
12... h6 13. Nd2 Nf4
{ In Parligras,M @@StartBracket@@2581@@EndBracket@@-Lupulescu,C @@StartBracket@@2635@@EndBracket@@ Iasi 2015, 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@13@@EndBracket@@, the Romanian GM's consented on a gentleman's agreement. Kosintseva and Zhao however showed good fighting spirit after... }
14. Qc2
{ The knight could become a nuisance and should be kicked out with g2-g3. First White should avoid any knight jumps to d3. }
14... f5
{ 0-1 @@StartBracket@@49@@EndBracket@@ Kosintseva,T @@StartBracket@@2496@@EndBracket@@-Zhao,X @@StartBracket@@2568@@EndBracket@@ Beijing 2013 }
15. exf5
{ Please notice that after  15.g3  Black can develop a dangerous assault on our king.  15...Nh3+  16.Kg2  f4!  17.Kxh3  fxe3  18.fxe3  h5!  There were more interesting options, but I believe activating the bishop with Bh6 is the most thematic.  19.Kg2  Bh6⇆  . }
15... Rxf5
{ Black gives up on the e4-square. An omission that doesn't go unnoticed to you, dear reader! }
16. g3 Nh3+ 17. Kg2
{ The King is the perfect defender: guarding f2, meanwhile hitting the h3-knight. }
17... Nf4+ 18. Kh1
{ Walking away from the checks. In fact, we never intended to take on f4. Instead, we want to get full grip on the light squares around the king, gradually solidifying our position.   18.gxf4?  is only helping Black on the account of  18...exf4  . Here White is suffering because of his exposed king. }
18... Nh3 19. Nde4
{ Or  19.f3  , regaining the control over the light squares would also favour White. The full control of the blockading square e4 gives White the superior chances. }
