{ Losing a move, but a necessary evil in order to drive off the c5-knight with b4.   12.a3?!  this is too hasty, as Black can fix our b-pawn.  12...a4⩱  . }
12... O-O 13. a3
{ Nothing can stop us now: after Rb1 we finally come to our beloved b3-b4. }
13... Nh5
{ This move was tried by German IM Christian Seel against Dutch GM Jan Smeets. }
14. Rb1 { Ready for action! b3-b4 will certainly be good for us! } 14... Nf4
15. Be3 { An useful move while defusing Nd3. } 15... Qd7
{ 15...Ncd3  won't do any harm, because of  16.Rf1!  Black can't keep his knights on these active squares.  16...Qd7  17.g3  Qg4  18.Kh1  Our strategy pays off now:  Black has to retreat to h5 after we can enjoy our structural edge. }
16. Bxc5
{ Smeets is shifting gears, no longer trying to push the pawns on the queenside but pointing his arrows on the kingside. }
16... dxc5 17. Ne2
{ The knight on f4 is on White's to-do-list. In other words, it has to be expelled. }
17... Rfe8 18. Qc2 { Preparing for Nxf4 and - eventually - e4-e5. } 18... Nh5
{ Black retreats, but } 19. Nc1
{ Here, gradually, in King's Indian style, White starts operating in a strategic fashion. The white knight is best placed on d3 - keeping an eye on e5 and eventually preparing for the pawn break with b3-b4. }
19... Nf4 { This is an unwelcome guest! } 20. Ne2
{ On the top of the priority list of Smeets was to fight the f4-knight. } 20...
Nh5 21. g3
{ White doesn't mind putting his pawns on the color of the bishop of the opponent. On the contrary, in this way its mobility is maximally restricted. }
21... Qh3 22. Kh1 { Aiming for Ne2-g1, to drive off the queen. } 22... h6
{ 22...Nf4?!  23.Nxf4!  exf4  24.e5  when White takes the lead in the center. }
23. Nfg1
{ White's strategy consists of driving averting the threats and dominant enemy's pieces, then the slowly manoeuvring of the pieces to the optimal squares. }
23... Qd7 24. Nc1 { Finally the knight is about to reach its destination: d3. }
24... f5 25. Nd3
{ The knight is perfectly placed as it is hitting the central point e5. } 25...
b6 26. Nf3 Qd6
{ 26...c6!?  Probably Black's best chance in the entire game. Our center is under attack and it won't be easy to glue it together. }
27. Nd2 f4 28. Qd1
{ Smeets fights his way into Black's position through the weakened light squares. }
28... Rf8 29. Qg4
{ White's position improved considerably here. There are several plans available, such as hitting g6 by Rg1 and , evt. gxf4. }
29... Kh7 30. Qh3
{ The queen is perfectly placed here on the diagonal and h-file. Black has to cope with the opening of the g-file, subsequently an attack on his king. }
30... a4
{ Here, White could have rewarded himself instantly by launching an assault on the enemy's king. }
31. g4
{ 31.b4  cxb4  32.Rxb4  was only a slightly better in Smeets, J @@StartBracket@@2609@@EndBracket@@ - Seel, C @@StartBracket@@2472@@EndBracket@@ Netherlands 2013, 1-0 @@StartBracket@@83@@EndBracket@@. }
31... Nf6 32. g5
{ The point! The g-file will be opened for the rook, while the f3-knight will attack e5 additionally aiming for Nd2-f3-g5-e6. }
32... Nh5 33. gxh6 { Opening the g-file. } 33... Bxh6 34. Nf3
{ Let's cease our undertakings here. Positionally speaking, White obtained an overwhelming advantage and he has an easy plan to conduct: the doubling of the rooks on the g-file after which both e5 as g5 seem to be indefensible.   34...axb3   34...Rae8  35.bxa4  +-  35.Rg1  Obviously, White could take back the pawn. However, this continuation is even more direct and winning.   35.Ndxe5!?  is also winning.  35...Rxa3  36.Ndxe5  Like a house of cards, our adversary's position collapses.  Rg8  37.Nxg6  Rxg6  38.Qxh5  and the score sheets could have been signed. }
