[White "4...d6 5.O-O Bd7"]
[Black "Introduction: 4...d6 5.O-O Bd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 d6
{ In the early phase of the creation of this course, it was my sole intention to create a Bxc6-repertoire against the Ruy Lopez and the Berlin Wall, and it went beyond the scope to cover all the sidelines after 5.O-O. Nevertheless, along the way I got inspired by all the astonishing plans and variations available for White here, resulting in a complete repertoire against all of Black's main responses after 3.Bb5. }
5. O-O
{ Here our plan of taking on c6 will not deliver us the so desired opening advantage: Black can just take back with the b-pawn. Therefore, we are going to take in the Ruy Lopez set-up with c3 and d4. }
5... Bd7 6. Re1
{ The ensuing positions arising resemble a lot to the next chapters, after @@StartBracket@@5... Be7@@EndBracket@@.   However the positions are resembling a lot, the difference between them can be marked by the position of the bishop on d7, since in these chapters Black is not urged to and frequently refrains from this move in the further course of the game. }
6... Be7 7. c3
{ The commonly used set-up in these Ruy Lopez systems, making a bishop retreat to c2 possible and - eventually - supporting the push of the d-pawn. }
7... O-O 8. h3
{ This small move is standard here, taking away the square of  g4  from black's pieces. Black has 3 main options here:  8...a6  ,  8...h6  , and  8...Re8 }
8... a6
{ 8...Re8  Played by Vachier Lagrave, Naiditsch and plenty of other grandmasters, this move is currently quite popular on top level.  9.a4!?  Caruana grabs space and makes the path clear for the bishop to the long a2-g8 diagonal.  9...Bf8  10.Bg5  This is an idea which is applied frequently in the Giuoco Piano lines. The bishop ends up on g3.  10...h6  11.Bh4  g5  At the end of the day, Black should get rid of the pin.  12.Bg3  Ne7  This is part of White's strategy. By keeping his bishop on b5, he awaits until the moment arises to exchange the strong light-squared bishop of Black.  13.Bxd7  Qxd7  14.Nbd2⩲  Simple and strong! The knight is on its way to f5. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@42@@EndBracket@@ Caruana,F @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@-Naiditsch,A @@StartBracket@@2701@@EndBracket@@ Karlsruhe/Baden-Baden 2018   8...h6  with this move Black mostly adheres to the strategy of move the knight to h7, exchanging the black squared bishops or push f7-f5. It is these plans I will put focus on in the ensuing lines.  9.Nbd2  Black can play Nh7 here, or postpone this move with a6, and possibly, b5.  9...a6   9...Nh7!?  10.a4!?  This is a novelty. The idea is to gain ground on the queenside, since we can encounter the break f7-f5 in the center, meanwhile preparing d3-d4 without bothering about the earlier seen tactic Nc6xd4.  10...f5  11.d4!  We engage on the central point e5.  11...fxe4  12.Bc4+!  With the aim to deprive Black of d6-d5.  12...Kh8  13.Nxe4  with an initiative for White.  10.Ba4  Nh7   10...Qe8  Black is going for a 'cheapo', or 'an easy tactical shot' winning a pawn with Nxd4, Bxd7 and Nxf3+.  11.Bb3  Nh7  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@22@@EndBracket@@ Efimenko,Z @@StartBracket@@2652@@EndBracket@@ -Shyam,S @@StartBracket@@2492@@EndBracket@@ Konya 2015  12.Nc4!  The knight is heading to d5, in the meantime keeping an eye on g5, hindering black's main maneuver Nh7-g5.  12...b5  13.Ne3⩲  11.d4!  Before that Black gets the chance to exchange a pair of minor pieces by Ng5, we strike in the center.  11...Bf6  12.Nf1  Executing the particular Ruy-Lopez knight maneuver to g3.  12...Ng5  13.Bxg5!  This strong move is aiming for the control on the light squares, meanwhile walling in the bishop on f6 behind his own pawn on black @@StartBracket@@g5 and e5@@EndBracket@@.  13...hxg5  This doubled pawn can be considered a weakness.  Black is losing a pawn after   13...Bxg5  14.Bxc6  14.Ne3⩲ }
9. Ba4
{ 9.Bc4?  can't be advised, because of  9...Na5!  when White will be deprived of his strong bishop. }
9... b5 10. Bc2
{ The resulting positions resemble a lot to the ones in the next chapter, with the difference that the bishop is on d7 here. }
10... Re8 11. Nbd2
{ Naturally, in line with the main Ruy-Lopez strategy, the knight should first be employed. }
11... Bf8 12. Nf1
{ We can our deploy our knight on g3, to protect e4 and be able to launch an attack, or on e3 from where the knight can be additionally deployed on d5. }
12... h6 13. d4
{ We reached a position in which our opponent has to show his colors. His 3 main options are  13...Na5  ,  13...a5  , or  13...g6 }
13... g6
{ 13...a5  14.a4  I'd rather not allow our opponent to gain more ground on the queenside.  14...b4  15.d5!?  Nb8  16.cxb4  With the aim of creating a passed a-pawn.  16...axb4  17.N3d2  N  Maybe even stronger than the move played by Adams.  17...c6  18.Nc4  The knight is heading to b6.  18...cxd5  19.exd5⩲   13...Na5  14.b3  Not allowing the knight to c4.  14...c5  15.d5⩲  I'd rather keep the knight out of the game on b5 or b7, instead of allowing him to c6, successively to e7 and g6. }
14. Ng3 { The Ruy-Lopez knight reached it destination! } 14... Na5
{ 14...Bg7  Another popular line for Black.  15.Be3  Qe7  16.Qd2⩲ } 15. b3
{ Keeping the knight from c4. } 15... c5
{ 15...Bg7  16.Be3  Nb7  17.Qd2  Kh7  18.a4  c5  1-0 @@StartBracket@@50@@EndBracket@@ Puranik,A @@StartBracket@@2443@@EndBracket@@ -Dimakiling,O @@StartBracket@@2372@@EndBracket@@ Olongapo City 2015  19.b4!?  This is an improvement over the game, isolating the knight on b7. White is simply better here. }
16. d5 { In order to gain space and to give the a5-knight inferior prospects. }
16... Bg7 17. Be3
{ Completing the development, keeping from e3 an eye on the queen- and kingside, connecting the rooks. }
17... Nh7
{ 17...Kh7  18.Bd3  c4  19.Be2  Qc7  20.b4  Nb7  21.a4!  bxa4  22.Nd2⩲  1-0 @@StartBracket@@56@@EndBracket@@ Palladino,M @@StartBracket@@2141@@EndBracket@@-Schneider,H @@StartBracket@@2157@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2012 }
18. Qd2
{ Provoking h6-h5, after which the squares g5 and h6 are available for our pieces. }
18... h5 19. Ng5
{ We are following the game of Kasimdhzhanov against Sokolov here. I deem the further course of the game as natural. Obviously, both sides could deviate in such a closed positions from this stem game. }
19... Nb7
{ 19...Nxg5  20.Bxg5  Black is not eager to weaken his kingside further, by allowing f7-f6.  20...Bf6  21.Be3  Avoiding the exchange, in order not to lose grip on the black squares.  21...Bg7  22.Rf1  Aiming an attack with f2-f4.  22...Nb7  23.Ne2  Black took all the available squares @@StartBracket@@i.e. h5 and f5@@EndBracket@@, so the rerouting will improve its mobility. }
20. Rf1 { Kasimdhzanov is getting ready for f2-f4. } 20... Nxg5 21. Bxg5 Qa5
{ Hindering f2-f4, since the pawn on c3 would be hanging. } 22. Kh1
{ One more prophylactic move, before opening the position. } 22... Rf8 23. Bd1
{ Provoking another weakening of our adversary's kingside. Please see for more detailed analysis the model game section. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@48@@EndBracket@@ Kasimdzhanov,R @@StartBracket@@2653@@EndBracket@@-Sokolov,I @@StartBracket@@2684@@EndBracket@@ Pamplona 2002. }
