7... O-O 8. h3
{ This small move is standard here, taking away the g4-square from Black's pieces. Black has 3 main options here: @@StartBracket@@1@@EndBracket@@  8...a6  , @@StartBracket@@2@@EndBracket@@  8...h6  , and @@StartBracket@@3@@EndBracket@@  8...Re8  .   The move  8.d4  doesn't really yield us anything, because of  8...Nxd4  9.Nxd4  exd4  10.Bxd7  Qxd7  11.cxd4  d5!  Black is well prepared for this counterstrike in the center.  12.e5  Ne8  13.Nc3  c6  14.Re3  g6⇆  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@24@@EndBracket@@ Georgiadis,N @@StartBracket@@2516@@EndBracket@@-Mastrovasilis,A @@StartBracket@@2488@@EndBracket@@ Heraklion 2017   Or  14...f6⇆ }
8... a6 9. Ba4
{ 9.Bc4?  can't be advised, because of  9...Na5!  when White will be deprived of his strong bishop. }
9... b5 { 9...h6  transposes to the variation 8...h6 after  10.Nbd2  . } 10.
Bc2
{ The resulting positions resemble the ones in the next chapter, with the difference that the bishop is on d7 here. }
10... Re8 11. Nbd2
{ Naturally, in line with the main Ruy Lopez strategy, the knight should first be employed. }
11... Bf8 12. Nf1
{ We can deploy our knight on g3, to protect e4 and be able to launch an attack, or on e3 from where the knight can be additionally deployed on d5. }
12... h6 13. d4
{ We reached a position in which our opponent has to show his colours. His 3 main options are @@StartBracket@@1@@EndBracket@@  13...Na5  , @@StartBracket@@2@@EndBracket@@  13...a5  , or @@StartBracket@@3@@EndBracket@@  13...g6  . }
13... a5 14. a4
{ I'd rather not allow our opponent to gain more ground on the queenside. For instance,  14.Ng3  a4!?  15.Bd2  Qc8  16.Bd3  Qb7⇆  0-1 @@StartBracket@@113@@EndBracket@@ Polgar,J @@StartBracket@@2682@@EndBracket@@-Nakamura,H @@StartBracket@@2733@@EndBracket@@ Cap d'Agde 2010 }
14... b4 15. d5
{ Of course,  15.Ng3  would have been quite playable too.  15...bxc3  16.bxc3  exd4  17.cxd4  Nb4  18.Bb1  c5  19.Bb2  With a double-edged position in: Vaishali-Kunte 2019 @@StartBracket@@0-1@@EndBracket@@. }
15... Nb8 { 15...Ne7  16.Ne3  c6  17.c4⩲  . } 16. cxb4
{ With the aim of creating a passed a-pawn. } 16... axb4 17. N3d2
{ Maybe even stronger than the move played by Adams.   17.Bd2!?  Na6  18.Ng3  c6  19.dxc6  Bxc6  20.Be3  Adams is taking counter-measures against d6-d5, placing his pieces optimally. Besides, he stops Na6-c5 for the moment.  20...d5  21.exd5  Bxd5  22.Bb3  e4  23.Nd2  and we reached a position which Michael Adams was aiming for. As a Ruy Lopez specialist, he knows perfectly well how to play these types of positions. Adams, M @@StartBracket@@2712@@EndBracket@@ - Jumabayev,R @@StartBracket@@2605@@EndBracket@@ Batumi 2018 1-0 @@StartBracket@@49@@EndBracket@@. }
17... c6 18. Nc4 { The knight is heading to b6. } 18... cxd5 19. exd5 Qc7 20.
Nfe3
{ The configuration of the pieces is excellent. The knights - protecting each other - control a lot of central squares. }
20... Na6 21. a5
{ The knight on b6 will be invincible: White managed to gain the upper hand. }
*

