{ This small move is standard here, taking away the g4-square from Black's pieces. Black has 3 main options here: @@StartBracket@@1@@EndBracket@@  8...a6  , @@StartBracket@@2@@EndBracket@@  8...h6  , and @@StartBracket@@3@@EndBracket@@  8...Re8  .   The move  8.d4  doesn't really yield us anything, because of  8...Nxd4  9.Nxd4  exd4  10.Bxd7  Qxd7  11.cxd4  d5!  Black is well prepared for this counterstrike in the center.  12.e5  Ne8  13.Nc3  c6  14.Re3  g6⇆  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@24@@EndBracket@@ Georgiadis,N @@StartBracket@@2516@@EndBracket@@-Mastrovasilis,A @@StartBracket@@2488@@EndBracket@@ Heraklion 2017   Or  14...f6⇆ }
8... a6 9. Ba4
{ 9.Bc4?  can't be advised, because of  9...Na5!  when White will be deprived of his strong bishop. }
9... b5 { 9...h6  transposes to the variation 8...h6 after  10.Nbd2  . } 10.
Bc2
{ The resulting positions resemble the ones in the next chapter, with the difference that the bishop is on d7 here. }
10... Re8 11. Nbd2
{ Naturally, in line with the main Ruy Lopez strategy, the knight should first be employed. }
11... Bf8 12. Nf1
{ We can deploy our knight on g3, to protect e4 and be able to launch an attack, or on e3 from where the knight can be additionally deployed on d5. }
12... h6 13. d4
{ We reached a position in which our opponent has to show his colours. His 3 main options are @@StartBracket@@1@@EndBracket@@  13...Na5  , @@StartBracket@@2@@EndBracket@@  13...a5  , or @@StartBracket@@3@@EndBracket@@  13...g6  . }
13... Na5 14. b3 { Not allowing the knight to c4. } 14... c5 15. d5
{ I'd rather keep the knight out of the game on b5 or b7, instead of allowing him to c6, successively to e7 and g6.   15.Ng3  Nc6  16.d5!?   16.Be3?!  cxd4!  17.cxd4  exd4  18.Nxd4  d5!  with counterplay. 1/ 2 @@StartBracket@@20@@EndBracket@@-1/2 @@StartBracket@@20@@EndBracket@@ Van Kampen,R @@StartBracket@@2609@@EndBracket@@-Ernst,S @@StartBracket@@2545@@EndBracket@@ Amsterdam 2015  16...Ne7  This is quite a popular line for Black, tried out by Nikolic and Sokolov.  17.a4  Ng6  18.Be3  Nh7  0-1 @@StartBracket@@91@@EndBracket@@ Cheparinov,I @@StartBracket@@2657@@EndBracket@@-Nikolic,P @@StartBracket@@2646@@EndBracket@@ Amsterdam 2007  19.b4⩲ }
15... Nb7 16. Be3
{ Just improving our pieces, we await the further course of events.   Also interesting is  16.Ne3  g6  17.Nh2  Bg7  18.Nhg4→  1-0 @@StartBracket@@38@@EndBracket@@ Papp,G @@StartBracket@@2482@@EndBracket@@-Lukacs,P @@StartBracket@@2412@@EndBracket@@ Hungary 2006 }
16... g6
{ I think we have to flip coins: shall we aim our arrows at the queen- or kingside? It's seductive to go for the kingside after the slightly weakening g7-g6. }
17. Qd2
{ Of course, there are several plans to follow, like b4 or a4, but I am charmed by this expansion on the kingside. }
17... Kh7 18. g4
{ Here, I deem White's chances preferable. White could try to bring his rooks to the kingside @@StartBracket@@i.e., the g-file@@EndBracket@@ and, in due time, aim for Ng3-f5. }
