[White "4...d6 5.O-O Bd7"]
[Black "4...d6 5.O-O Bd7 6.Re1 Be7 7.c3 O-O 8.h3 a6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ This variation - after 3... Nf6 - is called the 'Berlin Defense' or the 'Berlin Wall', due to its supersolid nature. Rooted in the family of the Ruy Lopez opening @@StartBracket@@i.e. 3.Bb5@@EndBracket@@, the Berlin Defense was first seen in practice since 1801, and examined by @@StartBracket@@it's in the name - who else?@@EndBracket@@ Berliners, as recorded in history. }
4. d3
{ With this move we set foot into the 'Anti-Berlin'. Keeping the queens on the board for the moment, we are sidestepping the forced lines arising after 4..Nxe4, amongst others the supersolid ending c.q. the 'Berlin Wall', deployed 4 times by Kramnik against Kasparov with great success in the World Championship Match @@StartBracket@@London, 2000@@EndBracket@@. }
4... d6
{ In the early phase of the creation of this course, it was my sole intention to create a Bxc6-repertoire against the Ruy Lopez and the Berlin Wall, and it went beyond the scope to cover all the sidelines after 4. d3 d6 5.0-0. Nevertheless, along the way I got inspired by all the astonishing plans and variations available for White here, resulting in a complete repertoire against all of Black's main responses after 3.Bb5. }
5. O-O
{ Here our plan of taking on c6 will not deliver us the so desired opening advantage: Black can just take back with the b-pawn. Therefore, we switch to a Ruy Lopez set-up with c3 and d4. }
5... Bd7 { We can reach a transposition to the 4.d3 d6 5.O-O g6 line. } 6. Re1
{ The ensuing positions are very similar to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/2np1n2/1B2p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Be7  , as covered in the next chapters.  Though the positions resemble each other a lot, the difference between them can be marked by the position of the bishop on d7, since in these chapters Black is not urged to and frequently refrains from this move in the further course of the game.   In case of  6.d4  Black can transpose into the lines arising after  6...g6  @@StartBracket@@4...d6 Fianchetto Variation: 5.O-O g6@@EndBracket@@, or choose for another quite plausible option, like taking on d4:   @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pppb1ppp/2np1n2/1B2p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nxd4  7.Bxd7+  Qxd7  8.Nxd4  exd4  9.Qxd4  Be7  10.c4  O-O  11.Nc3  Qe6  12.f3  Nd7  13.b3  Bf6  when Black managed to get an equal position. }
6... Be7
{ 6...g6  7.d4  Bg7  8.d5  is another transposition to the aforementioned line. }
7. c3
{ The commonly used set-up in these Ruy Lopez systems, making a bishop retreat to c2 possible and - eventually - supporting the push of the d-pawn. }
