{ This small move is standard here, taking away the g4-square from Black's pieces. Black has 3 main options here: @@StartBracket@@1@@EndBracket@@  8...a6  , @@StartBracket@@2@@EndBracket@@  8...h6  , and @@StartBracket@@3@@EndBracket@@  8...Re8  .   The move  8.d4  doesn't really yield us anything, because of  8...Nxd4  9.Nxd4  exd4  10.Bxd7  Qxd7  11.cxd4  d5!  Black is well prepared for this counterstrike in the center.  12.e5  Ne8  13.Nc3  c6  14.Re3  g6⇆  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@24@@EndBracket@@ Georgiadis,N @@StartBracket@@2516@@EndBracket@@-Mastrovasilis,A @@StartBracket@@2488@@EndBracket@@ Heraklion 2017   Or  14...f6⇆ }
8... a6 9. Ba4
{ 9.Bc4?  can't be advised, because of  9...Na5!  when White will be deprived of his strong bishop. }
9... b5 { 9...h6  transposes to the variation 8...h6 after  10.Nbd2  . } 10.
Bc2
{ The resulting positions resemble the ones in the next chapter, with the difference that the bishop is on d7 here. }
10... Re8 11. Nbd2
{ Naturally, in line with the main Ruy Lopez strategy, the knight should first be employed. }
11... Bf8 12. Nf1
{ We can deploy our knight on g3, to protect e4 and be able to launch an attack, or on e3 from where the knight can be additionally deployed on d5. }
12... h6 13. d4
{ We reached a position in which our opponent has to show his colours. His 3 main options are @@StartBracket@@1@@EndBracket@@  13...Na5  , @@StartBracket@@2@@EndBracket@@  13...a5  , or @@StartBracket@@3@@EndBracket@@  13...g6  . }
13... g6 14. Ng3 { The Ruy-Lopez knight reached it destination! } 14... Bg7
{ Another popular line for Black. } 15. Be3
{ Also interesting is  15.d5  Ne7  16.b3  c5  17.a4  Nh7  18.Nh2  Rf8  19.Ra2⩲  preparing for the doubling of the rooks along the a-file. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@64@@EndBracket@@ Leko,P @@StartBracket@@2707@@EndBracket@@-Kryvoruchko,Y @@StartBracket@@2710@@EndBracket@@ Berlin 2015. }
15... Qe7 16. Qd2
{ Black as to make a difficult choice: will he protect or move the pawn? In case of the latter option, I would like to refer you to the stem game Kasimdzhanov-Sokolov @@StartBracket@@1-0@@EndBracket@@. }
16... Kh7 17. Rad1
{ An interesting new idea could be  17.Nh2!?  Preparing for f2-f4.  17...Rad8  18.f4  White obtained a small advantage. }
17... Rad8 18. Qc1
{ Likewise, White moves the queen from the lines of the rooks. } 18... Qf8 19.
b3
{ Meanwhile, White's mobilized pieces are ready for any hostile action in the center, White slowly tries to build up an initiative on the queenside. }
19... d5 20. dxe5
{ The pawn structure and with it, the characteristic of the position are changing drastically. In this open position, White pursues a dark-squared strategy. }
20... Nxe4 21. Bxe4
{ White feels that he can gain the upper hand on the dark squares. The knight will be excellently placed on e4, looking at both f6 and c5. }
21... dxe4 22. Nxe4
{ Evidently, numerous dark squares can't be given the protection required @@StartBracket@@i.e. c5, f6 and h6@@EndBracket@@. }
22... Nxe5 23. Nxe5
{ It seems that Black doesn't sense the danger, taking back with the bishop. In case of  23...Rxe5  24.Bf4  , the position seems again highly inconvenient for Black. }
23... Bxe5 24. Bf4
{ Challenging all of the weak points on the dark squares. First and foremost, taking on e5, followed by Nf6+, is a huge threat to be dealt with.   After  24.Bd4!?  , likewise challenging the dark squares, would also have led to a comfortable position. }
24... Qg7 25. Bxe5 { In case of } 25... Rxe5 26. Qf4
{ The ordeal is not yet over. White's threat of 26.Nf6+, subsequently taking on e5, can hardly be parried. }
26... f5 27. Nf6+ *

