18... h5 19. Ng5
{ We are following the game of Kasimdhzhanov against Sokolov here. I deem the further course of the game as natural. Obviously, both sides could deviate in such a closed positions from this stem game. }
19... Nxg5 20. Bxg5
{ Black is not eager to weaken his kingside further, by allowing f7-f6. } 20...
Bf6 21. Be3
{ Avoiding the exchange, in order not to lose grip on the dark squares. } 21...
Bg7 22. Rf1
{ Aiming for an attack with f2-f4.   Another way of playing:  22.Nf1  Rerouting the knight to more fertile soil.  22...Qc7  23.Nh2  23...Nb7  Once f4, exf4 is played, the knight on f3 is controlling e5.  24.Bh6  Bh8  25.Rf1  a5  0-1 @@StartBracket@@56@@EndBracket@@ Tseshkovsky,V @@StartBracket@@2560@@EndBracket@@ -Geller,E @@StartBracket@@2550@@EndBracket@@ Minsk 1979  26.f4!  exf4  27.Qxf4  and the pressure on f7 is highly inconvenient for Black. }
