{ Black took all the available squares @@StartBracket@@i.e., h5 and f5@@EndBracket@@, so the rerouting will improve its mobility. }
23... Qe7 24. f4
{ This opening of the position is good here, because of the poor placed knight on b7. Imagine it would reach d7 and e5 @@StartBracket@@e.g. via Nc6-a5-c4-b6-d7-e5@@EndBracket@@, Black would be better. }
24... exf4 25. Rxf4
{ As we can see, Black's pawn structure is quite OK, as he controls e5, and c3 could become weak@@StartBracket@@er@@EndBracket@@. Nonetheless, White is slightly better here because of the poor position of the b7-knight. Our target is the f7-point, doubling the rooks.   For example,  25.Rxf4  Rf8  26.Raf1  Rae8  27.R4f3  White is on top here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4...d6 5.O-O Bd7"]
[Black "4...d6 5.O-O Bd7 6.Re1 Be7 7.c3 O-O 8.h3 a6 #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ This variation - after 3... Nf6 - is called the 'Berlin Defense' or the 'Berlin Wall', due to its supersolid nature. Rooted in the family of the Ruy Lopez opening @@StartBracket@@i.e. 3.Bb5@@EndBracket@@, the Berlin Defense was first seen in practice since 1801, and examined by @@StartBracket@@it's in the name - who else?@@EndBracket@@ Berliners, as recorded in history. }
4. d3
{ With this move we set foot into the 'Anti-Berlin'. Keeping the queens on the board for the moment, we are sidestepping the forced lines arising after 4..Nxe4, amongst others the supersolid ending c.q. the 'Berlin Wall', deployed 4 times by Kramnik against Kasparov with great success in the World Championship Match @@StartBracket@@London, 2000@@EndBracket@@. }
4... d6
{ In the early phase of the creation of this course, it was my sole intention to create a Bxc6-repertoire against the Ruy Lopez and the Berlin Wall, and it went beyond the scope to cover all the sidelines after 4. d3 d6 5.0-0. Nevertheless, along the way I got inspired by all the astonishing plans and variations available for White here, resulting in a complete repertoire against all of Black's main responses after 3.Bb5. }
5. O-O
{ Here our plan of taking on c6 will not deliver us the so desired opening advantage: Black can just take back with the b-pawn. Therefore, we switch to a Ruy Lopez set-up with c3 and d4. }
5... Bd7 { We can reach a transposition to the 4.d3 d6 5.O-O g6 line. } 6. Re1
{ The ensuing positions are very similar to @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/2np1n2/1B2p3/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Be7  , as covered in the next chapters.  Though the positions resemble each other a lot, the difference between them can be marked by the position of the bishop on d7, since in these chapters Black is not urged to and frequently refrains from this move in the further course of the game.   In case of  6.d4  Black can transpose into the lines arising after  6...g6  @@StartBracket@@4...d6 Fianchetto Variation: 5.O-O g6@@EndBracket@@, or choose for another quite plausible option, like taking on d4:   @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pppb1ppp/2np1n2/1B2p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nxd4  7.Bxd7+  Qxd7  8.Nxd4  exd4  9.Qxd4  Be7  10.c4  O-O  11.Nc3  Qe6  12.f3  Nd7  13.b3  Bf6  when Black managed to get an equal position. }
6... Be7
{ 6...g6  7.d4  Bg7  8.d5  is another transposition to the aforementioned line. }
7. c3
{ The commonly used set-up in these Ruy Lopez systems, making a bishop retreat to c2 possible and - eventually - supporting the push of the d-pawn. }
7... O-O 8. h3
{ This small move is standard here, taking away the g4-square from Black's pieces. Black has 3 main options here: @@StartBracket@@1@@EndBracket@@  8...a6  , @@StartBracket@@2@@EndBracket@@  8...h6  , and @@StartBracket@@3@@EndBracket@@  8...Re8  .   The move  8.d4  doesn't really yield us anything, because of  8...Nxd4  9.Nxd4  exd4  10.Bxd7  Qxd7  11.cxd4  d5!  Black is well prepared for this counterstrike in the center.  12.e5  Ne8  13.Nc3  c6  14.Re3  g6⇆  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@24@@EndBracket@@ Georgiadis,N @@StartBracket@@2516@@EndBracket@@-Mastrovasilis,A @@StartBracket@@2488@@EndBracket@@ Heraklion 2017   Or  14...f6⇆ }
8... a6 9. Ba4
{ 9.Bc4?  can't be advised, because of  9...Na5!  when White will be deprived of his strong bishop. }
9... b5 { 9...h6  transposes to the variation 8...h6 after  10.Nbd2  . } 10.
Bc2
{ The resulting positions resemble the ones in the next chapter, with the difference that the bishop is on d7 here. }
10... Re8 11. Nbd2
{ Naturally, in line with the main Ruy Lopez strategy, the knight should first be employed. }
11... Bf8 12. Nf1
{ We can deploy our knight on g3, to protect e4 and be able to launch an attack, or on e3 from where the knight can be additionally deployed on d5. }
12... h6 13. d4
{ We reached a position in which our opponent has to show his colours. His 3 main options are @@StartBracket@@1@@EndBracket@@  13...Na5  , @@StartBracket@@2@@EndBracket@@  13...a5  , or @@StartBracket@@3@@EndBracket@@  13...g6  . }
13... g6 14. Ng3 { The Ruy-Lopez knight reached it destination! } 14... Na5 15.
b3 { Keeping the knight from c4. } 15... c5
{ 15...Bg7  16.Be3  Nb7  17.Qd2  Kh7  18.a4  c5  1-0 @@StartBracket@@50@@EndBracket@@ Puranik,A @@StartBracket@@2443@@EndBracket@@-Dimakiling,O @@StartBracket@@2372@@EndBracket@@ Olongapo City 2015  19.b4!?  This is an improvement over the game, isolating the knight on b7. White is simply better here. }
16. d5 { In order to gain space and to give the a5-knight inferior prospects. }
16... Bg7 17. Be3
{ Completing the development, keeping from e3 an eye on the queen- and kingside, connecting the rooks. }
17... Nh7
{ 17...Kh7  18.Bd3  c4  19.Be2  Qc7  20.b4  Nb7  21.a4  bxa4  22.Nd2  Bb5  23.Nb1  Ng8  24.Qc2  Rf8  25.Na3  Ne7  26.Nf1⩲  1-0 @@StartBracket@@56@@EndBracket@@ Palladino,M @@StartBracket@@2141@@EndBracket@@-Schneider,H @@StartBracket@@2157@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2012 }
18. Qd2
{ Provoking h6-h5, after which the squares g5 and h6 are available for our pieces. }
18... h5 19. Ng5
{ We are following the game of Kasimdhzhanov against Sokolov here. I deem the further course of the game as natural. Obviously, both sides could deviate in such a closed positions from this stem game. }
19... Nb7 20. Rf1 { Kasimdhzanov is getting ready for f2-f4. } 20... Nxg5 21.
Bxg5 Qa5 { Hindering f2-f4, since the pawn on c3 would be hanging. } 22. Kh1
{ One more prophylactic move, before opening the position. } 22... Rf8 23. Bd1
{ Provoking another weakening of our adversary's kingside. } 23... Qc7 24. Bxh5
{ This sacrifice is bulletproof. } 24... gxh5 25. Nxh5
{ It strikes me that in many of those lines the knight on b7 is badly placed. White has the free hand for his attack on the kingside. }
25... f6 26. Bh6 Bxh6 27. Qxh6 Be8 28. Nxf6+
{ Along the road, White won just too much material. } *

