{ Returned to the base on c2, having provoked and aiming at the weakness of g6. White's positional threat is to play f2-f4, after which the bishop manoeuvre proved its value. }
25... Nd8
{ 25...f5  loses a pawn to  26.exf5  gxf5  27.Bh6!   27.Nxh5  f4⇆  is not so clear yet.  27...f4  28.Bxg7  Kxg7  29.Qd3  White is winning. }
26. a4 { opening a second front, now that Black focussed on the kingside. }
26... b4
{ 26...bxa4  27.b4  Qc7  28.bxc5  dxc5  29.Bxa4±  Black can't hold his position together. }
27. cxb4
{ Undoubtedly, former FIDE World Champion Kasimdhzanov pointed his eagle eye on b4. }
27... Qxb4 28. Qxb4
{ Especially after the queen's exchange, the black queenside pawns fall prey to white's pieces. }
28... cxb4 29. Bd3
{ Black has no counterplay at all and his queenside pawns will fall very shortly. }
