[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4...d6 5.O-O Be7 Main Line 8...b5"]
[Black "Introduction: 4...d6 5.O-O Be7 Main Line 8...b5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 d6 5. O-O Be7 6. c3 O-O
{ 6...a6  7.Ba4  O-O  8.Re1  is a transposition to our main line. } 7. Re1
{ White supports the central pawn on e4, in order to play a future d3-d4. Besides, the f1-square is vacated for the knight-maneuver @@StartBracket@@Nb1-d2-f1-g3/e3@@EndBracket@@. }
7... a6 8. Ba4
{ Our opponent has to make an important decision. Will he play  8...b5  and  9... d5 or  8...Re8  with the idea of moving the bishop to f8. }
8... b5 9. Bc2
{ In the next lines we deal with Black's response of 9... d5 in the center. Please have a look at all the other lines, such as Bb7, Re8, h6 & g6, in the next chapters. }
9... d5 10. Nbd2 dxe4
{ 10...d4  11.h3  According to my research, this move - stopping Bc8-g4, is essential in the struggle for an advantage. Moreover, White doesn't mind to let Black play the most obvious move here or the next move: Bc8-b7.  11...Nd7  The only move which makes sense. The knight on f6 is rerouted to c5.  The move   11...Re8?  is bad because of Jain Singhai,N  @@StartBracket@@1977@@EndBracket@@-Swayams, M @@StartBracket@@2187@@EndBracket@@ New Delhi 2007 0-1 @@StartBracket@@53@@EndBracket@@.  12.cxd4  exd4  13.Nb3±   11...a5?!  12.a4!  Black's structure is falling apart.  12...dxc3  13.bxc3  b4  14.Bb2!  As it appears, Black is playing in white's hands. He can simply complete develop his pieces while hitting the weak points of Black.  14...Nd7  1-0 @@StartBracket@@44@@EndBracket@@ Swiercz,D @@StartBracket@@2620@@EndBracket@@ -Ragger,M @@StartBracket@@2698@@EndBracket@@ Berlin 2015  15.Bb3!  Activating the bishop and freeing the c-file for the rook.  12.a4!  We play on all the fronts! The a1-rook gets a role in the play.  12...Bb7  As we will see in the upcoming events, like 12..Rb8, this bishop move has its drawbacks as well. The block of pawns d3/e4 is a thorn in the sight of the bishop.  13.Nb3  13...Nb6  14.axb5!  By forcing Black to take back on a8 with the bishop, it occupies a less ideal position. Black can't temporarily use this square for his heavy pieces.  14...axb5  15.Rxa8  Bxa8  16.Bd2!  Na4  17.Qc1!  This little queen move contains a profound strategical idea of exerting cq increasing pressure across the c-file.  17...Bb7  This 'useless' move wasting time, is a necessary evil.  18.cxd4!  exd4  19.Na5!  This strong move, exchanging the c6-knight who controls the crucial central square and pawn e5 and d4, has been made possible by 16.Bd2.  19...Nxa5  20.Bxa5⩲  As seen so often in the Catalan, the weird-looking a5-bishop @@StartBracket@@especially with a pawn on b4@@EndBracket@@ is not bad at all there. 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@60@@EndBracket@@ Fressinet,L @@StartBracket@@2687@@EndBracket@@-Aronian,L @@StartBracket@@2792@@EndBracket@@ Paris 2016   10...Bg4  11.h3!  Bh5  Giving up the strong bishop and bishop pair in such an early phase is not a thing most players are keen on.  12.Qe2  Re8   12...d4  13.g4  Mostly Black retreated with the bishop, but in 5 games he opted for a relieve in the center with dxc3.  13...Bg6  14.cxd4!  Striving for a pawn majority on the kingside after exd4.  14...exd4  15.Nh4⩲  Preparing for Nf5, f4, and N2f3. Tactically Black can not use the temporary unprotected position of the knight. For instance, after: 1-0 @@StartBracket@@60@@EndBracket@@. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@49@@EndBracket@@ Pashikian,A @@StartBracket@@2473@@EndBracket@@-Vardanian,H @@StartBracket@@2304@@EndBracket@@ Yerevan 2004  13.Nf1!  The meanwhile so well-known knight maneuver to g3.. something we can dream of by now.  13...d4  14.g4!  Before putting the knight on g3, we gain plenty of space on the kingside. In the near future we are intending to push are pawns even further, or move our f1-knight to f5.  14...Bg6  15.Ng3→   10...Re8  11.Bb3!  11...Bf8  12.exd5  Strangely enough, this is not white's most common move.  12...Nxd5  13.d4  Notwithstanding, Black cannot handle all the threats along the a2-g8 diagonal and e-file.  13...Bg4  14.dxe5!  Opening the position, relying on the unpinning with h3 and evt g4.  14...Nxe5   14...Rxe5  15.Ne4!  Next to come is h3 and evt g4, when both e5 as d5 could be hanging.  15...Rf5   15...h6  16.Bxh6!!  once again, this move reveals the implied powers of white's pieces.  16...gxh6  17.Bxd5  Rxd5  18.Qxd5  white is winning material and the game.  16.Ng3!  Black is lost. He cannot keep the things together.  16...Bxf3  17.gxf3  Black is losing his rook or knight.  15.Rxe5!  Here again, the tactics work for us.  15...Rxe5  16.h3!  For Black it is essential to maintain the pin.  16...Bh5   16...Bxf3  17.Nxf3  Despite that white's pieces are not all developed, Black is thunderstruck by the sudden unpinned white pieces.  17...Rf5  18.g4  The rook got astray whereas the knight on d5 should be left unguarded.  18...Rxf3  19.Qxf3  Due to the bishop pair White enjoys a stable and lasting plus.  17.g4!  Here, all of black's pieces are hanging.  17...Re8  18.gxh5  White's minor pieces are much stronger here than the rook in this open position.  18...Nf4  19.Nf1±  when black's attack comes to an end. }
11. dxe4
{ Black's 3 main options here are:  11...Be6  ,  11...Bd6  , and  11...Bc5  .  Before we delve into these theoretical and interesting positions, I would like to stress that there is not such a thing as an 'antidote' against these positions. However, based on some strong ideas of the current leading players we can get a grasp of the strategies involved and turn on the heat on our opponent maximally. }
11... Be6
{ 11...Bd6  with the idea of transferring the knight to the kingside.  12.Nf1  Aren't we herd animals? Despite the fact that Black has plenty of choices here, in all the games played the players went for Ne7-Ng6 @@StartBracket@@which is a very plausible plan by the way.@@EndBracket@@ 12.. h6  12...Ne7  13.Nh4  N  Black intends to move the knight to g6. This novelty 13.Nh4! anticipates on this move with 14. Nf5. @@StartBracket@@In this commentary I try the best I can to explain the moves with words, colors and arrows. However, it does not compare to the extensive explanation on video.@@EndBracket@@  13...Ng6  14.Nf5!  when White got an excellent knight on f5 and is slightly better here.   11...Bc5  12.Qe2!?  I would rather postpone the move 12.h3, which is mainstream theory and immediately increase the tension on black's b5-pawn.  12...Be6   12...Ng4  13.Rf1  We should keep in mind that under all circumstances h2-h3 is a useful move for us to play, so we don't care about temporarily moving the rook back to f1.  13...Qe7  14.b4  Taking space on the queenside and preparing a2-a4.  14...Bd6  After   14...Bb6  again  15.a4!  15.a4  15...Rb8  16.Nb3⩲  The knight on g4 is misplaced and as a consequence, we don't have to be concerned about Bg4. We follow up with taking on b5 and Bd3, or h3, and subsequently Be3.  13.a4  The most obvious move of our opponent is to cover the unguarded pawn..  13...Rb8   13...b4  14.Nc4!  The c4-square is an excellent outpost for our knight.  14.axb5  axb5  15.b4!  Fixing the pawn on b5.  15...Bb6  16.Bd3⩲  This set-up engaging on b5, is the most to-the-point. But the following line is highly promising as well and needs to be tested! }
12. a4
{ This is the soft spot of black's position. Our plan is to engage on this target by means of Qe2 and evt. Bd3. }
12... Bc5
{ 12...b4  13.Qe2  Developing and preparing Nc4.  13...Qc8  14.Nc4  Black has to protect his pawn on e5.  14...Nd7  15.a5⩲ }
13. Qe2
{ Black is about to make an important and difficult decision. Is he leaving the a-file for granted after 13..Rb8, is he giving up the c4-square with b4, or is he keeping the rook on a8 possibly sacrificing the b5-pawn? }
13... Ba7 { So it's the latter one. } 14. h3
{ Halting Ng4 for once and for all. } 14... Nh5 15. Nf1
{ The expert reveals how White should approach these positions: in a positional and calm manner. For the moment Nf4 is off the table. }
15... Qf6 { 15...Nf4?  16.Bxf4  exf4  17.e5  White is much better. } 16. Bd3
{ Plain and simple. Maybe even stronger was } 16... Ne7
{ A sample line could be:   16...b4  17.a5  bxc3  18.bxc3  Bc8  19.Bc4⩲ } 17.
axb5
{ Mickey Adams has a special radar for when to strike in these carefully and strategically build up positions. The queen on f6 is choking due to a shortage of fresh air.. }
17... axb5 18. Rxa7
{ A wonderful double attack is about to follow, using the bad position of the a7-rook. }
18... Rxa7 19. Bg5 Qg6 20. Qe3
{ Black is helpless against the double threats of Nh4 and Qxa7. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@31@@EndBracket@@ Adams,M @@StartBracket@@2738@@EndBracket@@-Baramidze, D @@StartBracket@@2594@@EndBracket@@ Baden-Baden 2015 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4...d6 5.O-O Be7 Main Line 8...b5"]
[Black "4...d6 5.O-O Be7 Main Line 8...b5 − 10...d4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 d6 5. O-O Be7 6. c3 O-O
{ 6...a6  7.Ba4  O-O  8.Re1  is a transposition to our main line. } 7. Re1
{ White supports the central pawn on e4, in order to play a future d3-d4. Besides, the f1-square is vacated for the knight manoeuvre @@StartBracket@@Nb1-d2-f1-g3/e3@@EndBracket@@. }
7... a6 8. Ba4
{ Our opponent has to make an important decision. Will he play 8...b5 and 9...d5 or 8...Re8 with the idea of moving the bishop to f8. }
8... b5
{ 8...Bg4  9.Nbd2  Nd7  10.h3  Bh5  11.Nf1  leads to a transposition to 4...d6 Pin Variation: 5.O-O Bg4. }
9. Bc2
{ In the next lines we deal with Black's response of  9...d5  in the center. Please have a look at all the other lines, such as  9...Bb7  ,  9...Re8  ,  9...h6  &  9...g6  , in thenext chapter. }
9... d5 10. Nbd2 d4 11. h3
{ According to my research, this move - stopping Bc8-g4, is essential in the struggle for an advantage.   Moreover, White doesn't mind letting Black play the most obvious move here or the next move: Bc8-b7. }
11... a5
{ We are following an interesting but slightly dubious idea of Markus Ragger with Black in his game against David Swiercz. It is easy to underestimate the hidden strength of White's position and the Austrian strong GM will soon regret his choice.   The move  11...Re8?  is bad because of  12.cxd4  exd4  13.Nb3±  , Jain Singhai, N @@StartBracket@@1977@@EndBracket@@-Swayams, M @@StartBracket@@2187@@EndBracket@@ New Delhi 2007 0-1 @@StartBracket@@53@@EndBracket@@.@@EndBracket@@ }
12. a4
{ Black's structure is falling apart, as will be illustrated in case when Black takes on a4. }
12... dxc3
{ 12...bxa4?!  13.Bxa4  Our poor opponent can no longer maintain his center. }
13. bxc3 b4 14. Bb2
{ As it appears, Black is playing in White's hands. He can simply complete developing his pieces while hitting the weak points of Black. }
14... Nd7
{ 1-0 @@StartBracket@@44@@EndBracket@@ Swiercz,D @@StartBracket@@2620@@EndBracket@@ -Ragger,M @@StartBracket@@2698@@EndBracket@@ Berlin 2015 }
15. Bb3 { Activating the bishop and freeing the c-file for the rook. } 15...
Nc5 16. Bd5
{ Wielding his active pieces to undermine the e5-pawn. White has tremendous pressure and Black's position is prone to crack down. }
