9. Bc2
{ In the next lines we deal with Black's response of  9...d5  in the center. Please have a look at all the other lines, such as  9...Bb7  ,  9...Re8  ,  9...h6  &  9...g6  , in thenext chapter. }
9... d5 10. Nbd2 d4 11. h3
{ According to my research, this move - stopping Bc8-g4, is essential in the struggle for an advantage.   Moreover, White doesn't mind letting Black play the most obvious move here or the next move: Bc8-b7. }
11... Nd7
{ The only move that makes sense. The knight on f6 is rerouted to c5.   The move  11...Re8?  is bad because of  12.cxd4  exd4  13.Nb3±  Jain Singhai, N @@StartBracket@@1977@@EndBracket@@-Swayams, M @@StartBracket@@2187@@EndBracket@@ New Delhi 2007 0-1 @@StartBracket@@53@@EndBracket@@. }
12. a4 { We play on all fronts! The a1-rook gets a role in the play. } 12...
Bb7
{ As we will see in the upcoming events, like 12...Rb8, this bishop move has its drawbacks as well. The block of pawns d3/e4 is a thorn in the sight of the bishop. }
13. Nb3
{ The central pawns are kept in our gunsights. Though the position has a typical Ruy Lopez structure and can be considered as 'solid' for Black, my prevailing feeling is that he is with his back against the wall due to the immense pressure on Black's center and our smooth and compact piece play. }
13... Nb6 14. axb5
{ By forcing Black to take back on a8 with the bishop, it occupies a less ideal position. Black can't temporarily use this square for his heavy pieces. }
14... axb5 15. Rxa8 Bxa8
{ Black can't take back with the queen as his center can't be maintained.  15...Qxa8??  16.cxd4  exd4  17.Nbxd4  when White is much better. }
16. Bd2 { A sample line, which could appear in practice, is: } 16... Qd6
{ Followed up by Rd8, fortifying the center: e5 and d4. } 17. cxd4 exd4 18. Qc1
{ A strong positional concept. For us, this is the starting point of a 'carefree existence' for the remainder of the game.  I rejoice the positional edges here for White. We are a central pawn up, the bishop on a8 is isolated, and c7 is a backward and weak pawn at the moment. We follow up with Bf4. }
18... Nd7
{ Black should play very cautiously, as each misstep could lead to an overwhelming advantage for White. }
19. Bf4 Nde5
{ Establishing an outpost on e5, seems the only idea in order not to be overrun. }
20. Bxe5 Nxe5 { But it is at the cost of a pawn.. } 21. Nfxd4
{ Black should invest some time to stop Nd4-f5. } 21... g6 22. Qf4
{ Improving our pieces first rather than grabbing a lousy pawn. White is better, as the bishop on a8 is secluded and it will be a hell of a job to prove his compensation for being a pawn down.   22.Nxb5  would be another attempt, but Black can gain the pawn back after  22...Qb6!  23.Nc3  Nxd3!  24.Bxd3  Qxb3  25.e5  although the position is balanced due to Black's sufficient compensation in the shape of his 'open' bishops, practically White may be slightly better here. }
