{ In the next lines we deal with Black's response of  9...d5  in the center. Please have a look at all the other lines, such as  9...Bb7  ,  9...Re8  ,  9...h6  &  9...g6  , in thenext chapter. }
9... d5 10. Nbd2 d4 11. h3
{ According to my research, this move - stopping Bc8-g4, is essential in the struggle for an advantage.   Moreover, White doesn't mind letting Black play the most obvious move here or the next move: Bc8-b7. }
11... Nd7
{ The only move that makes sense. The knight on f6 is rerouted to c5.   The move  11...Re8?  is bad because of  12.cxd4  exd4  13.Nb3±  Jain Singhai, N @@StartBracket@@1977@@EndBracket@@-Swayams, M @@StartBracket@@2187@@EndBracket@@ New Delhi 2007 0-1 @@StartBracket@@53@@EndBracket@@. }
12. a4 { We play on all fronts! The a1-rook gets a role in the play. } 12...
Bb7
{ As we will see in the upcoming events, like 12...Rb8, this bishop move has its drawbacks as well. The block of pawns d3/e4 is a thorn in the sight of the bishop. }
13. Nb3
{ The central pawns are kept in our gunsights. Though the position has a typical Ruy Lopez structure and can be considered as 'solid' for Black, my prevailing feeling is that he is with his back against the wall due to the immense pressure on Black's center and our smooth and compact piece play. }
13... Nb6 14. axb5
{ By forcing Black to take back on a8 with the bishop, it occupies a less ideal position. Black can't temporarily use this square for his heavy pieces. }
14... axb5 15. Rxa8 Bxa8
{ Black can't take back with the queen as his center can't be maintained.  15...Qxa8??  16.cxd4  exd4  17.Nbxd4  when White is much better. }
16. Bd2
{ Please notice White's cunning plan, found by the strong French GM Laurent Fressinet. Before he captures on d4, he prepares a highly unpleasant set-up for Black. }
16... Na4 17. Qc1
{ This little queen move contains a profound strategical idea of exerting cq increasing pressure across the c-file. }
17... Bb7
{ This 'useless' time-wasting move is a necessary evil for Black.   After  17...dxc3  18.bxc3  Qd7  19.d4  White gets the upper hand in the center. }
18. cxd4
{ Although there can be found interesting alternatives here, such as 18.Bb1, I really can't dissuade you from the next series of events. }
18... exd4 19. Na5
{ This strong move, exchanging the c6-knight who controls the crucial central square and pawn e5 and d4, has been made possible by @@StartFEN@@b2q1rk1/2p1bppp/1nn5/1p2p3/3pP3/1NPP1N1P/1PB2PP1/2BQR1K1 w - - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16.Bd2  . }
19... Nxa5 20. Bxa5
{ As seen so often in the Catalan, the weird-looking a5-bishop @@StartBracket@@especially with a pawn on b4@@EndBracket@@ is not bad at all there. }
20... Nc5 21. b4
{ Expelling the knight from its dominant post, clearing the path for the bishop to b3. }
21... Ne6 22. Bb3
{ White obtained a position we could only have dreamed of from move 1 with the white pieces. All his pieces are just too active, and Black has to carry the weight of defending the flaws of his position. }
22... Qd7 23. Bxe6 { It's time to cash in the chips! } 23... fxe6 24. Qxc7 Qxc7
25. Bxc7 Bxb4
{ At first hand, the black passed b-pawn in conjunction with the bishop pair may seem dangerous. Notwithstanding, the white pieces control the board and White has time for the powerful manoeuvre Rf1-a1-a7. }
26. Ra1
{ The game went  26.Rb1  Bc3  27.Bb6   27.Rxb5  Ba6!  with counterplay.  27...b4  28.Bxd4  Ba6  29.Bxc3  bxc3  30.Ne1!  Blocking the pawn on c3, and preparing for the king's advance to e3.  30...Rd8  31.Rd1  Kf7  32.f3  Rb8  33.Ra1  Rb6  @@StartBracket@@1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@60@@EndBracket@@ Fressinet, L @@StartBracket@@2687@@EndBracket@@ -Aronian, L @@StartBracket@@2792@@EndBracket@@ Paris 2016@@EndBracket@@  34.Kf2!  bringing the king to  e3  , would have led to a winning advantage for White. }
26... Bc3
{ It would have been more wisely to refrain from immediate action, defending the 7th rank.  26...Rf7  27.Rb1  Bc3  28.Bd6  Ba6   28...Rd7?  loses to  29.Rxb5  29.Rb3  Rd7  30.Bb4  Rc7  31.Kf1  White is much better here: he has securely halted the advance of the b-pawn and is bringing his other pieces into play. }
27. Ra7 Bc6 28. Ne5
{ The proverbial 'octopus' found his garden of Eden on e5. } 28... Be8 29. Bd6
{ Have you ever witnessed better pieces as in this ending? White is winning. }
