[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4...d6 5.O-O Be7 Main Line 8...b5"]
[Black "4...d6 5.O-O Be7 Main Line 8...b5 − 10...d4 #7 (Alternative 11.Nb3)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 d6 5. O-O Be7 6. c3 O-O
{ 6...a6  7.Ba4  O-O  8.Re1  is a transposition to our main line. } 7. Re1
{ White supports the central pawn on e4, in order to play a future d3-d4. Besides, the f1-square is vacated for the knight manoeuvre @@StartBracket@@Nb1-d2-f1-g3/e3@@EndBracket@@. }
7... a6 8. Ba4
{ Our opponent has to make an important decision. Will he play 8...b5 and 9...d5 or 8...Re8 with the idea of moving the bishop to f8. }
8... b5
{ 8...Bg4  9.Nbd2  Nd7  10.h3  Bh5  11.Nf1  leads to a transposition to 4...d6 Pin Variation: 5.O-O Bg4. }
9. Bc2
{ In the next lines we deal with Black's response of  9...d5  in the center. Please have a look at all the other lines, such as  9...Bb7  ,  9...Re8  ,  9...h6  &  9...g6  , in thenext chapter. }
9... d5 10. Nbd2 d4 11. Nb3
{ Another line, played by the current leading players of the world, is interesting though it may not be sufficient to gain an advantage against a well-prepared opponent. }
11... Bg4
{ 11...a5  12.a4  bxa4  13.Rxa4  dxc3  14.bxc3  Nd7  15.Be3  Nb6  was not so clear, in Carlsen, M @@StartBracket@@2838@@EndBracket@@ -Ghosh, D @@StartBracket@@2581@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2017, 1-0 @@StartBracket@@29@@EndBracket@@. }
12. h3
{ Our play can be compared with the hedgehog. Improving our pieces, we see that our opponent is blowing himself up. }
12... Bh5 13. cxd4 exd4 14. Bf4
{ Aesthetically, this position is outstanding: the open c-file the coordinating pieces the influence on the center and pressure on the weak pawns on c7 and d4. }
14... Bd6
{ is releasing the tension for Black, and - in my humble opinion - equalizing. The idea is that after }
15. e5 { Black is not losing a piece. On the contrary, after } 15... Nd5
{ he found a dominant post for its knight on d5. } 16. Bg3 Be7 17. a3
{ White can follow with Nbd2, Qc1 and Bb1-a2 or Bd1, and White may have the slightly favourable position here. }
