1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 d6 5. O-O Be7 6. c3 O-O
{ 6...a6  7.Ba4  O-O  8.Re1  is a transposition to our main line. } 7. Re1
{ White supports the central pawn on e4, in order to play a future d3-d4. Besides, the f1-square is vacated for the knight manoeuvre @@StartBracket@@Nb1-d2-f1-g3/e3@@EndBracket@@. }
7... a6 8. Ba4
{ Our opponent has to make an important decision. Will he play 8...b5 and 9...d5 or 8...Re8 with the idea of moving the bishop to f8. }
8... b5
{ 8...Bg4  9.Nbd2  Nd7  10.h3  Bh5  11.Nf1  leads to a transposition to 4...d6 Pin Variation: 5.O-O Bg4. }
9. Bc2
{ In the next lines we deal with Black's response of  9...d5  in the center. Please have a look at all the other lines, such as  9...Bb7  ,  9...Re8  ,  9...h6  &  9...g6  , in thenext chapter. }
9... d5 10. Nbd2 Bg4
{ This move looks adventurous, but often the bishop ends up on g6. } 11. h3
{ In my previous course concerning the Ruy Lopez Exchange Variation, I received the question if there are any guidelines for the timing playing h3.  None of the positions are similar and require independent decision-making, I'd say that taking the square of g4 of your opponent with a tempo, meanwhile letting the bishop leave the c8-g4 diagonal, is as useful as it can be. }
11... Bh5
{ Giving up the strong bishop and bishop pair in such an early phase is not a thing most players are keen on. }
12. Qe2
{ We are following the game of Wei Yi with the white pieces.  The configuration seems rather passive, but beyond the first signs of daylight are signalled. White is striving for a kingside expansion with g2-g4 and Ng3, h3-h4-h5 etc. }
12... d4 13. g4
{ Mostly Black retreated with the bishop, but in 5 games he opted for a relieve in the center with dxc3. }
13... Bg6
{ 13...dxc3  14.bxc3  Bg6  15.Nf1  following the same plan.  15...Nd7  16.Ng3  f6  1-0 @@StartBracket@@33@@EndBracket@@ Psakhis, L @@StartBracket@@2535@@EndBracket@@ -Gusev, V @@StartBracket@@2410@@EndBracket@@ Kazan 1980  17.Nf5  Bf7  18.h4→ }
14. cxd4 { Striving for a pawn majority on the kingside after exd4. } 14...
Nxd4 15. Nxd4
{ Now that our knight hops to f3, Black is losing control of the center. }
15... Qxd4 16. Nf3
{ Our adversary should be careful not to lose the central pawn. } 16... Qd6 17.
d4 { Using a small tactic in our favour. } 17... exd4 18. e5 *

