Bb1
{ One step backwards, to make two forwards.   17.Bb3  Peculiar enough, this nice-looking move is sketchy.  17...Nc5!  Black was winning the d3-pawn and obtained the advantage. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@90@@EndBracket@@ Meszaros,L @@StartBracket@@2101@@EndBracket@@ -Jires,J @@StartBracket@@2059@@EndBracket@@ Brno 2018 }
17... c5 18. a3 { The bishop will reoccupy the a2-diagonal. } 18... Nc6 19. Ba2
{ Black has to encounter the super bishop on a2 and should forge the plan consisting of the moves: Kh8, f6 and Bf7. }
19... Kh8 20. Nf3
{ 20.f4  Appearances are deceptive. Despite the fact that this move is a delight to the eye, this move comes too early.  20...Bxf5  21.gxf5   21.exf5  c4!  21...c4!  Black counters in the center as White started an operation on the flank.  22.dxc4  Nc5  with counterplay. }
20... f6 21. Bd2
{ We are increasing the 'voltage', aiming for Rac1 and b4.   Another way:  21.Bf4  Nde5  22.Nxe5  fxe5  23.Bg3  with a balanced position, though I think White's game is easier to play. }
21... Rc8 22. Rac1
{ White is slightly better here, as a result of his superior pieces. More important is that Black faces the difficult task to parry all the threats. One of them is Bd5 and b4. }
