{ Mostly Black retreated with the bishop, but in 5 games he opted for a relieve in the center with dxc3. }
13... Bg6
{ 13...dxc3  14.bxc3  Bg6  15.Nf1  following the same plan.  15...Nd7  16.Ng3  f6  1-0 @@StartBracket@@33@@EndBracket@@ Psakhis, L @@StartBracket@@2535@@EndBracket@@ -Gusev, V @@StartBracket@@2410@@EndBracket@@ Kazan 1980  17.Nf5  Bf7  18.h4→ }
14. cxd4 { Striving for a pawn majority on the kingside after exd4. } 14...
exd4 15. Nh4
{ Preparing for Nf5, f4, and N2f3. Tactically Black can not use the temporary unprotected position of the knight. For instance, after }
15... Nd7 16. Nf5 { White scored 3 out of 3 from this position. } 16... Bxf5
17. gxf5 Bd6
{ 1-0 @@StartBracket@@49@@EndBracket@@ Pashikian,A @@StartBracket@@2473@@EndBracket@@ -Vardanian,H @@StartBracket@@2304@@EndBracket@@ Yerevan 2004. }
18. Nf3
{ Pashikian choose for  18.a3  Qf6  19.Nf1  , but the knight is probably better placed on f3, reaching d4, e5 and g5. }
18... Nb4 19. Bg5
{ Like before, White could also try to preserve his bishop by moving it to b1, following up with a3 and Ba2. }
19... Be7 20. Bxe7
{ An interesting alternative could have been  20.Bf4  Nxc2  21.Qxc2  c5  22.e5  and, personally speaking, I'd rather be White here because of the two powerful pawns @@StartBracket@@e5 and f5@@EndBracket@@. }
20... Qxe7 21. e5
{ The pawns seem a bit vulnerable and strong at the same time. As a matter of fact, Black cannot engage on them so White can slowly move his pieces around them. }
21... Rae8 22. Qd2 { These small subtle moves are the hardest to find. } 22...
Nc6 23. e6 { Paving the way for the c2-bishop.. } 23... fxe6 24. Rxe6
{ Is the pawn on f5 weak or strong? White's pawn structure is a mess, but, in fact, his initiative - because of the active pieces - is mounting. }
24... Qc5 25. Bb3
{ Black has no choice but stepping out of the discovered checks. } 25... Kh8
26. Rae1 { the pressure is mounting. } *

