{ 8...Bg4  9.Nbd2  Nd7  10.h3  Bh5  11.Nf1  leads to a transposition to 4...d6 Pin Variation: 5.O-O Bg4. }
9. Bc2
{ In the next lines we deal with Black's response of  9...d5  in the center. Please have a look at all the other lines, such as  9...Bb7  ,  9...Re8  ,  9...h6  &  9...g6  , in thenext chapter. }
9... d5 10. Nbd2 dxe4 11. dxe4
{ Black's three main options here are: @@StartBracket@@1@@EndBracket@@  11...Be6  , @@StartBracket@@2@@EndBracket@@  11...Bd6  and @@StartBracket@@3@@EndBracket@@  11...Bc5  .    Before we delve into these theoretical and interesting positions, I would like to stress that there is not such a thing as an 'antidote' against these positions.  However, based on some strong ideas of the current leading players, we can get a grasp of the strategies involved and turn on the heat on our opponent maximally. }
11... Bd6 { with the idea of transferring the knight to the kingside. } 12. Nf1
{ Aren't we herd animals? Despite the fact that Black has plenty of choices here, in all the games played the players went for Ne7-Ng6 @@StartBracket@@which is a very plausible plan@@EndBracket@@. }
12... Ne7 { Black intends to move the knight to g6. } 13. Nh4
{ This novelty  13.Nh4!  anticipates  13...Ng6  with  14.Nf5!  .   We can't neglect the theoretical moves and plans of Dutch superstar Jorden van Foreest.  13.a4  Rb8  14.Ng3  h6  15.b4  Be6  16.h3  Qc8!  Black fully equalized here, however, the position remains erratic and White could start a promising offense on Black's king. Van Foreest, J @@StartBracket@@2612@@EndBracket@@ - Sokolov, I @@StartBracket@@2584@@EndBracket@@ Amsterdam 2019 1-0 @@StartBracket@@40@@EndBracket@@. }
13... Ng6 14. Nf5
{ when White got an excellent knight on f5 and is slightly better here. } 14...
h6 15. N1g3
{ A picture is worth a thousand words..the knights rule the board and Black could better do something against it. }
15... Ne7 16. Nxd6 cxd6
{ 16...Qxd6  17.Qxd6  cxd6  18.Be3  leads to a lasting advantage in the ending. }
17. a4
{ A tough call: Black is about to give up the b-file or damage his pawn structure with bxa4. }
17... Rb8 { 17...bxa4  18.Rxa4± } 18. axb5 axb5 19. Be3
{ Please note that the freeing move } 19... d5
{ doesn't work here, because of: } 20. exd5 Qxd5 21. Ba7
{ simply winning the pawn on e5. } 21... Ra8 22. Qxd5 Nexd5 23. Rxe5
{ with a big advantage for White. } *

