9... d5 10. Nbd2 dxe4 11. dxe4
{ Black's three main options here are: @@StartBracket@@1@@EndBracket@@  11...Be6  , @@StartBracket@@2@@EndBracket@@  11...Bd6  and @@StartBracket@@3@@EndBracket@@  11...Bc5  .    Before we delve into these theoretical and interesting positions, I would like to stress that there is not such a thing as an 'antidote' against these positions.  However, based on some strong ideas of the current leading players, we can get a grasp of the strategies involved and turn on the heat on our opponent maximally. }
11... Bc5 12. Qe2
{ I would rather postpone the move  12.h3  ,  which is mainstream theory, and immediately increase the tension on Black's b5-pawn. }
12... Ng4 13. Rf1
{ We should keep in mind that under all circumstances h2-h3 is a useful move for us to play, so we don't care about temporarily moving the rook back to f1. }
13... Qe7 14. b4
{ Taking space on the queenside and preparing a2-a4.   This is my improvement over  14.h3  , which was played in ½-½ @@StartBracket@@42@@EndBracket@@ Hladik, O @@StartBracket@@2187@@EndBracket@@ - Valenta, V @@StartBracket@@2199@@EndBracket@@, Czech Republic 2010. That game continued  14...Nf6  15.Nh4  g6  16.Nb3  Bb6  17.Bg5  Qe6  18.Nd2  Kg7  19.Nf5+  gxf5  20.exf5  Qd6  21.Rad1  White is winning, because of the Ne4 and xf6 threat. }
14... Bd6 { After  14...Bb6  again  15.a4! } 15. a4 Rb8 16. Nb3
{ The knight on g4 is misplaced and as a consequence we don't have to be concerned about Bg4. We follow up with taking on b5 and Bd3, or h3 and subsequently Be3. }
