9... d5 10. Nbd2 dxe4 11. dxe4
{ Black's three main options here are: @@StartBracket@@1@@EndBracket@@  11...Be6  , @@StartBracket@@2@@EndBracket@@  11...Bd6  and @@StartBracket@@3@@EndBracket@@  11...Bc5  .    Before we delve into these theoretical and interesting positions, I would like to stress that there is not such a thing as an 'antidote' against these positions.  However, based on some strong ideas of the current leading players, we can get a grasp of the strategies involved and turn on the heat on our opponent maximally. }
11... Bc5 12. Qe2
{ I would rather postpone the move  12.h3  ,  which is mainstream theory, and immediately increase the tension on Black's b5-pawn. }
12... Be6 13. a4
{ The most obvious move of our opponent is to cover the unguarded pawn.. }
13... Rb8
{ 13...b4  14.Nc4!  The c4-square is an excellent outpost for our knight. } 14.
axb5 axb5 15. b4 { Fixing the pawn on b5. } 15... Bb6 16. Bd3
{ This set-up engaging on b5, is the most to-the-point. But the following line is highly promising as well and needs to be tested! }
16... Ne7
{ A beautiful counter-idea comprising a pawn sacrifice, but, unfortunately for Black, not fully equalizing.   Seen before was  16...Ra8?  17.Rxa8  Qxa8  In the game White didn't pay heed to ...Ng4, ...Nxf2 and ...Qa1. This can simply be prevented with  18.h3  , maintaining all the threats.   18.Bxb5  Ng4  19.Rf1  Nxf2!  20.Rxf2  Qa1!  1-0 @@StartBracket@@47@@EndBracket@@ Zajic, M @@StartBracket@@2497@@EndBracket@@-Gajadin, D @@StartBracket@@2010@@EndBracket@@ Batumi 2018 }
17. Nxe5 Ng6 { An exclamation mark for the beauty.. } 18. Nxg6 fxg6
{ Revealing his true intentions: the f-file is opened for the rook. } 19. Nf3
{ The pre-emptive  19.h3?  comes too late:  19...Ng4!!  20.hxg4  Rxf2  21.Qxf2  Bxf2+  22.Kxf2  Qxd3  when Black is winning. }
19... Ng4 20. Be3 { The only move to stop taking on f2. } 20... Nxe3 21. fxe3
{ It may seem that Black is fine due to his bishop pair and weakened white double pawns. But at the end of the day is a pawn a pawn.. @@StartBracket@@a very wise chess saying@@EndBracket@@. }
21... c6 22. Nd4
{ Despite Black's bishop pair, White has a comfortable edge here. The knight on d4 feels like fish in the water... or just like a knight in the stable. }
