{ White supports the central pawn on e4, in order to play a future d3-d4. Besides, the f1-square is vacated for the knight manoeuvre @@StartBracket@@Nb1-d2-f1-g3/e3@@EndBracket@@. }
7... a6 8. Ba4
{ Our opponent has to make an important decision. Will he play 8...b5 and 9...d5 or 8...Re8 with the idea of moving the bishop to f8. }
8... b5
{ 8...Bg4  9.Nbd2  Nd7  10.h3  Bh5  11.Nf1  leads to a transposition to 4...d6 Pin Variation: 5.O-O Bg4. }
9. Bc2
{ In the next lines we deal with Black's response of  9...d5  in the center. Please have a look at all the other lines, such as  9...Bb7  ,  9...Re8  ,  9...h6  &  9...g6  , in thenext chapter. }
9... d5 10. Nbd2 dxe4 11. dxe4
{ Black's three main options here are: @@StartBracket@@1@@EndBracket@@  11...Be6  , @@StartBracket@@2@@EndBracket@@  11...Bd6  and @@StartBracket@@3@@EndBracket@@  11...Bc5  .    Before we delve into these theoretical and interesting positions, I would like to stress that there is not such a thing as an 'antidote' against these positions.  However, based on some strong ideas of the current leading players, we can get a grasp of the strategies involved and turn on the heat on our opponent maximally. }
11... Be6 12. a4
{ This is the soft spot of Black's position. Our plan is to engage on this target by means of Qe2 and evt. Bd3. }
12... Bc5 13. Qe2
{ Black is about to make an important and difficult decision.  • Is he leaving the a-file for granted after  13...Rb8   • Is he giving up the c4-square with  13...b4   • or is he keeping the rook on a8 possibly sacrificing the b5-pawn? }
13... Ba7
{ So it's the latter.   Not much better would be  13...Rb8  . Play could continue  14.Nf1  Qc8  15.b4  Bd6  16.Bd3  with a slight edge for White. }
14. h3 { Halting Ng4 for once and for all. } 14... Nh5 15. Nf1
{ The expert reveals how White should approach these positions: in a positional and calm manner. For the moment Nf4 is off the table. }
15... Qf6 { White is much better after  15...Nf4?  16.Bxf4  exf4  17.e5  . }
16. Bd3 { It's too late to stop the Bg5 plans with h6. For example, } 16... h6
17. axb5 axb5 18. Bxb5 Bxf2+ 19. Qxf2 Rxa1 20. Bxc6
{ and White is on top, even after Bxh3, Bb5. } *

