[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4...d6 5.O-O Be7 Main Line 8...Re8 9.Nbd2 With 9...Bf8"]
[Black "Introduction: 4...d6 5.O-O Be7 Main Line 8...Re8 9.Nbd2 With 9...Bf8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ This variation is called the 'Berlin Defense' or the 'Berlin Wall', due to its super solid nature. Rooted in the family of the Ruy Lopez opening @@StartBracket@@i.e. 3.Bb5@@EndBracket@@, the Berlin Defense was first seen in practice anno 1801, and examined by @@StartBracket@@it's in the name - who else?@@EndBracket@@ Berliners, as recorded in history. }
4. d3
{ After this move, we set foot into the 'Anti-Berlin'. We are keeping the queens on the board for the moment, sidestepping the forced lines arising after  4...Nxe4  , amongst others the super solid ending c.q. the 'Berlin Wall', deployed 4 times by Kramnik against Kasparov with great success in the World Championship Match @@StartBracket@@London, 2000@@EndBracket@@. }
4... d6
{ It goes beyond the scope of this course - containing a Bxc6-repertoire against the Ruy Lopez and the Berlin Wall - to cover all the sidelines after 4... d6. Nevertheless, I would like to give you an instrument against all Black's lines here. }
5. O-O
{ Here our plan of taking on c6 will not offer us salvation: Black can just take back with the b-pawn. Therefore, we take in the Ruy Lopez set-up with c3 and d4. }
5... Be7 6. c3 O-O
{ 6...a6  7.Ba4  O-O  8.Re1  is a transposition to our main line. } 7. Re1
{ White supports the central pawn on e4, in order to play a future d3-d4. Besides, the f1-square is vacated for the knight-maneuver @@StartBracket@@Nb1-d2-f1-g3/e3@@EndBracket@@. }
7... a6 8. Ba4
{ Our opponent has to make an important decision. Will he play  8...b5  and  9... d5 or  8...Re8  with the idea of moving the bishop to f8. }
8... Re8 9. Nbd2
{ Clearly, White should first get his pieces involved before opening the position with d3-d4. }
9... Bf8 10. Nf1 h6 11. Ng3
{ This is topical line is not the line I would like to enter, as I recommend the move d3-d4 before Nf1-g3. In order to give you an alternative to the surprise weapon 11.d4, I come up with some characteristic ideas in the main line after 11.Ng3. In this way you know where the sore points of the opponent lie, consecutively you can play these types of positions.   11.d4!?  exd4   11...b5  12.Bc2  leads to a transposition.  12.Nxd4!?  White seized some space and enjoys the more active piece play.   12.cxd4?  is just losing a pawn, because of  12...Rxe4∓  12...Bd7  13.Bc2  This is a novelty. Seen before was taking on c6. Guarding the central e4-pawn, which provides us with a space advantage. Maybe the most sound option for Black, activating the bishop and waiting for the opportunity to play d5 to equalize.  13...g6  14.h3  Stealing the square g4 of our adversary.  14...Bg7  15.a4!?  A very subtle and useful move, postponing Nf1-g3. The reason behind this is to avoid any knight swap after 15..d5 16.e5 Ne4 @@StartBracket@@without the knight on g3@@EndBracket@@.   15.Ng3!?  White can play this obvious move with all chances on success. However, 15.a4!? can be even more subtle, luring or discouraging Black playing d6-d5.  15...d5?!  Probably not the best, but a logical consequence of the fact that Black is seeking for ways activating his pieces.  16.Nxc6  Bxc6  17.e5⩲  Obviously, we shouldn't open the center with exd5, as Black is the one who could profit from his more active pieces in an open position. }
11... b5
{ 11...Bd7  12.d4!?  The time is right to act in the center.  12...b5  13.Bc2  g6  14.h3  Taking in the typical configuration of pieces in the Ruy-Lopez. White follows up with Be3.  14...Na5   14...Bg7  15.d5  The time is ripe to take the initiative!  15...Ne7   15...Na5!?  Our opponent's idea is to hit the center instantly with c7-c6, without giving the chance to us to maintain it with b3 and c4.  16.Nh2!?  This standard idea in the Ruy Lopez encompasses the idea to swap the f6 knight, in the struggle for square d5 after c6, dxc6.  16...c6  17.dxc6  Bxc6  18.Ng4  Making the plan d6-d5 less attractive for Black.  18...Nxg4  Here, I would like to come up with a novelty:  19.hxg4!?  Qe7  20.Nf1!  the knight is rerouted to d5.  16.b3!  Endorsing the center; in case of c7-c6, White can keep his pawn chain intact with c3-c4. ½- @@StartBracket@@28@@EndBracket@@ ½ @@StartBracket@@64@@EndBracket@@ Leko,P @@StartBracket@@2707@@EndBracket@@-Kryvoruchko,Y @@StartBracket@@2710@@EndBracket@@ Berlin 2015  15.b3!  Not allowing the uninvited guest to c4.  15...c5  16.d5  this position is transposing  @@StartBracket@@Kasimdzhanov-Sokolov 2002 @@StartBracket@@1-0@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@48@@EndBracket@@.   11...g6  12.h3  Before playing d4, White is taking the square of g4 away for black's pieces.  12...Bg7  13.d4  Seizing the initiative, forcing our opponent to come with a retort.  13...Bd7  14.Bc2  In case of 14.d5, Black has options @@StartBracket@@Ne7, Na5 and Nb8@@EndBracket@@. After 14..Nb8, the knight can try to get back in the game via d7 or a6.  14...Qe7  15.Be3  Also seen in practice was:   15.d5  Nb8  16.Be3  a5!?  when Black managed to find a new destination for the knight. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@44@@EndBracket@@ Sengupta,D @@StartBracket@@2589@@EndBracket@@-Shyam,S @@StartBracket@@2481@@EndBracket@@ Thiruvarur 2015  Kh7  16.Qd2  Building up the pressure, connecting the rooks. Black is slightly suffering from a lack of space, and will have trouble to come up with a decent response.  16...b5  The next move couldn't be good as there is a lack of coordination of the pieces.   16...Rad8?!  17.d5  Nb8  18.c4  c6  19.b4  when White got the upper hand by his space dominance. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@63@@EndBracket@@ Karjakin,S @@StartBracket@@2779@@EndBracket@@-Chadaev,N @@StartBracket@@2580@@EndBracket@@ Astana 2012  17.Nh2!  This move can be considered a novelty.  17...Rad8  18.f4  Further increasing the pressure on black's center, White is in firm control here. His battle plan will consist of slowly improving his pieces with - for instance - Nf3 and Rad1. }
12. Bc2
{ Moving the bishop to c2 and not to b3, is a matter of choice.  For instance,   12.Bb3  Be6   12...a5  13.a4  b4  14.h3  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@46@@EndBracket@@ Caruana,F @@StartBracket@@2800@@EndBracket@@-Predke,A  @@StartBracket@@2666@@EndBracket@@ Riga 2021  13.Bc2  d5⇆  0-1 @@StartBracket@@67@@EndBracket@@ Firouzja, A @@StartBracket@@2702@@EndBracket@@ -Carlsen,M  @@StartBracket@@2876@@EndBracket@@ chess24. com INT 2020 }
12... d5 13. exd5
{ Purely checking the pawn structure arising after 13.exd5, it looks like we accept a slightly inferior position. However, there lies an immense power within the white position. The upcoming variations will reveal that the break d2-d4 in connection with Bc2-b3, is extremely dangerous for our adversary. }
13... Nxd5
{ 13...Qxd5  14.d4  The timing of this move seems right since our opponent is not yet fully coordinated.  14...Bg4   14...exd4?!  15.Rxe8  Nxe8  16.Be4!  Obviously, Black should not get the chance to complete his development. Therefore action is required! :@@EndBracket@@  16...Qd6  17.Bf4!  A picture is worth a thousand words: Black won't get the chance to rest on his laurels. After Qxf4, Bxc6, I don't see a way out for him.   14...Bb7  15.Ne4!  The only move which is causing problems for Black.  15.Bb3  Qd6  16.h3!  After this move, Black has to make a concession. Giving up his g4-bishop is resulting in the resignation of the lights squares.  16...Bxf3  17.Qxf3  Black is winning a pawn, but White is better developed.  17...exd4  18.Bf4  Driving the queen from the sixth rank to make the following sacrifice possible.  18...Qd7  19.Bxh6→  Using the fact that the f6-knight is not sufficiently protected. }
14. Bd2 { An innocent-looking move but not without poison. } 14... Bb7
{ 14...g6  15.Bb3!  for Black it's hard to face the impending threats.  15...Bg7  16.d4!  Black can't take on d4, since the d5-knight would drop of the board. }
15. b4 Qd7
{ 15...Nf6  16.a4  Outflanking our opponent, playing on 2 sides of the board.  16...Qd7  17.Ne4!  The pressure is piling up. How should Black react to this knight on e4?  17...Nxe4  18.dxe4  Nd8  19.Be3  Black is worse on all fronts: the d-file is in white's hands, after Ne6 the pawn on e5 is hanging, and the White can any moment open the a-file. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@81@@EndBracket@@. }
16. Ne4
{ A bit of a provocative move. Black can try to chase the knight away with f5, but then Black has to deal with more weak points in his position. }
16... Rad8
{ 16...f5  17.Bb3!  Making optimal use of the pin, maintaining the knight on its central point e4. }
17. Bb3 { White's pressure on the light squares is mounting. } 17... Kh8 18.
Nh4
{ The queen can be moved to h5 or f3. 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@53@@EndBracket@@ Sethuraman,S @@StartBracket@@2623@@EndBracket@@-Bruzon Batista,L @@StartBracket@@2691@@EndBracket@@ Tsaghkadzor 2015 }
*

