[White "4...d6 5.O-O Be7 Main Line 8...Re8 9.Nbd2 With 9...Bf8"]
[Black "4...d6 5.O-O Be7 Main Line 8...Re8 9.Nbd2 With 9...Bf8 − 11.Ng3 Bd7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 d6 5. O-O
{ Here our plan of taking on c6 will not offer us salvation: Black can just take back with the b-pawn. Therefore, we take in the Ruy Lopez set-up with c3 and d4. }
5... Be7 6. c3 O-O
{ 6...a6  7.Ba4  O-O  8.Re1  is a transposition to our main line. } 7. Re1
{ White supports the central pawn on e4, in order to play a future d3-d4. Besides, the f1-square is vacated for the knight-manoeuvre @@StartBracket@@Nb1-d2-f1-g3/e3@@EndBracket@@. }
7... a6 8. Ba4
{ Our opponent has to make an important decision. Will he play 8... b5 and 9... d5 or 8... Re8 with the idea of moving the bishop to f8. }
8... Re8
{ 8...Bg4  9.Nbd2  Nd7  10.h3  Bh5  11.Nf1  leads to a transposition to 4...d6 Pin Variation: 5.O-O Bg4. }
9. Nbd2
{ Clearly, White should first get his pieces involved before opening the position with d3-d4. }
9... Bf8
{ We should act wisely here to try to get into our main line  9...b5  10.Bc2  Bf8  11.Nf1  followed by 12.d4. }
10. Nf1 h6
{ Our opponent kind of tricked us by deferring the move b7-b5. In case of b5, Bc2, we would transpose to our main line in which we opt for an instant d3-d4 with the knight on f1. However, here we can't enter this line: }
11. Ng3
{ This topical line is not the line I would like to enter, as I recommend the move d3-d4 before Nf1-g3.   In order to give you an alternative to the surprise weapon  11.d4  , I explain the characteristic ideas in the main line after  11.Ng3  . This will show you where the sore points of the opponent lie, consequently you can play these types of positions. }
11... Bd7 12. d4
{ The time is right to act in the center.   A slower approach would be  12.h3  Deciding between these two moves is a matter of taste. Here is a starter for this line:  12...Ne7  13.Bc2   13.Bxd7  Qxd7  and  14.Qc2  would lead to a small advantage as well.  13...Ng6  14.d4⩲  Taking the lead in the center. The game resumed with:  14...c5  15.Be3  Rc8  16.Qd2  Qa5  17.dxc5  dxc5  18.Nh5!  when White obtained a small edge due to his bishop pair in Ragger, M @@StartBracket@@2686@@EndBracket@@ -Mastrovasilis, D @@StartBracket@@2603@@EndBracket@@ Vienna 2016 1-0 @@StartBracket@@49@@EndBracket@@. }
12... Bg4 13. h3
{ The next idea is one to remember. White is not merely unpinning himself. }
13... Bxf3 14. gxf3
{ This strange-looking move contains a huge portion of poison. Now that the g-file has been opened we can launch an attack on the hostile king with Kh2 followed by Rg1. }
14... b5 15. Bc2 g6 16. f4
{ The doubled pawn is resolved and we gain the upper hand in the center. White is better here. }
*

