{ White supports the central pawn on e4, in order to play a future d3-d4. Besides, the f1-square is vacated for the knight-manoeuvre @@StartBracket@@Nb1-d2-f1-g3/e3@@EndBracket@@. }
7... a6 8. Ba4
{ Our opponent has to make an important decision. Will he play 8... b5 and 9... d5 or 8... Re8 with the idea of moving the bishop to f8. }
8... Re8
{ 8...Bg4  9.Nbd2  Nd7  10.h3  Bh5  11.Nf1  leads to a transposition to 4...d6 Pin Variation: 5.O-O Bg4. }
9. Nbd2
{ Clearly, White should first get his pieces involved before opening the position with d3-d4. }
9... Bf8
{ We should act wisely here to try to get into our main line  9...b5  10.Bc2  Bf8  11.Nf1  followed by 12.d4. }
10. Nf1 h6
{ Our opponent kind of tricked us by deferring the move b7-b5. In case of b5, Bc2, we would transpose to our main line in which we opt for an instant d3-d4 with the knight on f1. However, here we can't enter this line: }
11. Ng3
{ This topical line is not the line I would like to enter, as I recommend the move d3-d4 before Nf1-g3.   In order to give you an alternative to the surprise weapon  11.d4  , I explain the characteristic ideas in the main line after  11.Ng3  . This will show you where the sore points of the opponent lie, consequently you can play these types of positions. }
11... b5 12. Bc2
{ Moving the bishop to c2 instead of b3 is a matter of taste. For instance,  12.Bb3  Be6  13.Bc2  d5⇆  0-1 @@StartBracket@@67@@EndBracket@@ Firouzja, A @@StartBracket@@2702@@EndBracket@@ -Carlsen, M @@StartBracket@@2876@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020. }
12... d5 { 12...Bb7  13.d4!  ⩲ } 13. exd5
{ Purely checking the pawn structure arising after 13.exd5, it looks like we accept a slightly inferior position. However, there lies an immense power within the white position. The upcoming variations will reveal that the break d2-d4 in connection with Bc2-b3, is extremely dangerous for our adversary. }
13... Qxd5 14. d4
{ The timing of this move seems right, since our opponent is not yet fully coordinated. }
14... Bb7 15. Ne4 { The only move which is causing problems for Black. } 15...
exd4 16. Nxf6+
{ The whole operation allowing gxf6, makes Black walk on eggshells for the further course of the game. }
16... gxf6 17. Qd3 { Threatening mate on h7. } 17... f5 18. Bf4
{ With the sole purpose of completing the development, keeping the initiative. }
18... Bg7 { Here, White could have taken the lead with } 19. Nh4
{ besieging f5. } 19... Re4 20. Qg3
{ Black can't hold his position together and is lost. } *

