20. Bc2
{ To me it seems that this move leads to better chances of success than  20.Bg5  .   20.Bg5  Nh7!  Black manages to swap one of the bishops.  21.Bf4  Nxb3  22.axb3  dxc3  23.bxc3  The position is equal. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@36@@EndBracket@@ Shomoev, A @@StartBracket@@2550@@EndBracket@@ -Alekseev, E @@StartBracket@@2610@@EndBracket@@ Minsk 2017. }
20... d3 21. Bxd3 { The bishop is now hanging on d3. } 21... gxh6 22. b4
{ White couldn't take the knight on f6, now that d3 is hanging. Black has to find one more accurate move to equalize, which proved to be too difficult for the next two strong black players. }
22... Nc6
{ After  22...Nc4?  White is also clearly better after  23.Bxc4  bxc4  24.Qxf6 }
23. Qxf6
{ Black cannot take now on d3 since the knight would be hanging, but he pinned his hopes on the next move... }
23... Bg7 24. Nh5
{ Missed by Black: White is maintaining his extra piece and finally won the game. Volokitin,A @@StartBracket@@2639@@EndBracket@@-Vavulin,M @@StartBracket@@2583@@EndBracket@@ Batumi 2018 1-0 @@StartBracket@@29@@EndBracket@@. }
