{ Purely checking the pawn structure arising after 13.exd5, it looks like we accept a slightly inferior position. However, there lies an immense power within the white position. The upcoming variations will reveal that the break d2-d4 in connection with Bc2-b3, is extremely dangerous for our adversary. }
13... Nxd5
{ Peter Svidler managed to exert insurmountable pressure on his opponent quickly, by means of: }
14. a4 b4 15. Bd2 bxc3 16. bxc3
{ The remaining position looks 'OK' for Black. At first sight, this was my impression at least. Delving deeper into the position, it appears that White can mount the pressure on the soft spots, creating threats. }
16... a5
{ Maybe this move is better, but also here White can make his adversary's life hard. }
17. Rb1 Ba6 18. Ne4
{ Let's take a moment to go through the lowdown of the position. Black's position looks active, but what next move can he play?   In case of  18...Qd7  19.Bxh6  , followed by 20.c4.   After  18...Re6  White can use the pin with  19.Bb3  ,   while after  18...Rb8  19.Rxb8  Qxb8  20.Bb3  Qd8  21.Qc2  with the idea of 22.d4! is very strong. }
18... g6 19. Qc1 { Shooting behind the barricades! } 19... Kh7 20. Bb3
{ This move manifests the massive power of White's pieces. From all sides Black is under siege. Black here jeopardizes losing a queen after Bxd5, Qxd5, Nf6+. }
20... Bg7 { 20...Bxd3?  loses to  21.Bxd5+-  . } 21. Nc5
{ Now that the overloaded f8-bishop had to protect the f6-square, he leaves the c5-square unguarded.   A sad truth for our opponent is, that he is about to lose his strongest minor piece on a6 which means losing control over the light squares. White can follow up with his kingside aggression by means of h2-h4-h5. }
