{ Clearly, White should first get his pieces involved before opening the position with d3-d4. }
9... Bf8
{ We should act wisely here to try to get into our main line  9...b5  10.Bc2  Bf8  11.Nf1  followed by 12.d4. }
10. Nf1 h6
{ Our opponent kind of tricked us by deferring the move b7-b5. In case of b5, Bc2, we would transpose to our main line in which we opt for an instant d3-d4 with the knight on f1. However, here we can't enter this line: }
11. Ng3
{ This topical line is not the line I would like to enter, as I recommend the move d3-d4 before Nf1-g3.   In order to give you an alternative to the surprise weapon  11.d4  , I explain the characteristic ideas in the main line after  11.Ng3  . This will show you where the sore points of the opponent lie, consequently you can play these types of positions. }
11... b5 12. Bc2
{ Moving the bishop to c2 instead of b3 is a matter of taste. For instance,  12.Bb3  Be6  13.Bc2  d5⇆  0-1 @@StartBracket@@67@@EndBracket@@ Firouzja, A @@StartBracket@@2702@@EndBracket@@ -Carlsen, M @@StartBracket@@2876@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020. }
12... d5 { 12...Bb7  13.d4!  ⩲ } 13. exd5
{ Purely checking the pawn structure arising after 13.exd5, it looks like we accept a slightly inferior position. However, there lies an immense power within the white position. The upcoming variations will reveal that the break d2-d4 in connection with Bc2-b3, is extremely dangerous for our adversary. }
13... Nxd5
{ Peter Svidler managed to exert insurmountable pressure on his opponent quickly, by means of: }
14. a4 b4 15. d4
{ This move can become useful in a blitz or rapid game, and when Black is not well informed here. }
15... exd4
{ Black would be better off after  15...bxc3!  16.Nxe5  Nxe5  17.dxe5  cxb2  18.Bxb2  Nb4!  when White can forget about his attacking aspirations. }
16. Rxe8 { Black is underdeveloped and uncoordinated. } 16... Qxe8 17. Qd3
{ Svidler's play is plain and simple.. going for the mate on h7! } 17... g6 18.
cxd4
{ Enginewise, the position is balanced. However, all White's pieces are aimed at the black king. There is still a long road ahead of Black averting all the impending threats. }
18... Bg7 19. Bd2 { Simply completing the development with 20.Re1 } 19... Be6
{ Probably not the best move. But, especially with limited time on the clock, this move seems the most logical one. }
20. Re1
{ I am giving here the exclamation mark for the move to follow, which divulges White's ominous plans on the kingside. Given White's massive attacking potential on the kingside, he could also go for h2-h4-h5, demolishing the foundation of Black's castle. }
20... Qd8 21. Rxe6
{ Naturally, in this blitz game it's hard to repel all the threats. Black should have gone to d7 with his queen. }
21... fxe6 22. Qxg6 { Black is totally overrun on the kingside. } 22... Nf6 23.
Bxh6 Qe7 24. Ng5 { The attackers outnumber the defenders. } 24... Nxd4 25. Nh5
{ 1-0 @@StartBracket@@25@@EndBracket@@ Svidler, P @@StartBracket@@2729@@EndBracket@@ -Gozzoli,Y @@StartBracket@@2604@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020 }
