{ 8...Bg4  9.Nbd2  Nd7  10.h3  Bh5  11.Nf1  leads to a transposition to 4...d6 Pin Variation: 5.O-O Bg4. }
9. Nbd2
{ Clearly, White should first get his pieces involved before opening the position with d3-d4. }
9... Bf8
{ We should act wisely here to try to get into our main line  9...b5  10.Bc2  Bf8  11.Nf1  followed by 12.d4. }
10. Nf1 h6
{ Our opponent kind of tricked us by deferring the move b7-b5. In case of b5, Bc2, we would transpose to our main line in which we opt for an instant d3-d4 with the knight on f1. However, here we can't enter this line: }
11. d4 exd4 12. Nxd4
{ White seized some space and enjoys the more active piece play.   12.cxd4?  is just losing a pawn, because of  12...Rxe4∓  . }
12... Bd7 13. Bc2
{ This is a novelty. Seen before was taking on c6. Guarding the central e4-pawn, which provides us with a space advantage.   13.Nxc6  Bxc6  14.Bxc6  bxc6  15.Ng3  g6  was more than fine for Black in Soumya, S @@StartBracket@@2359@@EndBracket@@ - Mohota, N @@StartBracket@@2260@@EndBracket@@ Chengdu 2017, ½-½ @@StartBracket@@43@@EndBracket@@. Maybe the soundest option for Black, activating the bishop and waiting for the opportunity to play ...d5 to equalize. }
13... Ne5 14. f4 Ng6 15. Ng3
{ White's position is again slightly better because of his active pieces. } *

