[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 d6 5. O-O Be7 6. c3 O-O
{ 6...a6  7.Ba4  O-O  8.Re1  is a transposition to our main line. } 7. Re1
{ White supports the central pawn on e4, in order to play a future d3-d4. Besides, the f1-square is vacated for the knight-maneuver @@StartBracket@@Nb1-d2-f1-g3/e3@@EndBracket@@. }
7... a6 8. Ba4
{ Our opponent has to make an important decision. Will he play  8...b5  and  9... d5 or  8...Re8  with the idea of moving the bishop to f8*. }
8... Re8 9. Nbd2
{ Clearly, White should first get his pieces involved before opening the position with d3-d4. }
9... b5 10. Bc2
{ The bishop looks rather passive on c2, but it covers the central and besieged pawn on e4. Thus, it helps us in the preparation of the pawn-push d3-d4. }
10... Bf8
{ The positions arising resemble the ones from the previous chapter with the only difference that Black didn't spend time on Bd7. }
11. Nf1
{ Here again, Black has choice. He can continue with 11.. h6 or 11..Bb7.  There are so many possible ways to go here. Let's give you another popular line..   11.d4  Bb7  12.a4  Nb8  13.Bd3  c6  14.b3  when we get a typical Breyer position with chances for both sides. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@48@@EndBracket@@ Svidler,P @@StartBracket@@2723@@EndBracket@@-Carlsen, M @@StartBracket@@2863@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020 }
11... h6
{ 11...Bb7  12.Ng3  The difference with the main line of the Zaitsev, White included here h3 and d4, and the B is on b3, forcing Black to deal with the Ng5 threat, including h7-h6, but on the other hand White has to waste time on Bb3-c2 to protect e4. Only then the d2N can be moved to g3. Looking at our position on the board, the N is already on g3, and we don't really miss the h2-h3 move.  12...g6   12...Nb8  In the style of the Breyer-variation of the Ruy Lopez, improving the knight's position to d7.  13.a4  Nbd7  Instructive is the recent online game:  14.b4!?  The plan consisting of expanding on the queenside is a sound alternative to the topical Breyer-variations arising after 14.d4.  14...g6   14...d5!?  leads to double-edged positions.  15.Bb3  White's play consists of combining play on the queen- together with the kingside.  15...Bg7  16.h4!?  As far as I am concerned, the plan h2-h4-h5 can be considered as highly promising and be seen as an entirely new approach against Black's kingside in these types of Ruy-Lopez positions.  13.d4!  Seizing space and the initiative in the center.  13...Bg7  The break with d6-d5 leads to disaster for Black.   13...d5  14.exd5  It appears that Black is not ready yet for the opening of the position. White could as well start with Bg5 when Black would have gotten in trouble too.  14...Qxd5   14...Nxd5  this move leads to disaster for Black. He wins back the e5-pawn, but against a high price.  15.dxe5  Bg7  16.e6!  causing a weakening of the opponent's kingside.  15.Bg5!  Black's pieces will be harassed from all angles.  15...Bg7  16.Bb3  A very pleasant tempo is gained in this open position.  14.d5  Nb8  This move has been mostly seen in tournament practice.   14...Ne7  The knight has less bright prospects on e7 than on d7.  15.b3!  anticipating on c7-c6..  15...c6  Black tries to break our center.  16.c4  but after this move, we keep the center and the farthest point of the phalanx intact. 1/2 @@StartBracket@@18@@EndBracket@@-1/2 @@StartBracket@@31@@EndBracket@@.  15.b3!  Since Black tries to enhance his influence in the center by means of c7-c6, so we use the prophylaxis to maintain our center by responding with c3-c4.  15...c6  16.c4!  Our pawn chain stays intact. See the model games section for more detailed notes. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@35@@EndBracket@@ Fressinet,L @@StartBracket@@2654@@EndBracket@@-Johannessen,L @@StartBracket@@2536@@EndBracket@@ Germany 2008.   11...d5  12.exd5  This move seems most natural to me, as Black has to spend time on h7-h6 whereas we will build up the pressure on black's weak spots.  12...Nxd5  13.d4!  Each move we carefully deliberate about the move breaking free. It seems that this is the right timing playing this move, as Black is quite unorganized.  13...exd4  14.Ng5!?  The arising positions are sketchy for our opponent. White will take in on f7.  14...Nf6   14...h6?  15.Bh7+!  Kh8  16.Nxf7++-  15.Bb3  This bishop has transformed into a monster.  15...Rxe1  16.Qxe1→  Though the engine might not be convinced by our advantage, I truly believe that Black is having a hard time defending against white's attack.   11...g6  12.d4!  Bg7  13.d5!  In these closed positions, slightly resembling the King's Indian Defense, the rook seems somewhat misplaced on e8.  13...Ne7  14.a4  Playing on two flanks..  14...Bd7  15.Ng3  The knight conducts an excellent function on g3, halting f7-f5 while guarding e4. Deploying the c-pawn to hit the center, would have the disadvantage that the a2-diagonal will be opened..  15...c6  16.dxc6  Bxc6  17.axb5  axb5  18.Rxa8  Black cannot take back with the queen, since the d6-pawn would be hanging.  18...Bxa8  19.h4!  This new idea, seen throughout these chapters, causes Black sleepless nights. }
12. d4
{ This is not the main line, but - after examining the other possible lines and responses for Black as suggested by - amongst others - Kannappan in his book regarding the Modernized Berlin Wall, it’s White's best attempt in the quest for an advantage. }
12... exd4
{ 12...Bg4!?  13.Ng3!  Allowing a doubled pawn on f3, but counting on the arising attacking chances along the g-file.  13...exd4  14.cxd4  Bxf3  15.gxf3→   12...Bb7  13.Ng3  g6  14.h4!  This new idea manifests itself on several places in these topical Ruy-Lopez positions. We all know the old set-up with h3 and Nh2-g4 @@StartBracket@@in the characteristic Fischer-style@@EndBracket@@ building up pressure on the kingside. h2-h4 is a radical attempt to blow up the kingside with h4-h5, endorsed by the bishop from b3.   12...g6  13.h3  Bg7  14.Ng3  Supporting the most important and central point on e4.  14...Bb7  15.a4!  As more often, White plays on both flanks.  15...Rb8  16.Bd3!  The second weak point in black's position: b5. }
13. cxd4 Bg4
{ At first glance, an utterly annoying pin. However, there is a cure against it! }
14. Ng3 Nh5 15. Be3
{ That may be, but the backward c-pawn is still a source of trouble for Black. }
15... Nxg3
{ 15...g6  with the idea of further increasing the pressure on the d4-pawn.  16.h3!  Now that d4 is protected, White can take back with the queen after 16..B:f3. Now that d4 is protected, White can take back with the queen after 16..B:f3.  16...Nxg3  17.hxg4  Nxe4  Now there follow a lot of forced tactics of which Black cannot escape.  18.Bxe4  Rxe4  19.Qc2 }
16. hxg3
{ In any case, Black wants to move his knight @@StartBracket@@to a5 or b4@@EndBracket@@ as he is urged to undo himself of the backward pawn on c7. }
16... Na5
{ 16...Nb4  17.Bb1  c5  18.d5  White seizes a lot of space, and the poor knight on b4 has to consider his retreat.  18...Qf6  Attacking the pawn on b2.  19.Qd2⩲  White is better here. Black should waste time on bringing the b4-knight back in the house, whilst White will exploit his pawn majority on the kingside by means of Nh2, f4, Nf3 and e5. }
17. b3 { With the obvious idea to stop the knight to c4. } 17... c5 18. d5
{ The Black knight has bad prospects on a5. He cannot reach a square of importance. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@59@@EndBracket@@ Piecusch,R-Weber Widmer,D @@StartBracket@@2299@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2010 }
