{ The positions arising resemble the ones from the previous chapter 4...d6 5.O-O Bd7, with the only difference that Black didn't spend time on Bd7. }
11. Nf1
{ Here again, Black has a choice. He can continue with  11...h6  or  11...Bb7  .   There are so many possible ways to go here. Let's give you another popular line.  11.d4  Bb7   11...exd4  12.cxd4  Bg4  13.Nf1  g6  14.Ng3  1-0 @@StartBracket@@40@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ - Carlsen, M @@StartBracket@@2862@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020.  12.a4  Nb8  13.Bd3  c6  14.b3  when we get a typical Breyer position with chances for both sides. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@48@@EndBracket@@ Svidler, P  @@StartBracket@@2723@@EndBracket@@ - Carlsen, M @@StartBracket@@2863@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020. }
11... Bb7 12. Ng3
{ The difference with the main line of the Zaitsev, White included there h3 and d4 and the Bishop is on b3, forcing Black to deal with the Ng5 threat, including h7-h6, but on the other hand, White has to waste time on Bb3-c2 to protect e4.  Only then the d2 knight can be moved to g3. Looking at our position on the board, the knight is already on g3, and we don't really miss the h2-h3 move. }
12... Nb8
{ In the style of the Breyer variation of the Ruy Lopez, improving the knight's position to d7.   12...h6  13.d4  transposes to the lines after  @@StartFEN@@r1bqrbk1/2p2ppp/p1np1n2/1p2p3/4P3/2PP1N2/PPB2PPP/R1BQRNK1 b - - 3 11@@EndFEN@@  11...h6  12.d4  Bb7  13.Ng3  .   12...h6  13.Nf5?!  d5  14.Qe2  Ne7!  with equal play in 0-1 @@StartBracket@@38@@EndBracket@@ Van Foreest,J @@StartBracket@@2682@@EndBracket@@ - Sevian,S @@StartBracket@@2660@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2020. }
13. a4 Nbd7 14. b4
{ The plan consisting of expanding on the queenside is a sound alternative to the topical Breyer variations arising after  14.d4  . }
14... g6
{ 14...d5!?  leads to double-edged positions, but Black isn't fully mobilized for the fight in the center yet. }
15. Bb3
{ White's play consists of combining play on the queen- together with the kingside. }
15... h6 16. Qc2
{ The new idea of  16.h4!?  breaking up the pawn chain seems very promising too. }
16... c5 17. Qa2
{ Aesthetically a beautiful move, raising the tension on the diagonal and weak point f7. }
17... Qe7 18. Nh4
{ This idea of sacrificing the knight on f5, endorsed by the battery of bishop and queen, should give White the upper hand. }
18... d5 19. exd5 Qd6 20. Nhf5
{ This is even more powerful than  20.Ne4  , which was played in Kobalia - Ahvenjarvi, Tallinn 2016. }
20... gxf5 21. Nxf5
{ White's powerplay reaps its fruits. Black can't face White's knight and pressure along the a2-g8 diagonal. }
21... Qb6 22. a5 { driving the queen off to a worse position. } 22... Qd8 23.
d6 { Black's position becomes more crippled every move. } *

