15... Bg7 16. h4
{ As far as I am concerned, the plan h2-h4-h5 can be considered as highly promising and be seen as an entirely new approach against Black's kingside in these types of Ruy Lopez positions.   16.h3  Nb6  17.a5  Releasing the tension on b5 but gaining some space.  17...Nbd7  18.Bg5  h6  19.Be3  d5  20.Qd2  As seen before, White is going ahead with putting pressure on the kingside of Black.  20...Kh7  21.Rad1  Qe7  22.Qa2  White exerted massive pressure across the diagonal a2-f7 and went on to win in Tabatabaei, M  @@StartBracket@@2629@@EndBracket@@ - Wagner, D @@StartBracket@@2581@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 1-0 @@StartBracket@@42@@EndBracket@@. }
16... c5 17. Ng5 { The target is in sight. } 17... Rf8 18. h5
{ White is maximally exerting pressure on the black kingside. As far as I am concerned, this is an entirely new approach against these Ruy Lopez set-ups. }
18... Qc7
{ White's main threat comes to light after  18...d5  19.h6!  Black can't let his bishop be cornered, but the alternative won't be much to his taste as well.  19...Bxh6  20.Nxf7  simply wins material.  20...Rxf7  21.Bxh6±  . }
19. h6
{ Even though, the black queen stepped out of the discovered attack after Nxf7, White's tactics haven't stopped. }
19... Bxh6 20. Bxf7+ { Quite the contrary.. } 20... Rxf7
{ 20...Kh8  simply loses to  21.Ne6+-  . } 21. Ne6
{ Both the queen and bishop are hanging. } 21... Qc8 22. Bxh6
{ Even though after this extensive sequence of moves, White is still not any material up, his strategy flourished. Black's king's position is like Suisse cheese and many promising plans show themselves, e.g. d3-d4. }
