{ 12...h6  13.d4  transposes to the lines after  @@StartFEN@@r1bqrbk1/2p2ppp/p1np1n2/1p2p3/4P3/2PP1N2/PPB2PPP/R1BQRNK1 b - - 3 11@@EndFEN@@  11...h6  12.d4  Bb7  13.Ng3  .   12...h6  13.Nf5?!  d5  14.Qe2  Ne7!  with equal play in 0-1 @@StartBracket@@38@@EndBracket@@ Van Foreest,J @@StartBracket@@2682@@EndBracket@@ - Sevian,S @@StartBracket@@2660@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2020. }
13. d4 { Seizing space and the initiative in the center. } 13... Bg7 14. d5
{ 14.h3  is another way of playing. Notwithstanding the previous note, concerning the usefulness of the inclusion in regards to h2-h3, in this particular position, it can help White to move the bishop to e3 without being worried about ...Ng4.  14...exd4  15.cxd4  Nb4  16.Bb1  c5  17.d5  a5  18.a3  Na6  19.Be3  a4  20.Bc2  Qd7  21.Qd2  left White for choice in in 1-0 @@StartBracket@@79@@EndBracket@@ Kobalia, M @@StartBracket@@2672@@EndBracket@@ - Mikhalevski, V @@StartBracket@@2584@@EndBracket@@ Aix les Bains 2011. }
14... Ne7 { The knight has less bright prospects on e7 than on d7. } 15. b3
{ Anticipating ...c7-c6. } 15... c6 { Black tries to break our center. } 16. c4
{ but after this move we keep the center and the farthest point of the phalanx intact. }
16... Bc8 17. Bd2 { A consolidating move, connecting the rooks. } 17... Rf8 18.
Bd3
{ Because of the space advantage White is slightly better here. Vallejo Pons,F @@StartBracket@@2660@@EndBracket@@ -Miton,K @@StartBracket@@2628@@EndBracket@@ Heraklion 2007 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@31@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4...d6 5.O-O Be7 Main Line 8...Re8 9.Nbd2 With 9...b5"]
[Black "4...d6 5.O-O Be7 Main Line 8...Re8 9.Nbd2 With 9...b5 − 11...Bb7 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 d6 5. O-O
{ Here our plan of taking on c6 will not offer us salvation: Black can just take back with the b-pawn. Therefore, we take in the Ruy Lopez set-up with c3 and d4. }
5... Be7 6. c3 O-O
{ 6...a6  7.Ba4  O-O  8.Re1  is a transposition to our main line. } 7. Re1
{ White supports the central pawn on e4, in order to play a future d3-d4. Besides, the f1-square is vacated for the knight-manoeuvre @@StartBracket@@Nb1-d2-f1-g3/e3@@EndBracket@@. }
7... a6 8. Ba4
{ Our opponent has to make an important decision. Will he play 8...b5 and 9...d5 or 8...Re8 with the idea of moving the bishop to f8. }
8... Re8
{ 8...Bg4  9.Nbd2  Nd7  10.h3  Bh5  11.Nf1  leads to a transposition to 4...d6 Pin Variation: 5.O-O Bg4. }
9. Nbd2
{ Clearly, White should first get his pieces involved before opening the position with d3-d4. }
9... b5 10. Bc2
{ The bishop looks rather passive on c2, but it covers the central and besieged pawn on e4. Thus, it helps us in the preparation of the pawn-push d3-d4. }
10... Bf8
{ The positions arising resemble the ones from the previous chapter 4...d6 5.O-O Bd7, with the only difference that Black didn't spend time on Bd7. }
11. Nf1
{ Here again, Black has a choice. He can continue with  11...h6  or  11...Bb7  .   There are so many possible ways to go here. Let's give you another popular line.  11.d4  Bb7   11...exd4  12.cxd4  Bg4  13.Nf1  g6  14.Ng3  1-0 @@StartBracket@@40@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ - Carlsen, M @@StartBracket@@2862@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020.  12.a4  Nb8  13.Bd3  c6  14.b3  when we get a typical Breyer position with chances for both sides. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@48@@EndBracket@@ Svidler, P  @@StartBracket@@2723@@EndBracket@@ - Carlsen, M @@StartBracket@@2863@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020. }
11... Bb7 12. Ng3
{ The difference with the main line of the Zaitsev, White included there h3 and d4 and the Bishop is on b3, forcing Black to deal with the Ng5 threat, including h7-h6, but on the other hand, White has to waste time on Bb3-c2 to protect e4.  Only then the d2 knight can be moved to g3. Looking at our position on the board, the knight is already on g3, and we don't really miss the h2-h3 move. }
12... g6
{ 12...h6  13.d4  transposes to the lines after  @@StartFEN@@r1bqrbk1/2p2ppp/p1np1n2/1p2p3/4P3/2PP1N2/PPB2PPP/R1BQRNK1 b - - 3 11@@EndFEN@@  11...h6  12.d4  Bb7  13.Ng3  .   12...h6  13.Nf5?!  d5  14.Qe2  Ne7!  with equal play in 0-1 @@StartBracket@@38@@EndBracket@@ Van Foreest,J @@StartBracket@@2682@@EndBracket@@ - Sevian,S @@StartBracket@@2660@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2020. }
13. d4 { Seizing space and the initiative in the center. } 13... Bg7 14. d5
{ 14.h3  is another way of playing. Notwithstanding the previous note, concerning the usefulness of the inclusion in regards to h2-h3, in this particular position, it can help White to move the bishop to e3 without being worried about ...Ng4.  14...exd4  15.cxd4  Nb4  16.Bb1  c5  17.d5  a5  18.a3  Na6  19.Be3  a4  20.Bc2  Qd7  21.Qd2  left White for choice in in 1-0 @@StartBracket@@79@@EndBracket@@ Kobalia, M @@StartBracket@@2672@@EndBracket@@ - Mikhalevski, V @@StartBracket@@2584@@EndBracket@@ Aix les Bains 2011. }
14... Nb8 { This move has been mostly seen in tournament practice. } 15. b3
{ Since Black tries to enhance his influence in the center by means of c7-c6, so we use the prophylaxis to maintain our center by responding with c3-c4. }
15... c6 16. c4 { Our pawn chain stays intact. } 16... Qc7 17. Be3
{ Simply the best square for the bishop. } 17... Nbd7 18. h3
{ White not only secures the bishop on e3 without being harassed by a possible Ng4, this little pawn move serves attacking purposes as well. A well-timed Nf3-h2-g4 when the time is ripe will be played. }
18... Rec8 19. Rc1
{ Useful prophylaxis in case that the c-file would be opened, meanwhile putting the rook on the same file as the queen. }
19... Bf8 { After  19...Qa5  20.Bb1  White keeps the better position. } 20. Bd3
{ Before White undertakes action on the kingside, everything should be under control on the queenside. The pawns and squares are well protected now. Please have a look in the Model Games section for some cunning ideas in Fressinet,L @@StartBracket@@2654@@EndBracket@@ -Johannessen,L  @@StartBracket@@2536@@EndBracket@@ Germany 2008, 1-0 @@StartBracket@@35@@EndBracket@@. }
