{ The bishop looks rather passive on c2, but it covers the central and besieged pawn on e4. Thus, it helps us in the preparation of the pawn-push d3-d4. }
10... Bf8
{ The positions arising resemble the ones from the previous chapter 4...d6 5.O-O Bd7, with the only difference that Black didn't spend time on Bd7. }
11. Nf1
{ Here again, Black has a choice. He can continue with  11...h6  or  11...Bb7  .   There are so many possible ways to go here. Let's give you another popular line.  11.d4  Bb7   11...exd4  12.cxd4  Bg4  13.Nf1  g6  14.Ng3  1-0 @@StartBracket@@40@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ - Carlsen, M @@StartBracket@@2862@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020.  12.a4  Nb8  13.Bd3  c6  14.b3  when we get a typical Breyer position with chances for both sides. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@48@@EndBracket@@ Svidler, P  @@StartBracket@@2723@@EndBracket@@ - Carlsen, M @@StartBracket@@2863@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020. }
11... g6 12. d4
{ 12.d4  is rarely played, but not necessarily weaker than the more frequently seen  12.a4  .   For example  12.a4!?  Bb7  13.Bg5  h6  14.Bh4  Bg7  15.Ne3  Qd7  16.b4  Ne7   16...Nd8!  17.Nd2  Ne6⇆  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@61@@EndBracket@@ Fressinet, L @@StartBracket@@2711@@EndBracket@@ - Amin, B @@StartBracket@@2628@@EndBracket@@ Saint Quentin 2014.  17.Bb3  Nh5⇆  1-0 @@StartBracket@@26@@EndBracket@@ Carlsen, M @@StartBracket@@2847@@EndBracket@@ -Yip, C @@StartBracket@@2430@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2021. }
12... Bg7 { 12...h6  transposes to the 11...h6 12.d4! g6 variation. } 13. d5
{ In these closed positions, slightly resembling the King's Indian Defense, the rook seems somewhat misplaced on e8. }
13... Ne7 14. a4 { Playing on two flanks.. } 14... Bd7 15. Ng3
{ The knight does an excellent job on g3, halting ...f7-f5 while guarding the e4-pawn. }
15... c5 16. h3 Qb8 17. Nh2
{ A common theme in these Ruy Lopez type of positions. White prepares f2-f4 meanwhile the knight can be deployed on g4. }
17... h6 18. Rf1 bxa4 19. Bxa4
{ White obtained a stable advantage in Volokitin,A @@StartBracket@@2677@@EndBracket@@-Kryvoruchko, Y @@StartBracket@@2640@@EndBracket@@ Kiev 2011, 1-0 @@StartBracket@@72@@EndBracket@@. You can find more detailed analysis how to play these type of positions in the video. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4...d6 5.O-O Be7 Main Line 8...Re8 9.Nbd2 With 9...b5"]
[Black "4...d6 5.O-O Be7 Main Line 8...Re8 9.Nbd2 With 9...b5 − 11...h6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 d6 5. O-O
{ Here our plan of taking on c6 will not offer us salvation: Black can just take back with the b-pawn. Therefore, we take in the Ruy Lopez set-up with c3 and d4. }
5... Be7 6. c3 O-O
{ 6...a6  7.Ba4  O-O  8.Re1  is a transposition to our main line. } 7. Re1
{ White supports the central pawn on e4, in order to play a future d3-d4. Besides, the f1-square is vacated for the knight-manoeuvre @@StartBracket@@Nb1-d2-f1-g3/e3@@EndBracket@@. }
7... a6 8. Ba4
{ Our opponent has to make an important decision. Will he play 8...b5 and 9...d5 or 8...Re8 with the idea of moving the bishop to f8. }
8... Re8
{ 8...Bg4  9.Nbd2  Nd7  10.h3  Bh5  11.Nf1  leads to a transposition to 4...d6 Pin Variation: 5.O-O Bg4. }
9. Nbd2
{ Clearly, White should first get his pieces involved before opening the position with d3-d4. }
9... b5 10. Bc2
{ The bishop looks rather passive on c2, but it covers the central and besieged pawn on e4. Thus, it helps us in the preparation of the pawn-push d3-d4. }
10... Bf8
{ The positions arising resemble the ones from the previous chapter 4...d6 5.O-O Bd7, with the only difference that Black didn't spend time on Bd7. }
11. Nf1
{ Here again, Black has a choice. He can continue with  11...h6  or  11...Bb7  .   There are so many possible ways to go here. Let's give you another popular line.  11.d4  Bb7   11...exd4  12.cxd4  Bg4  13.Nf1  g6  14.Ng3  1-0 @@StartBracket@@40@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ - Carlsen, M @@StartBracket@@2862@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020.  12.a4  Nb8  13.Bd3  c6  14.b3  when we get a typical Breyer position with chances for both sides. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@48@@EndBracket@@ Svidler, P  @@StartBracket@@2723@@EndBracket@@ - Carlsen, M @@StartBracket@@2863@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020. }
11... h6 12. d4
{ This is not the main line, but - after examining the other possible lines and responses for Black as suggested by - amongst others - Kannappan in his book regarding the Modernized Berlin Wall, it's White's best attempt in the quest for an advantage. }
12... Bg4
{ Black is using the fact that White has not @@StartBracket@@yet@@EndBracket@@ played h3. However, as we see in the following moves, White can use this fact to his advantage too. }
13. Ng3
{ Allowing a doubled pawn on f3, but counting on the arising attacking chances along the g-file. }
13... exd4 14. cxd4 Bxf3 15. gxf3 { is a transposition to the main line. }
15... Nb4
{ Black's idea of Nb4 and c5 is common - as well in the Ragozin line of the Ruy Lopez. }
16. Bb1 c5 17. d5
{ It may seem that Black has excellent play on the dark squares after g6, h5, h4 followed up by Nh5 etc. However, we will downplay this sequence by anticipating on these ideas in time. }
17... a5 { Otherwise the knight would have been trapped after a3. } 18. a3 Na6
{ Now Black will try to move his knight to d3 or b3 after c4. White can prevent all of this, by demolishing the connected black queenside pawns. }
19. a4 bxa4 20. Rxa4 Nc7 21. Bd3 g6 22. Bd2
{ Now the a5-pawn will be lost and Black will not obtain sufficient compensation. }
