{ The positions arising resemble the ones from the previous chapter 4...d6 5.O-O Bd7, with the only difference that Black didn't spend time on Bd7. }
11. Nf1
{ Here again, Black has a choice. He can continue with  11...h6  or  11...Bb7  .   There are so many possible ways to go here. Let's give you another popular line.  11.d4  Bb7   11...exd4  12.cxd4  Bg4  13.Nf1  g6  14.Ng3  1-0 @@StartBracket@@40@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ - Carlsen, M @@StartBracket@@2862@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020.  12.a4  Nb8  13.Bd3  c6  14.b3  when we get a typical Breyer position with chances for both sides. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@48@@EndBracket@@ Svidler, P  @@StartBracket@@2723@@EndBracket@@ - Carlsen, M @@StartBracket@@2863@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020. }
11... h6 12. d4
{ This is not the main line, but - after examining the other possible lines and responses for Black as suggested by - amongst others - Kannappan in his book regarding the Modernized Berlin Wall, it's White's best attempt in the quest for an advantage. }
12... Bb7 13. Ng3
{ So far there is nothing new in this set-up. The knight takes in its natural square in these Ruy Lopez types of positions. The only difference which can be marked is that we have lost one tempo on d2-d3-d4, compared to the open Spanish @@StartBracket@@or Ruy Lopez@@EndBracket@@ positions where White plays d2-d4 instantly. However, we haven't spent time on h2-h3. }
13... g6 14. h4
{ This new idea manifests itself in several places in these topical Ruy Lopez positions. We all know the old setup with h3 and Nh2-g4 @@StartBracket@@in the characteristic Fischer-style@@EndBracket@@ building up pressure on the kingside. h2-h4 is a radical attempt to blow up the kingside with h4-h5, endorsed by the bishop from b3. }
14... h5 15. Bg5
{ So, as it appears, h6-h5 contains its flaws too. White greedily uses the g5-square for his pieces. }
15... Bg7 16. d5
{ Obviously, White is ready now for the upcoming developments in the center. }
16... Ne7 17. a4 { We are fighting a war on two fronts. } 17... c6 18. axb5
{ The reason behind all the exchanges is that we are aiming for an open position in which we can put pressure on d6, while we maintain all of our good prospects on the kingside. }
18... axb5 19. Rxa8 Bxa8 { 19...Qxa8?  20.dxc6  when d6 is hanging. } 20. dxc6
{ Opening the a2-g8 diagonal for our bishop. } 20... Bxc6 21. Qd2
{ The contours of our kingside attack are slowly taking shape.. } 21... Qc7 22.
Bb3
{ Black is in a bind, as he can barely move. The break d5 is losing a pawn }
22... Rd8 23. Bxf6 { Creating an entrance square for our queen on h6. } 23...
Bxf6 24. Qh6
{ There only is one defensive resource available, namely Bg7, since White threatened Nxh5. }
24... Bg7 25. Bxf7+
{ The final blow. Crucial is the availability of the g5-square for our pieces. }
25... Kxf7 26. Ng5+ { First the bishop and now the knight comes in. } 26... Kf6
27. Nxh5# *

