{ As usual, White plays on both flanks.  Anand didn't encounter a lot of problems after  15.Be3  exd4  16.cxd4  Nb4  17.Bb1  Nxe4  18.Nxe4  Bxe4  19.Bxe4  Rxe4  20.Qb3  c5  with unclear play in: Morozevich, A @@StartBracket@@2741@@EndBracket@@-Anand, V @@StartBracket@@2786@@EndBracket@@ Monte Carlo 2005, ½-½ @@StartBracket@@28@@EndBracket@@ }
15... Rb8 16. Bd3 { The second weak point in Black's position: b5. } 16... exd4
17. cxd4 Nb4 18. Bb1 c5
{ These types of positions are familiar to all the Ruy Lopez - Ragozin players. }
19. axb5 axb5 20. Bf4
{ With a keen eye for minor differences, i.e. the rook on b8. The difference with the previous line @@StartBracket@@exd4 without Rb8@@EndBracket@@ is that the rook on b8 is protecting the b7-bishop.  20.Bd2  Nc6  21.e5  Nd5  22.e6  f5  23.Bxf5  gxf5  24.Nxf5  Qf6  and the position remains balanced as Nxd6 is no longer so devastating. }
20... Rc8 21. Qd2 { A strong alternative would have been  21.Ra7!?  ⩲ } 21...
g5 22. Be3
{ We ought to be satisfied with the serious weakening by Black's last move. A bit more speculative, but not necessarily worse, was  22.Bxg5!?  hxg5  23.Qxg5  Nh7  24.Qg4→  1-0 @@StartBracket@@35@@EndBracket@@ Flores, D @@StartBracket@@2408@@EndBracket@@ - Sanal, V @@StartBracket@@2731@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2020. }
22... Nxe4 { This is not working tactically. } 23. Nxe4 Bxe4 24. Bxg5
{ The discovered attack serves White well. } 24... hxg5 25. Bxe4
{ White restores the material balance and has a decisive advantage: Black's kingside is weakened and the opposite-colored bishops make White's kingside attack only stronger. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4...d6 5.O-O Be7 Main Line 8...Re8 9.Nbd2 With 9...b5"]
[Black "4...d6 5.O-O Be7 Main Line 8...Re8 9.Nbd2 With 9...b5 − 11...h6 #12"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 d6 5. O-O
{ Here our plan of taking on c6 will not offer us salvation: Black can just take back with the b-pawn. Therefore, we take in the Ruy Lopez set-up with c3 and d4. }
5... Be7 6. c3 O-O
{ 6...a6  7.Ba4  O-O  8.Re1  is a transposition to our main line. } 7. Re1
{ White supports the central pawn on e4, in order to play a future d3-d4. Besides, the f1-square is vacated for the knight-manoeuvre @@StartBracket@@Nb1-d2-f1-g3/e3@@EndBracket@@. }
7... a6 8. Ba4
{ Our opponent has to make an important decision. Will he play 8...b5 and 9...d5 or 8...Re8 with the idea of moving the bishop to f8. }
8... Re8
{ 8...Bg4  9.Nbd2  Nd7  10.h3  Bh5  11.Nf1  leads to a transposition to 4...d6 Pin Variation: 5.O-O Bg4. }
9. Nbd2
{ Clearly, White should first get his pieces involved before opening the position with d3-d4. }
9... b5 10. Bc2
{ The bishop looks rather passive on c2, but it covers the central and besieged pawn on e4. Thus, it helps us in the preparation of the pawn-push d3-d4. }
10... Bf8
{ The positions arising resemble the ones from the previous chapter 4...d6 5.O-O Bd7, with the only difference that Black didn't spend time on Bd7. }
11. Nf1
{ Here again, Black has a choice. He can continue with  11...h6  or  11...Bb7  .   There are so many possible ways to go here. Let's give you another popular line.  11.d4  Bb7   11...exd4  12.cxd4  Bg4  13.Nf1  g6  14.Ng3  1-0 @@StartBracket@@40@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ - Carlsen, M @@StartBracket@@2862@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020.  12.a4  Nb8  13.Bd3  c6  14.b3  when we get a typical Breyer position with chances for both sides. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@48@@EndBracket@@ Svidler, P  @@StartBracket@@2723@@EndBracket@@ - Carlsen, M @@StartBracket@@2863@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020. }
11... h6 12. d4
{ This is not the main line, but - after examining the other possible lines and responses for Black as suggested by - amongst others - Kannappan in his book regarding the Modernized Berlin Wall, it's White's best attempt in the quest for an advantage. }
12... exd4 13. cxd4 Bg4
{ At first glance, an utterly annoying pin. However, there is a cure against it! }
14. Ng3 Bxf3 15. gxf3 { is a transposition to the main line. } *

