{ 8...Bg4  9.Nbd2  Nd7  10.h3  Bh5  11.Nf1  leads to a transposition to 4...d6 Pin Variation: 5.O-O Bg4. }
9. Nbd2
{ Clearly, White should first get his pieces involved before opening the position with d3-d4. }
9... b5 10. Bc2
{ The bishop looks rather passive on c2, but it covers the central and besieged pawn on e4. Thus, it helps us in the preparation of the pawn-push d3-d4. }
10... Bf8
{ The positions arising resemble the ones from the previous chapter 4...d6 5.O-O Bd7, with the only difference that Black didn't spend time on Bd7. }
11. Nf1
{ Here again, Black has a choice. He can continue with  11...h6  or  11...Bb7  .   There are so many possible ways to go here. Let's give you another popular line.  11.d4  Bb7   11...exd4  12.cxd4  Bg4  13.Nf1  g6  14.Ng3  1-0 @@StartBracket@@40@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ - Carlsen, M @@StartBracket@@2862@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020.  12.a4  Nb8  13.Bd3  c6  14.b3  when we get a typical Breyer position with chances for both sides. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@48@@EndBracket@@ Svidler, P  @@StartBracket@@2723@@EndBracket@@ - Carlsen, M @@StartBracket@@2863@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020. }
11... h6 12. d4
{ This is not the main line, but - after examining the other possible lines and responses for Black as suggested by - amongst others - Kannappan in his book regarding the Modernized Berlin Wall, it's White's best attempt in the quest for an advantage. }
12... exd4 13. cxd4 Bg4
{ At first glance, an utterly annoying pin. However, there is a cure against it! }
14. Ng3 Nh5
{ Kannappan mentions that Black will put pressure on the d4-pawn and create active play. }
15. Be3
{ That may be, but the backward c-pawn is still a source of trouble for Black. }
15... g6 { with the idea of further increasing the pressure on the d4-pawn. }
16. h3
{ Now that d4 is protected, White can take back with the queen after  16...Bxf3 }
16... Nxg3 17. hxg4
{ A strange position occurred on the board. The knight is almost trapped. }
17... Nxe4
{ Now there follow a lot of forced tactics of which Black cannot escape. } 18.
Bxe4 Rxe4 19. Qc2 { The double attack can only be parried in one way. } 19...
Qe8
{ Only the following tactical blow guarantees White a comfortable advantage for the rest of the game. }
20. Bxh6 { White won the pawn back while Black's position remains ruinous. }
20... Rxe1+ 21. Rxe1 Qd7
{ The only move for Black. The queen cannot give up on the c6-knight. } 22.
Bxf8 Rxf8 23. Rc1
{ With great force the rook moves to the c-file. Now that the knight has to move, the c7-pawn can be taken. }
