{ By winning the pawn, White spent time on taking on e5, and retreat. As a result, Black's strategy comprises of a quick development of the pieces in order to gain the supremacy. One of the key elements here is that when White succeeds to disentangle from the pin after Bg4, our prospects are bright.   7...Bd6  Our adversary is pointing his bishop indirectly on h2.  8.Nc4!  Leaving the trodden paths after the mostly played 8.Nf3. It requires some courage to place the knight far off the king. However, we can always swap the most dangerous attacking piece on d6 when things get a little too steamy around our king.  8...Bg4   8...Bxh2+?  9.Kxh2  Ng4+  10.Kg1  This is the simplest, however 10.Kg3 would lead to a better position as well.  10...Qh4  11.Bf4!  The white bishop prevents Qh4-h2.  9.Qe1  With this move White is keeping all his options open. We can choose between @@StartBracket@@A@@EndBracket@@ the solid 10. f3, or @@StartBracket@@B@@EndBracket@@ the more aggressive 10.f4, in the meantime just being a pawn up without any counterplay for our opponent.   7...Qe7  8.Nf3  We are about to face the pin after Bg4 and should brace ourselves.  8...Bg4  9.h3!  Bh5  10.Bf4!  I truly believe that this is a very solid and strong move. The bishop serves attacking @@StartBracket@@the pawn on c7@@EndBracket@@ as defensive purposes @@StartBracket@@guarding the king@@EndBracket@@. }
8. Nf3 Bg4
{ Without any doubt, this pin encompasses the most danger for White. Now it's our turn to find the right answer to our adversary's aggressivity.   8...a5  9.Be3  Bd6  Black could better refrain from exchanges with his attacking aspirations and being a pawn down.  10.h3  It's a continuing story  @@StartBracket@@as so often seen in the first course of this series about the Ruy Lopez Exchange@@EndBracket@@: the implementation of h2-h3 is for positional reasons in our favor.  10...a4  11.a3  c5  12.Nc3  c6  13.Re1  Qc7  14.Qd2  b5  15.e5!  After all, the weak c5-pawn doesn't do Black any good.  15...Bxe5  16.Bxc5 }
9. h3
{ It's a continuing story @@StartBracket@@as so often seen in the first course of this series about the Ruy Lopez Exchange@@EndBracket@@: the implementation of h2-h3 is for positional reasons in our favor. }
9... Bh5 10. Be3
{ We will proceed with 11.Nbd2 on the next move, when the harmony is back between White's pieces. }
10... Bxe3
{ 10...Qe7  11.Bxc5  By a couple of exchanges, White reduces the tension on his position and plays himself gradually free.  11...Qxc5  12.Nbd2  Rad8  13.Qc1!  Unpinning herself and aiming for f4. We are clearly better here.   10...Bb6  In an attempt to maintain the tension, Black avoids the exchange of bishops.  11.Nbd2  The knights are well coordinated, and the queen can step out of the pin.  11...Re6  12.Qe1!  Qd7  13.a4  13...a5  14.Nh2  White obtained a massive advantage here, the pawn phalanx c2-d3-e4 is of granite. Moreover, black's counterplay is hard to find and I don't see how he is going to face f2-f4.   10...Bd6  This seemingly not unnatural move can be encountered in the same way as in the other lines discussed @@StartBracket@@i.e. 10..Bb6, 10..Qe7 and 10..Bxe3@@EndBracket@@.  11.Nbd2  b5!?  Stopping White from moving out, putting him in a squeeze.  12.a4  a5  13.Qc1  Bxf3   13...h6  14.Nd4!  14.Nxf3  1-0 @@StartBracket@@29@@EndBracket@@. }
11. fxe3
{ The f-file is now opened for the rook, and we commence our operations for the final stage of the game. There is nothing left of Black's compensation and White has a free hand in the upcoming play. }
11... Nd7
{ 11...Qd6  This move has been played once, but there aren't any soft spots in our defense to be revealed.  12.Qe1!  Stepping out of the pin.. I couldn't find any counterplay for Black here. Given the fact that White is also a pawn up, things turn out quite desperate for him. }
