{ This move has been played once, but there aren't any soft spots in our defense to be revealed. }
12. Qe1
{ Stepping out of the pin. I couldn't find any counterplay for Black here. Given the fact that White is also a pawn up, things turn out quite desperate for him. }
12... Bxf3 13. Rxf3 Nd7 14. Nd2 Qb4 15. Nb3
{ In this correspondence game the Black player played the 'inhuman' move  15...Qxe1  , after which White entered an endgame with simply one full pawn up. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Anti-Berliner Gambit 6...O-O"]
[Black "4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Anti-Berliner Gambit 6...O-O 7.Nxe5 Re8 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. O-O O-O
{ This move introduces a gambit; Black sacrifices a pawn in return for smooth developments and active play. }
7. Nxe5
{ Our opponent leaves a pawn 'en prise'. Be courageous and snatch the pawn, apply the greed-and-grit strategy and defend well... for you are destined for a great reward! }
7... Re8
{ By winning the pawn, White spent time on taking on e5, and retreat. As a result, Black's strategy comprises of a quick development of the pieces to gain the supremacy. One of the key elements here is that when White succeeds to disentangle from the pin after Bg4, our prospects are bright. }
8. Nf3
{ The best move, guarding the king. The fact that we are susceptible for the pin by  8...Bg4  , is something we have to bear with. }
8... Bg4
{ Without any doubt, this pin encompasses the most danger for White. Now it's our turn to find the right answer to our adversary's aggressivity. }
9. h3
{ It's a continuing story @@StartBracket@@as so often seen in the first course of this series about the Ruy Lopez Exchange@@EndBracket@@: the implementation of h2-h3 is for positional reasons in our favour. }
9... Bh5 10. Be3
{ We will proceed with Nbd2 on the next move when the harmony is back between White's pieces. }
10... Bxe3 11. fxe3
{ The f-file is now opened for the rook, and we commence our operations for the final stage of the game. There is nothing left of Black's compensation and White has a free hand in the upcoming play. }
11... Nd7 12. Qe1 { From here we do our job on automatic pilot. } 12... f6 13.
a4 { The knight manoeuvre  13.Nh4!?  would be good as well. } 13... c5 14. Nbd2
b6 15. Qg3
{ The pawn sacrifice turned out badly for Black.   Nothing remained of his compensation Balshaw, A -Taylor, T 2010:  15...Rc8  16.b3  Kh8  17.Rf2  a6  18.Raf1  Qe7  19.Nh4  Qe6  20.a5  b5  21.d4  Qc6  22.c4  when White got everything he could dream of in Balshaw, A @@StartBracket@@2207@@EndBracket@@-Taylor,T @@StartBracket@@2358@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2010, 1-0 @@StartBracket@@85@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Bd6"]
[Black "Introduction: 4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Bd6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. O-O
{ Now that the e5-pawn is poisoned, White brings his king in safety, breathing new life in taking on e5. Moreover, the bishop is not ideally placed on c5 now and often it goes back to d6 - Black losing one move. }
6... Bd6
{ Black has to defend the e5-pawn and by this move the pawn is protected. As a result, Black is losing valuable time. }
7. Bg5
{ Before Black can regroup his knight @@StartBracket@@e.g. Nd7, and then possibly to f8 and e6@@EndBracket@@ he is facing a difficult choice. Should he unpin his knight with his king still in the center? }
7... h6
{ 7...Bg4  8.h3  Useful as always. Especially in this particular line as soon will be revealed.  8...Bh5  9.Nbd2  The knights protecting each other. That makes an offense on the kingside possible.  9...h6  10.Be3  The 3 minor pieces act harmoniously.  10...O-O  11.g4!  Here I would like to come up with this strong new idea.  11...Bg6  12.Kh1!  Making room for the rook.  12...a5  13.Rg1!  The rook on g1, it's called imminent danger. }
8. Bh4 Bg4
{ 8...Be6  9.d4!  We grab the opponent by the throat as he is not yet unpinned, and he cannot take on d4 because of e5.  9...g5   9...Be7  10.Nc3!?  This is my recommendation over the recently played online game between Giri and Radjabov.  10...exd4   10...Nxe4  11.Bxe7  after a long and forced line, White gets a promising attack.  11...Nxc3  12.Bxd8  White's mole inside black's troops escapes - after capturing the queen - by taking the pawn on c7, whereas Black does the same by escaping via b2.  12...Nxd1  13.Bxc7  Nxb2  14.Rfb1!  The essence of white's strategy is to invade on the 7th rank.  11.Nxd4  The position looks promising for White.  11...Qd7  12.Nxe6  Depriving Black of the bishops.  12...Qxe6  13.f4  Obviously, White has the better pawn structure.  13...Nd7  14.Bxe7  Qxe7  15.Qd4⩲  Black is stuck with his structural weakness: the doubled pawns.  10.dxe5  The best continuation, as our e4-pawn is hanging @@StartBracket@@as well@@EndBracket@@.  10...gxh4  11.exd6  It turns out that after a lot of exchanges our pawn structure is to be prevailed.  11...cxd6  12.Nc3  Completing the development, while we encounter  12...Nh5  with  13.Nd4  Nf4  and  14.Nce2!   8...O-O  Black is revealing his cards in an early stage.  9.Nbd2  Qe7  10.Re1  A mysterious move, but not without power.  10...c5  11.c3  Instead of playing the knight to e3, we pay all our attention to the center.  11...Rd8  12.d4!  Due to the rook on e1, Black cannot take with the e-pawn on d4.  12...cxd4  13.cxd4  c6   13...exd4??  14.e5+-  14.dxe5  White is going to capitalize on his pawn majority in the center.  14...Bxe5  15.Qc1!  Unpinning himself and preparing for N:e5. Now, Be5-c7 is not possible as White will win a piece with e4-e5. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@85@@EndBracket@@ Yusin, J-Zueger,A @@StartBracket@@1777@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2017   8...Qe7!?  9.Nbd2  This position appeared on top level, although in an online game. Please be aware of the different move orders.  9...Bg4  10.Nc4  A very interesting alternative would be   10.h3!?  Bh5  11.d4!  O-O-O  12.Re1  leads to sharp and concrete play, and should be crystallized out in future tournament play.  12...Qe6  13.c4  13...Bxf3  14.Nxf3  Qxc4   14...exd4??  15.e5  15.dxe5  Bxe5  16.Nxe5±  16...Qb5  17.Nxc6!  17...Qxc6  1-0 @@StartBracket@@60@@EndBracket@@ Carlsen,M  @@StartBracket@@2855@@EndBracket@@-Nakamura,H @@StartBracket@@2736@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2021  18.Qf3  O-O-O  11.h3  11...Bh5  12.Re1!?  This move hasn't been tried in practice yet and is a novelty over Firouzja-Nakamura @@StartBracket@@2020@@EndBracket@@. There follows a sample line.  12...g5  13.Bg3  Exerting pressure on the central point e5. Please note that g4 can be met with Nfxe5.  13...Qe6   13...g4?  14.Nfxe5!  gxh3  15.Qd2!  A fascinating plan, as will be laid out in the next couple of moves.  15...hxg2  16.Qf4!  I find white's plan beautiful: he will squash his adversary on the black squares by Nxd6 after which the other knight re-establishes on c4.  14.Qe2!  Ne8  15.Qe3!  By the queen maneuver of Qd1-e2-e3, the major point of concern vanished. Black can take the knight and will try to throw his kingside pawns forward whereas White does the same thing on the queenside. }
9. Nbd2
{ The knights on d2 and f3.. rocky solid! On top of that White is flexible in moving the d2-knight to c4 or f1. }
9... g5
{ 9...Qe7  This is a transposition to Firouzja-Nakamura @@StartBracket@@2020@@EndBracket@@. Please see 8..Qe7. }
10. Bg3
{ The bishop is not at all passively placed on g3, as it engages on the e5-pawn. }
10... Nh5 { After   10...Qe7  White simply follows his plan by  11.Nc4 } 11.
Nc4 { Again, the weak link on e5 needs guidance. } 11... Nxg3
{ Nakamura's choice, but not the best.   11...Nf4  12.h3  This move may seem weird, as Black is so dominant on the kingside. As a matter of fact, we are taking over there by a mysterious series of moves.  12...Bh5  13.Bxf4!  Casting a quick glance on this position, taking on f4 thereby opening the g-file, seems the last thing we should do.  13...gxf4  In case of   13...exf4  14.d4  we take over in the center.  14...Qd7  15.c3  Stabilizing our central pawns.  15...f6  16.Re1  O-O-O  ⩲  We have a small but stable advantage here. We can follow up with Qa4 and e4-e5, creating a strong outpost on e5 for the knights.  14.g4!!  14...fxg3  Black has no choice, since White is aiming to take on e5.   14...Rg8  15.Kh2!  15.fxg3  White's pawn structure improved considerably after the exchange. The f7-pawn is backward, meanwhile f5 an excellent outpost for white's pieces.  15...Rg8  16.Kh2  The king proves a strong defender of the g3 and h3 pawns. Black is left with the ruins. We can follow up with Qd2, and Nf3-h4-f5 or Nxe5. }
12. fxg3
{ Came this a surprise for Nakamura? White opens the f-file and a knight maneuver to f5 is in the air. }
12... Qe7 13. h3
{ This is a strong novelty over Aronian's game against Nakamura, and comprises the entire different concept of playing on the kingside.   13.c3  O-O-O  14.b4  Kb8  15.a3  h5⇆  0-1 @@StartBracket@@28@@EndBracket@@ Aronian,L @@StartBracket@@2773@@EndBracket@@-Nakamura,H @@StartBracket@@2736@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020 }
13... Bd7 14. Nxd6+
{ Black's main strength of the bishop pair has vanished and his pawn structure is worse than White's. }
14... cxd6 15. Nd2 { The knight is on its quest for his most natural square. }
15... Be6
{ 15...O-O-O  The king is still not entirely safe on c8. White keeps the option of a pawn advance on the queenside.  16.Qe2  Kb8  17.Nc4  Yep, the knight goes once more to f5!  17...f6  18.Ne3⩲   15...h5  Halting the queen outbreak to h5, which could turn out suffocating for Black.  16.Nc4⩲  Effortlessly we switch to another plan: rerouting the knight via d2-c4-e3 to f5. }
16. Qh5 { Preventing h5, and preparing Rf1 or Re1. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Bd6"]
[Black "4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Bd6 7.Bg5 Bg4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5
{ The bishop is placed actively on c5 and renders conquering the pawn on e5 less attractive for White. }
5. Bxc6
{ It's a recurring story: likewise in the Ruy Lopez Exchange @@StartBracket@@part 1@@EndBracket@@, we trade off the bishop for the knight in an early phase of the game, inflicting damages to Black's pawn structure, whereas we avoid - amongst others - the old but currently relevant variation after  5.O-O  Nd4!?  . }
5... dxc6 6. O-O
{ Now that the e5-pawn is poisoned @@StartBracket@@  6.Nxe5??  Qd4-+  @@EndBracket@@,  White brings his king to safety, breathing new life in taking on e5.  Moreover, the bishop is not ideally placed on c5 now and often it goes back to d6 - with Black losing one move.   Another popular option for White is  6.Nbd2  , but like in the Ruy Lopez Exchange, I prefer a quick short castling.  Why? We kind of finalize our development, keeping our options open for different set-ups such as c3-d4, Bg5 or Be3, and Nbd2-f1-g3, Na3-c4 or Nc3. }
6... Bd6
{ Black has to defend the e5-pawn and by this move the pawn is protected. As a result, Black is losing valuable time. }
7. Bg5
{ Before Black can regroup his knight @@StartBracket@@e.g. Nd7, and then possibly to f8 and e6@@EndBracket@@ he is facing a difficult choice. Should he unpin his knight with his king still in the center? }
7... Bg4 8. h3
{ Useful as always. Especially in this particular line as soon will be revealed. }
8... Bh5 9. Nbd2
{ The knights protecting each other. That makes an offense on the kingside possible. }
9... h6 10. Be3 { The 3 minor pieces act harmoniously. } 10... O-O 11. g4
{ Here I would like to come up with this strong new idea.   Our reference game continued with  11.Nc4!?  b6  12.a4  Qe7  13.Bd2⩲  1-0 @@StartBracket@@62@@EndBracket@@ Merrheim, X @@StartBracket@@2377@@EndBracket@@ -Susedenko, V @@StartBracket@@2364@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2014. }
11... Bg6 12. Kh1 { Making room for the rook. } 12... a5 13. Rg1
{ The rook on g1, it's called imminent danger. } 13... a4 14. Rg2
{ Useful prophylaxis: we await affairs while keeping the option open to double or move the rook to h2 }
14... b5 15. g5 { Time to rock the boat! } 15... hxg5 16. Bxg5
{ White created himself a great attack on Black's king. One of the moves to be played: Nh4 or Qe2 and doubling. }
16... c5 { 16...Bh5?!  17.Nf1±  . } 17. Qe2
{ So, it became doubling after all.. } 17... Re8 18. Rag1
{ with superior attacking chances. All White's pieces are taking part in the assault. }
