7... h6 8. Bh4 { Maintaining the pin. } 8... Be6
{ 8...g5  9.Bg3  Bg4  leads to a transposition of moves. } 9. d4
{ We grab the opponent by the throat as he is not yet unpinned, and he cannot take on d4 because of e5.   Recently, Firouzja played the following line and won, but the acquired position out of the opening was double-edged:   9.Nbd2  Black can now smoothly start his attacking operations, while not having to care about any tension in the center:  9...g5  10.Bg3  Nd7  We should get acquainted with Black's knight manoeuvre by now.  11.d4  Qf6!  Fortifying e5 and preparing to hide the king to a safer place.  12.Re1  O-O-O  1-0 @@StartBracket@@36@@EndBracket@@ Firouzja, A @@StartBracket@@2723@@EndBracket@@-Le, Q @@StartBracket@@2713@@EndBracket@@ Moscow 2019. }
9... Be7 10. Nc3
{ This is my recommendation over the recently played online game between Giri and Radjabov.   10.Bxf6  This leads to complications.  10...gxf6  11.dxe5  Qxd1   11...Rg8!?  with counterplay.  12.Rxd1  fxe5  13.Nxe5  Bf6  14.Nd3  with a slightly better position for White, as Black should still prove his full compensation for the pawn. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@58@@EndBracket@@ Giri, A @@StartBracket@@2780@@EndBracket@@-Radjabov, T @@StartBracket@@2765@@EndBracket@@ chess24. com INT 2021. }
10... Nxe4 11. Bxe7
{ After a long and forced line, White gets a promising attack. } 11... Nxc3 12.
Bxd8
{ White's mole inside Black's troops escapes - after capturing the queen - by taking the pawn on c7, whereas Black does the same by escaping via b2. }
12... Nxd1 13. Bxc7 Nxb2 14. Rfb1
{ The essence of White's strategy is to invade on the 7th rank. } 14... Nc4 15.
Rxb7
{ Of course, Black can castle here but the toll of a full pawn would be high. }
15... exd4 16. Nxd4
{ Now the bishop is in danger. Black doesn't get the time to castle. } 16...
Bd5 17. Re1+ { With an attack. } *

