[Round "?"]
[White "4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Bd6"]
[Black "4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Bd6 7.Bg5 h6 8.Bh4 O-O"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5
{ The bishop is placed actively on c5 and renders conquering the pawn on e5 less attractive for White. }
5. Bxc6
{ It's a recurring story: likewise in the Ruy Lopez Exchange @@StartBracket@@part 1@@EndBracket@@, we trade off the bishop for the knight in an early phase of the game, inflicting damages to Black's pawn structure, whereas we avoid - amongst others - the old but currently relevant variation after  5.O-O  Nd4!?  . }
5... dxc6 6. O-O
{ Now that the e5-pawn is poisoned @@StartBracket@@  6.Nxe5??  Qd4-+  @@EndBracket@@,  White brings his king to safety, breathing new life in taking on e5.  Moreover, the bishop is not ideally placed on c5 now and often it goes back to d6 - with Black losing one move.   Another popular option for White is  6.Nbd2  , but like in the Ruy Lopez Exchange, I prefer a quick short castling.  Why? We kind of finalize our development, keeping our options open for different set-ups such as c3-d4, Bg5 or Be3, and Nbd2-f1-g3, Na3-c4 or Nc3. }
6... Bd6
{ Black has to defend the e5-pawn and by this move the pawn is protected. As a result, Black is losing valuable time. }
7. Bg5
{ Before Black can regroup his knight @@StartBracket@@e.g. Nd7, and then possibly to f8 and e6@@EndBracket@@ he is facing a difficult choice. Should he unpin his knight with his king still in the center? }
7... h6 8. Bh4 { Maintaining the pin. } 8... O-O
{ Black is revealing his cards in an early stage.   8...g5  9.Bg3  Bg4  leads to a transposition of moves. }
9. Nbd2 Qe7 10. Re1 { A mysterious move, but not without power. } 10... c5
{ Using his doubled pawn in a good way preventing 11. d4. However, we are not sailing a different course. }
11. c3
{ Instead of playing the knight to e3, we pay all our attention to the center. }
11... Rd8 12. d4
{ Due to the rook on e1, Black cannot take with the e-pawn on d4. } 12... cxd4
13. cxd4 c6 { 13...exd4??  14.e5+-  . } 14. dxe5
{ White is going to capitalize on his pawn majority in the center.   14.Qc1!  With the same idea as in the game, would have led to an advantage all the same. }
14... Bxe5 15. Qc1
{ Unpinning himself and preparing for Nxe5. Now, Be5-c7 is not possible as White will win a piece with e4-e5. }
15... Bg4 16. Nxe5 Qxe5 17. h3
{ First controlling the g4-square to prevent any nasty counters. } 17... Bh5
18. Nb3
{ White's positional plus is massive, both on the queen- as on the kingside. Black has to reckon with both f4 and Nc5. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@85@@EndBracket@@ Yusin,J-Zueger,A @@StartBracket@@1777@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2017 }
*

[Event "?"]
