[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Bd6"]
[Black "4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Bd6 7.Bg5 h6 8.Bh4 Qe7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5
{ The bishop is placed actively on c5 and renders conquering the pawn on e5 less attractive for White. }
5. Bxc6
{ It's a recurring story: likewise in the Ruy Lopez Exchange @@StartBracket@@part 1@@EndBracket@@, we trade off the bishop for the knight in an early phase of the game, inflicting damages to Black's pawn structure, whereas we avoid - amongst others - the old but currently relevant variation after 5.0-0 Nd4!? }
5... dxc6 6. O-O
{ Now that the e5-pawn is poisoned @@StartBracket@@  6.Nxe5??  Qd4-+  @@EndBracket@@,  White brings his king to safety, breathing new life in taking on e5.  Moreover, the bishop is not ideally placed on c5 now and often it goes back to d6 - with Black losing one move.   Another popular option for White is  6.Nbd2  , but like in the Ruy Lopez Exchange, I prefer a quick short castling.  Why? We kind of finalize our development, keeping our options open for different set-ups such as c3-d4, Bg5 or Be3, and Nbd2-f1-g3, Na3-c4 or Nc3. }
6... Bd6
{ Black has to defend the e5-pawn and by this move the pawn is protected. As a result, Black is losing valuable time. }
7. Bg5
{ Before Black can regroup his knight @@StartBracket@@e.g. Nd7, and then possibly to f8 and e6@@EndBracket@@ he is facing a difficult choice. Should he unpin his knight with his king still in the center? }
7... h6 8. Bh4 { Maintaining the pin. } 8... Qe7
{ 8...g5  9.Bg3  Bg4  leads to a transposition of moves. } 9. Nbd2
{ This position appeared on the top level, although in an online game. Please be aware of the different move orders. }
9... Bg4
{ This position can be reached after @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/ppp2pp1/2pb1n1p/4p3/4P2B/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RN1Q1RK1 b kq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Bg4  9.Nbd2  Qe7  .  This is a transposition to Firouzja-Nakamura @@StartBracket@@2020@@EndBracket@@. }
10. Nc4
{ A very interesting alternative would be  10.h3!?  Bh5  11.d4!  O-O-O  12.Re1  which leads to sharp and concrete play and should be crystallized out in future tournament play. }
10... O-O-O 11. h3
{ I received some questions from the followers of part 1 of this series @@StartBracket@@the Ruy Lopez Exchange, in which we encounter similar positions as here@@EndBracket@@ of what is the right timing playing h2-h3.  Here I can say that h3 can be useful, as it drives off the bishop to h5 after which the knight cannot occupy, but involves risk too, namely the quick opening of the g-file after ...g7-g5-g4. }
11... Bh5 12. Re1
{ This move hasn't been tried in practice yet and is a novelty over Firouzja-Nakamura @@StartBracket@@2020@@EndBracket@@.   There follows a sample line.  12.Qe2  g5  13.Bg3  Rhg8!  I find the upcoming lines highly inconvenient for White. It appears he lacks a clear plan.   13...g4?!  this is a mistake, as White's pieces reign after occupying the central point of e5.  14.hxg4   14.Nfxe5!  gxh3  15.Qe3  hxg2  16.Qxa7  gxf1=Q+  17.Kxf1  when White is winning after Qa8 or Na5.  17...Nd7  18.Nxc6  bxc6  19.Qa6+  Kb8  20.Na5+-  14...Bxg4  15.Bh4  here Black could get the upper hand by unpinning the knight by  15...Qe6⩱  .  0-1 @@StartBracket@@63@@EndBracket@@ Firouzja,A @@StartBracket@@2728@@EndBracket@@ - Nakamura,H @@StartBracket@@2736@@EndBracket@@ Lichess.org INT 2020. }
12... g5 13. Bg3 { Exerting pressure on the central point e5. } 13... g4 14.
Nfxe5
{ Not fearing ghosts after gxh3 and hxg2. My only disclaimer is that all the lines ought to be calculated or remembered carefully. }
14... gxh3 15. Qd2
{ A fascinating plan, as will be laid out in the next couple of moves. } 15...
hxg2 16. Qf4
{ I find White's plan beautiful: he will squash his adversary on the dark squares by Nxd6 after which the other knight re-establishes on c4. }
16... Qe6 { On its way to h3 and h1. } 17. Nxd6+ cxd6 18. Nc4
{ Most awkward for our poor opponent is the poor position of his king. } 18...
Qh3 { Too little, too late. } 19. Bh2
{ Closing the gates. White is winning. For example, after  19...Ne8  20.e5!  the black king is just too exposed. }
