14... fxg3 { Black has no choice, since White is aiming to take on e5. } 15.
fxg3
{ White's pawn structure improved considerably after the exchange. The f7-pawn is backward, meanwhile f5 an excellent outpost for white's pieces. }
15... Rg8 16. Kh2
{ The king proves a strong defender of the g3 and h3 pawns. Black is left with the ruins. We can follow up with Qd2, and Nf3-h4-f5 or Nxe5. }
16... Qe7 17. Nxd6+
{ 'Sometimes you have to give something to gain something better'. In this position we improve our opponent's structure, but by the exchange we simplify and as a result the weaknesses on the kingside get even more exposed. }
17... cxd6 18. Qd2 { Threatening Qxh6. } 18... Qe6 19. Nh4
{ White's position is superior, he is the lord and master over the f-file. } *

