[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Qd6 7.c3 Sidelines"]
[Black "Introduction: 4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Qd6 7.c3 Sidelines"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. O-O Qd6
{ This queen can serve Black perfectly as a surprise weapon, and it has been used in practice by the GM's Almasi, Sokolov and Naiditsch. Its attacking aspirations are clear: after the bishop of c8 is released to e6 or g4, Black castles long. }
7. c3
{ Now that the queen has taken a position on d6, it's worthwhile to open the center with d4. }
7... Qe7
{ Moving the queen back is or very subtle or stupid. In fact, the queen compromised our pawn structure and steps back from the threat d3-d4. Pretty subtle, I would say :@@EndBracket@@   7...O-O  8.d4!  8...Bb6  9.a4  Grabbing space on the queenside.  9...a5  10.Qc2  We are following a correspondence game. Black can't take on d4, because of e4-e5.  10...Nd7  11.Na3  c4, the perfect square for the knight.  11...Qe6  12.Re1  It transpires that White has enough time to stabilize before undertaking action.  12...Re8  13.Bd2!  This move contains a deep plan, as seen in the further part of this line.  13...f6  14.b3!  Paving the way for the knight jump to c4.  14...Qg4  15.Nc4  15...exd4   15...Qh5  16.dxe5!  Again this strategy, isolating the e5-pawn.  16...fxe5  17.Nxb6  Because of the opening of the diagonal and pressure on f2, this bishop should be in the wooden box of chess pieces.  17...Nxb6  18.Re3  Consolidating, freeing the e1-square for the knight.  18...Nd7  19.c4⩲  Vacating c3 for the bishop.  16.cxd4  Black will try to break the center down. However, he disposes over limited means.  16...Nf8  17.h3  Increasing our grip on the light squares.  17...Qg6  18.Qd3⩲  The threat of Bxh3 has been neutralized with Nh4 and Qxh3. Please have a look at the model games section for more comments on this highly instructive game. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@47@@EndBracket@@ Vozda,J @@StartBracket@@2488@@EndBracket@@-Postl,R @@StartBracket@@2242@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2009   7...Bb6  8.d4!  Without hesitation, White hits the center.  8...Bg4  We cannot take on e5 now, as our opponent will take on d1 and e4.  9.Nbd2!  A multi-purpose move: White protects f3 and e4, but can strive for more aggressive aims after Nc4.  9...Nd7  Black solidifies his central point: e5.  10.Nc4  Qe7  11.a4  Once again, this move proves itself, grabbing important space.  11...a5  12.h3  As well a useful move, trying to unpin and grabbing space on the kingside.  12...Bxf3   12...Bh5?!  White will win the e5-pawn, whilst our opponent want get sufficient compensation in return.  13.g4!  Bg6  14.Nfxe5  Of course, a pawn is a pawn!  14...Nxe5  15.Nxe5  13.Qxf3  Here again, within short terms White increased his spatial influence of the board dramatically.  13...exd4  Black is giving up his central e5-pawn, relying upon a counterattack of the White's central pawns.  14.Nxb6!  Nxb6  15.cxd4⩲ }
8. Nxe5 Qxe5 9. d4
{ In case of Bxd4, cxd4, it turns out that White has the better odds because of his strong center. }
9... Qe7 10. dxc5 Qxc5 11. Qd4 Qxd4
{ 11...Qe7  12.Bg5!  when Black has to cope with a nagging pin and disadvantage }
12. cxd4
{ The better pawn structure secures our advantage. Please notice that Black should refrain from his knight getting pinned after Nxe4?, Re1. }
12... Be6 { 12...Nxe4??  13.Re1+- } 13. Nc3
{ Making the knight on f6 redundant . } 13... O-O-O 14. Rd1
{ Not merely defending the pawn, but as well looking for his own chances by e.g. d4-d5 when the time comes. }
14... Nd7 15. d5
{ This move conceals a massive inner strength. The black king can get in huge trouble in case of Bf4 and Rac1 and after cxd5 exd5. }
15... cxd5 16. exd5
{ With the exchange of these pawns White, it transpires that the adversary's king is in danger. The soft spot is now the pawn on c7. }
16... Bf5 17. Bf4
{ How should Black avert the threat of Rac1 and Nb5? White has excellent attacking chances. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Qd6 7.c3 Sidelines"]
[Black "4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Qd6 7.c3 O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ This variation - after 3..Nf6 - is called the 'Berlin Defense' or the 'Berlin Wall', due to its supersolid nature. Rooted in the family of the Ruy Lopez opening @@StartBracket@@i.e. 3.Bb5@@EndBracket@@, the Berlin Defense was first seen in practice anno 1801, and examined by @@StartBracket@@it's in the name - who else?@@EndBracket@@ Berliners, as recorded in history. }
4. d3
{ After this move, we set foot into the 'Anti-Berlin'. We are keeping the queens on the board for the moment, sidestepping the forced lines arising after 4..Nxe4, amongst others the supersolid ending c.q. the 'Berlin Wall', deployed 4 times by Kramnik against Kasparov with great success in the World Championship Match @@StartBracket@@London, 2000@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Bc5
{ The bishop is placed actively on c5 and renders conquering the pawn on e5 less attractive for White. }
5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. O-O
{ Now that the e5-pawn is poisoned @@StartBracket@@  6.Nxe5??  Qd4-+  @@EndBracket@@,  White brings his king to safety, breathing new life in taking on e5.  Moreover, the bishop is not ideally placed on c5 now and often it goes back to d6 - with Black losing one move.   Another popular option for White is  6.Nbd2  , but like in the Ruy Lopez Exchange, I prefer a quick short castling.  Why? We kind of finalize our development, keeping our options open for different set-ups such as c3-d4, Bg5 or Be3, and Nbd2-f1-g3, Na3-c4 or Nc3. }
6... Qd6 7. c3
{ Now that the queen has taken position on d6, it's worthwhile to open the center with d4. }
7... O-O 8. d4
{ Assumingly, this is a highly promising continuation. Black's coordination seems to be missing. }
8... Bb6 9. a4 { Grabbing space on the queenside. } 9... a5 10. Qc2
{ We are following a correspondence game. Black can't take on d4, because of e4-e5. }
10... Nd7 { 10...exd4??  11.e5  winning a piece. } 11. Na3
{ c4, the perfect square for the knight. } 11... Qe6 12. Re1
{ It transpires that White has enough time to stabilize before undertaking action. }
12... Re8 13. Bd2
{ This move contains a deep plan, as seen in the further part of this line. }
13... f6 14. b3 { Paving the way for the knight jump to c4. } 14... Qg4 15. Nc4
{ We are following the correspondence game Vozda vs Postl. The previous queen move to g4 may be deemed extraordinary. Notwithstanding, it doesn't change much to our strategy. }
15... Qh5 16. dxe5 { Again this strategy, isolating the e5-pawn. } 16... fxe5
17. Nxb6
{ Because of the opening of the diagonal and pressure on f2, this bishop should be in the wooden box of chess pieces. }
17... Nxb6 18. Re3 { Consolidating, freeing the e1-square for the knight. }
18... Nd7 19. c4 { Vacating c3 for the bishop. } 19... Nf8 20. Bc3
{ Frequently seen, likewise in the first course of this series, the e5-pawn is under siege. }
20... Ng6 21. Ne1 { The square d3 is an excellent base for the knight. } 21...
b6 22. Nd3 { White is slightly better due to is better pawn structure. } *

