[White "4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Qd6 7.c3 Sidelines"]
[Black "4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Qd6 7.c3 O-O #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ This variation - after 3..Nf6 - is called the 'Berlin Defense' or the 'Berlin Wall', due to its supersolid nature. Rooted in the family of the Ruy Lopez opening @@StartBracket@@i.e. 3.Bb5@@EndBracket@@, the Berlin Defense was first seen in practice anno 1801, and examined by @@StartBracket@@it's in the name - who else?@@EndBracket@@ Berliners, as recorded in history. }
4. d3
{ After this move, we set foot into the 'Anti-Berlin'. We are keeping the queens on the board for the moment, sidestepping the forced lines arising after 4..Nxe4, amongst others the supersolid ending c.q. the 'Berlin Wall', deployed 4 times by Kramnik against Kasparov with great success in the World Championship Match @@StartBracket@@London, 2000@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Bc5
{ The bishop is placed actively on c5 and renders conquering the pawn on e5 less attractive for White. }
5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. O-O
{ Now that the e5-pawn is poisoned @@StartBracket@@  6.Nxe5??  Qd4-+  @@EndBracket@@,  White brings his king to safety, breathing new life in taking on e5.  Moreover, the bishop is not ideally placed on c5 now and often it goes back to d6 - with Black losing one move.   Another popular option for White is  6.Nbd2  , but like in the Ruy Lopez Exchange, I prefer a quick short castling.  Why? We kind of finalize our development, keeping our options open for different set-ups such as c3-d4, Bg5 or Be3, and Nbd2-f1-g3, Na3-c4 or Nc3. }
6... Qd6 7. c3
{ Now that the queen has taken position on d6, it's worthwhile to open the center with d4. }
7... O-O 8. d4
{ Assumingly, this is a highly promising continuation. Black's coordination seems to be missing. }
8... Bb6 9. a4 { Grabbing space on the queenside. } 9... a5 10. Qc2
{ We are following a correspondence game. Black can't take on d4, because of e4-e5. }
10... Nd7 { 10...exd4??  11.e5  winning a piece. } 11. Na3
{ c4, the perfect square for the knight. } 11... Qe6 12. Re1
{ It transpires that White has enough time to stabilize before undertaking action. }
12... Re8 13. Bd2
{ This move contains a deep plan, as seen in the further part of this line. }
13... f6 14. b3 { Paving the way for the knight jump to c4. } 14... Qg4 15. Nc4
{ We are following the correspondence game Vozda vs Postl. The previous queen move to g4 may be deemed extraordinary. Notwithstanding, it doesn't change much to our strategy. }
15... exd4 16. cxd4
{ Black will try to break the center down. However, he disposes over limited means. }
16... Nf8 17. h3 { Increasing our grip on the light squares. } 17... Qg6 18.
Qd3
{ The threat of Bxh3 has been neutralized with Nh4 and Qxh3. Please have a look at the Model Games section for more comments on this highly instructive game. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@47@@EndBracket@@ Vozda,J @@StartBracket@@2488@@EndBracket@@-Postl,R @@StartBracket@@2242@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2009 }
*

