[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Qd6 7.c3 Bb6 & Bg4 Main Lines"]
[Black "Introduction: 4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Qd6 7.c3 Bb6 & Bg4 Main Lines"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. O-O Qd6
{ In part I of this series concerning the Ruy Lopez Exchange variation, Black had a similar issue protecting the e5-pawn. And, also there, he resorted to Qd6 to guard the central foot soldier. Additionally, Black is preparing long castling. }
7. c3
{ Now that the queen has taken position on d6 where it is prone to be attacked by white's pieces, it's worthwhile to open the center with d4. }
7... Bg4
{ Probably the best move as it is preventing the pawn push in the center with d3-d4. White should be on its qui vive, since after O-O-O the d3-pawn is a matter of concern. }
8. Nbd2
{ One may wonder why Black can't take on d3. Well, a highly complicated line follows in which White takes on e5. }
8... Nd7
{ 8...Qxd3  9.Nxe5  The board is on fire.. one may wonder: what would Alexey Shirov play here?  9...Qe2!  Peculiar enough, Black can avoid material losses.   9...Bxd1??  10.Nxd3!  White is winning material. Both of the bishops are hanging.  10...Be2  11.Nxc5  Bxf1  12.Kxf1  10.Nxg4  Black is obliged to take back with the queen, since after Qxd1 there is an immediate check on f6.  10...Qxg4   10...Bxf2+  11.Qxg4!  After the queen's exchange, White unleashes his pieces.  11...Nxg4  12.Nb3  Black has to make a hard call. In case of the bishop retreat from the a7/g1 diagonal, he will suffer in the ending because of his worse pawn structure.   8...O-O-O  9.Nc4  This position appeared twice in  @@StartBracket@@correspondence@@EndBracket@@ practice.  9...Qe6   9...Qxd3  This doesn't work for Black, but White should be careful how to take on e5.  10.Qxd3  Rxd3  11.Ncxe5!  White is winning material here.  10.Ncxe5  Nxe4  11.Qc2!  chasing away the e4-knight, meanwhile preparing d4 and evt. Ng5.  11...Nf6  12.d4!  Our adversary should watch his steps. In case of Bd6, we play Ng5 and xf7.  12...Bxf3  13.Nxf3  Bd6  14.Re1!  Qg4  15.c4!  An ingenious move, in which suddenly has every chance on obtaining an even larger advantage. The clue behind white's strategy is that the black bishop is restricted in its scope.   8...Qe6!?  9.h3  8..Qe6 appeared 3 times, merely in correspondence games. It is a useful prophylaxis against Nc4  9...Bh5  The next line was tried once in a correspondence game.  10.Qb3  I would like to follow the only @@StartBracket@@correspondence@@EndBracket@@ game played here.  10...Qxb3  11.axb3!?  This is a novelty.  11...Nd7  12.b4  In this case the doubled pawn is definitely not a weakening of the structure! The open a-file can be used for the rooks.  12...Be7  13.d4!  This strong and instructive move resolves the backward d3-pawn. Black faces a difficult choice: allow the deterioration of the structure after f6, dxe5, fxe5, or allowing the knight to d4 after exd4, Nxd4.  13...f6   13...exd4?!  14.Nxd4  We get two active knights on b3 and d4. Suddenly black's position is deteriorating rapidly.  14...f6  15.N2b3  White is much better.  14.dxe5!  A common theme in the Ruy Lopez series. Meanwhile we are acquainted with the ideas behind.  14...fxe5  15.Nc4!  Increasing the pressure on the weak pawn.  15...Bf6  16.Be3  Black has to make a difficult choice. Will he suffer from a worse structure or give up his bishop pair?  16...Bxf3  17.gxf3  Our plan is plain and simple: as the black pieces are tied down to the defense of the e5-pawn, we improve our king's position and increase the pressure on the g-file by putting there a rook.  17...a6  18.Rfd1  O-O-O  19.Kf1  The thing with black's position is the hopelessness of his situation: he can barely move and is bound to passive defense. }
9. h3
{ In my previous course the move h2-h3 occurred in almost each line. Providing an explanation per request at which moment we should play h2-h3, we can say that it positionally favorable to kick the bishop off the diagonal c8-h3 and we take space, c.q. the g4-square and we can unpin ourselves by g2-g4. In contrast, we should be aware of our adversary launching a counteroffensive with a quick g7-g5-g4, opening the g-file. }
9... Bxf3
{ Surprisingly, this move is the most common here. Maintaining the pin with Bh5 would be the most obvious one.   9...Bh5  10.b4  This is a novelty. The Black bishop will be chased and we can gain some tempi on the queenside by moving our pawns forward.  10...Bb6  We are on our own here. The rest of the lines is all fabricated by your author. So, please have faith in me..  11.Nc4  Qf6  Kind of forced in the struggle for equal play in the opening. Black should avoid Qe6, Ng5!  12.g4  One of the benefits of an early h3 is that we can push the pawn to g4.  12...Bg6  13.a4!  Taking space on the queenside. Black has to encounter a4-a5.  13...a6  14.Kh2!!  Clearing the g-file for the rook. Black's king cannot escape its fate. Both on the queen- as on the kingside it will be under attack. }
10. Nxf3 { One of the ideas behind 10.Nxf3 is to push the backward d3-pawn. }
10... O-O 11. d4 { This can be considered a novelty. } 11... exd4 12. cxd4
{ Here, we can use the central pawns in our favor to launch an offense. } 12...
Bb6 13. a4
{ Not merely taking space, but as well activating the a1-rook. There was no urgency for moving the bishop: on c1 it is well placed currently. }
13... a5 14. Re1 { All the pieces should join in the game. } 14... Rfe8 15. Ra3
{ This rook-shift is used for attacking purposes. } 15... Qe7 16. Rd3
{ This move is in line with the old theory of Aron Nimzowitsch: 'überdeckung', or in English: overprotection. It's a prophylaxis against the mounting pressure on the central pawns which is about to follow. }
*

