[Round "?"]
[White "4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Qd6 7.c3 Bb6 & Bg4 Main Lines"]
[Black "4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Qd6 7.c3 Bb6 Main Line #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. O-O
{ Now that the e5-pawn is poisoned @@StartBracket@@  6.Nxe5??  Qd4-+  @@EndBracket@@,  White brings his king to safety, breathing new life in taking on e5.  Moreover, the bishop is not ideally placed on c5 now and often it goes back to d6 - with Black losing one move.   Another popular option for White is  6.Nbd2  , but like in the Ruy Lopez Exchange, I prefer a quick short castling.  Why? We kind of finalize our development, keeping our options open for different set-ups such as c3-d4, Bg5 or Be3, and Nbd2-f1-g3, Na3-c4 or Nc3. }
6... Qd6
{ In Part I of this series concerning the Ruy Lopez Exchange variation @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  a6  4.Bxc6  @@EndBracket@@  , Black had similar issues protecting the e5-pawn. And, also there, he resorted to Qd6 to guard the central foot soldier. Additionally, Black is preparing long castling. }
7. c3
{ Now that the queen has taken position on d6 where it is prone to be attacked by White's pieces, it's worthwhile to open the center with d4. }
7... Bb6 8. d4
{ Without hesitation, White hits the center. The Black pawn on e5 is under siege. }
8... Bg4 { We cannot take on e5 now, as our opponent will take on d1 and e4. }
9. Nbd2
{ A multi-purpose move: White protects f3 and e4, but can strive for more aggressive aims after Nc4. }
9... Nd7 { Black solidifies his central point: e5. } 10. Nc4 Qe7 11. a4
{ Once again, this move proves itself, grabbing important space. } 11... a5 12.
h3
{ As well a useful move, trying to unpin and grabbing space on the kingside. }
12... Bh5
{ White will win the e5-pawn, whilst our opponent want get sufficient compensation in return. }
13. g4 Bg6 14. Nfxe5 { Of course, a pawn is a pawn! } 14... Nxe5 15. Nxe5 f6
{ Forcing the opening of the h-file. } 16. Nxg6 hxg6
{ Unfortunately for Black, we can easily defend our h3-pawn, maintaining our material plus. }
17. Qf3 { White will proceed with Kg2 and Bf4, enjoying a big advantage. } *

