[White "4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Qd6 7.c3 Bb6 & Bg4 Main Lines"]
[Black "4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Qd6 7.c3 Bg4 Main Line #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. O-O
{ Now that the e5-pawn is poisoned @@StartBracket@@  6.Nxe5??  Qd4-+  @@EndBracket@@,  White brings his king to safety, breathing new life in taking on e5.  Moreover, the bishop is not ideally placed on c5 now and often it goes back to d6 - with Black losing one move.   Another popular option for White is  6.Nbd2  , but like in the Ruy Lopez Exchange, I prefer a quick short castling.  Why? We kind of finalize our development, keeping our options open for different set-ups such as c3-d4, Bg5 or Be3, and Nbd2-f1-g3, Na3-c4 or Nc3. }
6... Qd6
{ In Part I of this series concerning the Ruy Lopez Exchange variation @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  a6  4.Bxc6  @@EndBracket@@  , Black had similar issues protecting the e5-pawn. And, also there, he resorted to Qd6 to guard the central foot soldier. Additionally, Black is preparing long castling. }
7. c3
{ Now that the queen has taken position on d6 where it is prone to be attacked by White's pieces, it's worthwhile to open the center with d4. }
7... Bg4
{ Probably the best move as it is preventing the pawn push in the center with d3-d4. White should be on its qui vive, since after 0-0-0 the d3-pawn is a matter of concern. }
8. Nbd2
{ One may wonder why Black can't take on d3. Well, a highly complicated line follows in which White takes on e5. }
8... Qxd3 9. Nxe5
{ The board is on fire - one may wonder: what would Alexei Shirov play here? }
9... Qe2
{ Peculiar enough, Black can avoid material losses.   9...Bxd1??  10.Nxd3!  White is winning material. Both of the bishops are hanging.  10...Be2  11.Nxc5+-  . }
10. Nxg4
{ Black is obliged to take back with the queen, since after Qxd1 there is an immediate check on f6. }
10... Qxg4 11. Qxg4 { After the queen's exchange, White unleashes his pieces. }
11... Nxg4 12. Nb3
{ Black has to make a hard call. In case of the bishop retreat from the a7/g1 diagonal, he will suffer in the ending because of his worse pawn structure. }
12... Bb6 13. c4
{ A strong move trying to trap the bishop. The doubled pawns make that Black will suffer in the ensuing ending. }
13... a6
{ In the correspondence game we follow, the game continued with  13...a5  14.c5  Ba7  15.h3  Ne5  16.Nxa5  O-O-O  17.b4  b6  18.cxb6  cxb6  19.Be3  bxa5  20.Bxa7  Rd7  21.Be3  axb4  22.Rfb1  after this long and inhuman variation, White is still slightly better. Manzo, A @@StartBracket@@2405@@EndBracket@@ -Laffranchise, L @@StartBracket@@2130@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2010 ½-½ @@StartBracket@@42@@EndBracket@@. }
14. c5 { Closing the diagonal. } 14... Ba7 15. Rd1
{ I am showing you this line because of dismantling Black's main threat: a5-a4 and taking on c5. }
15... a5 16. a4
{ A crucial move acquiring an advantage. We are halting the a5-a4 advance after which Black can't disentangle.   16.Nxa5?  Bxc5!  ∓ }
16... Nf6 17. f3
{ White is enjoying a big positional plus. The worse pawn structure and incarcerated bishop make Black's position on the ropes. }
*

