{ In Part I of this series concerning the Ruy Lopez Exchange variation @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  a6  4.Bxc6  @@EndBracket@@  , Black had similar issues protecting the e5-pawn. And, also there, he resorted to Qd6 to guard the central foot soldier. Additionally, Black is preparing long castling. }
7. c3
{ Now that the queen has taken position on d6 where it is prone to be attacked by White's pieces, it's worthwhile to open the center with d4. }
7... Bg4
{ Probably the best move as it is preventing the pawn push in the center with d3-d4. White should be on its qui vive, since after 0-0-0 the d3-pawn is a matter of concern. }
8. Nbd2
{ One may wonder why Black can't take on d3. Well, a highly complicated line follows in which White takes on e5. }
8... O-O-O 9. Nc4 { This position appeared twice in correspondence play. } 9...
Qe6 10. Ncxe5 Nxe4 11. Qc2
{ chasing away the e4-knight, meanwhile preparing d4 and eventually Ng5.   11.Nxg4?!  spoils the advantage after  11...Qxg4  12.Qe2  Nf6  13.d4  Bd6  with Rhe8 to follow, is just fine for Black. }
11... Nf6 12. d4
{ Our adversary should watch his steps. In case of Bd6, we play Ng5 and xf7. }
12... Bxf3 13. Nxf3 Bd6 14. Re1 Qg4 15. c4
{ An ingenious move, in which suddenly has every chance on obtaining an even larger advantage. The clue behind White's strategy is that the black bishop is restricted in its scope. }
15... c5 16. h3 { Chasing the queen to a worse square. } 16... Qg6 17. Qa4 Kb8
18. dxc5
{ At first sight, it seems Black is simply better since his pieces are more active. However, a closer look reveals that the black bishop will be chased and he doesn't have a place to go to. }
18... Bxc5 19. b4
{ Lunacy! Black is completely lost! The only safe spot for the bishop is on f8. }
19... Bd6 20. c5 { The only move..sad but true.. Bf8.. } 20... Bf8 21. Bf4
{ With the stunning plan of taking on c7! } 21... Nd5 22. Rad1
{ As it seems, the bad position of the bishop makes Black's position lost. }
22... Qc6 23. Qxc6
{ According to the principle of two weaknesses, the c6-pawn is one too many. }
23... bxc6 24. Ne5
{ There's no way that Black can defend both of the weak spots. } *

