{ A common theme in the Ruy Lopez series. Meanwhile we are acquainted with the ideas behind. }
14... fxe5 { 14...Nxe5  also here Black is worse  15.Nxe5  fxe5  16.Re1⩲  . }
15. Nc4 { Increasing the pressure on the weak pawn. } 15... Bf6 16. Be3
{ Black has to make a difficult choice. Will he suffer from a worse structure or give up his bishop pair? }
16... Bxf3 17. gxf3
{ Our plan is plain and simple: as the Black pieces are tied down to the defense of the e5-pawn, we improve our king's position and increase the pressure on the g-file by putting a rook there. }
17... a6 18. Rfd1 O-O-O 19. Kf1
{ The thing with Black's position is the hopelessness of his situation: he can barely move and is bound to passive defense. }
19... Rhf8 20. Ke2 { Arrived on the destination! } 20... Be7 21. Ra5
{ White hits the nail on the head. We tie the pieces of the opponent to the protection of the e5-point. }
21... Rfe8 22. Nd2
{ 22.Nxe5  Fetching greedily the pawn jeopardizes victory.  22...b6!  23.Rxd7  A long forced line will now ensue.  23...bxa5  24.Rxe7  Rxe7  25.Nxc6  Rde8  26.Nxe7+  Rxe7  27.bxa5  True, so many pawns for the exchange should give White winning chances - if it weren't for the powerful  27...Re5!  followed by ...Rh5. }
22... Bd6 23. Rg1
{ It is surprising how quickly our position is improving from an equally looking position to a position in which all our pieces take the better places. }
23... g6 24. h4
{ The minority attack on the h-file secures our large advantage and maintain our chances on a good end. }
24... Rg8 25. h5
{ If Black ever takes, then White should put his rooks on the h-file and then try for the f3-f4 advance which will get White two connected passed pawns. }
