{ 11.a4!?  a5  12.Nc4  Qf6  13.Be3  Bxf3  14.Qxf3  Qxf3  15.gxf3  axb4  16.cxb4  Ke7  17.a5  Bxe3  18.fxe3  The position is aesthetically pleasing. For a more comprehensive explanation, please have a look at the video. }
11... Qf6
{ Kind of forced in the struggle for equal play in the opening.   Black should avoid  11...Qe6  12.Ng5!  Bxd1  13.Nxe6  fxe6  14.Rxd1+=  . }
12. g4
{ One of the benefits of an early h3 is that we can push the pawn to g4. }
12... Bg6 13. a4
{ Taking space on the queenside. Black has to encounter a4-a5. } 13... a6 14.
Kh2
{ Clearing the g-file for the rook. The black king cannot escape its fate; it will be under a dangerous attack both on the queenside or the kingside. }
14... O-O 15. h4
{ Since we are far off from the betrodden paths, consider this a sample line on which can be deviated. However, the plan remains the same.. a frontal attack on our adversary's king! }
15... h6 { 15...h5  16.Ng5  hxg4  17.Qxg4  with an attack. } 16. h5
{ Chasing the bishop away from the g-file. We are aiming our arrows purely towards the g7-pawn. }
16... Bh7 17. g5 { And the opening of this file is a 'fait accompli'. } 17...
hxg5 18. Nxg5
{ The rest is simple: Qg4 and move one @@StartBracket@@or two@@EndBracket@@ rooks to the g-file. }
18... Qe7 19. Nxb6 cxb6 20. Rg1
{ I am glad not to stand in Black's shoes. White's play is just so easy, for instance after }
20... f5 21. h6 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Qd6 7.c3 Bb6 & Bg4 Main Lines"]
[Black "4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Qd6 7.c3 Bg4 Main Line #13"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. O-O
{ Now that the e5-pawn is poisoned @@StartBracket@@  6.Nxe5??  Qd4-+  @@EndBracket@@,  White brings his king to safety, breathing new life in taking on e5.  Moreover, the bishop is not ideally placed on c5 now and often it goes back to d6 - with Black losing one move.   Another popular option for White is  6.Nbd2  , but like in the Ruy Lopez Exchange, I prefer a quick short castling.  Why? We kind of finalize our development, keeping our options open for different set-ups such as c3-d4, Bg5 or Be3, and Nbd2-f1-g3, Na3-c4 or Nc3. }
6... Qd6
{ In Part I of this series concerning the Ruy Lopez Exchange variation @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  a6  4.Bxc6  @@EndBracket@@  , Black had similar issues protecting the e5-pawn. And, also there, he resorted to Qd6 to guard the central foot soldier. Additionally, Black is preparing long castling. }
7. c3
{ Now that the queen has taken position on d6 where it is prone to be attacked by White's pieces, it's worthwhile to open the center with d4. }
7... Bg4
{ Probably the best move as it is preventing the pawn push in the center with d3-d4. White should be on its qui vive, since after 0-0-0 the d3-pawn is a matter of concern. }
8. Nbd2
{ One may wonder why Black can't take on d3. Well, a highly complicated line follows in which White takes on e5. }
8... Nd7 9. h3
{ In my previous course, the move h2-h3 occurred in almost every line. Providing an explanation per request at which moment we should play h2-h3, we can say that it is positionally favourable to kick the bishop off the diagonal c8-h3 and we take space, c.q. the g4-square and we can unpin ourselves by g2-g4.  In contrast, we should be aware of our adversary launching a counteroffensive with a quick ...g7-g5-g4, opening the g-file. }
9... Bh5 10. b4
{ This is a novelty. The black bishop will be chased and we can gain some tempi on the queenside by moving our pawns forward.   The only game I found in this position, continued with  10.d4  exd4  11.cxd4  Bb6  12.Nc4  Qb4  Our central pawns are under siege from all angles.  13.Qd3  Bxf3  14.gxf3  with unclear play in Parshin, V-Von der Burg,J Remote email 2013, ½-½ @@StartBracket@@30@@EndBracket@@. }
10... Bb6
{ We are on our own here. The rest of the lines are all fabricated by your author. So, please have faith in me... }
11. Nc4
{ 11.a4!?  a5  12.Nc4  Qf6  13.Be3  Bxf3  14.Qxf3  Qxf3  15.gxf3  axb4  16.cxb4  Ke7  17.a5  Bxe3  18.fxe3  The position is aesthetically pleasing. For a more comprehensive explanation, please have a look at the video. }
11... Qf6
{ Kind of forced in the struggle for equal play in the opening.   Black should avoid  11...Qe6  12.Ng5!  Bxd1  13.Nxe6  fxe6  14.Rxd1+=  . }
12. g4
{ One of the benefits of an early h3 is that we can push the pawn to g4. }
12... Bg6 13. a4
{ Taking space on the queenside. Black has to encounter a4-a5. } 13... a6 14.
Kh2
{ Clearing the g-file for the rook. The black king cannot escape its fate; it will be under a dangerous attack both on the queenside or the kingside. }
14... h5 15. g5
{ One of the other merits of the subtle king move: the pawn on h3 will be protected after Qe6. }
15... Qe6 16. Qe2
{ Another interesting option could be  16.Nh4  stopping h4 and Bh5. } 16... h4
17. Qa2
{ My dear readers, I must apologize for the fact that your author has a soft spot for such manoeuvres which are a delight to the eye.  Due to the better odds of White in the ending it is in our favor to swap off the queens. More it can take out the sting out of Black's attack: after all our king's position is slightly exposed. }
17... f6 18. Rg1
{ From all sides White places additional strains on his opponent. } 18... Qf7
{ White can play more adventurously with } 19. a5
{ Our position is also much better after  19.gxf6  gxf6  20.Nxb6  cxb6  and White is much better after  21.Qa3  and/or  21.Be3  , as Black can't find a shelter for his king. }
19... Ba7 20. Be3 { Defusing the strong a7-bishop and bishop pair. } 20... Bxe3
21. Nxe3 { giving Black the option to avoid the exchange of queens. } 21...
Qxa2 22. Rxa2
{ Black should act, as on the threat gxf6 the g6-bishop is hanging. } 22... Bf7
23. Rd2 O-O-O 24. Nf5
{ Black can't maintain his pawn chain g7-f6-e5, since after Rg8 he is losing the exchange after the Ne7+.   Read 'em and weep.. they will all drop off the board.  24...g6  25.Ne7+  Kb8  26.gxf6  Nxf6  27.Nxe5 }
*

