[Black "4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Qd6 7.c3 Bg4 Main Line #22 (Alternative 17.e5)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. O-O
{ Now that the e5-pawn is poisoned @@StartBracket@@  6.Nxe5??  Qd4-+  @@EndBracket@@,  White brings his king to safety, breathing new life in taking on e5.  Moreover, the bishop is not ideally placed on c5 now and often it goes back to d6 - with Black losing one move.   Another popular option for White is  6.Nbd2  , but like in the Ruy Lopez Exchange, I prefer a quick short castling.  Why? We kind of finalize our development, keeping our options open for different set-ups such as c3-d4, Bg5 or Be3, and Nbd2-f1-g3, Na3-c4 or Nc3. }
6... Qd6
{ In Part I of this series concerning the Ruy Lopez Exchange variation @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bb5  a6  4.Bxc6  @@EndBracket@@  , Black had similar issues protecting the e5-pawn. And, also there, he resorted to Qd6 to guard the central foot soldier. Additionally, Black is preparing long castling. }
7. c3
{ Now that the queen has taken position on d6 where it is prone to be attacked by White's pieces, it's worthwhile to open the center with d4. }
7... Bg4
{ Probably the best move as it is preventing the pawn push in the center with d3-d4. White should be on its qui vive, since after 0-0-0 the d3-pawn is a matter of concern. }
8. Nbd2
{ One may wonder why Black can't take on d3. Well, a highly complicated line follows in which White takes on e5. }
8... Nd7 9. h3
{ In my previous course, the move h2-h3 occurred in almost every line. Providing an explanation per request at which moment we should play h2-h3, we can say that it is positionally favourable to kick the bishop off the diagonal c8-h3 and we take space, c.q. the g4-square and we can unpin ourselves by g2-g4.  In contrast, we should be aware of our adversary launching a counteroffensive with a quick ...g7-g5-g4, opening the g-file. }
9... Bxf3
{ Surprisingly, this move is the most common here. Maintaining the pin with Bh5 would be the most obvious one. }
10. Nxf3
{ One of the ideas behind  10.Nxf3  is to push the backward d3-pawn.   I couldn't find any advantage here with  10.Qxf3  , for example, after  10...a5  11.Nc4  Qe6  12.Be3  O-O  13.Qg3  f6  14.f4  exf4  15.Rxf4  Rf7  16.Rf5  b5  17.Nd2  Bd6  18.Qe1  a4  Black was doing fine since White's queenside needs protection. Kravtsiv,M @@StartBracket@@2677@@EndBracket@@ - Almasi,Z @@StartBracket@@2707@@EndBracket@@ Heraklion 2017 1-0 @@StartBracket@@34@@EndBracket@@. }
10... O-O 11. d4
{ This can be considered a novelty.   In two old correspondence games, White didn't manage to obtain any advantage after:  11.Qc2  Rfe8  12.Rd1   12.Nh4  a5  13.Nf5  Qe6  14.b3  Nf8  15.Kh1  Ng6  @@StartBracket@@1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@26@@EndBracket@@ Bobykin, K @@StartBracket@@2336@@EndBracket@@ -Schreiber, K @@StartBracket@@2479@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2011  12...a5  13.b3  Nf8  14.Bb2  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@51@@EndBracket@@ Urban, M @@StartBracket@@2274@@EndBracket@@-Schwenk, H @@StartBracket@@2110@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2015@@EndBracket@@  14...Qf6  15.d4  Bd6  and Black comfortably equalized. }
11... exd4 12. cxd4
{ Here, we can use the central pawns in our favour to launch an offense. }
12... Bb6 13. a4
{ Not merely taking space, but as well activating the a1-rook. There was no urgency for moving the bishop: on c1 it is well placed currently. }
13... a5 14. Re1 { All the pieces should join in the game. } 14... Rfe8 15. Ra3
{ This rook-shift is used for attacking purposes. } 15... Qe7 16. Rd3
{ This move is in line with the old theory of Aron Nimzowitsch: 'überdeckung' or overprotection in English. It's prophylaxis against the mounting pressure on the central pawns which is about to follow. }
16... Nf6 17. e5
{ My alternative recommendation is  17.e5  giving up the d5-square, but taking important space on the kingside with the purpose of launching an assault. }
17... Nd5 18. Re4
{ Black is in a pickle: how to repel the attack? White has easy play after Rg4 and eventually Bh6 or Nf3-h4-f5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4...Bc5 Pin Variation I: 6...Bg4 7.h3 Bxf3"]
[Black "Introduction: 4...Bc5 Pin Variation I: 6...Bg4 7.h3 Bxf3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5
{ This topical and most popular line for Black is used by most of the world class players. The strongest protagonists of this powerful bishop move are Carlsen, Kramnik and Anand. Carlsen used it with success against Anand at the world championships in Chennai, 2013. The bishop is placed actively on c5 and renders conquering the pawn on e5 less attractive for White. }
5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. O-O Bg4
{ This move has a solid reputation. It has been played by Ding Liren, Anand, Nakamura, and Ivanchuk, and - last but definitely not least @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ - your very own and favorite author! }
7. h3
{ Questioning the bishop where to go. Leaving the c8-h3 diagonal, in case of Bh5, can be considered as a small plus for us. On top of that, we take control over the g4-square and we can unpin by - when the time is ripe - g2-g4. The downside of the small pawn move, could be that Black accelerates his attack across the g-file by g7-g5-g4. }
7... Bxf3
{ Black is getting rid of the pressure on e5, but, by contrast, he is giving up on his strong bishop and the pin.   7...Bh5  Is seen in The Berliner Pin-Variation II.   7...h5  This move doesn't really work here.  8.Nbd2  Taking on g4 is too dangerous, yet.  8...Qe7  9.Nc4  O-O-O  10.Bg5!  Now there is no convenient way to defend the pawn on e5. Black is forced to release the tension with 10... Bxf3 }
8. Qxf3 Nd7
{ Black is not yet choosing the side where to castle, and is improving the position of his knight.   8...O-O  9.Nd2  Via c4, the knight can be moved towards e3 and f5.  9...Re8  10.Nc4  Nd7  11.Bd2  Connecting the rooks, keeping the passage open for the knight.  11...Re6  The knight is pre-destined for the f5-square, and will not deviate from its plan after - for example - 11.. Nb6.  12.g3!?  This set-up gives White some extra options, like h3-h4-h5, and taking back on f4 with the g-pawn once White manages to push his f-pawn. 0-1 @@StartBracket@@63@@EndBracket@@ Adams,M @@StartBracket@@2738@@EndBracket@@-Rodshtein,M  @@StartBracket@@2695@@EndBracket@@ Tbilisi 2017 }
9. Nd2
{ The knight route Nb1-d2-c4 can be regarded as the most flexible for White, targeting e5 @@StartBracket@@from c4@@EndBracket@@ and keeping the option Nc4-e3-f5 open. }
9... Qe7
{ 9...Qf6  This move has been seen frequently on a high level. This move has been seen frequently on a high level.  10.Qxf6  Nxf6  11.Nc4  11...Nd7  12.Bd2  f6  13.a4!  Flanking the opponent from the queen- and possibly later as well the kingside. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@52@@EndBracket@@ Bacrot,E @@StartBracket@@2691@@EndBracket@@-Fressinet,L  @@StartBracket@@2673@@EndBracket@@ Pau 2008. }
10. a4
{ Most often  10.Nc4  was played here. However, I believe this move is to be preferred as White grabs space on the queenside and secures the c4-square for the knight. }
10... Nf8
{ Presumably, this move is the best. The knight is on the road to e6, meanwhile keeping all options open where to place the king.  In the game Willow, M  (2278)  -Zawadski,A  (2171)  ICCF email 2015, ½-½  (33)  there followed:   10...O-O  11.Nc4  f6  12.Qg4  12...Rfd8  b5  13.Ne3  Nf8  14.Nf5→  White quite easily gained the favorable chances. }
11. Nc4
{ First the pawn on e5 should be defended, before Black can move his knight to e6. Hence, Black should spend time on f7-f6 first. First the pawn on e5 should be defended, before Black can move his knight to e6. Hence, Black should spend time on f7-f6 first. }
11... f6
{ 11...Ne6!?  12.c3!  Hindering Ne6-d4 and preparing b2-b4.   12.Nxe5?  Nd4!  12...f6  13.b4→  It's pleasant that this goes with a tempo. It's pleasant that this goes with a tempo. }
12. Na5 { This novelty may well cause Black plenty of troubles. } 12... Bb6
{ Or   12...O-O-O  13.c3  Again, White is faster on the queen- than Black on the kingside with its attack. }
13. Nxb7
{ An audacious operation now that the knight is far beyond enemy borders, but when knowing its credentials, this is the most dangerous continuation for Black. An audacious operation now that the knight is far beyond enemy borders, but when knowing its credentials, this is the most dangerous continuation for Black. }
13... a5
{ 13...Rb8  14.a5  Rxb7  the only move.   14...Bd4?  would leave White just with a pawn up. would leave White just with a pawn up.  15.a6  15.axb6  Black can't take back with the a-pawn, as it would allow 16.Ra8+. Black can't take back with the a-pawn, as it would allow 16.Ra8+.  15...cxb6  16.Qh5+!  Harassing Black meanwhile preparing f2-f4. Harassing Black meanwhile preparing f2-f4. }
14. d4
{ Of course, with our knight locked in on b7, no half measures are being asked for! Anyway, our knight can no longer be trapped, since it can escape to c5. }
14... Ne6
{ aiming to finalize the development.   14...exd4  15.e5!  White is opening the position where Black's king is in the middle.  15...Kd7!  The only move.  16.b4!  Of course! The position should be opened! Of course! The position should be opened!  16...axb4  17.Bd2  The b4-pawn is going to fall, as Black can not allow c5, Qd5+.  17...fxe5  18.a5!  Black has to pull back and his king's position becomes more and more alarming.   14...Bxd4  White gains time as the bishop gave up on the defense on a5. White gains time as the bishop gave up on the defense on a5.  15.Bd2  15...Bb6  16.b4!  Of course, our knight is still in danger.  16...axb4  17.a5→  Jumping Black down the throat! }
15. d5
{ not giving Black the time to capture our knight. not giving Black the time to capture our knight.   15.dxe5?  Ra7  when the knight is captured. }
15... cxd5 16. exd5 Nd4
{ The knight seems to be well placed on d4, doesn't it? The knight seems to be well placed on d4, doesn't it? }
17. Qd3
{ White also has a threat of his own: after c3 also the Black knight has no more squares left @@StartBracket@@it can't jump to b3, because of the check on b5@@EndBracket@@. }
17... O-O
{ 17...Rb8  18.c3!  White doesn't apply the ostrich policy, accepting the challenge. White doesn't apply the ostrich policy, accepting the challenge. }
18. Be3
{ After 18. c3, Black could still have played Nb3, as there is no longer a check on b5. After 18. c3, Black could still have played Nb3, as there is no longer a check on b5. }
18... Ra7 19. c3
{ Both knights are in danger. After a mass of exchanges Black faces the ruins of his queenside structure. }
19... Nf3+
{ A desperado, giving the knight up under the most favorable circumstances. A desperado, giving the knight up under the most favorable circumstances.   19...Nb3?  20.d6!  The b6-bishop is wavering, whereas White will try to catch the knight with Qc4+. }
20. gxf3 Rxb7 21. d6
{ I believe that this idea is testing Black most severely. } 21... Qxd6
{ 21...cxd6  22.Bxb6  Rxb6  23.b4!  A pawn sacrifice in order to create a passed a-pawn. }
22. Qc4+
{ With a tempo White brings in his rook, and, thereby seizes the initiative. The point behind white's 21st move! }
