9. Nd2 { Via c4, the knight can be moved towards e3 and f5. } 9... Re8 10. Nc4
Nd7 11. Bd2 { Connecting the Rooks, keeping the passage open for the Knight. }
11... Re6
{ The knight is pre-destined for the f5-square, and will not deviate from its plan after - for example -  11...Nb6 }
12. g3
{ This set-up gives White some extra options, like h3-h4-h5, and taking back on f4 with the g-pawn once White manages to push his f-pawn. }
12... b5 13. Ne3 Bf8 14. a4
{ White is tightening the screws further for Black, playing simultaneously on the king- and the queenside.  14.h4!?  would also promise White the advantage. }
14... a6 15. Ra2
{ It seems like there are only two results possible here, as White possesses all the positional trumps. I am honestly surprised that Adams lost this position. }
15... Nc5 16. axb5 axb5
{ Adams,M @@StartBracket@@2738@@EndBracket@@ -Rodshtein,M @@StartBracket@@2695@@EndBracket@@ Tbilisi 2017, 0-1 @@StartBracket@@63@@EndBracket@@. }
17. Rxa8 { A strong deviation from the game and a novelty. } 17... Qxa8 18. b3
{ White's pawn chain is set and one; he is ready for further action on the kingside. }
18... Re8 19. Bc3
{ White is playing on two sides, as he will take over the control of the a-file. }
