9... Qe7 10. a4
{ Most often  10.Nc4  was played here. However, I believe this move is to be preferred as White grabs space on the queenside and secures the c4-square for the knight.  Often seen is:  10.Nc4  f6  , and then  11.a3  - Or  11.Bd2  O-O  12.a3  Rfd8  13.b4  Bd4  @@StartBracket@@1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@23@@EndBracket@@ Kanarek, M @@StartBracket@@2530@@EndBracket@@ - Mastrovasilis, D @@StartBracket@@2596@@EndBracket@@ Suwalki 2017 - @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/pppnq1pp/2p2p2/2b1p3/2N1P3/P2P1Q1P/1PP2PP1/R1B2RK1 b kq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...a5  12.Qg3  Nf8  13.Be3  Bxe3  14.Qxe3  Ne6  @@StartBracket@@with an equal game in: Durarbayli, V @@StartBracket@@2626@@EndBracket@@ -Melkumyan, H @@StartBracket@@2653@@EndBracket@@ Saint Louis 2019, 1-0 @@StartBracket@@75@@EndBracket@@. }
10... Nf8
{ Presumably, this move is the best. The knight is on the road to e6, meanwhile keeping all options open where to place the king.  In the game Willow, M @@StartBracket@@2278@@EndBracket@@ - Zawadski, A @@StartBracket@@2171@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2015, ½-½ @@StartBracket@@33@@EndBracket@@  10...O-O  11.Nc4  f6  12.Qg4  Rfd8  13.Ne3  Nf8  14.Nf5  White quite easily gained the favorable chances. }
