{ An audacious operation now that the knight is far beyond enemy borders, but when knowing its credentials, this is the most dangerous continuation for Black. }
13... a5 14. d4
{ Of course, with our knight locked in on b7, no half measures are being asked for! Anyway, our knight can no longer be trapped, since it can escape to c5. }
14... exd4 15. e5
{ White is opening the position where Black's king is in the middle.  15...fxe5  can't be played, because of the c6-pawn and the exposed king.  16.Qxc6+  Kf7  @@StartBracket@@and now the discovered check determines the outcome of the game.  17.Nd6+!  +- }
15... Kd7 { The only move. } 16. b4
{ Of course! The position should be opened! } 16... axb4 17. Bd2
{ The b4-pawn is going to fall, as Black can not allow c5, Qd5+. } 17... fxe5
18. a5
{ Black has to pull back and his king's position becomes more and more alarming. }
18... Ba7 19. Qe4 Ng6 20. Ra4
{ White knocks on Black's door. Though objectively speaking, Black's position may be holdable, facing such a position being caught by surprise isn't a laughing matter. }
20... c5
{ Now it comes to light that the knight is a thorn in Black's flesh.. } 21.
Qd5+
{ Due to the knight Black's defensive palet of options is limited. The knight impedes Qd6 and the king ought to return to the 8th rank. }
21... Kc8 22. Nxc5 { when Black is on the verge of defeat. } *

