{ This move has a solid reputation. It has been played by Ding Liren, Anand, Nakamura, and Ivanchuk, and - last but definitely not least @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ - your very own and favorite author! }
7. h3
{ Questioning the bishop where to go. Leaving the c8-h3 diagonal, in case of Bh5, can be considered as a small plus for us. On top of that, we take control over the g4-square and we can unpin by - when the time is ripe - g2-g4. The downside of the small pawn move could be that Black accelerates his attack across the g-file by g7-g5-g4. }
7... Bxf3
{ Black is getting rid of the pressure on e5, but, by contrast, he is giving up on his strong bishop and the pin. }
8. Qxf3 Nd7
{ Black is not yet choosing the side where to castle and is improving the position of his knight.  Little relevance can be attributed to  8...h6  . White simply gets the upper hand by  9.Nd2  Qe7  10.Nc4  O-O-O  11.Bd2  when White's attack is much faster than Black's. }
9. Nd2
{ The knight route Nb1-d2-c4 can be regarded as the most flexible for White, targeting e5 @@StartBracket@@from c4@@EndBracket@@ and keeping the option Nc4-e3-f5 open.   White could choose another route for the knight,  9.Nc3  Qe7  10.Ne2  but as it seems, it is less convincing.  10...O-O-O  11.Ng3  g6  the knight is somewhat lost on g3. }
9... Qe7 10. a4
{ Most often  10.Nc4  was played here. However, I believe this move is to be preferred as White grabs space on the queenside and secures the c4-square for the knight.  Often seen is:  10.Nc4  f6  , and then  11.a3  - Or  11.Bd2  O-O  12.a3  Rfd8  13.b4  Bd4  @@StartBracket@@1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@23@@EndBracket@@ Kanarek, M @@StartBracket@@2530@@EndBracket@@ - Mastrovasilis, D @@StartBracket@@2596@@EndBracket@@ Suwalki 2017 - @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/pppnq1pp/2p2p2/2b1p3/2N1P3/P2P1Q1P/1PP2PP1/R1B2RK1 b kq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...a5  12.Qg3  Nf8  13.Be3  Bxe3  14.Qxe3  Ne6  @@StartBracket@@with an equal game in: Durarbayli, V @@StartBracket@@2626@@EndBracket@@ -Melkumyan, H @@StartBracket@@2653@@EndBracket@@ Saint Louis 2019, 1-0 @@StartBracket@@75@@EndBracket@@. }
10... Nf8
{ Presumably, this move is the best. The knight is on the road to e6, meanwhile keeping all options open where to place the king.  In the game Willow, M @@StartBracket@@2278@@EndBracket@@ - Zawadski, A @@StartBracket@@2171@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2015, ½-½ @@StartBracket@@33@@EndBracket@@  10...O-O  11.Nc4  f6  12.Qg4  Rfd8  13.Ne3  Nf8  14.Nf5  White quite easily gained the favorable chances. }
11. Nc4
{ First the pawn on e5 should be defended, before Black can move his knight to e6. Hence, Black should spend time on f7-f6 first. }
11... f6 12. Na5
{ This novelty may well cause Black plenty of troubles.  12.c3  was played by Anand, but Inarkiev never got really in trouble.  12...a5  13.Nxa5  Rxa5  14.b4  Bxb4  15.cxb4  Ra8  The knight has good prospects @@StartBracket@@d4@@EndBracket@@ and the d3-pawn can become weak.  16.Be3  Ne6  The position was in balance and the game ended in a draw a couple of moves later. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@23@@EndBracket@@ Anand, V @@StartBracket@@2788@@EndBracket@@ -Naiditsch, A @@StartBracket@@2697@@EndBracket@@ Mainz 2009   12.Bd2  Ne6  13.Rab1  @@StartBracket@@is another interesting attempt in the struggle for obtaining an opening advantage. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@74@@EndBracket@@ Inarkiev, E @@StartBracket@@2680@@EndBracket@@ -Jakovenko, D @@StartBracket@@2713@@EndBracket@@ Khanty-Mansiysk 2013. }
12... Bb6
{ Giving up the right of castling long, won't be according to the taste of many black players.  12...Rb8  13.c3  Ne6  14.b4⩲  @@StartBracket@@White rejoices more space and, therefore, is slightly better.   Or  12...O-O-O  13.c3  Ne6  14.b4!  Bb6?!  15.Nc4  Black's position looks pretty hopeless to me. }
13. Nxb7
{ An audacious operation now that the knight is far beyond enemy borders, but when knowing its credentials, this is the most dangerous continuation for Black. }
13... a5 14. d4
{ Of course, with our knight locked in on b7, no half measures are being asked for! Anyway, our knight can no longer be trapped, since it can escape to c5. }
14... Bxd4 { White gains time as the bishop gave up on the defense on a5. } 15.
Bd2 Bb6
{ 15...Bxb2  is dangerous, on the account of  16.Rab1  followed by taking on a5. }
16. b4 { Of course, our knight is still in danger. } 16... axb4 17. a5
{ Jumping Black down the throat!   17.Rfb1  c5  18.a5  Ba7  19.c3  doesn't seem like much fun for our adversary. }
17... Bd4 18. c3 { Once more, we should not allow Black any breathing space! }
18... bxc3 19. Bxc3 Ne6 20. Bxd4
{ By the exchanges, the a6-pawn is gaining importance. Black will find it harder to stop it with his remaining forces. }
20... Nxd4 21. Qd3 O-O 22. a6
{ Having attained a terrific a6-pawn, our needs should be satisfied. The rest is up to you! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4...Bc5 Pin Variation I: 6...Bg4 7.h3 Bxf3"]
[Black "4...Bc5 Pin Variation I: 6...Bg4 7.h3 Bxf3 8.Qxf3 Nd7 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ This variation - after 3...Nf6 - is called the 'Berlin Defense' or the 'Berlin Wall', due to its supersolid nature.   Rooted in the family of the Ruy Lopez opening @@StartBracket@@i.e. 3.Bb5@@EndBracket@@, the Berlin Defense was first seen in practice around 1801, and examined by @@StartBracket@@it's in the name - who else?@@EndBracket@@ Berliners, as recorded in history. }
4. d3
{ With this move we set foot into the 'Anti-Berlin'.  Keeping the queens on the board for the moment, we are sidestepping the forced lines arising after  4...Nxe4  , amongst others the supersolid ending c.q. the 'Berlin Wall', deployed 4 times by Kramnik against Kasparov with great success in the World Championship Match @@StartBracket@@London, 2000@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Bc5
{ This topical and most popular line for Black is used by most of the world class players. The strongest protagonists of this powerful bishop move are Carlsen, Kramnik and Anand. Carlsen used it with succes against Anand at the world championships in Chennai, 2013. The bishop is placed actively on c5 and renders conquering the pawn on e5 less attractive for White. }
5. Bxc6
{ It's a recurring story: likewise in the Ruy Lopez Exchange @@StartBracket@@part 1@@EndBracket@@, we trade off the bishop for the knight in an early phase of the game, inflicting damages to Black's pawn structure, whereas we avoid - amongst others - the old but currently relevant variation after 5.0-0 Nd4!? }
5... dxc6
{ Here, the e5-pawn is poisoned, since after taking Black will strike back on f2 by 6..Qd4. Therefore, White brings his king in safety at first, whereafter he is ready to take on e5. }
6. O-O
{ Now that the e5-pawn is poisoned, White brings his king in safety, breathing new life in taking on e5. Moreover, the bishop is not ideally placed on c5 now and often it goes back to d6 - Black losing one move. }
6... Bg4
{ This move has a solid reputation. It has been played by Ding Liren, Anand, Nakamura, and Ivanchuk, and - last but definitely not least @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ - your very own and favorite author! }
7. h3
{ Questioning the bishop where to go. Leaving the c8-h3 diagonal, in case of Bh5, can be considered as a small plus for us. On top of that, we take control over the g4-square and we can unpin by - when the time is ripe - g2-g4. The downside of the small pawn move could be that Black accelerates his attack across the g-file by g7-g5-g4. }
7... Bxf3
{ Black is getting rid of the pressure on e5, but, by contrast, he is giving up on his strong bishop and the pin. }
8. Qxf3 Nd7
{ Black is not yet choosing the side where to castle and is improving the position of his knight.  Little relevance can be attributed to  8...h6  . White simply gets the upper hand by  9.Nd2  Qe7  10.Nc4  O-O-O  11.Bd2  when White's attack is much faster than Black's. }
9. Nd2
{ The knight route Nb1-d2-c4 can be regarded as the most flexible for White, targeting e5 @@StartBracket@@from c4@@EndBracket@@ and keeping the option Nc4-e3-f5 open.   White could choose another route for the knight,  9.Nc3  Qe7  10.Ne2  but as it seems, it is less convincing.  10...O-O-O  11.Ng3  g6  the knight is somewhat lost on g3. }
9... Qe7 10. a4
{ Most often  10.Nc4  was played here. However, I believe this move is to be preferred as White grabs space on the queenside and secures the c4-square for the knight.  Often seen is:  10.Nc4  f6  , and then  11.a3  - Or  11.Bd2  O-O  12.a3  Rfd8  13.b4  Bd4  @@StartBracket@@1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@23@@EndBracket@@ Kanarek, M @@StartBracket@@2530@@EndBracket@@ - Mastrovasilis, D @@StartBracket@@2596@@EndBracket@@ Suwalki 2017 - @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/pppnq1pp/2p2p2/2b1p3/2N1P3/P2P1Q1P/1PP2PP1/R1B2RK1 b kq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...a5  12.Qg3  Nf8  13.Be3  Bxe3  14.Qxe3  Ne6  @@StartBracket@@with an equal game in: Durarbayli, V @@StartBracket@@2626@@EndBracket@@ -Melkumyan, H @@StartBracket@@2653@@EndBracket@@ Saint Louis 2019, 1-0 @@StartBracket@@75@@EndBracket@@. }
10... Nf8
{ Presumably, this move is the best. The knight is on the road to e6, meanwhile keeping all options open where to place the king.  In the game Willow, M @@StartBracket@@2278@@EndBracket@@ - Zawadski, A @@StartBracket@@2171@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2015, ½-½ @@StartBracket@@33@@EndBracket@@  10...O-O  11.Nc4  f6  12.Qg4  Rfd8  13.Ne3  Nf8  14.Nf5  White quite easily gained the favorable chances. }
11. Nc4
{ First the pawn on e5 should be defended, before Black can move his knight to e6. Hence, Black should spend time on f7-f6 first. }
11... f6 12. Na5
{ This novelty may well cause Black plenty of troubles.  12.c3  was played by Anand, but Inarkiev never got really in trouble.  12...a5  13.Nxa5  Rxa5  14.b4  Bxb4  15.cxb4  Ra8  The knight has good prospects @@StartBracket@@d4@@EndBracket@@ and the d3-pawn can become weak.  16.Be3  Ne6  The position was in balance and the game ended in a draw a couple of moves later. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@23@@EndBracket@@ Anand, V @@StartBracket@@2788@@EndBracket@@ -Naiditsch, A @@StartBracket@@2697@@EndBracket@@ Mainz 2009   12.Bd2  Ne6  13.Rab1  @@StartBracket@@is another interesting attempt in the struggle for obtaining an opening advantage. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@74@@EndBracket@@ Inarkiev, E @@StartBracket@@2680@@EndBracket@@ -Jakovenko, D @@StartBracket@@2713@@EndBracket@@ Khanty-Mansiysk 2013. }
12... Bb6
{ Giving up the right of castling long, won't be according to the taste of many black players.  12...Rb8  13.c3  Ne6  14.b4⩲  @@StartBracket@@White rejoices more space and, therefore, is slightly better.   Or  12...O-O-O  13.c3  Ne6  14.b4!  Bb6?!  15.Nc4  Black's position looks pretty hopeless to me. }
13. Nxb7
{ An audacious operation now that the knight is far beyond enemy borders, but when knowing its credentials, this is the most dangerous continuation for Black. }
13... a5 14. d4
{ Of course, with our knight locked in on b7, no half measures are being asked for! Anyway, our knight can no longer be trapped, since it can escape to c5. }
14... Ne6 { aiming to finalize the development. } 15. d5
{ Not giving Black the time to capture our knight.  15.dxe5?  This position requires special attention, since after  15...Ra7  the knight is captured. }
15... cxd5 16. exd5 Nd4
{ The knight seems to be well placed on d4, doesn't it? } 17. Qd3
{ White also has a threat of his own: after c3 also the black knight has no more squares left @@StartBracket@@it can't jump to b3, because of the check on b5@@EndBracket@@. }
17... Rb8 18. c3
{ White doesn't apply the ostrich policy, accepting the challenge. } 18... Rxb7
19. cxd4 Bxd4 20. Qa6
{ When we manage to capture the a5-pawn, we can claim a considerable advantage due to our passed a-pawn. }
20... Ra7 21. Qb5+ Kf7 22. Be3
{ Sooner or later, this energetic bishop should be eliminated. } 22... Bxe3 23.
fxe3
{ The weak a- and c-pawn make that Black will suffer for the further part of the game. }
