{ This novelty may well cause Black plenty of troubles.  12.c3  was played by Anand, but Inarkiev never got really in trouble.  12...a5  13.Nxa5  Rxa5  14.b4  Bxb4  15.cxb4  Ra8  The knight has good prospects @@StartBracket@@d4@@EndBracket@@ and the d3-pawn can become weak.  16.Be3  Ne6  The position was in balance and the game ended in a draw a couple of moves later. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@23@@EndBracket@@ Anand, V @@StartBracket@@2788@@EndBracket@@ -Naiditsch, A @@StartBracket@@2697@@EndBracket@@ Mainz 2009   12.Bd2  Ne6  13.Rab1  @@StartBracket@@is another interesting attempt in the struggle for obtaining an opening advantage. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@74@@EndBracket@@ Inarkiev, E @@StartBracket@@2680@@EndBracket@@ -Jakovenko, D @@StartBracket@@2713@@EndBracket@@ Khanty-Mansiysk 2013. }
12... Bb6
{ Giving up the right of castling long, won't be according to the taste of many black players.  12...Rb8  13.c3  Ne6  14.b4⩲  @@StartBracket@@White rejoices more space and, therefore, is slightly better.   Or  12...O-O-O  13.c3  Ne6  14.b4!  Bb6?!  15.Nc4  Black's position looks pretty hopeless to me. }
13. Nxb7
{ An audacious operation now that the knight is far beyond enemy borders, but when knowing its credentials, this is the most dangerous continuation for Black. }
13... a5 14. d4
{ Of course, with our knight locked in on b7, no half measures are being asked for! Anyway, our knight can no longer be trapped, since it can escape to c5. }
14... Ne6 { aiming to finalize the development. } 15. d5
{ Not giving Black the time to capture our knight.  15.dxe5?  This position requires special attention, since after  15...Ra7  the knight is captured. }
15... cxd5 16. exd5 Nd4
{ The knight seems to be well placed on d4, doesn't it? } 17. Qd3
{ White also has a threat of his own: after c3 also the black knight has no more squares left @@StartBracket@@it can't jump to b3, because of the check on b5@@EndBracket@@. }
17... O-O 18. Be3
{ After  18.c3  , Black could still have played  18...Nb3  , as there is no longer a check on b5. }
18... Ra7 19. c3
{ Both knights are in danger. After a mass of exchanges Black faces the ruins of his queenside structure. }
19... Nf3+
{ A desperado, giving the knight up under the most favorable circumstances. }
20. gxf3 Rxb7
{ This position needs further practice, but I'd rather be White. There are several interesting ideas for White. E.g. to create a passed pawn with b4. }
21. d6 { I believe that this idea is testing Black most severely. } 21... Qxd6
22. Qc4+ { Clearing the d-file for the rooks. } 22... Kh8 23. Rad1
{ The point behind White's 21st move! With a tempo White brings in his rook, and, thereby seizes the initiative. }
23... Qe7 24. Qc6
{ After finding all the best moves, which is very unlikely on these untrodden paths in this razor-sharp line, Black hasn't still escaped the danger zone. White intends to play, Rd7, and Rd1 or Kh2 and Rg1. The initiative and attack on the hostile king still promise us chances on a serious advantage. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4...Bc5 Pin Variation II: 6...Bg4 7.h3 Bh5"]
[Black "Introduction: 4...Bc5 Pin Variation II: 6...Bg4 7.h3 Bh5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. O-O Bg4
{ This move has a solid reputation. It has been played by Ding Liren, Anand, Nakamura, and Ivanchuk, and - last but definitely not least @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ - your very own and favorite author! }
7. h3 Bh5
{ Likewise in the Pin-variation of the first course of this series about the RLE, Black maintains the pin.   7...Bxf3  is another main option for Black.  8.Qxf3   7...h5  This move doesn't really work here.  8.Nbd2  Taking on g4 is too dangerous, yet.  8...Qe7  9.Nc4  O-O-O  10.Bg5!  There is no convenient way to defend the pawn on e5. Black is forced to release the tension with  10...Bxf3  . }
8. g4 { White wants to get rid of the annoying pin as soon as possible. } 8...
Nxg4
{ In the battle for the initiative, Black should not hold back. Honestly speaking, I believe that after 8..Bg6 we get the upper hand.   8...Bg6  This move would leave e5 unguarded, while Black won't get the opportunity to take profit of our temporarily weak king's position.  9.Nxe5  Qe7   9...Qd6  10.Bf4!  10.Nxg6!  hxg6  11.Kg2!  White stabilizes his kingside successfully. In case of emergency, for instance when Black doubles on the h-file, we can cover the h-pawn by Rh1.  11...O-O-O  12.Nd2  This position needs further practice but I believe the gods are on White's side. His knight will reach his Royal Highness's soil @@StartBracket@@f3@@EndBracket@@ soon whereas it's likely he will repel his enemy's attack without too much effort. }
9. hxg4 Bxg4
{ Quoting the devil's advocate: 'The writing is on the wall, Black's attack is threatening as the two bishops are powerfull and our king is in the open field. ' This is the end.. isn't it? }
10. Be3
{ By this move we expel the strong-c5 bishop while completing the development. White is gaining time since Black cannot allow the exchange of the bishops. The fact of being a piece up would gain significance. }
10... Be7
{ Played by Magnus Carlsen in a recent internet game. Analysis is showing that this deviation from the main path Bd6 @@StartBracket@@which had been played 4 times@@EndBracket@@ is an improvement.   10...Bd6  Protecting the e5-pawn, leaving space for the queen to be moved to f6 eventually.  11.Kh1!  The idea with Rh1, is giving White the edge.  11...f5  Now that Black opens up the f-file, White must be fast.  12.Rg1  12...h5  Black is renewing the threat of f5-f4.  In case of   12...O-O  White can play  13.Nbd2  13...Qe8  Watch out that you will not be mated after Qh5+, Kg2 and Qh3 mate.  14.Qf1!  Qh5+  15.Nh2±  13.exf5!  Perfect timing! We can afford to open the f-file as we are just in time with the defense of the knight on f3.  13...Qf6  14.Nbd2  The knights collaborate well.  14...Qxf5  15.Rg3!  Securing the square of h3. 1/2 @@StartBracket@@18@@EndBracket@@-1/2 @@StartBracket@@44@@EndBracket@@ Leko,P @@StartBracket@@2691@@EndBracket@@-Navara,D  @@StartBracket@@2741@@EndBracket@@ Linares 2018 }
11. Kg2
{ I believe this is an improvement over the game Nakamura-Carlsen. The content of this course was already prepared before it appeared on top level in the Wijk aan Zee Masters tournament, between Giri vs. Tari @@StartBracket@@2021, 1-0@@EndBracket@@. White should brace himself for the pin and - in conjunction - the opening of the f-file. Therefore, there is no time to lose in unpinning himself and so he protects the knight with the king.   11.Kh1?  Was played by elite GM Hikaru Nakamura. After this move White got in serious trouble against the reigning world champion.  11...f5!  Black's attack is more than promising.  12.Rg1  h5!  keeping the strong g4-bishop and threatening to take on e4. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@33@@EndBracket@@ Nakamura,H @@StartBracket@@2736@@EndBracket@@-Carlsen,M  @@StartBracket@@2863@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020 }
11... f5 12. Qe1
{ Now that White steps out from the pin, he intends to play Nh2. Black must act! }
12... Bxf3+ 13. Kxf3
{ Important here to realize is that our king escapes to the queenside, we move our heavy pieces to the semi-open h- and g-file, halting and neutralizing the g- and h-passers. }
13... f4
{ Since I started writing on the second part of my series about the Berlin Wall, before I commenced with part 1 @@StartBracket@@Ruy Lopez Exchange@@EndBracket@@ I was delighted to witness Anish Giri set off his Tata Steel Masters tournament in round 1 excellently with a victory in the Berlin Wall and in this position! }
14. Bd2
{ I truly believe that with the king escaping to e2, White has chances to get the slightly better position. In all events, Black gets compensation for the sacced piece in the shape of the dangerous kingside pawns. }
14... g5 15. Bc3
{ Not just hitting e5, but simultaneously freeing the path for the knight. }
15... Bf6
{ This move played by the Norwegian GM Tari in the 2021 Tata Steel Masters tournament in Wijk aan Zee, might be considered a waste of time. Wouldn't it be better to castle meanwhile bringing out the queen?   15...Qd6!?  Presumably, this move will occur more often in the near future. In this way Black is faster with his development and set to castle.  16.Nd2  Qe6  17.Ke2  with the slightly preferable chances for White. }
16. Nd2 { Played by Anish Giri, so who am I to disregard his set-up? } 16...
Qe7 17. Rh1 h5 18. Ke2 g4 19. f3
{ Hereafter, Black cannot keep his grip on the light squares on the kingside. }
19... g3
{ Likely not the best move, as it closes the position. Now that Black has no more knights on the board, the white king can find shelter on g2. }
20. Kf1
{ Anish Giri blocks the pawns and finds a secure spot for his king on g2. Please have a look at the recent model game: 1-0 @@StartBracket@@47@@EndBracket@@ Giri,A @@StartBracket@@2764@@EndBracket@@ -Tari,A  @@StartBracket@@2625@@EndBracket@@ Wijk aan Zee NED 2021. }
