4. d3
{ With this move we set foot into the 'Anti-Berlin'. Keeping the queens on the board for the moment, we are sidestepping the forced lines arising after  4...Nxe4  , amongst others the super solid ending c.q. the 'Berlin Wall', deployed 4 times by Kramnik against Kasparov with great success in the World Championship Match @@StartBracket@@London, 2000@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Bc5
{ The bishop is placed actively on c5 and renders conquering the pawn on e5 less attractive for White. }
5. Bxc6
{ It's a recurring story: likewise in the Ruy Lopez Exchange @@StartBracket@@part 1@@EndBracket@@, we trade off the bishop for the knight in an early phase of the game, inflicting damages to Black's pawn structure, whereas we avoid - amongst others - the old but currently relevant variation after  5.O-O  Nd4!?  . }
5... dxc6 6. O-O
{ Now that the e5-pawn is poisoned @@StartBracket@@  6.Nxe5??  Qd4-+  @@EndBracket@@,  White brings his king to safety, breathing new life in taking on e5.  Moreover, the bishop is not ideally placed on c5 now and often it goes back to d6 - with Black losing one move.   Another popular option for White is  6.Nbd2  , but like in the Ruy Lopez Exchange, I prefer a quick short castling.  Why? We kind of finalize our development, keeping our options open for different set-ups such as c3-d4, Bg5 or Be3, and Nbd2-f1-g3, Na3-c4 or Nc3. }
6... Bg4
{ This move has a solid reputation. It has been played by Ding Liren, Anand, Nakamura, and Ivanchuk, and - last but definitely not least @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ - your very own and favourite author! }
7. h3
{ Questioning the bishop where to go. Leaving the c8-h3 diagonal, in case of Bh5, can be considered as a small plus for us. On top of that, we take control over the g4-square and we can unpin by - when the time is ripe - g2-g4. The downside of the small pawn move, could be that Black accelerates his attack across the g-file by g7-g5-g4. }
7... Bh5
{ Likewise in the Pin-variation of the first course of this series about the RLE, Black maintains the pin.   7...Bxf3  is another main option for Black. }
8. g4
{ White wants to get rid of the annoying pin as soon as possible. Mutatis mutandis, as in the Pin variation of the Ruy Lopez Exchange @@StartBracket@@Volume 1@@EndBracket@@, a sound plan for White.   When White hesitates to play this move, he could easily end up in a worse position:  8.Nbd2  Nd7  9.Nc4  f6  10.Rb1  a5  11.Bd2  b6  12.Be3  Be7  13.b3  Nc5  14.a4  Ne6=+  as a result of Black's strong minor pieces, he was already better and went on to win in Firouzja, A @@StartBracket@@2728@@EndBracket@@ - Carlsen, M @@StartBracket@@2863@@EndBracket@@ Lichess.org INT 2020 0-1 @@StartBracket@@70@@EndBracket@@. Eventually, under inferior circumstances, on move 20 White had to play g2-g4 after all, to unpin himself. }
8... Nxg4
{ In the battle for the initiative, Black should not hold back.   I believe we get the upper hand after  8...Bg6  . }
9. hxg4 Bxg4
{ Quoting the devil's advocate: 'The writing is on the wall, Black's attack is threatening as the two bishops are powerful and our king is in the open field.' This is the end.. isn't it? }
10. Be3
{ By this move we expel the strong-c5 bishop while completing the development. White is gaining time since Black cannot allow the exchange of the bishops. The fact of being a piece up would gain significance. }
10... Be7
{ Played by Magnus Carlsen in a recent internet game. The analysis is showing that this deviation from the main path Bd6 @@StartBracket@@which had been played 4 times@@EndBracket@@ is an improvement. }
11. Kg2
{ I believe this is an improvement over the game Nakamura-Carlsen. The content of this course was already prepared before it appeared on top level in the Wijk aan Zee Masters tournament, between Giri vs. Tari @@StartBracket@@2021, 1-0@@EndBracket@@.  White should brace himself for the pin and - in conjunction - the opening of the f-file. Therefore, there is no time to lose in unpinning himself and so he protects the knight with the king.   11.Kh1?  Was played by elite GM Hikaru Nakamura. After this move White got in serious trouble against the reigning world champion.  11...f5!  Black's attack is more than promising.  12.Rg1  h5!  keeping the strong g4-bishop and threatening to take on e4.  13.Nc3   13.exf5?  e4!  here the difference with the Bd6-line comes to the light.  14.dxe4  Qxd1  is winning for Black.  f4!  Black changes his strategy comprising a kingside attack to a pawn avalanche on the kingside.  14.Bd2  g5  There they come! And there is nothing White can do.  15.Nb1  Bc5  Not only hitting f2 but threatening ...Bxf3, g4 and Qh4 as well.  16.Bc3  Bxf2  17.Nbd2  White can't afford to lose precious time and should give in handing material back.   17.Rf1  Bg3  18.Bxe5  Rf8  the pawn on e5 is of no importance. The 3 pawns on the kingside do the job.  19.Nbd2  Bh3  20.Rg1  g4  and the pawns are unstoppable. Black is winning here.  17...Qe7!  preparing for long castling.  18.Qf1  Bxg1  19.Qxg1  Bxf3+  20.Nxf3  1-0 @@StartBracket@@33@@EndBracket@@ Nakamura,H @@StartBracket@@2736@@EndBracket@@-Carlsen,M @@StartBracket@@2863@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020  20...Rg8  N  A strong improvement over Magnus his play. Black will bet all his chips on his pawns.  21.Nxe5  Qe6  The queen is aiming for h3.  22.Qh2  O-O-O  ⩱  In terms of his 3 connected passed pawns, it occurs that Black obtained plenty of compensation and can conveniently complete his development. }
11... f5 { White cannot take on f5, because of 12...O-O followed by ...Rxf5. }
12. Qe1
{ Now that White steps out from the pin, he intends to play Nh2. Black must act! }
12... Bxf3+
{ And so he does. In order to play ...f5-f4, Carlsen should not allow Nxe5 - when the bishop on g4 is hanging. }
13. Kxf3
{ A weird-looking position arose on the board. With the king on f3, and two pawns in return for the piece, there exists compensation. Imagine a black queen on g4, and it would be mate! Having taken into consideration the dangers, we look now at our plusses and possible ways of capitalizing on our extra material. Important to realize is that our king escapes to the queenside, we move our heavy pieces to the semi-open h- and g-file, halting and neutralizing the g- and h-passers. }
13... f4
{ Since I started writing on the second part of my series about the Berlin Wall, before I commenced with part 1 @@StartBracket@@Ruy Lopez Exchange@@EndBracket@@ I was delighted to witness Anish Giri set off his Tata Steel Masters tournament in round 1 excellently with a victory in the Berlin Wall and in this position! }
14. Bd2
{ I truly believe that with the king escaping to e2, White has chances to get the slightly better position. In all events, Black gets compensation for the sacced piece in the shape of the dangerous kingside pawns. }
14... g5 15. Bc3
{ Not just hitting e5, but simultaneously freeing the path for the knight. }
15... Bf6
{ This move, played by the Norwegian GM Tari in the 2021 Tata Steel Masters tournament in Wijk aan Zee, might be considered a waste of time. Wouldn't it be better to castle meanwhile bringing out the queen? }
16. Nd2 { Played by Anish Giri, so who am I to disregard his set-up? } 16...
Qe7 17. Rh1 h5 18. Ke2 O-O-O 19. Qg1 Kb8 20. f3 Rdg8 21. Rf1
{ White is ready to counter the pawn advance g5-g4. } 21... g4 22. fxg4 hxg4
23. Rxh8 { The exchange of rooks makes our defensive task easier. } 23... Bxh8
24. Kd1
{ White is better here and the reason is plain and simple: he is a piece up! Once Black moves his f-pawn we set up a block on g3, while after g4-g3 we do the same thing but then on f3. }
24... Bf6 25. b3
{ White is working on a secure place for his king @@StartBracket@@i.e., b2@@EndBracket@@.. }
25... b6 26. a4
{ Meanwhile improving his pawn structure, gaining space on the queenside. }
26... Qe6 27. Kc1
{ The bottom line of the entire variation can be concise: winning the piece, stopping the pawns, bringing the king in safety when White obtains slightly preferably chances.  Having said that, the entire line is so complex and even here on move 27 the question remains: how can we win such a position, our pieces tied down on the two passed pawns of Black? Giri illustrated the way to victory; the lesson to be learned from his game that patience is required and we should be prepared for slow manoeuvring! }
*

