{ Black will find himself down in rabbit hole, as will be shown in the next lines. }
15. Qe2
{ It doesn't seem like that this dull-looking position could disbalance our opponent in a couple of moves. In fact, this position contains prosperous attacking prospects: White is set to start an awful attack on Black.   15.a4?  We can't allow Rxd3, as will be shown in the next line.  15...Rxd3  16.a5  Bxf3  17.gxf3  Qe6  18.axb6  cxb6  19.Ne3  Ng6  is winning for Black.   19...Ng6!  20.Ng2  to stop Nh4.  20...Rhd8  21.Rb2  Qd6  White must return the piece, ending up in a hopeless situation. }
15... Qd7
{ This is the goat path our opponent must take on his way to a draw. } 16. a4
{ In spite of the fact this line ends in a repetition of moves, I can't emphasize enough how much our poor opponent is in a pickle. Now he has to deal with the threat of a4-a5. }
16... a6
{ Black could better temper his greed, because after  16...Qxd3  17.Qxd3  Rxd3  18.a5  he is losing a piece. }
17. d4
{ We are crossing the Rubicon! Our opponent didn't leave us a choice, as d3 was hanging. }
17... exd4 18. b5 dxc3
{ As a matter of fact, all the difficulties Black has to overcome in the upcoming lines, go beyond imagination.   Black is balancing on a chord in all of the ensuing lines, as is illustrated here.  18...axb5  19.axb5  cxb5  20.Nxb6+  cxb6  21.cxd4  The remnants of our adversary's position appear hideous. }
19. Nxb6+ cxb6 20. Bxc3 Qd3
{ The only move, otherwise Black will be wiped out. } 21. Qb2 Bxf3 22. bxc6
{ White could easily end up worse, e.g., after  22.bxa6  Qxa6!  23.gxf3  Ne6=+ }
22... Bxe4
{ Not only to save the bishop but as well to let him join the defense. } 23.
Qxb6 Bxc6 24. Ba5
{ Our opponent is facing a daring exploit - it won't be easy to avoid mate. }
24... Rd7 { 24...Ne6  25.Rfc1!  is dangerous for Black. } 25. Qa7 b5
{ This is defense anno 2021, and the only way for Black to avoid wet feet.   25...Rd6  26.Rfe1→ }
26. Qxa6+ Bb7 27. Qa7
{ We could better refrain from  27.Qb6  considering the next continuation:  27...Kb8  28.Rxb5  Qd6!  when Black is clearly better. }
27... Bc6 { Black doesn't have much choice but to repeat the moves. } 28. Qa6+
*

