{ The first game in the 6...Qe7 line, started too cautiously with  7.Qe2?!  Bg4  8.h3  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@25@@EndBracket@@ Lehmann,K-Schramm, B Germany North 1980  8...Bh5  and Black is OK.   Specialist Vladimir Kramnik faced many White set-ups in this variation, like  7.h3?!  and felt that White should be punished for this inaccuracy... he deployed a direct assault on the king!  7...Rg8!!  8.Kh1  Nh5  9.c3  g5  10.Nxe5  g4  with promising attacking prospects for the former world champion, in Aronian, L @@StartBracket@@2794@@EndBracket@@-Kramnik, V @@StartBracket@@2800@@EndBracket@@ Berlin 2018, 0-1 @@StartBracket@@27@@EndBracket@@. }
7... Bg4
{ This can be considered as one of the main set-ups of Black in this line. And this is not without reason: Black pins the knight and prepares to castle long. White must come up with a plan. }
8. h3
{ Questioning the bishop where to go. Leaving the c8-h3 diagonal, in case of Bh5, can be considered as a small plus for us. On top of that, we take control over the g4-square and we can unpin by - when the time is ripe - g2-g4. The downside of the small pawn move could be that Black accelerates his attack across the g-file by g7-g5-g4.   The second game ever played in this line, and the first one on top-level, wasn't a big success for White. either.  8.Nc4  Nd7  9.Be3  Bd6  10.h3  Bh5  11.a4  f6  12.c3  Preparing d3-d4, but it won't be easy to make this move work.  12...b6  13.Re1  O-O  Black took in the ideal position and the position is equal. After d3-d4, Black can take on d4, then cxd4, Qxe4!  14.Bc1  Understandably, White endeavours to regroup the Knight to e3 and f5. But at the cost two tempos.. that comes at a high price! 0-1 @@StartBracket@@59@@EndBracket@@ Van der Wiel,J @@StartBracket@@2560@@EndBracket@@-Salov,V @@StartBracket@@2630@@EndBracket@@ Rotterdam 1989 }
8... Bh5 9. Nc4
{ The outset of the knight's long journey to green and prosperous lands. Primarily, our adversary must take care of the e5-pawn. }
9... Nd7
{ As the former world champion stated, this is the ideal set-up for Black after which he shouldn't have any trouble. So, dear reader, it is up to me to conduct the task of bringing the advantage home in good conscience! }
10. a3 { A popular line these days. White is going to play b4. } 10... O-O-O
{ We are following the English GM, Gawain Jones's, choice. Personally speaking, I find this move the most challenging for us and I am surprised that it falls so much behind in popularity compared to the 10...a5 line. }
11. b4 { In for a penny, in for a pound! } 11... Bd4 12. Rb1
{ All is set for the queenside operation with b4-b5. } 12... f6
{ Black is sustaining the e5-pawn while preparing for the attack with g7-g5. }
13. Bd2
{ This is a novelty. White prepares for the attack with a3-a4 and b4-b5.   13.Ne3?!  This insipid move gives our adversary the opportunity to launch his offense.  13...Bxe3!  14.fxe3  Vocaturo,D @@StartBracket@@2620@@EndBracket@@-Jones,G @@StartBracket@@2688@@EndBracket@@ Douglas 2019, ½-½ @@StartBracket@@80@@EndBracket@@. From here I would like to come up with an improvement:  14...g5  15.Qe1  Bxf3  Stronger than g5-g4, after which White can improve his knight by Nf3-h4-f5.  16.Rxf3  g4!  No time to lose: Black is opening the g- and h-file for the aim of the assault on white's king.  17.hxg4  h5!  White is in serious danger. }
13... Nf8 14. c3 Bb6
{ Black will find himself down in rabbit hole, as will be shown in the next lines. }
15. Qe2
{ It doesn't seem like that this dull-looking position could disbalance our opponent in a couple of moves. In fact, this position contains prosperous attacking prospects: White is set to start an awful attack on Black.   15.a4?  We can't allow Rxd3, as will be shown in the next line.  15...Rxd3  16.a5  Bxf3  17.gxf3  Qe6  18.axb6  cxb6  19.Ne3  Ng6  is winning for Black.   19...Ng6!  20.Ng2  to stop Nh4.  20...Rhd8  21.Rb2  Qd6  White must return the piece, ending up in a hopeless situation. }
15... Qd7
{ This is the goat path our opponent must take on his way to a draw. } 16. a4
{ In spite of the fact this line ends in a repetition of moves, I can't emphasize enough how much our poor opponent is in a pickle. Now he has to deal with the threat of a4-a5. }
16... a6
{ Black could better temper his greed, because after  16...Qxd3  17.Qxd3  Rxd3  18.a5  he is losing a piece. }
17. d4
{ We are crossing the Rubicon! Our opponent didn't leave us a choice, as d3 was hanging. }
17... exd4 18. b5 d3
{ Black is balancing on a chord in all of the ensuing lines, as is illustrated here.  18...axb5  19.axb5  cxb5  20.Nxb6+  cxb6  21.cxd4  The remnants of our adversary's position appear more than fragile. }
19. Nxb6+ { The white queen can be placed on e3, joining the assault. } 19...
cxb6 20. Qe3 axb5 { The only move for Black to stay in the game. } 21. Nd4
{ There is no time to lose! The knight sets off towards the queenside to support the assault on the black king. }
21... Be2 22. axb5 { Black could easily go wrong with } 22... Bxf1
{ By no means, even not for an exchange, Black could afford to let White go his way on the queenside. }
23. bxc6 bxc6 24. Rxb6
{ when it transpires that White is complete winning, for instance after  24...Ne6  25.Qg3  Nc7  26.Nxc6  when White is threatening mate on b87 and can even just win back the bishop on f1. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Qe7 − 10.a3 Sidelines"]
[Black "4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Qe7 − 10.a3 O-O-O #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ This variation - after  3...Nf6  - is called the 'Berlin Defense' or the 'Berlin Wall', due to its super solid nature. Rooted in the family of the Ruy Lopez opening @@StartBracket@@i.e., @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bb5  @@EndBracket@@, the Berlin Defense was first seen in practice anno 1801, and examined by @@StartBracket@@it's in the name - who else?@@EndBracket@@ Berliners, as recorded in history. }
4. d3
{ With this move we set foot into the 'Anti-Berlin'. Keeping the queens on the board for the moment, we are sidestepping the forced lines arising after 4...Nxe4, amongst others the super solid ending c.q. the 'Berlin Wall', deployed 4 times by Kramnik against Kasparov with great success in the World Championship Match  @@StartBracket@@London, 2000@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Bc5
{ The bishop is placed actively on c5 and renders conquering the pawn on e5 less attractive for White. }
5. Bxc6
{ It's a recurring story: likewise in the Ruy Lopez Exchange @@StartBracket@@part 1@@EndBracket@@, we trade off the bishop for the knight in an early phase of the game, inflicting damages to Black's pawn structure, whereas we avoid - amongst others - the old but currently relevant variation after  5.O-O  Nd4!?  . }
5... dxc6
{ Here, the e5-pawn is poisoned, since after taking Black will strike back on f2 by 6...Qd4. Therefore, White brings his king in safety, whereafter he is ready to take on e5. }
6. O-O
{ Now that the e5-pawn is poisoned @@StartBracket@@  6.Nxe5??  Qd4-+  @@EndBracket@@,  White brings his king to safety, breathing new life in taking on e5.  Moreover, the bishop is not ideally placed on c5 now and often it goes back to d6 - with Black losing one move.   Another popular option for White is  6.Nbd2  , but like in the Ruy Lopez Exchange, I prefer a quick short castling.  Why? We kind of finalize our development, keeping our options open for different set-ups such as c3-d4, Bg5 or Be3, and Nbd2-f1-g3, Na3-c4 or Nc3. }
6... Qe7
{ According to the beliefs of the connoisseur from black's end and my idol Vladimir Kramnik, who tried here various continuations such as 6...Nd7 and 6...Bg4, this queen move could well be the best. He states that in case White delays h2-h3, Black also holds back with the move Nf6-d7 and first develops the bishop to g4. }
