16... a6
{ Black could better temper his greed, because after  16...Qxd3  17.Qxd3  Rxd3  18.a5  he is losing a piece. }
17. d4
{ We are crossing the Rubicon! Our opponent didn't leave us a choice, as d3 was hanging. }
17... exd4 18. b5 d3
{ Black is balancing on a chord in all of the ensuing lines, as is illustrated here.  18...axb5  19.axb5  cxb5  20.Nxb6+  cxb6  21.cxd4  The remnants of our adversary's position appear more than fragile. }
19. Nxb6+ { The white queen can be placed on e3, joining the assault. } 19...
cxb6 20. Qe3 axb5 { The only move for Black to stay in the game. } 21. Nd4
{ There is no time to lose! The knight sets off towards the queenside to support the assault on the black king. }
21... Be2 22. axb5 c5
{ Under the given circumstances, the best continuation. In an attempt to avert our attack, our adversary is sealing the b-file. }
23. Ra1 { Fortunately, we have recourse to the a-file. } 23... Ng6
{ Stopping Bd2-f4, as is fatal for Black in the next line.   23...cxd4  24.Ra8+!  Kc7  The h2-b8 diagonal can be taken by White now.  25.Qg3+  Qd6  26.Bf4  and White is winning. }
24. Rfc1 { The following line marks white's superior attacking chances. } 24...
cxd4 25. cxd4+
{ The black king can seek refuge on b8. But as it soon turns out, his fortress isn't impenetrable. }
25... Kb8 26. d5 { White the sole purpose of Qxb6. } 26... Qd6 27. Rc6
{ The final blow. } 27... bxc6 28. Qxb6+ Kc8
{ The only thing that remains is to stop the king from fleeing via d7 to the kingside. }
29. bxc6 Qb8 30. Ra8 { A nice shot, going for the best game award! } 30... Qxa8
31. Ba5 Qb8 { 31...Qxa5  32.Qb7# } 32. Qa6+ { With mate on b7 the next move. }
