24. Rfc1 Ne5 25. Qg3
{ Although objectively, the position remains balanced; white's chances are superior due to black's poor king. This is the end of my theoretical line, but to give you an idea in what troubles Black can run into, I show you the next trainable sample line. White will follow up with f2-f4-f5, and eventually Ne6. The king is lacking a secure spot and is seriously in danger here.   25.Nxe2  This move is leading to a safe but drawish position.  25...dxe2  26.Qxe2  Qd3!   The move  26...Qxd2?  is a horrible blunder.  27.Ra8+  Kc7  28.Qxd2  Black is losing the rook on h8.  27.Qxd3  Nxd3  when Black managed to equalize. }
25... Rhe8 26. f4
{ Trying to open the h2-b8 diagonal, kicking the knight from its central post. }
26... Nc4 27. Ra8+ Kc7 28. f5+
{ Not merely reopening the diagonal but securing the e6-square as well. } 28...
Ne5 29. Ne6+ Rxe6 30. fxe6 { Black is dead lost, as he can't take back on e6. }
