{ In order to take control over the g5-square and to prevent any future Ng5 or g5. }
24... Nf8 25. Qb3 { White is ready for the assault on the black king. } 25...
Bxg3
{ Understandably, our opponent is tired of waiting, especially now that we revealed our plan. }
26. fxg3 { Black cannot take on e4 since his rook will be hanging. } 26... Ne6
27. d5
{ We are chasing away the knight, in the meantime opening the files for our heavy pieces and bishop. }
27... cxd5 28. exd5
{ The change of the pawn structure implies a further weakening of the pawn on c7. }
28... Ng7 29. d6
{ As the plot unfolds, one realizes that there are many ways for Black to go wrong in his seemingly stable position.   29.g4!?  in order to keep the knight out of the game is also interesting. }
29... Rxd6 30. Rxd6 cxd6 31. Rxd6
{ So the character of the position became more open. This is favourable for White, whose bishop is going to be a 'monster' . }
31... Nf5 32. Re6 Qd7 33. Bf4+
{ The difference in strength between the minor pieces becomes visible. As we all know, in an open position, bishops render better prospects than knights.   33...Ka8  Black's king is in danger and the white bishop rules over the board. }
