{ After a long route, the knight reached its destiny: g3.   16.Bxa7  is too greedy, since after  16...b6  17.a4  Bxf3  18.Qxf3  Kb7  19.a5  Ra8  his bishop won't get out. }
16... Bxf3
{ We are following the game Giri-Topalov here. Certainly, there are alternatives for Black here. Amongst them is Bf7 and g5. }
17. Qxf3 Kb8
{ Privately hidden in the corner, neutralizing the threat of Bxa7 for once and for all. }
18. Rfd1 g6 19. d4
{ Topalov applies the best strategy here: attacking the central pawns. If he keeps the e-pawn on the board White may launch a dangerous queenside attack.   19.Qxf6  doesn't bring White anywhere.  19...Rdf8  20.Qh4  h5⇆  when the queen is in danger. }
19... exd4 20. cxd4
{ Black cannot undisturbedly attack the central pawns. White has counterthreats, such as Qxf6. }
20... Rhf8
{ Both players are shuffling their pieces in a subtle, positional manner. After black's last move, Giri should anticipate on Ne6-g5. }
21. Bh6
{ 21.Rab1!?  Ng5!  22.Bxg5  fxg5  23.Qe2  h5!  with counterplay for Black. }
21... Rf7
{ We followed 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@50@@EndBracket@@ Giri, A @@StartBracket@@2797@@EndBracket@@ - Topalov, V @@StartBracket@@2740@@EndBracket@@, Shamkir 2019 so far. Here, I would like to propose a novelty. }
22. Rd2
{ In line with the ancient concept of 'Uberdeckung' @@StartBracket@@i.e., Overprotection@@EndBracket@@ Nimzowitsch,  22.Rd2  is going to protect d4 a little extra. When White will succeed in keeping these pawns unharmed, and well protected, he will get his hands free for other operations - such as a kingside attack.   After the consolidation phase resulting in Black finding himself in a squeeze, we have our hands free for a minority attack on the queenside. }
22... Qe8 23. Rad1 a6 { 23...g5  24.Nf5+= } 24. h4
{ In order to take control over the g5-square and to prevent any future Ng5 or g5. }
24... Nf8 25. Qb3 { White is ready for the assault on the black king. } 25...
Bxg3
{ Understandably, our opponent is tired of waiting, especially now that we revealed our plan. }
26. fxg3 { Black cannot take on e4 since his rook will be hanging. } 26... Nd7
{ The knight is on its way to b6. } 27. Bf4
{ White's bishop is well placed on f4, while our king can be stashed on h2 behind a wall of pawns. }
27... Nb6 28. a4 Re7
{ Black's strategy is clear: wait, wait, wait, and try to get to White's central pawns from behind the barricades. }
29. a5 Nd7 30. e5
{ Black cannot take back on e5, as he will lose the exchange after 31. Bg5. Moreover, I like White's position because of his strong f4-bishop and fixed Black's queenside pawn structure. I find it hard to come up with a strong Black move here. }
*

