1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. O-O Qe7
{ According to the beliefs of the connoisseur from black's end and my idol Vladimir Kramnik, who tried here various continuations such as  6...Nd7  and  6...Bg4  , this queen move could well be the best. He states that in case White delays h2-h3, Black also holds back with the move Nf6-d7 and first develops the bishop to g4. }
7. Nbd2
{ The first game in the 6... Qe7 line, started too cautiously with   7.Qe2?!  Bg4  8.h3  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@25@@EndBracket@@ Lehmann,K-Schramm, B Germany North 1980  8...Bh5  and Black is OK.  Specialist Vladimir Kramnik faced many White set-ups in this variation, like   7.h3?!  and felt that White should be punished for this inaccuracy.. he deployed a direct assault on the king!  7...Rg8!!  8.Kh1  Nh5  9.c3  g5  10.Nxe5  g4  with promising attacking prospects for the former world champion, in: Aronian, L @@StartBracket@@2794@@EndBracket@@-Kramnik,V @@StartBracket@@2800@@EndBracket@@ Berlin 2018, 0-1 @@StartBracket@@27@@EndBracket@@. }
7... Bg4
{ This can be considered as one of the main set-ups of Black in this line. And this is not without reason: Black pins the knight and prepares to castle long. White has to come up with a plan. }
8. h3 Bh5
{ 8...h5?  is not dangerous for White, as we will disregard this brutal force and continue with  9.Nc4!  and the bishop will be moved to g5. Black is left empty-handed. His attacking chances have evaporated and White is positionally much better, after e.g. Ne3.  9...Nd7  10.hxg4  hxg4  11.Ng5!  White impedes the queen transfer to h4. }
9. Nc4
{ The outset of the knight's long journey to green and prosperous lands. Primarily, our adversary has to take care of the e5-pawn. }
9... Nd7
{ As the former world champion stated, this is the ideal set-up for Black after which he shouldn't have any trouble. So, dear reader, it is up to me to conduct the task of bringing the advantage home in good conscience! }
10. a3 { A popular line these days. White is going to play b4. } 10... a5
{ To me, this seems like the most natural move. Black is hindering White's evil plans on the queenside of 'property theft'.   10...a6  Assumingly a natural move, but on a7 the bishop will nevertheless be swapped.  11.b4  Ba7  12.Be3!  Such a powerful bishop on a7 cannot be allowed.  12...Bxe3  13.Nxe3  Taking back meanwhile improving the knight's position.  13...f6  14.Nf5⩲  This is a maneuver to remember. The knight goes to f3 to chase the h5-bishop away. The alternative way of unpinning concerning g2-g4, merely causes a weak king. 0-1  @@StartBracket@@64@@EndBracket@@ So,W @@StartBracket@@2770@@EndBracket@@-Carlsen,M @@StartBracket@@2863@@EndBracket@@ chess24. com INT 2020. The arrows reflect the promising plans of White. He will try to slowly drive the Black pieces back and prepare for e5-e6.   10...O-O-O  We are following the English GM Gawain Jones's choice.  11.b4  In for a penny, in for a pound!  11...Bd4  12.Rb1  All is set for the queenside operation with b4-b5.  12...f6  Black is sustaining the e5-pawn while preparing for the attack with g7-g5.   12...g5  13.g4!  Probably, even stronger than  13.Bd2!  This is a novelty. White prepares for the attack with a3-a4 and b4-b5.  13...Nf8  14.c3  Bb6  Black will find himself down in the rabbit hole, as will be shown in the next lines.  15.Qe2  It doesn't seem like that this dull-looking position could disbalance our opponent in a couple of moves. In fact, this position contains prosperous attacking prospects: White is set to start an awful attack on Black.   15.a4?  We can't allow Rxd3, as will be shown in the next line.  15...Rxd3  16.a5  Bxf3  17.gxf3  Qe6  18.axb6  cxb6  19.Ne3  Ng6  is winning for Black.  15...Qd7!  This is the goat path our opponent has to take on his way to a draw.  16.a4!  In spite of the fact this line ends in a repetition of moves, I can't emphasize enough how much our poor opponent is in a pickle. Now he has to deal with the threat of a4-a5.  16...a6  Black could better temper his greed, because after   16...Qxd3  17.Qxd3  Rxd3  18.a5  he is losing a piece.  17.d4!  We are crossing the Rubicon! Actually, our opponent didn't let us have a choice, as d3 was hanging.  17...exd4  18.b5  d3   18...dxc3  As a matter of fact, all the difficulties Black has to overcome in the upcoming lines, go beyond imagination.  19.Nxb6+  cxb6  20.Be3  This is a very ambitious idea. One of the differences with the line 20.Bxc3, Qd3 21.Qb2, is that Black cannot take on f3.  20...Qd3  21.Qa2→  Aesthetically, a fine move. The queen is maximally mobilized on the a2-g8 diagonal, as on the a-file, which is expected to be opened swiftly.  19.Nxb6+!  The white queen can be placed on e3, joining the assault.  19...cxb6  20.Qe3→   10...f6  11.b4  The system is losing its innocence after this aggressive move.  11...Bd6  The dauntless   11...Bd4!?  leads to double-edged positions. For instance,  12.Rb1  Nb6  13.Ne3  13...Na4  The knight dangles somewhere near the edge of the board. If we react accurately, the hostile minor pieces could get into problems escaping the enemy zone.  14.Nf5  Nc3?  15.Nxe7  Nxd1  16.Nxd4  exd4  In case of 16..Nc3 17.Rb3, White is also better.  17.Nf5  1/2  @@StartBracket@@20@@EndBracket@@-1/2 @@StartBracket@@78@@EndBracket@@ Roebers,J @@StartBracket@@2237@@EndBracket@@ -Jonkman,H @@StartBracket@@2424@@EndBracket@@ Amsterdam 2000  12.Ne3!?  This maneuver @@StartBracket@@Nb1-d2-c4-e3-f5@@EndBracket@@ we see coming back repetitively.  12...Nf8  And this maneuver @@StartBracket@@Ng8-f6-d7-f8-e6@@EndBracket@@ doesn't fall behind.  13.Nf5  The amusing part about the long route is that the knight wasn't pre-destined for f5, but intends to go to g3 @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ to undo the pin.  13...Qd7  14.Be3  There is complete harmony between white's pieces.  14...Ne6  For Black goes the same: he is rewarded for the effort he put into the maneuvering of the pieces, as they all occupy perfect spots.  15.c3!  Securing square d4 and preparing for and advance in the center.  15...O-O-O  16.Ng3!  After a long route, the knight reached its destiny: g3. See the theoretical section and model games section for more detailed analysis. . ½-½ @@StartBracket@@50@@EndBracket@@ Giri,A @@StartBracket@@2797@@EndBracket@@-Topalov,V @@StartBracket@@2740@@EndBracket@@ Shamkir 2019   10...O-O  This move has been tried by former challenger Karjakin, with success.  11.g4!  I'd like to come with this novelty and allegedly improvement over the game.  11...Bg6  12.Ne3!  A recurring theme - the knight route from b1 to f5! }
11. g4 Bg6 12. b4
{ A magnificent move! There is no way stopping White on his expansion on the queenside. }
12... Bb6
{ 12...axb4  won't offer Black salvation, as White will gladly use the open a-file for his pieces.  13.Bg5!  f6  14.axb4!  Black doesn't have time to take on g5.  14...Rxa1   14...O-O  This is another serious alternative which should be taken seriously by us.  15.Rxa8!  This can be considered as 'deflection'. The rook on f8 has to leave its post.  15...Rxa8  16.Bxf6  Qxf6  Out of the 3 choices to take back, this is probably the most dangerous option for White.  17.bxc5  h5  Trying to hit g4 hard, but White has a suitable response.  18.Kg2  hxg4  19.hxg4  Qf4  20.Ne3!  Perfect harmony by the two splendid central knights.  15.Qxa1  Bd6   15...fxg5?  Giving up on the defense of the pawn on e5.  16.bxc5  Black's pawn structure is a mess.  16.Be3  O-O  17.Nxd6!  Qxd6   17...cxd6  The will to improve its pawn structure is comprehensible. Nonetheless, it won't change the balance of the position being in white's favor.  18.Qa7⩲  18.Nh4⩲  White has a clear plan in the shape of Nf3-h4-f5. Black cannot create any counter chances. }
13. Rb1
{ Personally speaking, I am most fond of this subtle move. We move our rook to b1 in order to activate our rook across the b-file after b4-b5. With the rook on b5, we enforce f7-f6, after which we can move our knight via h4 to f5. An inherent side-effect is that we can maintain the bishop on the c1-h6 diagonal, not losing time on Bb2, like Caruana did.   13.Nxb6!?  ½-½ @@StartBracket@@51@@EndBracket@@ Tari,A @@StartBracket@@2630@@EndBracket@@ -McShane,L @@StartBracket@@2680@@EndBracket@@ Karlsruhe 2020   13.bxa5!?  Caruana,F @@StartBracket@@2828@@EndBracket@@ -Xiong,J  @@StartBracket@@2663@@EndBracket@@ Saint Louis 2019 1-0 @@StartBracket@@45@@EndBracket@@. }
13... axb4 14. axb4 O-O 15. b5
{ The whole idea behind our strategy. Black is in a pickle, will he take on b5, he should is forced to protect e5 with f6. On the other hand, when he prefers to avoid uninvited guests on b5, he will suffer from irreparable structural damage to his pawn structure after bxc6, bxc6.  Just before publication, I found out about this game recently played..   15.Nxb6  cxb6  16.Bg5  f6  17.Be3  ½-½ @@StartBracket@@30@@EndBracket@@ Matlakov,M @@StartBracket@@2682@@EndBracket@@-Sadhwani,R @@StartBracket@@2609@@EndBracket@@ Riga 2021. Here Black might obtain serious counterplay with:  17...Ra4! }
15... cxb5
{ It seems likely that our opponent will go for this line.   15...c5?  Black is stuck with a dead bishop on b6 now.  16.Bb2  f6  17.Nh4  17...Bf7  18.Nf5  Qd8  19.Qf3  with a very comfortable position for White. We can follow up with Nf5-e3-d5. }
