{ The outset of the knight's long journey to green and prosperous lands. Primarily, our adversary must take care of the e5-pawn. }
9... Nd7
{ As the former world champion stated, this is the ideal set-up for Black after which he shouldn't have any trouble. So, dear reader, it is up to me to conduct the task of bringing the advantage home in good conscience! }
10. a3 { A popular line these days. White is going to play b4. } 10... a5
{ To me, this seems like the most natural move. Black is hindering White's evil plans on the queenside of 'property theft' . }
11. g4
{ Honestly speaking, I was not sure at all if I would succeed in finding an advantage here for White. As Kramnik stated Black set up a favourable position, the knight is pinned and the only way to cut loose is to chastise ourselves with g2-g4. }
11... Bg6 12. b4
{ A magnificent move! Aside from some correspondence games played in 2013 and 2014, Anand was the first who played it in 2017 albeit in a blitz game and followed by Caruana in 2019, after which it got into fashion. Could this aggressive idea, likely missed by Kramnik, be the reason why this first allegedly passive line revives? Assumingly, whatever Black does @@StartBracket@@e.g., 10...a5@@EndBracket@@, there is no way stopping White on his expansion on the queenside. }
12... axb4
{ won't offer Black salvation, as White will gladly use the open a-file for his pieces. }
13. Bg5 f6 14. axb4 { Black doesn't have time to take on g5. } 14... Rxa1 15.
Qxa1
{ The queen makes that taking on g5 is of the table, since after bxc5, Qxc5, the e5-pawn would be hanging. It shows us how well her majesty is placed on a1. }
15... Bd6 16. Be3 O-O 17. Nxd6 cxd6
{ The will to improve its pawn structure is comprehensible. Nonetheless, it won't change the balance of the position being in white's favour. }
18. Qa7 Rb8 19. Nh4 *

