12... Bb6
{ We are at crossroads in this topical line. On top-level, several moves have been tried out. I like Caruana's  13.Bg5  , while I think that Dominguez Perez's  13.Nxb6  is interesting.   Nevertheless, my main recommendation here is  13.Rb1  and the reason is simple: we are set to get the initiative on the b-file, whereas our bishop can become of use on the c1-h6 diagonal.   13.Bb2  was played by Firouzja when after Black's  13...f6  , white can move his knight to f5. But then our bishop is misplaced, and it will take time to regroup it.  For that reason, I'd rather prompt our opponent to play f7-f6 @@StartBracket@@after b4-b5, cxb5 and then Rxb5@@EndBracket@@, while our bishop is still on c1.   13.Bd2!?  a4  14.Kg2  h5  15.Qe2  O-O-O  with equal play in: Firouzja, A @@StartBracket@@2728@@EndBracket@@-Aronian, L @@StartBracket@@2773@@EndBracket@@ Lichess. org INT 2020, 0-1 @@StartBracket@@47@@EndBracket@@. }
13. Rb1
{ Personally speaking, I am most fond of this subtle move. We move our rook to b1 to activate our rook across the b-file after b4-b5. With the rook on b5, we enforce f7-f6, after which we can move our knight via h4 to f5. An inherent side-effect is that we can maintain the bishop on the c1-h6 diagonal, not losing time on Bb2, as Caruana did. }
13... axb4
{ One of the points behind @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/1ppnqppp/1bp3b1/p3p3/1PN1P1P1/P2P1N1P/2P2P2/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 1 13@@EndFEN@@  13.Rb1  is manifested after  13...h5  14.bxa5!  Right, the b7-pawn is hanging.  14...Bxa5  15.Nxa5  Rxa5  16.Rxb7  with a large advantage for White. }
14. axb4 O-O 15. b5
{ The whole idea behind our strategy. Black is in a pickle, will he take on b5, he's forced to protect e5 with f6. On the other hand, when he prefers to avoid uninvited guests on b5, he will suffer from irreparable structural damage to his pawn structure after bxc6, bxc6. }
15... cxb5
{ It seems likely that our opponent will go for this line.   15...c5?  Black is stuck with a dead bishop on b6 now.  16.Bb2  f6  17.Nh4  17...Bf7  18.Nf5  Qd8  19.Qf3  with a very comfortable position for White. We can follow up with Nf5-e3-d5.   15...Bc5  maybe well be best for black. Nevertheless, I wouldn't be happy sitting behind the black pieces with these hideous double pawns.  16.bxc6  bxc6   15...f6  16.bxc6  bxc6 }
16. Rxb5
{ Perfect harmony! The knights on f3 and c4, the rook on b5, and the bishop on c1: we created a deeply silent scenery where the mind is freed from the bustle of everyday life! 😀 }
16... f6 17. Nxb6 { Swapping off the bishop on b6. } 17... Nxb6 18. Be3
{ Positionally, white is better. His pawn phalanx c2-d3-e4 is intact, rejoicing the advantage of only having one pawn island vs. the two islands of Black. }
18... Qd7 19. Rb4
{ Increasing the tension across the b-file by  19.Qb1!?  would have been a sound alternative. }
19... Qc6 20. Qb1
{ Fully utilizing the open b-file, White is playing on both wings. } 20... Ra6
21. Nh4
{ The threat is stronger than its execution, as Aron Nimzowitsch once said. }
21... Rfa8 22. Kg2
{ We have time for such a small move. It's pleasant to leave the first rank in case when the black rooks are seeking for counterplay via a1. }
22... Bf7 23. Nf5
{ White gradually builds up the pressure, improving all of his pieces before he undertakes action. }
23... Kh8 24. Bxb6
{ Time to act! We are not only causing harm to black's pawns, but in the meantime we try to create an entrance in the black position. }
24... Rxb6
{ Our opponent could also play  24...cxb6  , but we keep the advantage after  25.Ne3  h6  26.c4  indenting Nd5. }
25. Rxb6 cxb6 26. Qb4
{ Like a jack in the box, the white queen takes suddenly part in the game after the exchange on b6. Please take notice of the fact that both the e7 and d6-square are weak. At all costs, Black should try to stop Qb4-e7. }
26... Qxc2
{ Being greedy taking the pawn, Black resigns himself to the terrible fate he can never see coming.   26...Be6  in order to meet Qb4-e7 with Qc6-d7  27.Ra1!  taking over the a-file.  27...Rxa1??   After  27...Re8  28.Ne3  White would be much better due to the weak b-pawns  28.Qf8  Bg8  29.Qxg7 }
27. Qe7 Kg8 28. Qxb7 Rf8 29. Ne7+
{ Black must stash his king on h8, where it is subject to all kinds of back rank mates.   29.Ra1  g6  30.Ne7+  Kg7  With the king on g7, Black can still hope for a result. }
29... Kh8 30. Ra1
{ 'Black has serious back rank issues', is an understatement. } 30... Qxd3
{ 30...Ba2  31.Qxb6± } 31. Ra8 Rd8 32. Nf5 Kg8 33. g5
{ White demolishes Black's castle.   In case White would like to harm the mental state of his opponent, he could go for the carousel with  33.Ra7  Rf8  34.Ne7+  Kh8  35.Ra8  Rd8  36.Nf5  Kg8  before playing  37.g5  . }
33... fxg5 34. Rb8
{ The point behind this seemingly innocent, but winning move, will become clear quickly. }
34... h6
{ Black should refrain from  34...Rxb8  35.Qxb8+  resulting in a mate. } 35.
Qa8 { The point! Black should give upon his back rank. } 35... Rxb8 36. Qxb8+
{ And here we find the clue of White's 33rd move g4-g5: we take on e5 and mate Black on g7! }
36... Kh7 37. Qxe5
{ Despite the fact that the rooks have been swapped and there remain only two pieces on the board, Black is mated on g7. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Qe7 − 10.a3 a5 Main Line"]
[Black "4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Qe7 − 10.a3 a5 Main Line − 12...Bb6 #7 (Alternative 13.Nxb6)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
{ This variation - after  3...Nf6  - is called the 'Berlin Defense' or the 'Berlin Wall', due to its super solid nature. Rooted in the family of the Ruy Lopez opening @@StartBracket@@i.e., @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Bb5  @@EndBracket@@, the Berlin Defense was first seen in practice anno 1801, and examined by @@StartBracket@@it's in the name - who else?@@EndBracket@@ Berliners, as recorded in history. }
4. d3
{ With this move we set foot into the 'Anti-Berlin'. Keeping the queens on the board for the moment, we are sidestepping the forced lines arising after 4...Nxe4, amongst others the super solid ending c.q. the 'Berlin Wall', deployed 4 times by Kramnik against Kasparov with great success in the World Championship Match  @@StartBracket@@London, 2000@@EndBracket@@. }
4... Bc5
{ The bishop is placed actively on c5 and renders conquering the pawn on e5 less attractive for White. }
5. Bxc6
{ It's a recurring story: likewise in the Ruy Lopez Exchange @@StartBracket@@part 1@@EndBracket@@, we trade off the bishop for the knight in an early phase of the game, inflicting damages to Black's pawn structure, whereas we avoid - amongst others - the old but currently relevant variation after  5.O-O  Nd4!?  . }
5... dxc6
{ Here, the e5-pawn is poisoned, since after taking Black will strike back on f2 by 6...Qd4. Therefore, White brings his king in safety, whereafter he is ready to take on e5. }
6. O-O
{ Now that the e5-pawn is poisoned @@StartBracket@@  6.Nxe5??  Qd4-+  @@EndBracket@@,  White brings his king to safety, breathing new life in taking on e5.  Moreover, the bishop is not ideally placed on c5 now and often it goes back to d6 - with Black losing one move.   Another popular option for White is  6.Nbd2  , but like in the Ruy Lopez Exchange, I prefer a quick short castling.  Why? We kind of finalize our development, keeping our options open for different set-ups such as c3-d4, Bg5 or Be3, and Nbd2-f1-g3, Na3-c4 or Nc3. }
6... Qe7
{ According to the beliefs of the connoisseur from black's end and my idol Vladimir Kramnik, who tried here various continuations such as 6...Nd7 and 6...Bg4, this queen move could well be the best. He states that in case White delays h2-h3, Black also holds back with the move Nf6-d7 and first develops the bishop to g4. }
7. Nbd2
{ The first game in the 6...Qe7 line, started too cautiously with  7.Qe2?!  Bg4  8.h3  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@25@@EndBracket@@ Lehmann,K-Schramm, B Germany North 1980  8...Bh5  and Black is OK.   Specialist Vladimir Kramnik faced many White set-ups in this variation, like  7.h3?!  and felt that White should be punished for this inaccuracy... he deployed a direct assault on the king!  7...Rg8!!  8.Kh1  Nh5  9.c3  g5  10.Nxe5  g4  with promising attacking prospects for the former world champion, in Aronian, L @@StartBracket@@2794@@EndBracket@@-Kramnik, V @@StartBracket@@2800@@EndBracket@@ Berlin 2018, 0-1 @@StartBracket@@27@@EndBracket@@. }
7... Bg4
{ This can be considered as one of the main set-ups of Black in this line. And this is not without reason: Black pins the knight and prepares to castle long. White must come up with a plan. }
8. h3
{ Questioning the bishop where to go. Leaving the c8-h3 diagonal, in case of Bh5, can be considered as a small plus for us. On top of that, we take control over the g4-square and we can unpin by - when the time is ripe - g2-g4. The downside of the small pawn move could be that Black accelerates his attack across the g-file by g7-g5-g4.   The second game ever played in this line, and the first one on top-level, wasn't a big success for White. either.  8.Nc4  Nd7  9.Be3  Bd6  10.h3  Bh5  11.a4  f6  12.c3  Preparing d3-d4, but it won't be easy to make this move work.  12...b6  13.Re1  O-O  Black took in the ideal position and the position is equal. After d3-d4, Black can take on d4, then cxd4, Qxe4!  14.Bc1  Understandably, White endeavours to regroup the Knight to e3 and f5. But at the cost two tempos.. that comes at a high price! 0-1 @@StartBracket@@59@@EndBracket@@ Van der Wiel,J @@StartBracket@@2560@@EndBracket@@-Salov,V @@StartBracket@@2630@@EndBracket@@ Rotterdam 1989 }
8... Bh5 9. Nc4
{ The outset of the knight's long journey to green and prosperous lands. Primarily, our adversary must take care of the e5-pawn. }
9... Nd7
{ As the former world champion stated, this is the ideal set-up for Black after which he shouldn't have any trouble. So, dear reader, it is up to me to conduct the task of bringing the advantage home in good conscience! }
10. a3 { A popular line these days. White is going to play b4. } 10... a5
{ To me, this seems like the most natural move. Black is hindering White's evil plans on the queenside of 'property theft' . }
11. g4
{ Honestly speaking, I was not sure at all if I would succeed in finding an advantage here for White. As Kramnik stated Black set up a favourable position, the knight is pinned and the only way to cut loose is to chastise ourselves with g2-g4. }
11... Bg6 12. b4
{ A magnificent move! Aside from some correspondence games played in 2013 and 2014, Anand was the first who played it in 2017 albeit in a blitz game and followed by Caruana in 2019, after which it got into fashion. Could this aggressive idea, likely missed by Kramnik, be the reason why this first allegedly passive line revives? Assumingly, whatever Black does @@StartBracket@@e.g., 10...a5@@EndBracket@@, there is no way stopping White on his expansion on the queenside. }
12... Bb6
{ The next continuation is not my main recommendation but could give White the advantage as well. }
13. Nxb6
{ I was inspired by my teammate from Werder Bremen @@StartBracket@@German league@@EndBracket@@ and incredibly talented English GM Luc McShane. During the Covid edition of the Bundesliga final in Karlsruhe - playing with glass shields dividing the boards - he played this fine move against Tari. }
13... cxb6 14. Be3
{ Placing the bishop on the central e3 is positionally sound, and an interesting attempt in the struggle for an advantage. }
14... h5
{ Black wants to take on g4, and follow up with Qe6, hitting the g4-pawn. } 15.
Kg2 { When our adversary attacks the g4-pawn, we can defend it with Kg3. }
15... hxg4 16. hxg4 { This looks dangerous for White, but that's only optics! }
16... Qe6 17. Kg3
{ True, a strange-looking move, but it works and Black is running out of attacking options.   For instance, after  17...Nf6  White can proceed with  18.Ng5! }
17... O-O-O 18. Nh4
{ A miraculous move and plan, but it works! White can slowly build now on his advantage with Qf3, Rh1 and Nf5. }
18... Rh7 19. Qf3 Rdh8 20. Rh1
{ and White is better due to his better pawn structure. The next move will be Nf5. }
*

