19. Rh1
{ This is the whole point! By leaving the 8th rank, the black rook is out in the woods and White seizes the h-file. }
19... Rxh1 20. Rxh1 Qxa3 21. Nh4
{ White shouldn't be too keen playing Rh1-h8, as Black can parry this with  21.Rh8+  Kf7  22.g5  Ra8!  with unclear play. As Grandmaster and famous chess author Aron Nimzowitsch taught us, 'The threat is stronger than the execution.' }
21... Bf7 22. g5 { A great move, as White mobilizes his last piece. } 22... Kd8
23. Qg4
{ with the better play for White as a result of the promising attack on Black's king. }
