[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Nd7 Main Line"]
[Black "Introduction: 4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Nd7 Main Line"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6
{ The e5-pawn is poisoned since after taking Black will strike back on f2 by 6... Qd4. Therefore, White brings his king in safety, whereafter he is ready to take on e5. Moreover, the bishop is not ideally placed on c5 now and often it goes back to d6 - losing one move. }
6. O-O
{ Another popular option for White is 6. Nbd2. But like in the Ruy Lopez Exchange, I prefer a quick short castling. Why? We kind of finalize on our development, keeping our options open for different set-ups such as c3-d4, Bg5 or Be3, and Nbd2-f1-g3, Na3-c4 or Nc3. }
6... Nd7
{ This move has a solid reputation. It has been played by Ding Liren, Anand, Nakamura, and Ivanchuk, and - last but definitely not least @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ - your very own and favorite author! }
7. c3
{ Mostly played is  7.Nbd2  . However, by this move  7.c3  , White seizes immediately the initiative in the center. }
7... O-O
{ 7...h6!?  An extremely clever positional move. Black stops white from the maneuver Bc1-g5-h4-g3, from where it hits the central pawn on e5.  8.d4  Bd6  We are still following the game between Firouzja and Ding.  9.Nbd2  exd4  10.Nxd4!  This is my recommendation to get our opponent off track. Instead of playing the obvious 10.cxd4, we prepare for the advance of the f-pawn meanwhile improving our knight.   10.cxd4  O-O  11.h3  Nb6!  preparing for the counterpunch in the center. ½- @@StartBracket@@14@@EndBracket@@ ½ @@StartBracket@@47@@EndBracket@@ Firouzja,A @@StartBracket@@2728@@EndBracket@@-Ding,L @@StartBracket@@2791@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020 }
8. d4
{ In order not to be overrun, Black refuses to give up on the central point e5. }
8... Bd6
{ 8...exd4  9.cxd4  Be7  10.Nc3  Nb6  Probably the safest option of the two.   10...b5  11.Bf4!  In the Ruy Lopez Exchange @@StartBracket@@Volume 1@@EndBracket@@ I was an ardent advocate bringing the bishop to f4, firing at the backward c-pawn. Here again it comes in use.  11.h3!  Restricting the c8-bishop: where can it go to now?  11...f5!?  Gaining influence on the light squares in the center.  12.Qb3+  Kh8  13.Ne5  Qe8  an often seen idea from our opponent to take into account. The queen is moving to our king.  14.Re1  White obtained the initiative without giving up on the light squares.   8...Bb6!?  9.Bg5  f6  10.Be3  Re8  11.Nbd2  Nf8  12.a4  a5  13.Qc2⩲ }
9. Bg5
{ In these kind of positions, would anyway go Qe8 and f6, so why would White give Black a nudge in that direction and help him on his way? The answer is that the bishop is excellently placed on g3, hitting e5. }
9... f6
{ 9...Be7  10.Bxe7  Qxe7  11.Nbd2  Black's position is solid, albeit he is far off from equality.  11...exd4  12.cxd4!?  White has the better pawn structure here and should be able to keep the control in the center.   9...Qe8!?  This moves contains a similar idea as 9..f6, only with a different move order. Besides, Black can instantly hit the center by c6-c5, meanwhile postponing f7-f6.  10.Nbd2  However, there is another - and quite sound - continuation for Black.  10...c5!?  Try to solve the ugly ducklings - c. q. the doubled c-pawns - meanwhile fighting the center.  11.dxe5  Nxe5  12.Nxe5  Bxe5  13.f4  White chases the bishop and is about to conquer the central squares after 13... Bd6 14. e5.  13...f6!  A crucial response. After 14.Bh4 Black goes back to d6 with his bishop when he gets sufficient counterplay in the shape of the two bishops.  14.fxe5  fxg5  15.Qb3+!  when Black is under serious pressure. }
10. Bh4
{ Black is limited in his options. First he wants to move the queen from the diagonal of the bishop, then he overprotects e5 with rook e8, while creating space for the knight-regrouping via f8 to g6. }
10... Qe8
{ 10...Qe7  11.Nbd2!  I find this the best move here. White wants to bring without further ado his knight to c4. Momentarily he postpones Rf1-e1.  11...Re8  12.Bg3  c5  Was played in a correspondence game.  13.Nc4!  Nb6  14.Nxd6!  We should look what is left on the board, not what pieces disappear. True, Black improves his pawn structure. But on the other hand, he is stuck without an active plan.  14...cxd6  15.a4!  White takes the lead on the queenside, whereas Black cannot start equal operations on the kingside.   10...c5!?  We cant blame Black getting caught watching the paint go dry. Unhesitant, he starts an offense in the center.  11.Bg3  Qe7  12.Na3!  We stick to our plan. We move our knight to c4 instantly!  12...cxd4  13.cxd4  exd4  This move is by far the best for Black. There aren't many alternatives left, since Nc4 or Nb5 is a real threat.  14.Bxd6  Qxd6  15.Nb5  Aesthetically pleasing, when White occupies his best set-up: Nf3 and Nd4, Qc2 and Rd1 and Rc1.  15...Qb6  16.Nbxd4⩲   10...a5!?  This move was played in several correspondence games. Thus, from an objective point of view, we should take this line serious!  11.Nbd2  a4  12.Re1  b5  13.Bg3  Putting up the heat on the crucial point of e5.  13...Qe7  14.Nf1⩲ }
11. Nbd2
{ White doesn't stand still obviously, postponing the move Re1 for the moment. Now Black has to reckon with Nc4 and - evt. - Nxd6. }
11... Qf7
{ Black prepares for Re8 and Nf8, meanwhile hindering Nc4.   11...Qe6  Ideally, stopping the knight hop to c4.  12.Bg3  Like in the main line after 11..Qf7, White is increasing the pressure on the central point e5.  12...b6  13.Re1  Fortifying the center, but also clearing the path for the knight @@StartBracket@@Nd2-f1-e3 and evt. Nf5@@EndBracket@@.  13...Ba6  14.Qc2  Kh8  15.b3!  This is an important move in the struggle for an advantage. White is aiming to enhance his influence on the White squares, after e.g. c3-c4. Occasionally, the c4-square can be used for the knight. }
12. Bg3
{ The bishop reached his destiny. Black must take precautionary measures to face the increasing pressure on e5. }
12... Re8 13. Qc2 Nf8
{ This essential rerouting of the knight to g6, is indispensable in Black's operations.   13...b6  14.Rfe1  a5  15.Nf1  White has options and could have opted for Nd2-c4 as well. Another plan would have been Nf3-h4-f5. I prefer this move due to its flexibility, meanwhile maintaining the pressure on e5 @@StartBracket@@keeping the f3-knight on its post@@EndBracket@@.  15...Nf8  16.dxe5!  fxe5  17.Ne3  The knight has anyways good prospects, but f5 is likely the toughest for Black to handle.  The move   13...a5  is leading to a transposition. Please compare the lines arising after 12..a5 13.Qc2 Re8.  14.b3!  Preparing for Nc4. }
14. dxe5
{ Good timing to take at this time on e5. When the Black knight reaches g6, he wouldn't have taken back with the pawn on e5. Good timing to take now on e5. When the Black knight reaches g6, he wouldn't have taken back with the pawn on e5. }
14... fxe5 15. Ng5
{ We enter a forced line with a lot of exchanges. White paves the way for Qb3+. We enter a forcing line with a lot of exchanges. As a result of this chasing away of the black queen of the a2-diagonal, White paves the way for Qb3+. }
15... Qf6 16. Qb3+ Ne6
{ Blocking the diagonal, whereas the major drawback for Black here is that after 17.Nxe6 he can't take back with the bishop. }
17. Nxe6 { When Black takes on e6 with the bishop, the pawn on b7 is hanging. }
17... Qxe6
{ The most obvious continuation for Black, although 17... Rxe6 shouldn't be underestimated by us!  This rather odd-looking move taking back the piece with the rook, possibly allows a trick for us on which we ought to be alert.   17...Rxe6!?  18.Nc4!?  It is a recurring theme in most of the lines: the knight maneuver Nb1-d2-c4, and then Nxd6, causing a backward pawn on d6. }
18. Nc4
{ Black can't hold on two the advantage consisting of the two bishops. After Nxd6, Black remains with a backward pawn on d6. The ensuing positions are in White's favor. Warmerdam,M @@StartBracket@@2497@@EndBracket@@ -Werle, J @@StartBracket@@2545@@EndBracket@@ Netherlands NED 2020 1/2 @@StartBracket@@20@@EndBracket@@-1/2 @@StartBracket@@22@@EndBracket@@. }
