exd4 10. Nxd4
{ This is my recommendation to get our opponent off track. Instead of playing the obvious  10.cxd4  , we prepare for the advance of the f-pawn while improving our knight.   10.cxd4  O-O  11.h3  Nb6!  preparing for the counterpunch in the center.  12.Nb3  f5!  Ding sets up a blockade on the light squares.  13.e5  Be7  the squares on d5 and e6 are in his pocket now.  14.Qc2  f4!  By this move, Ding provides his bishop sufficient strong squares to go to @@StartBracket@@e6 and f5@@EndBracket@@. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@47@@EndBracket@@ Firouzja,A @@StartBracket@@2728@@EndBracket@@-Ding,L @@StartBracket@@2791@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020 }
10... O-O 11. f4
{ In the struggle for the center we can say: in for a penny, in for a pound! }
11... Bc5 12. Nf3
{ It's too early to say that White is better, albeit he is building up a serious initiative in the center. Black must watch his steps! }
12... Re8 13. Qc2 Nf6
{ attacking the center is a sound plan, but Black is not yet fully prepared. }
14. e5 Nd5 15. f5 { when the avalanche of pawns seems threatening. } *

