exd4 10. Nxd4
{ This is my recommendation to get our opponent off track. Instead of playing the obvious  10.cxd4  , we prepare for the advance of the f-pawn meanwhile improving our knight.   10.cxd4  O-O  11.h3  Nb6!  preparing for the counterpunch in the center.  12.Nb3  f5!  Ding sets up a blockade on the light squares.  13.e5  Be7  the squares on d5 and e6 are in his pocket now.  14.Qc2  f4!  By this move, Ding provides his bishop sufficient strong squares to go to @@StartBracket@@e6 and f5@@EndBracket@@. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@47@@EndBracket@@ Firouzja,A @@StartBracket@@2728@@EndBracket@@-Ding,L @@StartBracket@@2791@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020 }
10... O-O 11. f4
{ In the struggle for the center we can say: in for a penny, in for a pound! }
11... Bc5 12. Nf3
{ It's too early to say that White is better, albeit he is building up a serious initiative in the center. Black must watch his steps! }
12... Re8 13. Qc2 Bb6 14. Be3 Nf6
{ Black's strategy - containing some evil plans targeted against White's center - become manifest. }
15. Ne5 { White's cavalry takes a stand against Black's oppression on e4. }
15... Ng4
{ Understandably, Black wants to encounter the supremacy of the knights. } 16.
Nxg4 Bxg4 17. h3
{ It's always good to get the opportunity to play this useful move without wasting time. We get the upper hand due to our better pawn structure. For instance, }
17... Bd7
{ The bishop has trouble finding a proper square. The c6-pawn is blocking him too.    17...c5!?  is hard to find for our opponent. It may well be the best way to fight for equality.  18.Nf3  Bxf3  19.Rxf3  c4!  Black is definitely not beating around the bush. Exchanges are programmed for, and... no time to waste!  20.e5  Qd5  21.Rd1  Qc6  White has two interesting plans here. I illustrate the positional one, in which White allows the exchanges of the rooks.  22.Kh2   The other one is the kingside attack by means of  22.Rg3  ,  moving the queen @@StartBracket@@via e2 or d1@@EndBracket@@ to g4.  22...Rad8  should be slightly more pleasant, because of the better pawn structure of ours. }
18. Rae1
{ We are conducting the strategy of fighting the bishop pair: exchanging a pair of bishops and limiting the scope of the other one. So, we are not seduced by moving our pawn to e5.   Instead of maintaining the central pawn on a light square, this pawn push is less aesthetically pleasing as it enhances the power of the light-squared black bishop.  18.e5?!  f6!  ⇆ }
18... Qe7 19. Bf2
{ The saga continues: we are again not seduced by moving the pawn to e5, but keep it here on e4 for a while restricting the bishop on d7. }
19... Rad8 20. Kh2
{ A useful prohylaxis preparing the push of the pawns leaving the diagonal on which the king can get in danger. }
20... Bc8 21. f5
{ The same move and plan played as well by Fischer and Lasker in the games noted below. The black bishop is restricted and the pawn majority is set in motion. These plusses outweigh the downside of creating a backward e-pawn }
21... f6 22. Nf3
{ Here, I would like to refer you to my extensive analysis in the classical model games of Lasker-Capablanca, St. Petersburg 1914  (1-0)  and Fischer-Unzicker, Olympiad Siegen, 1970  (1-0)  included in part 1 of the Smart Ruy Lopez, in which they outplayed their opponents in an outstanding way. The technique of the players illustrates the way how such games ought to be played. }
