7... O-O
{ 7...a5  This move was tried with success by Wesley So against Anish Giri, played in a recent online rapid game.  8.d4  Bd6  9.Bg5  We are aiming for similar ideas and to reach positions alike as in our main line, though with a different move order.  9...f6  10.Bh4  O-O  11.Nbd2  would transpose to our main line after 10...a5.   @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1ppn1ppp/2pb4/p3p3/3PP3/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Re1  a4  10.Nbd2  exd4  11.cxd4   11.Nc4!?  dxc3  12.Nxd6+  cxd6  13.Qxd6  Qe7  14.Qd4  with compensation for the sacrificed pawn in: Pavlov, V @@StartBracket@@2430@@EndBracket@@-Panitevsky, I @@StartBracket@@2489@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2016 ½-½ @@StartBracket@@30@@EndBracket@@.  11...Nb6  12.Nf1  O-O  13.Bg5  f6  14.Bh4  Bg4  15.h3  Bh5  16.Qd3  Qd7  17.g4  Bg6  Black was better in Giri, A @@StartBracket@@2776@@EndBracket@@-So, W @@StartBracket@@2770@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2021 1-0 @@StartBracket@@50@@EndBracket@@. }
8. d4 exd4
{ From a classical perspective, it's a concession for Black to give up on the center. White will get a space advantage whereas the bishops don't possess any long diagonals to thrive. Nonetheless, Black attempts to fight for the light central squares by f7-f5. }
9. cxd4 Be7 10. Nc3
{ Nakamura played this position twice with Black. First, he tried the audacious  10...b5  but found himself in trouble. By the way, it shouldn't be overlooked that the games in question were a blitz and a rapid game. }
10... b5 11. Bf4
{ In the Ruy Lopez Exchange @@StartBracket@@Volume 1@@EndBracket@@ I was an ardent advocate bringing the bishop to f4, firing at the backward c-pawn. Here again it comes in use. }
11... Bb7 12. Qc2 { connecting the rooks. Life for White seems so easy here. }
12... a6 13. Rad1 Qc8 14. Ne2
{ The knight heads for the black king.   14.Ne5?!  I don't see a reason to help Black exchange his poorly-placed pieces; it considerably eases his defensive task.  14...Nxe5  15.Bxe5  Re8  16.Bf4  c5  17.dxc5  Bxc5  18.Nd5  Bxd5  19.exd5  Bd6  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@19@@EndBracket@@ Anand, V @@StartBracket@@2764@@EndBracket@@ -Nakamura, H @@StartBracket@@2754@@EndBracket@@ Paris 2019. }
14... Re8 15. Ng3
{ Black is facing hard times. He hasn't solved the problems regarding his b7-bishop yet. }
15... c5 16. d5 Bd6 17. Bxd6 cxd6 18. Nf5
{ There is no doubt that White is better here. The d6-pawn and b7-bishop are weak, whereas the f5-knight can't be driven away by Black. At least, not in the foreseeable future. }
