8. d4 exd4
{ From a classical perspective, it's a concession for Black to give up on the center. White will get a space advantage whereas the bishops don't possess any long diagonals to thrive. Nonetheless, Black attempts to fight for the light central squares by f7-f5. }
9. cxd4 Be7 10. Nc3
{ Nakamura played this position twice with Black. First, he tried the audacious  10...b5  but found himself in trouble. By the way, it shouldn't be overlooked that the games in question were a blitz and a rapid game. }
10... Nb6 { Probably the safest option of the two. } 11. h3
{ Restricting the c8-bishop: where can it go to now? } 11... f5
{ Gaining influence on the light squares in the center. } 12. Qb3+
{ Please don't close the center and put your pawns on the colour of your own bishop, by  12.e5?  Be6  Black gained the upper hand by his full control over the central light squares. }
12... Kh8 13. Ne5 Qe8
{ an often-seen idea from our opponent to take into account. The queen is moving to our king. }
14. Re1 fxe4 { This may be an inaccuracy. } 15. Nxe4 Nd5
{ Here, I would like to recommend the following improvement over the game. }
16. Bd2
{ I like these kind of 'small' and useful moves. We improve our development whereas Black finds it hard to move his pieces out.   16.Bg5  Bb4!  a nice defensive configuration of the pieces. Black blocks the b-file, after which he is free to move the c8-bishop.  17.Nc3  Be6!  completing the development.  18.Qc2  Qh5  whereafter it seems that Black solved most of his problems. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@50@@EndBracket@@ So, W @@StartBracket@@2767@@EndBracket@@-Nakamura, H @@StartBracket@@2745@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020. }
16... Qh5
{ What else? The c8-bishop can't get out since the b7-pawn would be hanging. }
17. Ng3 { There aren't real suitable square for the queen. } 17... Qh4
{ In case of  17...Qe8  , White could have followed up by  18.Re4  and Rae1. }
18. Nf3 { One move back two make two forward! } 18... Qf6 19. Bg5
{ By exchanging the bishop, we expose even more the weakened e-file and f7-square. }
19... Qd6 20. Bxe7 Nxe7
{ and now the gates of Black's castle are opened for us. Please take notice of the fact that Black is missing a f-pawn to guard his king. }
21. Ng5 Nd5
{ Closing the a2-g8 diagonal again, but he is not out of the troublesome situation. }
22. Qc2 g6 { won't save Black, due to the next 'powerplay' of White. } 23. Re5
{ A sign of superiority of the white troops. } 23... Bd7 24. Rae1
{ All of White's pieces are dominant in comparison to their black counterparts. }
24... Kg8 25. N3e4 { with Nc5 to follow is winning for White. } *

