{ We find ourselves in a double-edged position. In my opinion, we can raise tension by }
16. a4
{ after which our opponent can be deceived by the following snare:   16.Rxf7  Qxf7  17.Qxf7+   17.Qd5!  would complicate the matters somehow but wouldn't put Black at risk of losing.  17...Be6!  18.Qxb7  Rd8=∞  19.Nf3  h6⇆  and the knight is struggling to find a proper square.  17...Kxf7  18.Rf1+  Ke7  leaves Black on top. }
16... b6 { A logical, but bad move. } 17. Rxf7 Qxf7
{ Even though,  17...Be6!  would have been a better option.  18.Rxg7+!  Kxg7  19.Qd1  with a big advantage for White. }
18. Qd5
{ The point behind this move is that Black doesn't have time for Be6, while we force our adversary to take on d5. }
18... Rb8 19. Rf1 { forcing the exchange of the queens. } 19... Qxd5 20. exd5
{ with a close to winning position, as White's pawn structure improved significantly. }
*

