9... f6 10. Bh4
{ Black is limited in his options. First, he wants to move the queen from the diagonal of the bishop, then he overprotects e5 with rook e8, while creating space for the knight-regrouping via f8 to g6.   10.Qb3+!?  Kh8  11.Bh4  b6  12.Nbd2  Ba6  13.Rfe1  Qe7  14.dxe5  Nxe5  15.Nxe5  Qxe5  16.Bg3  followed by taking on d6, left White slightly for choice in Eljanov,P @@StartBracket@@2751@@EndBracket@@-Radjabov,T @@StartBracket@@2710@@EndBracket@@ Shamkir 2017, 1-0 @@StartBracket@@46@@EndBracket@@. Please have a look at the Model Games section how to play such a position. }
10... Qe7 11. Nbd2
{ I find this the best move here. White wants to bring without further ado his knight to c4. Momentarily he postpones Rf1-e1. }
11... Re8 12. Bg3 c5 { Was played in a correspondence game. } 13. Nc4
{ This is my novelty. I like this move even more than the move  13.Re1  in the correspondence game: Zugrav-Romm @@StartBracket@@2016@@EndBracket@@ @@StartBracket@@1-0@@EndBracket@@. The idea behind this move is to swap the bishop before starting with the expansion on the queenside.   13.Re1  Qf7  14.d5  c6  15.c4   The move  15.dxc6  leads to a better position as well.  15...Nb6  16.Qc2  Bd7  17.a4  Nc8  18.Nf1  Ne7  19.Ne3  was slightly better for White in 1-0 @@StartBracket@@70@@EndBracket@@ Zugrav, W @@StartBracket@@2567@@EndBracket@@-Romm, M @@StartBracket@@2473@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2016. }
13... Nb6 14. Nxd6
{ We should look what is left on the board, not what pieces disappear. True, Black improves his pawn structure. But on the other hand, he is stuck without an active plan. }
14... cxd6 15. a4
{ White takes the lead on the queenside, whereas Black cannot start equal operations on the kingside. }
15... Be6 16. Re1 Rad8 17. a5
{ The poor knight must leave its post, while White takes a lot of space. }
17... Nd7 18. h3
{ Preventing the pin by Be6-g4 for once and for all. Moreover, placing the pawns on white squares is restricts the scope of the adversary's bishop. }
18... Nf8 19. d5
{ White is fully prepared to close the center, not fearing counterplay against his king. }
19... Bd7 20. Nd2
{ Once Black plays f5, we take on f5 securing the e4-outpost for our knight. }
20... Ng6 21. b4 { The black queenside is starting to falter. } *

