{ Black is limited in his options. First, he wants to move the queen from the diagonal of the bishop, then he overprotects e5 with rook e8, while creating space for the knight-regrouping via f8 to g6.   10.Qb3+!?  Kh8  11.Bh4  b6  12.Nbd2  Ba6  13.Rfe1  Qe7  14.dxe5  Nxe5  15.Nxe5  Qxe5  16.Bg3  followed by taking on d6, left White slightly for choice in Eljanov,P @@StartBracket@@2751@@EndBracket@@-Radjabov,T @@StartBracket@@2710@@EndBracket@@ Shamkir 2017, 1-0 @@StartBracket@@46@@EndBracket@@. Please have a look at the Model Games section how to play such a position. }
10... Qe7 11. Re1
{ This has been tried in practice by Firouzja, but I couldn't find anything serious here for White. }
11... a5 12. Nbd2 Qf7 13. Bg3 Re8 14. b3
{ This theme is recurring in the plenty lines here. White enhances his influence on the light squares while preparing for Nc4. }
14... a4 { Black is seeking counterplay and he finds it across the a-file. }
15. Qc2 axb3
{ Black is opting for a forced line with a lot of exchanges, in his quest for relief. Of course there were plenty of alternatives, but one way or another, the screws are tightened after Nd2-c4. }
16. axb3 Rxa1 17. Rxa1
{ The outcome after the exchanges is that one pair of rooks are off the board, which gets him breathing a bit more. On the other side, White tries to break in by Ra1-a8 or a7 in conjunction with Nd2-c4, hitting e5, is still not off the table. }
17... exd4 18. cxd4 Nb6 19. Nc4
{ This is my recommendation, asking the d6-bishop to show his cards.   After  19.h3  Bxg3  20.fxg3  Be6  21.Ra7  Rb8  22.Kh2  h6  23.b4  Nc8  24.Ra1  Nd6  Black was doing fine in ½-½ @@StartBracket@@41@@EndBracket@@ Firouzja, A @@StartBracket@@2728@@EndBracket@@-So, W @@StartBracket@@2770@@EndBracket@@ Lichess.org INT 2020. }
19... Bf8 { Black's position is very robust. } 20. Ne3
{ This involves a pawn sacrifice. } 20... Be6 21. Ra7
{ White must try to play as active as possible. The passive Rb1 is not an option in the tense battle for an advantage. }
21... Rb8 22. h3 { White is inviting his opponent to grab the pawn. } 22...
Bxb3 23. Qc3 { Intending d4-d5 here, after which the bishop on b3 is trapped. }
23... Be6 24. d5 { White is aiming for the weak backward c7-pawn. } 24... cxd5
25. Qxc7 { 25.Bxc7  can't be recommended, because of  Rc8-+ } 25... Rc8
{ Fighting his way out of the pressure, improving his rook.   The point behind this move is that after  26.Qxb6  Bc5  Black is winning back material.  Moreover, White wants to make his initiative count, and therefore, would rather avoid the exchange of the queens. }
26. Qxb6
{ Black should find all these difficult moves, and this is not yet the end. The pawn on b7 is taken when Black takes on e4. }
26... Bc5 27. Qa5 Bxa7 { strangely enough, Black ought to take first on e4. }
28. Qxa7 dxe4 29. Nd4 { when the white pieces are just too dominant. } *

