[Black "4...Bc5 5.Bxc6 dxc6 6.O-O Nd7 Main Line 7.c3  − 9...f6 #5 (Alternative 11.Re1)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. O-O Nd7
{ This move has a solid reputation. It has been played by Ding Liren, Anand, Nakamura, and Ivanchuk, and - last but definitely not least @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ - your very own and favourite author! }
7. c3
{ Mostly played is  7.Nbd2  .  However, by this move  7.c3  , White seizes immediately the initiative in the center.   For instance,  7.Nbd2  O-O  8.Nc4  f6  9.Kh1!?  a5  10.a4  Nb6  11.Be3  Bxe3  12.Nxe3  Be6  13.Ng1!  1-0 @@StartBracket@@108@@EndBracket@@ Giri, A @@StartBracket@@2764@@EndBracket@@-Lysyj, I @@StartBracket@@2593@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2020. }
7... O-O
{ 7...a5  This move was tried with success by Wesley So against Anish Giri, played in a recent online rapid game.  8.d4  Bd6  9.Bg5  We are aiming for similar ideas and to reach positions alike as in our main line, though with a different move order.  9...f6  10.Bh4  O-O  11.Nbd2  would transpose to our main line after 10...a5.   @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1ppn1ppp/2pb4/p3p3/3PP3/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Re1  a4  10.Nbd2  exd4  11.cxd4   11.Nc4!?  dxc3  12.Nxd6+  cxd6  13.Qxd6  Qe7  14.Qd4  with compensation for the sacrificed pawn in: Pavlov, V @@StartBracket@@2430@@EndBracket@@-Panitevsky, I @@StartBracket@@2489@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2016 ½-½ @@StartBracket@@30@@EndBracket@@.  11...Nb6  12.Nf1  O-O  13.Bg5  f6  14.Bh4  Bg4  15.h3  Bh5  16.Qd3  Qd7  17.g4  Bg6  Black was better in Giri, A @@StartBracket@@2776@@EndBracket@@-So, W @@StartBracket@@2770@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2021 1-0 @@StartBracket@@50@@EndBracket@@. }
8. d4 Bd6
{ In order not to be overrun, Black refuses to give up on the central point e5. }
9. Bg5
{ In this kind of positions, would anyway go Qe8 and f6, so why would White give Black a nudge in that direction and help him on his way? The answer is that the bishop is excellently placed on g3, hitting e5. }
9... f6 10. Bh4
{ Black is limited in his options. First, he wants to move the queen from the diagonal of the bishop, then he overprotects e5 with rook e8, while creating space for the knight-regrouping via f8 to g6.   10.Qb3+!?  Kh8  11.Bh4  b6  12.Nbd2  Ba6  13.Rfe1  Qe7  14.dxe5  Nxe5  15.Nxe5  Qxe5  16.Bg3  followed by taking on d6, left White slightly for choice in Eljanov,P @@StartBracket@@2751@@EndBracket@@-Radjabov,T @@StartBracket@@2710@@EndBracket@@ Shamkir 2017, 1-0 @@StartBracket@@46@@EndBracket@@. Please have a look at the Model Games section how to play such a position. }
10... Qe7 11. Re1
{ This has been tried in practice by Firouzja, but I couldn't find anything serious here for White. }
11... a5 12. Nbd2 Qf7 13. Bg3 Re8 14. b3
{ This theme is recurring in the plenty lines here. White enhances his influence on the light squares while preparing for Nc4. }
14... a4 { Black is seeking counterplay and he finds it across the a-file. }
15. Qc2 axb3 16. axb3 Rxa1 17. Rxa1 exd4 18. cxd4 Nb6 19. Nc4
{ This is my recommendation, asking the d6-bishop to show his cards.   After  19.h3  Bxg3  20.fxg3  Be6  21.Ra7  Rb8  22.Kh2  h6  23.b4  Nc8  24.Ra1  Nd6  Black was doing fine in ½-½ @@StartBracket@@41@@EndBracket@@ Firouzja, A @@StartBracket@@2728@@EndBracket@@-So, W @@StartBracket@@2770@@EndBracket@@ Lichess.org INT 2020. }
19... Bf8 { Black's position is very robust. } 20. Ne3
{ This involves a pawn sacrifice. } 20... Be6 21. Ra7
{ White must try to play as active as possible. The passive Rb1 is not an option in the tense battle for an advantage. }
21... Rb8 22. h3 { White is inviting his opponent to grab the pawn. } 22...
Bxb3 23. Qc3 { Intending d4-d5 here, after which the bishop on b3 is trapped. }
23... Be6 24. d5 { White is aiming for the weak backward c7-pawn. } 24... cxd5
25. Qxc7 { 25.Bxc7  can't be recommended, because of  Rc8-+ } 25... Rc8
{ Fighting his way out of the pressure, improving his rook.   The point behind this move is that after  26.Qxb6  Bc5  Black is winning back material.  Moreover, White wants to make his initiative count, and therefore, would rather avoid the exchange of the queens. }
26. Qxb6
{ Black should find all these difficult moves, and this is not yet the end. The pawn on b7 is taken when Black takes on e4. }
26... Bc5 27. Qa5 dxe4 { After all these hard moves, Black is doing fine. } 28.
Nd2 Bxa7 29. Qxa7
{ We reached a balanced position after 29 moves, but we can't say that we haven't tested our opponent maximally! }
*

