10... c5
{ We can’t blame Black getting caught watching the paint go dry. Unhesitatingly, he starts an offense in the center. }
11. Bg3 Qe7 12. Na3
{ We stick to our plan. We move our knight to c4 instantly!   12.dxe5  fxe5  13.Nbd2  Nb6  14.Qe2  Bg4  led to unclear play in 0-1 @@StartBracket@@47@@EndBracket@@ Wang, H @@StartBracket@@2758@@EndBracket@@ -Paravyan, D @@StartBracket@@2629@@EndBracket@@ Caleta 2020. }
12... cxd4 13. cxd4 Nb6
{ Halting  14.Nc4  , but not  14.Nb5  . In the following sequence of moves, Black is obliged to concede a weak pawn on d6.   13...Bxa3  14.Qb3+!  with a small plus for White. }
14. Nb5 { The pressure on the squares on the diagonal h2-b8 is immense. } 14...
Bd7 15. dxe5 fxe5 16. a4 { This pawn push is surprisingly annoying for Black. }
16... Bc6 { 16...a5?  loses to  17.Nxd6  cxd6  18.Qb3+  . } 17. Nxd6 cxd6
{ The d6-pawn is backward and hard to defend: please notice that after Rad8, White can win the exchange by Bg3-h4. }
18. Qb3+ Kh8 19. a5
{ when White is clearly better. He is concentrating on d6, proceeding with Qb4 and Rfd1. }
