{ White doesn't stand still obviously, postponing the move Re1 for the moment. Now Black must reckon with Nc4 and - evt. - Nxd6.   Recently Grischuk played  11.Re1  in a blitz game with success:  11...Nb6  12.Nbd2  a5  13.Bg3  a4  14.Qc2  c5  15.dxe5  fxe5  16.Nf1  Rxf3!?  A drastic decision, burning all the bridges, but interesting.   In case of  16...Bg4  , White could follow up with  17.Nh4  ,  and evt., 18.Ne3, 19.Nhf5 etc.  17.gxf3  Qh5?!   17...Qf7!  would have been stronger, e.g.  18.Ne3  Be6  19.Nf5  Bxa2  with a double-edged position.  18.Qe2⩲  sacrificing the knight and pawn in return for Black's strong light-squared bishop. Grischuk, A @@StartBracket@@2777@@EndBracket@@-Maghsoodloo, P @@StartBracket@@2676@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 1-0 @@StartBracket@@60@@EndBracket@@. }
11... Qf7 { Black prepares for Re8 and Nf8, meanwhile hindering Nc4. } 12. Bg3
{ The bishop reached his destiny. Black must take precautionary measures to face the increasing pressure on e5. }
12... Re8 13. Qc2 b6
{ this move is from a positional perspective very playable: for the moment Black keeps the knight on d7 and grabs space on the queenside. Moreover, he gets a better grip on light squares now that his c8-bishop can get out. }
14. Rfe1 { Not merely defending e4, but vacating f1 for the knight as well. }
14... a5 15. Nf1
{ White has options and could have opted for Nd2-c4 as well. Another plan would have been Nf3-h4-f5. I prefer this move due to its flexibility, meanwhile maintaining the pressure on e5 @@StartBracket@@keeping the f3-knight on its post@@EndBracket@@. }
15... Nf8 16. dxe5
{ An improvement over the game we are following, as Black is forced to take the pawn back with the pawn.   16.Ne3  didn't cause Black much trouble.  16...Ng6  Now Black can take back with the knight and bishop on e5, when White takes.  17.Nf5∞  @@StartBracket@@Lagno, K @@StartBracket@@2549@@EndBracket@@-Lei, T @@StartBracket@@2483@@EndBracket@@ China 2019, 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@33@@EndBracket@@. }
16... fxe5 17. Ne3
{ The knight has anyways good prospects, but f5 is likely the toughest for Black to handle. }
17... Ng6 { Black allows here the forced line: } 18. Ng5
{ The resemblances with the main line are apparent. } 18... Qe7 19. Qb3+ Be6
20. Qxe6+ { Entering a slightly better ending. } 20... Qxe6 21. Nxe6 Rxe6 22.
Rad1
{ When White gained the better odds because of his superior pawn structure and the black pawn structure remains weak. }
