{ 7...a5  This move was tried with success by Wesley So against Anish Giri, played in a recent online rapid game.  8.d4  Bd6  9.Bg5  We are aiming for similar ideas and to reach positions alike as in our main line, though with a different move order.  9...f6  10.Bh4  O-O  11.Nbd2  would transpose to our main line after 10...a5.   @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/1ppn1ppp/2pb4/p3p3/3PP3/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Re1  a4  10.Nbd2  exd4  11.cxd4   11.Nc4!?  dxc3  12.Nxd6+  cxd6  13.Qxd6  Qe7  14.Qd4  with compensation for the sacrificed pawn in: Pavlov, V @@StartBracket@@2430@@EndBracket@@-Panitevsky, I @@StartBracket@@2489@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2016 ½-½ @@StartBracket@@30@@EndBracket@@.  11...Nb6  12.Nf1  O-O  13.Bg5  f6  14.Bh4  Bg4  15.h3  Bh5  16.Qd3  Qd7  17.g4  Bg6  Black was better in Giri, A @@StartBracket@@2776@@EndBracket@@-So, W @@StartBracket@@2770@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2021 1-0 @@StartBracket@@50@@EndBracket@@. }
8. d4 Bd6
{ In order not to be overrun, Black refuses to give up on the central point e5. }
9. Bg5
{ In this kind of positions, would anyway go Qe8 and f6, so why would White give Black a nudge in that direction and help him on his way? The answer is that the bishop is excellently placed on g3, hitting e5. }
9... f6 10. Bh4
{ Black is limited in his options. First, he wants to move the queen from the diagonal of the bishop, then he overprotects e5 with rook e8, while creating space for the knight-regrouping via f8 to g6.   10.Qb3+!?  Kh8  11.Bh4  b6  12.Nbd2  Ba6  13.Rfe1  Qe7  14.dxe5  Nxe5  15.Nxe5  Qxe5  16.Bg3  followed by taking on d6, left White slightly for choice in Eljanov,P @@StartBracket@@2751@@EndBracket@@-Radjabov,T @@StartBracket@@2710@@EndBracket@@ Shamkir 2017, 1-0 @@StartBracket@@46@@EndBracket@@. Please have a look at the Model Games section how to play such a position. }
10... Qe8 11. Nbd2
{ White doesn't stand still obviously, postponing the move Re1 for the moment. Now Black must reckon with Nc4 and - evt. - Nxd6.   Recently Grischuk played  11.Re1  in a blitz game with success:  11...Nb6  12.Nbd2  a5  13.Bg3  a4  14.Qc2  c5  15.dxe5  fxe5  16.Nf1  Rxf3!?  A drastic decision, burning all the bridges, but interesting.   In case of  16...Bg4  , White could follow up with  17.Nh4  ,  and evt., 18.Ne3, 19.Nhf5 etc.  17.gxf3  Qh5?!   17...Qf7!  would have been stronger, e.g.  18.Ne3  Be6  19.Nf5  Bxa2  with a double-edged position.  18.Qe2⩲  sacrificing the knight and pawn in return for Black's strong light-squared bishop. Grischuk, A @@StartBracket@@2777@@EndBracket@@-Maghsoodloo, P @@StartBracket@@2676@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 1-0 @@StartBracket@@60@@EndBracket@@. }
11... Qf7 { Black prepares for Re8 and Nf8, meanwhile hindering Nc4. } 12. Bg3
{ The bishop reached his destiny. Black must take precautionary measures to face the increasing pressure on e5. }
12... Re8 13. Qc2 a5 14. b3 { Preparing for Nc4. } 14... Nf8 15. dxe5 fxe5 16.
Nc4
{ As we see now, the knight conducts an important role in our struggle for an advantage. }
16... Ng6
{ Black is just in time to protect the pawn on e5, finalizing the knight manoeuvre Nd7-f8-g6. }
17. Rfe1
{ An interesting alternative is  17.Rad1!?  Bg4  18.Rd3  when White still has some pressure, especially on d6/the d-file. }
17... a4
{ Here, I would like to propose the following straightforward approach. } 18.
Nxd6
{ Seemingly, Black gets the opportunity to improve his structure. But, in fact, we dismantle his structure by creating an even bigger weakness, on d6. }
18... cxd6 19. bxa4
{ This provocative move has not merely the purpose of luring the queen to a4, after which the d6-weakness will even be more difficult to defend. We are also opening the b-file for our rook. }
19... Qc4
{ This position is on a computer-basis highly critical, and appeared in two relatively recent computer games. }
20. Rad1
{ I would like to come up with this novelty. With this move, we ascertain that we win the d6-pawn to enhance the pressure on e5, meanwhile, we let Black do 'his thing' on the a-file.   20.Qb3  To my taste, this is a bit of a timid move and less dangerous for Black in the quest for equality.  20...Rxa4  21.h3  Qxb3  22.axb3  Rxa1  23.Rxa1  Kf8  Bringing the king to the center, Black managed to repel White's pressing. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@30@@EndBracket@@ Broemme, S @@StartBracket@@2443@@EndBracket@@-Efimov, Y @@StartBracket@@2454@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2018. }
20... Qxa4 21. Qxa4 Rxa4
{ Black engages a2, but we set our mind on something far more valuable: a juicy little pawn on e5. }
22. Rxd6 Rxa2 23. h3
{ A subtle move, not only preventing Bg4. We put our rook on e3 while not fearing to get mated on the back rank. }
23... Ra3 24. Re3 { Another option for Black is: } 24... Ra5 25. Re2 Rc5 26.
Rc2 Nh8 27. Rd1 Nf7 28. Nd2
{ White will follow with f3 and Nd2-f1-e3. Our position is to be preferred as we own less pawn islands. }
*

