{ This provocative move has not merely the purpose of luring the queen to a4, after which the d6-weakness will even be more difficult to defend. We are also opening the b-file for our rook. }
19... Qc4
{ This position is on a computer-basis highly critical, and appeared in two relatively recent computer games. }
20. Rad1
{ I would like to come up with this novelty. With this move, we ascertain that we win the d6-pawn to enhance the pressure on e5, meanwhile, we let Black do 'his thing' on the a-file.   20.Qb3  To my taste, this is a bit of a timid move and less dangerous for Black in the quest for equality.  20...Rxa4  21.h3  Qxb3  22.axb3  Rxa1  23.Rxa1  Kf8  Bringing the king to the center, Black managed to repel White's pressing. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@30@@EndBracket@@ Broemme, S @@StartBracket@@2443@@EndBracket@@-Efimov, Y @@StartBracket@@2454@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2018. }
20... Qxa4 21. Qxa4 Rxa4
{ Black engages a2, but we set our mind on something far more valuable: a juicy little pawn on e5. }
22. Rxd6 Rxa2 23. h3
{ A subtle move, not only preventing Bg4. We put our rook on e3 while not fearing to get mated on the back rank. }
23... Ra3 24. Re3
{ All is set and done to hit Black hard. Starting with taking on e5. } 24...
Kf7 25. Kh2 { Pursuing the knight manoeuvre Nf3-e1-d3-c5. } 25... h6 26. Ne1
Be6 27. Nd3
{ Black would better not take on c3 due to a discovered check. White has a small but pleasant plus. The pawn on e5 is hard to protect and we can be 'creative' on several ways to make our opponent's life difficult. Here, Black has to deal with the perilous knight jump to c5. }
27... Ra5
{ An important defensive resource, keeping the things together, cq protecting the pawn on e5 and knight invasion via c5. }
28. c4 { No, we don't give our opponent time to breath! } 28... Bxc4 29. Rf3+
{ Here Black his king and g6-knight are in danger, resulting in the forced move Ng6-f4, after which we have options: taking on e5 or on f4 come to the fore. Both lines look terrifying for Black. Let's stop here and conclude that our opponent will encounter more than just 'difficulties' during a hand-to-hand fight.   After  29...Nf4  30.Nxf4  exf4  31.Bxf4  White enjoys central superiority and the black king is exposed. }
*

