20. Nf3
{ The line  20.Ng4!?  Qg5  21.e5  Qxg4  22.exd6  cxd6  looks easy giving White the advantage.   The line  20.Nc4  Rxe4  21.Nxd6  cxd6  22.Rfe1  Re7  23.Qb4  seems also very promising for White.   In the first instance, the engine liked  20.f4  , but after a while, it is less enthusiastic, because of  20...Qe7  21.Rf3  b6  22.Qc2  Bxe5  23.fxe5  Rg6!  A multi-purpose move, clearing the way for the bishop to e6 where it halts a rook invasion on f7.  24.e6  In order to clear the range of the bishop.   24.Raf1  Be6!  with a balanced position.  24...Bxe6  25.Raf1  Intending to follow up with 26. e5, pinning the rook. However, I couldn't find any strong continuations to make use of the pin. }
20... Rxe4 21. Rfe1 { Black can't take on e1 as he can't encounter Re8. } 21...
Rxe1+ { putting the fox in the henhouse, after } 22. Rxe1 Qg6
{ Stopping 22.Re8, but it doesn't take into account the next strong move of White. }
23. Nh4 { Black is tumbling down rapidly here. } 23... Qh5 24. h3
{ This mysterious and innocent-looking move deserves two exclamation marks?? The point is that }
24... b6 { 24...Bd7  is not possible, on the account of  25.Qxb7  . } 25. Qc4
{ Black has no suitable response to the attack on c6.   25...c5??  26.Qe4++-  .   The play could continue  25...Bd7  26.Bxd6  Paving the way for the rook's entrance to e7.  26...cxd6  27.Re7  Obviously, White obtained a preponderant advantage here due to the strong rook on the 7th rank, the weak black king and the vulnerable black pawns.  27...Rd8  A poor move, but what else?  28.Qe4+  Kg8  The course of events is so favourable for White, that due to this superiority of our pieces there inevitably arises the opportunity to strike by means of a combination.  29.Rxg7+!  Kxg7  30.Qe7+  Qf7  31.Qxd8  and White is winning. }
