{ Black is limited in his options. First, he wants to move the queen from the diagonal of the bishop, then he overprotects e5 with rook e8, while creating space for the knight-regrouping via f8 to g6.   10.Qb3+!?  Kh8  11.Bh4  b6  12.Nbd2  Ba6  13.Rfe1  Qe7  14.dxe5  Nxe5  15.Nxe5  Qxe5  16.Bg3  followed by taking on d6, left White slightly for choice in Eljanov,P @@StartBracket@@2751@@EndBracket@@-Radjabov,T @@StartBracket@@2710@@EndBracket@@ Shamkir 2017, 1-0 @@StartBracket@@46@@EndBracket@@. Please have a look at the Model Games section how to play such a position. }
10... Qe8 11. Nbd2
{ White doesn't stand still obviously, postponing the move Re1 for the moment. Now Black must reckon with Nc4 and - evt. - Nxd6.   Recently Grischuk played  11.Re1  in a blitz game with success:  11...Nb6  12.Nbd2  a5  13.Bg3  a4  14.Qc2  c5  15.dxe5  fxe5  16.Nf1  Rxf3!?  A drastic decision, burning all the bridges, but interesting.   In case of  16...Bg4  , White could follow up with  17.Nh4  ,  and evt., 18.Ne3, 19.Nhf5 etc.  17.gxf3  Qh5?!   17...Qf7!  would have been stronger, e.g.  18.Ne3  Be6  19.Nf5  Bxa2  with a double-edged position.  18.Qe2⩲  sacrificing the knight and pawn in return for Black's strong light-squared bishop. Grischuk, A @@StartBracket@@2777@@EndBracket@@-Maghsoodloo, P @@StartBracket@@2676@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 1-0 @@StartBracket@@60@@EndBracket@@. }
11... Qf7 { Black prepares for Re8 and Nf8, meanwhile hindering Nc4. } 12. Bg3
{ The bishop reached his destiny. Black must take precautionary measures to face the increasing pressure on e5. }
12... Re8 13. Qc2 Nf8
{ This essential rerouting of the knight to g6, is indispensable in Black's operations.   The move  13...a5  leads to a transposition to the variation 12...a5 13. Qc2 Re8. }
14. dxe5
{ Good timing to take at this time on e5. When the black knight reaches g6, he wouldn't have taken back with the pawn on e5. }
14... fxe5 15. Ng5
{ We enter a forcing line with a lot of exchanges. As a result of this chasing away of the black queen of the a2-diagonal, White paves the way for Qb3+. }
15... Qf6 16. Qb3+ Ne6
{ Blocking the diagonal, whereas the major drawback for Black here is that after  17.Nxe6  he can't take back with the bishop.   The idea behind the move  16...Be6  would miserably fail, due to  17.Nxe6  Qxe6  18.Qxb7  Rab8  19.Qxc6  Rxb2  longing in vain for compensation  20.Nc4  White is clearly better, being a pawn up in connection with the better structure and pieces.   16...Kh8??  Please don't force me to explicate this simple but nice mate 😆  17.Nf7+  Kg8  18.Nh6+  Kh8  19.Qg8# }
17. Nxe6
{ This rather odd-looking move taking back the piece with the rook, possibly allows a trick for us on which we ought to be alert. }
17... Rxe6 18. Nc4
{ It is recurring theme in most of the lines: the knight manoeuvre Nb1-d2-c4, and then Nxd6, causing a backward pawn on d6. }
18... h6
{ Another peculiar move, suggested and the main choice by/of the engine. The stunning underlying idea will present itself swiftly in the ensuing lines. }
19. Nxe5
{ This line illustrates White's potential in this type of position.   Black's @@StartFEN@@r1b3k1/ppp3pp/2pbrq2/4p3/2N1P3/1QP3B1/PP3PPP/R4RK1 b - - 1 18@@EndFEN@@  18...h6  took the sting out of  19.Nxd6  . How come, I hear you thinking. Let's delve into the most forcing continuation to find out!   19.Nxd6  cxd6  20.f4  Most critical, as Black is so low on development.  20...exf4  21.Bxf4  Qe7   Not good is  21...Qg6?  because of  22.Bxd6!±  22.Rad1  Kh8  23.Bxd6  Rxd6  24.Qb4  Here we see the deep point behind Black's move 18...h6! The pin is no longer lethal as Black doesn't have to worry about a back-rank mate anymore.  24...Re6!  25.Qxe7  Rxe7  Black will lose the piece on c8 after  26.Rd8+  Kh7  and  27.Rff8  , but not the game. }
19... Kh7
{ Here, we have plenty of choices. The moves  20.Nc4!?  ,  20.Nf3!  ,  20.Ng4!?  and  20.f4  all have their merits. I picked  20.Nf3  , since I believe it is the strongest continuation. }
20. Nf3
{ The line  20.Ng4!?  Qg5  21.e5  Qxg4  22.exd6  cxd6  looks easy giving White the advantage.   The line  20.Nc4  Rxe4  21.Nxd6  cxd6  22.Rfe1  Re7  23.Qb4  seems also very promising for White.   In the first instance, the engine liked  20.f4  , but after a while, it is less enthusiastic, because of  20...Qe7  21.Rf3  b6  22.Qc2  Bxe5  23.fxe5  Rg6!  A multi-purpose move, clearing the way for the bishop to e6 where it halts a rook invasion on f7.  24.e6  In order to clear the range of the bishop.   24.Raf1  Be6!  with a balanced position.  24...Bxe6  25.Raf1  Intending to follow up with 26. e5, pinning the rook. However, I couldn't find any strong continuations to make use of the pin. }
20... Rxe4 21. Rfe1 { Black can't take on e1 as he can't encounter Re8. } 21...
Re6 22. Rad1 b6 23. Qc2+
{ Preparing to take on e6, avoiding  23.Rxe6  Bxe6!  when the bishop can be placed on d5. }
23... Kg8 24. Rxe6 Qxe6
{ A sound alternative is to aim for the merits arising in the positions with opposite-coloured bishop middlegames. }
25. Re1 { 25.Nd4  Qe8!  stopping both  26. Re1 and 26. Nxc6. } 25... Qf7 26.
Ne5
{ Settling on e5, aiming for an attack - characterized by the strength of the bishop across the dark squares - on the black king. See for these distinctive plans the Model Game Stellwagen-Werle in part 1 of this Smart Ruy Lopez series. }
26... Bxe5 { Black can impossibly allow this 'octopus' on e5. } 27. Rxe5 Be6
28. b3
{ This position can be considered as pleasant for White. Even when Black succeeds in swapping the rooks off the board, the extra pawn on the kingside and the weak c7-pawn grant us winning chances. }
*

