25... Qc5 26. Be3 a3 { The passed pawn decides the outcome of the game. } 27.
Bxd4 Qxd4 28. c3 Qf6 29. f3 { 29.Qa2?  Qxc3-+ } 29... Red8
{ The game is over not because of the well known principle of two weaknesses.. no.. Kramnik pays hommage to the principle of three weaknesses! }
30. d4 c5 { It's time for some demolition work! } 31. d5 c6
{ White can't keep black's pieces at a distance: there are too many holes to be fixed. }
32. Qe3 cxd5 33. Qxc5+ Kg8 34. Qe3 a2 35. Ra1 dxe4 36. fxe4 Ra3
{ White's pawns are scattered. } 37. Rg3 h4 38. Rf3 b4
{ White's position is tumbling down. } 39. Qc5 Rxc3 40. Rxc3 Qxc3 *

