[SetUp "1"]

{ How should Black take back on e5? } 12... Bxe5
{ 12...Qxe5?  looks like the most natural move, but it isn't the best!  13.f4!  Qe8  White takes control of the center.  14.e5  White wins time and forces Black to hand over one of his bishops.  14...Be7  15.Bxe7  Qxe7  Black can still stop the advance of the f4-pawn, for the time-being.  16.Qf3±  Black is in deep trouble since he should stop f4-f5 at all costs and Bf5 can't be played because of Qxb7. White will proceed with Nd2-c4-e3, to lift the blockade on f5.  16...c6   16...f6!  In case Black fights the center, he will give White the opportunity to bring in the knight to e5.  17.Rae1  fxe5  18.Nc4  Qf7  19.Nxe5  Qxa2  20.g4!!  The bishop is boxed in.  20...Qa6  21.f5  The difference between the strength of the minor pieces is evident.   16...Rd8  1-0 @@StartBracket@@35@@EndBracket@@ Obodchuk,A @@StartBracket@@2374@@EndBracket@@-Denisov, D @@StartBracket@@1944@@EndBracket@@ Volgograd 2017  17.Nc4!±  17.Ne4± }
13. f4 f6
{ The only move to hold the lines on the kingside.   13...Bd6?  Would lead to a similar position as just discussed after 12.. Qxe5.  14.e5  Be7  15.Bxe7  Qxe7  16.Qf3± }
14. fxe5
{ After 14. Bh4 Black goes back, when the e5-square is @@StartBracket@@also@@EndBracket@@ in Black hands. }
14... fxg5 15. Qb3+ Rf7
{ Again an unnatural move, but the only one to keep square e6 under control. On the next move Black will be able to play 16..Be6, obtaining the better chances.   15...Be6  16.Rxf8+  forces Black to awkwardly recapture  16...Kxf8  17.Qxb7+-  and his position is in ruins. }
16. Rxf7
{ 16.Rad1  b6!?  and on the next move ...Be6.  Or   16...Be6  17.Qxb7  Rb8  18.Qxa7  Rxb2⇆  when Black's activity might compensate for the missing pawn. }
16... Qxf7 17. Qxf7+
{ 17.Qd5∞  would keep the position unbalanced. 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@24@@EndBracket@@ Potrata,J @@StartBracket@@2277@@EndBracket@@ -Lendero,L @@StartBracket@@2063@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2017 }
17... Kxf7 18. Rf1+ Ke7
{ Black has no weaknesses @@StartBracket@@the g5- and c5-pawns can easily be defended@@EndBracket@@ - on the contrary, these pawns control important central squares! White's knight is inferior to Black's bishop and he will have to worry about his doubled and isolated e-pawns for the rest of the game. }
