[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Alireza Firouzja − Liem Le Quang, Wch Rapid, Moscow 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. O-O Bd6 7. Bg5 h6 8.
Bh4 { Maintaining the pin. } 8... Be6 9. Nbd2 g5 10. Bg3 Nd7 11. d4
{ Increasing the tension on the central point e5. } 11... Qf6
{ 11...exd4  hasn't been tested yet but is quite interesting.  12.Bxd6  cxd6  13.Nxd4  Qf6  14.Nxe6  Qxe6  when Black can hold with accurate play. }
12. Re1 O-O-O 13. c4 g4
{ 13...h5!  in the game it appears that Black is missing the boat. With this move, and subsequently ...h5-h4, he is in time with his counterplay.  14.c5  h4  15.cxd6  hxg3! }
14. c5 Bxc5 15. dxc5 gxf3 16. Qxf3 Qe7
{ 16...Qxf3!?  was maybe enough for a draw. For instance,  17.Nxf3  f6  18.b4  b5⇆ }
17. b4 h5 18. h4
{ A defensive resource to remember. White is closes the files on the kingside. }
18... Rhg8 19. Qc3 Rg4 20. a4 { 20.Nf1!  Rdg8  21.Nh2  R4g6  22.a4→ } 20...
Rdg8
{ 20...a5!!  A splendid defensive concept. Black hits the b4-c5 pawn formation, subsequently with ...f7-f5.  21.Rec1  f5  22.exf5  axb4! }
21. Nf3
{ 21.Rac1!?  may have been a very interesting attempt to get the better position. White is preparing for b4-b5.  21...f6  22.b5  looks very promising for us. }
21... Rxg3
{ Black goes all-in.   After  21...f6  White could go for the same plan as in the 21. Rac1 line.  22.Nh2  R4g7  23.Nf1  proceeding with Rac1 and b5. }
22. fxg3 Rxg3
{ Funnily enough, also in this position we should not be too worried and apply the same attacking plan as before. }
23. Qe3 f6 24. Kh2 Rg4 25. Rac1 Qg7 26. Re2
{ The best practical chance here for Black was to play energetically, activating his knight and bishop. }
26... Nf8
{ 26...f5!  27.exf5  Bd5!  when the character of the position becomes very sharp. Black will follow up with ...Nf6 and - if he is allowed - ...Ng4 or ...Ne4. }
27. Rd2
{ 27.b5  Ng6  28.Rd2  Nf4  29.Rg1  and after g2-g3, White would be on top. }
27... Qh7 28. Qd3 Bd7 29. Re1 Ne6 30. Red1
{ We don't let our opponent's knight come to f4. } 30... Nf8 31. Qb3
{ The young superstar builds in a treacherous tactic. } 31... Rxe4
{ 31...Rg8  32.b5!  Besides solidifying the kingside, he never forgot about his own chances.  32...cxb5  33.axb5  After c5-c6 on the next move, Black's position collapses. }
32. Rxd7 Nxd7 33. Qe6
{ What can Black do against Qe8 mate? The rook on e4 can't come back in the house. }
33... Kd8 34. Qxf6+ { Whoops, that was threatening too. } 34... Ke8 35. Qe6+
Kd8 36. Nxe5 { The position collapsed like a house of cards. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Fabiano Caruana − Jeffery Xiong, USA-ch, Saint Louis 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. O-O Qe7 7. Nbd2 Bg4 8.
h3 Bh5 9. a3 a5 10. Nc4 Nd7 11. g4 Bg6 12. b4 Bb6 13. bxa5 Bxa5 14. Bb2
{ Forcing ...f7-f6, paving the way for Nf3-h4-f5. } 14... f6 15. Nxa5 Rxa5 16.
Nh4 O-O 17. Nf5 Qe6 18. Kh2
{ Another idea would be  18.h4  , but the text move prepares the same pawn storm. }
18... c5
{ Black expands his initiative by trying to open lines on the queenside. However, this will not be too easy. }
19. h4 { Now it's White's turn. } 19... c4 20. h5 Bf7
{ 20...Bxf5  doesn't look appealing for Black now that the g-file is opened.  21.gxf5  Qf7  22.Rg1  With the doubling on the g-file to come next. }
21. Rg1 cxd3 22. cxd3 Rb5 23. Bc1
{ Of course, pointing our pieces gradually increasingly on the hostile king. }
23... Kh8 24. Be3
{ But Caruana makes time to improve the position of the pieces. He does not hurry. }
24... Rb3 25. Rg3 c5 26. Qe2 { Clearing the path for the other rook. } 26... g5
{ Black felt that the net was closing in around his king, so he decided to break out, but now the kingside gets a more open character. }
27. hxg6 Bxg6
{ 27...hxg6  28.Rh3+  Kg8  29.Kg2!  Black is helpless against Rah1. } 28. a4
Qa6 29. Bh6 Rg8 30. Rag1 Qxa4 31. Ne7
{ Black couldn't save material anymore, as ...Re8 would neither end well for him. }
31... Qd4
{ 31...Re8  32.Nxg6+  hxg6  33.g5  f5  34.exf5  is neither what Black had desired for  34...gxf5?  35.Qh5+- }
32. Qd1
{ Caruana is showing his high standards with the following ingenious plan.   32.Be3?!  Qxd3   32.Nxg8  Rb2⇆ }
32... c4
{ Now the position gets an open character which is beneficial for the rooks.   32...Ra3  33.Nxg8  Kxg8  34.Bc1!?  Ra2   34...Qxf2+?  35.R1g2  and Black is losing material.  35.Be3± }
33. Nxg8 Kxg8 34. dxc4 Rxg3 35. Qxd4 exd4 36. Kxg3
{ Without hesitation the king is mobilised, defusing the d-pawn. } 36... Bxe4
37. Rd1 d3 38. f3 { The rest is a children's game; Black is hopelessly lost. }
38... Bg6 39. Ra1 Kf7 40. Ra7 Nc5 41. Be3 { The knight has to give up on b7. }
41... Ke8
{ Can White take the knight and keep his winning chances? What do you think? }
42. Bxc5 d2 43. Ra8+ { The king goes to d7 to stop Rd8. } 43... Kd7 44. Bb6 Kc6
45. Ba5
{ A grandiose final chord of an outstanding game.   45.Ba5  d1=Q  The queen will be X-rayed by:  46.Rc8+  Kd7  47.Rd8+  when White is winning. }
