1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 d6 5. O-O g6 6. d4 Bd7 7. d5 Ne7 8. Bxd7+
Nxd7 9. c4 Bg7 10. Be3 h6 11. Nfd2 f5 12. f3 f4 13. Bf2 g5 14. Nc3 Ng6
{ A sample line reflecting both sides plans, could be  14...O-O  15.b4!?  Compared to So's set-up, this is the more common pawn advance by White in these King's Indian type of positions.  15...Rf7  16.c5  Nf6  17.a4  h5  18.Nc4  Bf8  19.Kh1  g4  20.a5  Rg7  21.b5  g3  22.Be1  22...gxh2  23.b6 }
15. c5 { Strike while the iron is hot! } 15... Nxc5
{ 15...dxc5?  16.Qb3!  Not merely hitting b7, but as well with the idea of opening the diagonal.  16...b6  17.d6  Where should Black's king hide?  17...cxd6  18.Qe6+  Once more, it becomes clear in this line that Black is missing his light-squared bishop!  18...Ne7  19.Nc4  and White is winning after Nxd6 with a check @@StartBracket@@and mate@@EndBracket@@. }
16. Bxc5 dxc5 17. Qb3 { The queen takes in the perfect position. } 17... b6 18.
d6 { Of course this move! The king is still on e8! } 18... Qxd6 19. Nc4 Qc6
{ 19...Qe6  is possible, but Black is not out of danger.  20.Nb5  Qe7  21.Rad1  White obtained dangerous compensation. }
20. Rfd1
{ Taking stock of the position, White sacrificed 2 pawns giving him total control of the light squares, keeping the black king in the center. }
20... Nf8
{ 20...h5  Such a move can only be proposed by a computer! Someone of flesh and blood would probably take precautionary measures fearing all the danger approaching his king.  21.Nb5!  White is threatening Nd6+ and Qf7.  21...g4?   21...Ke7  anticipating Nd6+, was of course a better choice:  22.Rd5  Another light square which is fully in White's hands.  22...a6  23.Nbd6  Black cannot take the knight and is in serious danger, now that the king is so exposed.  23...Rhd8  24.Nf5+=∞ }
21. Rd5 Ne6 22. Nxe5 Bxe5 23. Rxe5 c4
{ 23...Kf7  24.Rd1  Rhd8  25.Rdd5⩲  Crawling in the light-squared holes, gaining territory. Because of its initiative, the white pieces should be preferred. }
24. Qa3 { The queen is luring for e7. } 24... Kf7 25. Rf5+ Kg6 26. Nd5
{ White's strategy prevailed: he found an entrance in Black's camp. } 26...
Qc5+ 27. Qxc5 Nxc5 28. Rf6+
{ The rook is on its way to c6: the best spot on the board. } 28... Kg7 29. Rc6
Rhe8 { 29...Rac8  30.Rc1!  when we win a pawn, as ...b5 is not possible. } 30.
Rxc7+ Kg6 31. h4
{ 31.Rc1  would have led to a big advantage to White. This move contains a tactical threat to the king. }
31... Rad8 32. h5+ Kxh5 33. Nf6+ Kh4 34. Nxe8 Rxe8 35. Kh2
{ Douze points for the eye-catching original idea containing Rh1, Kg1+ and Rh3 mate.   Nonetheless,  35.Rd1  with the idea of  Rd6 and Rxh6 was more efficient. }
35... g4 36. Rh1 g3+ 37. Kg1+ Kg5 38. Kf1 Rd8 39. Ke2 Ne6 40. Rxc4 Nd4+
{ Black chases the king back to the last rank, where the rook remains locked in. }
41. Ke1 h5
{ Now that the rook on h1 is out of play, there is still hope on survival. }
42. Rc7 Kg6 43. Rc3
{ The rook is building a bridge for the king on the d-file. Meanwhile, it pins. }
43... Kg5 44. Rd3 h4 45. Kd1 a5 46. a4 Rd6 47. e5
{ The final blow which is deciding the game. } 47... Rd8 48. Rd2 Kh5 49. Re1
