1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. O-O Bg4 7. h3 Bh5 8.
g4 { White wants to get rid of the annoying pin as soon as possible. } 8...
Nxg4
{ 8...Bg6  9.Nxe5  Qd6  10.Bf4   10.Nxg6  Qg3+  11.Kh1  Qxh3+  12.Kg1  Qg3+  13.Kh1  hxg6+ }
9. hxg4 Bxg4 10. Be3
{ completing the development. White is gaining time since Black cannot allow the exchange of the bishops. The fact of being a piece up would gain importance. }
10... Be7
{ Played by Magnus Carlsen in a recent internet game. Analysis is showing that this deviation from the main path Bd6  @@StartBracket@@which had been played 4 times@@EndBracket@@ is an improvement. }
11. Kh1
{ Was played by Nakamyra. After this move White got in serious trouble against the reigning world champion.   11.Kg2!  I believe this is an improvement over the game Carlsen-Nakamura. Please find the analysis in the theoretical section.  11...f5  12.Qe1  12...Bxf3+   12...O-O  13.Nh2  13.Kxf3  13...f4  14.Bd2  g5   14...Qd7  15.Ke2  15.Bc3  Bf6  16.Nd2  Qe7  17.Rh1⩲  1-0 @@StartBracket@@47@@EndBracket@@ Giri,A @@StartBracket@@2764@@EndBracket@@ -Tari,A @@StartBracket@@2625@@EndBracket@@ Wijk aan Zee 2021 }
11... f5 12. Rg1 h5
{ keeping the strong g4-bishop and threatening to take on e4. } 13. Nc3
{ 13.exf5?  e4!  here the difference wirth the Bd6-line comes to the light.  14.dxe4  Qxd1  15.Rxd1  Bxf3+   13.Rxg4  hxg4+ }
13... f4
{ Black changes his strategy comprising a kingside attack to a pawn avalanche on the kingside. }
14. Bd2 g5 { There they come! And there is nothing White can do. } 15. Nb1 Bc5
{ Not only hitting f2, but threatening B:f3, g4 and Qh4 as well. } 16. Bc3 Bxf2
17. Nbd2
{ White can't afford to lose precious time and should give in handing material back.   17.Rf1  Bg3  18.Bxe5  Rf8  the pawn on e5 is of no importance. The 3 pawns on the kingside do the job.  19.Nbd2  Bh3  20.Rg1  g4  and the pawns are unstoppable. Black is winning here. }
17... Qe7 { preparing for long castling. } 18. Qf1
{ 18.Rg2  Bb6  19.Qf1  Bxf3  20.Nxf3  Rg8  21.Nxe5  O-O-O  22.Re1  Rdf8 } 18...
Bxg1 19. Qxg1 Bxf3+ 20. Nxf3
{ 1-0 @@StartBracket@@33@@EndBracket@@ Nakamura,H @@StartBracket@@2736@@EndBracket@@ -Carlsen,M @@StartBracket@@2863@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020 }
20... g4
{ The king is stuck in the corner and Black will develop a dangerous attack. And to make matters worse, Black is positionally definitely not worse. He has 3 connected pawns in return for the exchange. }
21. Nxe5 Rg8
{ 21...O-O-O  can't be recommended.  22.Qxa7  As a jack-in-the-box, the queen would have met Black's king. }
22. Rf1 Qg5
{ 22...f3  there are more ways how Black can go wrong.  23.Nxf3   22...Qh4+  23.Qh2 }
23. Qd4
{ Objectively not the best move, but Nakamura is taking a chance going all-in.   23.Qf2  f3  is simply much better for Black.  24.Qg3  O-O-O  25.Nf7  h4!!  26.Qe5   26.Nxg5  hxg3  Qxe5  27.Bxe5  Rdf8  28.Nh6  g3  29.Kg1  f2+  30.Kg2  h3+  31.Kxh3  g2-+ }
23... Qh4+ { 23...Rd8  24.Qc4  would transpose to the line after 26.Kg1 Rd8. }
24. Kg1 Qg3+ 25. Kh1 Qh3+ 26. Kg1 g3
{ Carlsen overplays his hand. White can block the pawns while parrying all Black's underlying threats.   26...Rd8!  27.Qc4  with numerous threats, would have forced Black to give the pereptual check.  27...Rd5!!  28.exd5  f3  29.Rf2  g3  30.Nxf3  gxf2+  31.Kxf2  Rg4  32.Qc5  Qg2+  33.Ke3  Rg3-+ }
27. Nf3 g2 { In for a penny.. } 28. Re1 Qxf3
{ 28...Qe6  There is no return. After the exchange of queens with  29.Qf6  Qxf6  30.Bxf6  Black pawns are blockaded and ready to be picked up. }
29. Qe5+ Kd8 30. Qf6+ Ke8
{ Can you find the winning continuation for Naka?   30...Kd7  would be mate in 5:  31.Qf7+  Kd6  32.e5+  Kc5  33.Qc4+  Kb6  34.Qb4+  Ka6  35.Qa5   30...Kc8  31.Qe6+ }
31. Bb4 { No way that Black can stop the mate on e7. } 31... c5 32. Bxc5 Kd7
33. Qf7+
{ 1-0 @@StartBracket@@33@@EndBracket@@ Nakamura,H @@StartBracket@@2736@@EndBracket@@-Carlsen,M  @@StartBracket@@2863@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020   33.Qf7+  Kc6  34.Qd5+  Kb5  35.a4+  Ka6  36.Qc4+  and on the next move it's a mate. }
