1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. O-O Bg4 7. h3 Bh5
{ Likewise in the Pin-variation of the first course of this series about the RLE, Black maintains the pin.   7...Bxf3  is another main option for Black. }
8. g4
{ White wants to get rid of the annoying pin as soon as possible. Once more, as in the Pin variation of the Ruy Lopez Exchange @@StartBracket@@Volume 1@@EndBracket@@, a sound plan. }
8... Nxg4 { In the battle for the initiative, Black should not hold back. } 9.
hxg4 Bxg4
{ The writing is on the wall, Black's attack is threatening as the two bishops are powerful and our king is in the open field. This is our end, isn't it? }
10. Be3
{ By this move we expel the strong-c5 bishop while completing the development. White is gaining time since Black cannot allow the exchange of the bishops. The fact of being a piece up would gain importance. }
10... Be7
{ Played by Magnus Carlsen in a recent internet game. Analysis is showing that this deviation from the main path Bd6 @@StartBracket@@which had been played 4 times@@EndBracket@@ is an improvement. }
11. Kg2
{ I believe this is an improvement over the game Carlsen-Nakamura.   11.Kh1  was played by elite GM Hikaru Nakamura. After this move White got in serious trouble against the reigning world champion.  11...f5  12.Rg1  h5!  keeping the strong g4-bishop and threatening to take on e4. }
11... f5 { White cannot take on f5, because of 12..0-0 and 13..R:f5. } 12. Qe1
{ Now that White steps out from the pin, he intends to play Nh2. Black must act! }
12... Bxf3+
{ And so he does. In order to play f5-f4, Carlsen should not allow Nxe5 - when the bishop on g4 is hanging. }
13. Kxf3
{ A weird-looking position arose on the board. With the king on f3, and two pawns in return for the piece, there exists compensation. Imagine a black queen on g4, and it would be mate!   Having taken into consideration the dangers, we look now at our plusses and possible ways of capitalizing on our extra material. Important to realize is that our king can escape, likewise so often seen in the Ruy Lopez Exchange Variation @@StartBracket@@part 1@@EndBracket@@ , to e2. Moreover, we can move our heavy pieces to the semi-open h- and g-file. }
13... f4
{ Since I started writing on the second part of my series about the Berlin Wall, before I commenced with part 1 @@StartBracket@@Ruy Lopez Exchange@@EndBracket@@ I was delighted to witness Anish Giri set off his Tata Steel Masters tournament in round 1 excellently with a victory in the Berlin Wall and in this position! }
14. Bd2
{ I truly believe that with the king escaping to e2, White has chances to get the slightly better position. In all events, Black gets compensation for the sacced piece in the shape of the dangerous kingside pawns. }
14... g5 15. Bc3
{ Not just hitting e5, but simultaneously freeing the path for the knight. }
15... Bf6 16. Nd2
{ Played by Anish Giri, so who am I to disregard his set-up? } 16... Qe7 17.
Rh1 h5 18. Ke2 g4
{ 18...O-O-O  19.Qg1  Kb8  20.f3  Rdg8  21.Rf1  White is ready to counter the pawn advance g5-g4.  21...g4  22.fxg4  hxg4  23.Rxh8  The exchange of rooks makes our defensive task easier.  23...Bxh8  24.Kd1!  White is better here and the reason is plain and simple: he is a piece up! Once Black moves his f-pawn we set up a block on g3, while after g4-g3 we do the same thing but then on f3. }
19. f3
{ Hereafter, Black cannot keep his grip on the light squares on the kingside. }
19... g3
{ Likely not the best move, as it closes the position. Now that Black has no more knights on the board, the white king can find shelter on g2.   19...O-O-O  20.Qg1  Black is in danger, due to the double attack on a7 and g4.  20...g3  Wild complications are arising after  21.Qxa7  h4  22.Nb3  White is threatening mate by Nc5 and Qa8, while the d-file is about to be opened to make the black king's life even more difficult. Black should some supernatural moves to hold his position. Moves which can only be understood by the engine.. }
20. Kf1
{ Anish Giri blocks the pawns and finds a secure spot for his king on g2. }
20... h4 21. Rh3
{ First and foremost, the sting should be taken out of Black's dangerous passed g- and h-pawns. }
21... a5 22. a4 b6 23. Kg2 c5 24. Qb1 Kf7 25. b3
{ Anish could bring his queen deep down behind enemy lines, but for what purpose?   25.Qa2+  Kg6  26.Qd5  Rad8  27.Qc6  Rd6  And I don't see a follow up for White. }
25... Rad8 26. Nc4 Kg6 27. Qb2
{ Giri is maximizing the pressure on e5. Nonetheless, he doesn't see a concrete way to smash Black's position into pieces, he confides in his positional small edge providing him the opportunity to slowly build up the tension on his opponent. }
27... Rh5 28. Rah1 Rdh8 29. Qa1 Kg7 30. Bb2 Kg6 31. Qb1
{ Neither side make progress and it seems we take part in a psychological warfare in which Giri has the lead. }
31... Rd8 32. Qe1 Kg7 33. Qa1 Rdh8 34. Na3
{ In this cat-and-mouse game, the cat finally undertakes a serious course of action. The knight will be moved from c4 to b5-c3-e2. From there, White is threatening to take on f4 under the right circumstances. }
34... Kg6 35. Nb5 Bg7 36. Nc3 Qd8
{ Watching this match live, I was convinced that the knight was on its way to d5, provoking Black to weaken his pawn structure by c7-c6. }
37. Ne2 R8h7 38. Qe1 Qd6 39. Qc3 c6 40. Qc4 Rh8 41. Ba3
{ 41.c3!  opening the position.  41...Bf6  42.d4  would lead to a big advantage for White. }
41... Qf6
{ 41...R8h7?  42.d4!  with the sole purpose to weaken the pawn on f4.  42...exd4  43.Bc1  Be5  44.Qg8+  44...Rg7  45.Qe8+  Rf7  46.Rxh4  when White is winning. }
42. Qa6 Rb8 43. Bc1
{ Black's hands are tied since he has to deal with 3 threats: 1.Qa7 and evt. Qd7.2.Rxh4, and 3. Bxf4. }
43... Bh6 44. Qa7
{ Black is lost here, as he can no longer parry all the threats. } 44... Qd8
45. Bb2
{ Black is in zugzwang here. Each move of Black leads to the instant loss of material. }
45... Qc8
{ The move   45...Bf8  fails, due to  46.Bxe5!  Rxe5  47.Nxf4+  is winning for White. }
46. Qe7 Bf8 47. Nxf4+
{ And finally Black collapses, as 47.Nxf4 is leading to a force mate, after:   47.Nxf4+  exf4  48.Rxg3+!  in order to force the f-pawn to g3.  48...fxg3   48...hxg3  49.Qf6+!  with a mate.  49.Qf6+  Kh7  50.Qf7+  Kh6  51.Bc1+!  51...Rg5  52.Rxh4 }
