1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. d3 d6 7. c3 O-O 8. Nbd2
{ 8.Re1  is a transposition to our main line. } 8... b5 9. Bc2 Bb7 10. Re1 Re8
11. Nf1 g6 12. d4 Bf8 13. Ng3 Bg7 14. d5 Nb8
{ This move has been mostly seen in tournament practice.   14...Ne7  The knight has less bright prospects on e7 than on d7.  15.b3!  anticipating on c7-c6..  15...c6  Black tries to break our center.  16.c4  but after this move we keep the center and the farthest point of the phalanx intact. 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@31@@EndBracket@@ Vallejo Pons, F @@StartBracket@@2660@@EndBracket@@-Miton,K @@StartBracket@@2628@@EndBracket@@ Heraklion 2007 }
15. b3 { Likewise, anticipating on c7-c6.. } 15... c6 16. c4
{ The French GM maintains a firm grasp on the center by keeping his pawn chain intact. Moreover, the black bishop is biting on granite. }
16... Qc7 17. Be3 Nbd7 18. h3
{ This move is in line with White's strategy of controlling his space advantage. At any cost, he should endeavour that his opponent can't create chaos behind the enemy lines. White not only secures the bishop on e3 without being harassed by a possible Ng4, this little pawn move serves attacking purposes as well. A well-timed Nf3-h2-g4 when the time is ripe will be played. }
18... Rec8 19. Rc1 Bf8 20. Bd3
{ Before White undertakes action on the kingside, everything should be under control on the queenside. }
20... Qa5
{ I am not entirely sure whether this queen move is gaining much for Black. In case I would be standing in his shoes, I'd rather bring the bishop into play asap, by   20...bxc4  21.bxc4   21.Bxc4!?  leads to different kind of pawn structures and ensuing play.  a5  bringing the bishop into play via a6. }
21. Qe2 bxc4 22. bxc4 Nc5 23. Bb1
{ It is very important to keep the bishop. In case of   23.Red1?!  cxd5  24.cxd5  Nxd3!  Resolving the lack-of-space issue.  25.Rxd3  Rxc1+   25...Qb5⇆  26.Bxc1  Bc8!  After the exchange of the minor pieces, White is sincerely missing his light-squared bishop. Black will continue with Bd7 and evt., Bb5. }
23... Nfd7
{ Though this move appears to be ok, containing a totally sound strategic plan of moving the knight to a good square @@StartBracket@@d7@@EndBracket@@, it grants Fressinet permission to launch his attack, as he can move his knight to g4 unhindered. }
24. Nh2 { The right timing. White is ready tooooo rummmmmbbllllllllle. } 24...
Qd8 25. Ng4 Qe7
{ Trying to defend the king desperately. A little too late though. } 26. Nh6+
{ This audacious knight move turns out to inflict a lot of harm. } 26... Kh8
{ Of course, giving up on the bishop by Bxh6 was not an option as the dark squares around the king would be surrendered, while after   26...Kg7??  , there is:  27.Ngf5+! }
27. Qf3 { Suddenly, Black's position goes downhill swiftly. } 27... f6
{ Johannessen is compelled to allow another weakening of his kingside. } 28. h4
{ The next big thing is the assault on the g6 pawn, which has been severely weakened on the previous move. }
28... a5 29. h5 Bxh6
{ A panicking move, though Black doesn't have plenty of choice. For instance,   29...Ba6  30.Qg4!  30...Qg7  31.hxg6  hxg6  and with the next killer move, Fressinet could have concluded the game in great fashion:  32.Kh2!!  White's attack is crushing after 33.Rh1 and 34.Kg1. }
30. Bxh6 Kg8
{ In a desperate attempt to trap the bishop by   30...g5  , Black will be overrun entirely after  31.Nf5  31...Qf7  32.Nxd6  when it's time to resign. }
31. Qg4
{ I honestly believe that the most difficult part is over now. White's assault on the king goes on its own. }
31... Kf7 32. Rc3
{ The final blow. An extra rook in the attack is just too much to handle for Black. }
32... Nf8 33. hxg6+ hxg6 34. Nf5 Qd7
{ Why not accept the gift on f5 and run away via e8 with the king, right?   34...gxf5  35.Qh5+!  Of course, it's an utopy to believe that we let the king run away to a safer place.  35...Ng6  36.exf5  would mean the end of the game. }
35. Rh3 *

