1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. O-O Qe7 7. Nbd2
{ Specialist Vladimir Kramnik faced many White set-ups in this variation, like   7.h3?!  and felt that White should be punished for this inaccuracy.. he deployed a direct assault on the king!  7...Rg8!!  8.Kh1  Nh5  9.c3  g5  10.Nxe5  g4  with promising attacking prospects for the former world champion, in: Aronian, L @@StartBracket@@2794@@EndBracket@@-Kramnik,V @@StartBracket@@2800@@EndBracket@@ Berlin 2018, 0-1 @@StartBracket@@27@@EndBracket@@. }
7... Bg4 8. h3 Bh5
{ 8...h5?  is not dangerous for White, as we will disregard this brutal force and continue with  9.Nc4!  and the bishop will be moved to g5. Black is left empty-handed. His attacking chances have evaporated and White is positionally much better, after e.g. Ne3.  9...Nd7  10.hxg4  hxg4  11.Ng5!  White impedes the queen transfer to h4. }
9. a3 Nd7 10. b4 Bd6 11. Nc4 f6 12. Ne3 Nf8 13. Nf5
{ 13.c4  was tried in: 1-0 @@StartBracket@@42@@EndBracket@@ So,W @@StartBracket@@2767@@EndBracket@@ -Nakamura,H @@StartBracket@@2745@@EndBracket@@ chess. com INT 2020, but Black could have equalized here with:  13...Qf7  14.Nf5  Ne6  Black's position is very resilient. }
13... Qd7 14. Be3
{ Please see the theoretical line for the details of this variation. } 14...
Ne6 15. c3 { Aiming for the center. } 15... O-O-O 16. Ng3
{ 16.Bxa7  is too greedy, since after  16...b6  17.a4  Bxf3  18.Qxf3  Kb7  19.a5  Ra8  his bishop won't get out. }
16... Bxf3 17. Qxf3 Kb8 18. Rfd1 g6 19. d4
{ 19.Qxf6  doesn't bring White anywhere.  19...Rdf8  20.Qh4  h5⇆  when the queen is in serious danger. }
19... exd4 20. cxd4 Rhf8 21. Bh6
{ 21.Rab1!?  Ng5!  22.Bxg5  fxg5  23.Qe2  h5!  with counterplay for Black. }
21... Rf7 22. d5
{ The next move is my theoretical suggestion in the struggle for an opening advantage.   22.Rd2!  In line with the ancient concept of 'Uberdeckung' @@StartBracket@@i.e., Overprotection@@EndBracket@@ Nimzowitsch , 22.Rd2 is going to protect d4 a little extra. When White will succeed in keeping these pawns unharmed, and well protected, he will get his hands free for other operations - such as a kingside attack.  22...Qe8   22...g5  will not be as dangerous for White as it looks.  23.Nf5  to be followed up by h4, and the bishop will be able to 'breath' again.  23.Rad1  23...a6   23...g5  24.Nf5⩲  24.h4  To take control over the g5-square and to prevent any future Ng5 or g5 till kingdom come.  24...Nf8  25.Qb3  White is ready for the assault on the black king. For a dazzling load of exciting variations, please look at the theoretical section. }
22... cxd5 23. Rxd5
{ However, here it seems too that Black hasn't equalized fully. } 23... Qe8 24.
Rad1 { And White's play is pretty simple. } 24... Rc8 25. Qg4
{ 25.h4!?  In order to grab some space on the kingside avoiding our bishop to be trapped by g6-g5. Hereafter we can reroute our knight to e3. }
25... Bf8 26. Bxf8 Nxf8 27. Ne2 h5 28. Qf3 Nd7 29. Nc3
{ Black is in a pickle. White has full control over the d-file and all his pieces are actively placed. All is set and done for a minority attack on the king. }
29... Ne5
{ 29...c6  30.R5d4  Ne5  31.Qe2  Re7   31...g5  32.Qxh5  32.f4  Nf7  33.Qf2± }
30. Qe2 Re7 31. f4 Nf7 32. R5d4 Nd6 33. Qd3
{ Gradually, the screws are tightened. White is an extra pawn up in the center, threatens to move the knight to the very strong square any moment and is set for the minority attack on the king. }
33... Re6 34. b5 b6 35. a4
{ 35.h4!?  in order to stop once and for all Black's sole option on counterplay. }
35... g5 36. f5
{ 36.Rf1!  this was the move to be played. When Black takes on f4, the f6-pawn will become too weak.  36...h4   36...gxf4  opening the f-file.  37.Rxf4  Qg6  38.Qf3±  and the f-pawn is most likely going to fall.  37.f5  Re5  38.Nd5  The knight on d5 is superior to Black's one. It touches f6 and c7. The remaining part of White's strategy is simple: doubling the rooks on the c-file and/ or opening the a-file.  38...Qf7  39.Rc1  on top of this, the knight manoeuvre d5-b4-c6 is decisive. }
36... Re5 37. Rf1
{ Probably, Giri counted on   37.Nd5  But missed that  37...Nxe4!   37...Qf7  38.Nxc7  simply winning.  38.Rxe4   38.Nb4  Nc5  39.Qf3  Re1+  40.Kf2  Rxd1  41.Rxd1  Qe4!  and Black will hold.  Rxe4  39.Nxf6  Re1+  doesn't lead to a material advantage. }
37... Rd8 38. Rd1 Rc8 39. Ra1 g4
{ Just before the time control, Black manages to obtain sufficient counterplay. }
40. hxg4 hxg4 41. Rd1
{ The point behind Black's g4, was that after   41.a5?  Nxf5!  42.exf5  Re1+!  The king can no longer hide on h2. }
41... Kb7 42. Rd5 Rxd5 43. Qxd5+ Kb8 44. Qd4 Qh5
{ Now it's White who has to watch out. } 45. Nd5 g3 46. Nxf6 Qh2+ 47. Kf1 Qh1+
{ Fortunately for Anish, Topalov contented himself with a draw after this tough struggle. However, the Dutch star could have been tested seriously by   47...Rd8!  Black finds a way to bring in reinforcements.  48.Qe3  Qh1+  49.Qg1  Qh4  50.Qd4  Nb7  51.Nd5  Nc5-+ }
48. Qg1 Qh4 49. Qd4 Qh1+ 50. Qg1 { and the players agreed on a draw. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Etienne Bacrot - Laurent Fressinet, FRA-ch, Pau 2008"]
[Result "*"]

{ Apart from the theoretical value, I picked this game to be annotated because of the immaculate strategical style in the middle- and endgame illustrated by Bacrot and in which such Berlinner positions ought to be dealt with. Many of the Frenchman's games played, reminds of the great endgame technique Capablanca. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. d3 Bg4 7. h3 Bxf3 8.
Qxf3 Nd7
{ Black is not yet choosing the side where to castle, and is improving the position of his knight. }
9. Nd2
{ The knight route Nb1-d2-c4 can be regarded as the most flexible for White, targeting e5 @@StartBracket@@from c4@@EndBracket@@ and keeping the option Nc4-e3-f5 open. }
9... Qf6 { This move has been seen frequently on a high level. } 10. Qxf6 Nxf6
11. Nc4 Nd7 12. Bd2 f6 13. a4
{ Flanking the opponent from the queen- and possibly later as well the kingside. }
13... Nf8 14. b4 { White takes the lead. } 14... Bd6 15. Rfb1
{ Playable as well, is   15.b5  c5  16.g3  In order to capture back with the pawn on f4.. }
15... Kd7 16. Be3 Ne6 17. c3
{ Step by step, White is directing his pieces forward. Something to keep in mind in these positional games to maintain the balance between your pieces. }
17... Rhb8 18. Kf1
{ Before taking further steps, the king ought to be mobilized at first. } 18...
b6 19. b5 Bc5 { Hidden behind its own pawns, the bishop seeks a way out. } 20.
d4 exd4 21. Rd1 cxb5 22. axb5 d3 23. Rxd3+ Ke8 24. e5 Rd8 25. Rxd8+ Kxd8 26.
exf6 gxf6 27. Ke2 Ke7 28. Kf3 { The king on its way to fertile soil! } 28...
Bxe3 29. Nxe3
{ Taking stock of the position, White has all the aces. Most and foremost, Black suffers from all the pawn weaknesses on a7, c7, f6 and h7. }
29... c6
{ This move also contains its demerits, as it weakens the d6-square.   29...Kd6  this attempt in vain to become active  30.Rd1+  Kc5??  31.Rd5  smothers in a exquisite mate. }
30. Nf5+ Kd7 31. Rd1+ { White finds a new entrance square on d6. } 31... Kc7
32. Rd6 Nd8 33. c4
{ 33.Rxf6  would have been strong too, but why would you give your opponent any hopes, by means of the passed a-pawn.  33...cxb5  34.Rh6  a5  35.Rxh7+  Kc6  36.Ke4  a4  37.Nd4++- }
33... cxb5 34. cxb5
{ It's time for harvesting the low hanging fruit: the pawns on the kingside.. }
34... a6 35. bxa6 Rxa6 36. Rxf6 Ra5 37. Nd4
{ Playing in line with Capablanca's endgame's principle: ' do not hurry'. }
37... Rd5 38. Ke4 Rd7 39. g4
{ The reason why Bacrot is winning, is that he has the opportunity to create two connected passed pawns on the kingside. }
39... Re7+ 40. Kd3 Rf7 41. Rh6
{ To make matters worse for Fressinet: he can barely move. } 41... Rxf2 42.
Rxh7+ Kd6 43. Rh6+ Kc5 44. Rh5+ Kd6 45. Rb5
{ Black cannot obtain any counter chances as his b-pawn is firmly blockaded. }
45... Kc7 46. Ke3 Rh2 47. Rh5 Kd6 48. h4 { Time for the pushing of the pawns. }
48... Nf7 49. Nf3 Rg2 50. Kf4 Ke7 51. Rb5 Nh6 52. Ne5
{ Also the b6-pawn will drop off the board. The rest is a matter of technique, so Fressinet resigned. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Jindrich Vodza − Rostislav Postl, CZE-ch, ICCF email 2009"]
[Result "*"]

{ The reason I have chosen this game in my selection of Model Games for the Berlin Defense is that it provides us a long term plan in a topical line and position. Please take note my comprehensive annotations of Stellwagen-Werle  (1-0)  of the Model Games selection of part 1 of this Ruy Lopez series. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. O-O Qd6 7. c3
{ Now that the queen has taken position on d6, it's worthwhile to open the center with d4. }
7... O-O 8. d4
{ Assumingly, this is a highly promising continuation. Black's coordination seems to be missing. }
8... Bb6 9. a4 { Grabbing space on the queenside. } 9... a5 10. Qc2
{ We are following a correspondence game. Black can't take on d4, because of e4-e5. }
10... Nd7 { 10...exd4??  11.e5  winning a piece. } 11. Na3
{ c4, the perfect square for the knight. } 11... Qe6 12. Re1
{ It transpires that White has enough time to stabilize before undertaking action. }
12... Re8 13. Bd2
{ This move contains a deep plan, as seen in the further part of this line. }
13... f6 14. b3 { Paving the way for the knight jump to c4. } 14... Qg4 15. Nc4
exd4 { 15...Qh5  16.dxe5!  Again this strategy, isolating the e5-pawn. } 16.
cxd4
{ Black will try to break the center down. However, he disposes over limited means. }
16... Nf8 17. h3 { Increasing our grip on the light squares. } 17... Qg6 18.
Qd3
{ The threat of Bxh3 has been neutralized, with Nh4 and Qxh3. Initially, when I went through this line I had hard times finding any advantage for White here. But then I was pleasantly surprised by White's play in this correspondence game. The white player revealed some very interesting attacking plans which could easily prove fatal for Black.   18.Kh2⩲  this would have been another plan. Play could continue with  18...Qh5  19.Qc3  Ng6  20.Ng1!  White takes the lead on the kingside, moving his knight to e2 harassing the queen and by pushing his f-pawn forward.  20...Be6  21.Ne2  21...Qh4  22.f4!  Black has to make to react, otherwise he is steamrolled.  22...f5  Please take a moment here to find the best move.. It's not e4-e5, playing into Black's hands:  23.d5!!   23.e5?  Ne7!  when Black gained full control of the light squares.  cxd5  24.Nxb6  cxb6  25.e5!  White sacrificed his d-pawn, which is blocking the black pieces.  25...Rad8  26.Nd4!!  Tactics turn out in White's favour and serve us for positional purposes.   26.Qe3?  26...d4  27.Nxd4  Qxf4+ }
18... Be6 19. Qc3
{ Black cannot take on e4 any longer with the bishop on e6.   19.Nh4  Qf7!?  20.Nf5  Red8  21.Bc3  Rd7⇆ }
19... Bd7 20. Nh4 Qh5 21. Nxb6 cxb6 22. Qg3
{ This was a good opportunity to make the queen shift to the kingside. } 22...
Be6 23. Re3 { Preparing for Rae1, protecting b3. } 23... Rad8 24. Bc3
{ Another important part in White's strategy. The bishop is aimed at Black's king. }
24... Qf7
{ 24...Bxb3?  25.Nf5  Rd7  26.d5  leads to a total destruction of Black's castle. }
25. Bb2 Ng6 26. Rae1 Nxh4
{ As a matter of fact, White is happy with the exchange of knights. As a result, the difference in strength in of the bishops is revealed. }
27. Qxh4 Bxb3 28. d5
{ Now with the king exposed, it turns out that Black is a piece down on the dark squares. }
28... Bc4 29. Rg3
{ The position is untenable. 30.Bxf6 is a threat which can hardly be averted. }
29... Rxd5
{ 29...Kh8  30.Ree3!  the pressure on the black pawns is insurmountable.  30...Rd7  31.Rxg7!  Kxg7  32.Rg3+  Kf8  33.Bxf6  and White is winning. }
30. Bxf6 g6 31. Ree3 Rh5 32. Qxh5
{ White is winning material. The rest is a matter of technique. } 32... Qxf6
33. e5 Qf7 34. h4
{ Resuming with the demolition work. The pawn is on his way to h5. } 34... b5
35. axb5 cxb5 36. Qd1 Qd5 37. Qa1
{ Hitting a5, preparing for the opening of the files by e5-e6. } 37... a4 38.
e6 { The queen on a1 is superbly placed across the long diagonal. } 38... Rxe6
39. Rxe6 Qxe6 40. h5 Qe7 41. h6
{ Next to come is Re3. It turns out that White's attack was in all ways successful. }
41... Qf8 42. Rf3 Bf7 43. Rd3 { Threatening Rd8, Qxd8 and Qg7 mate. } 43...
Qxh6 44. Rd8+ Qf8 45. Rxf8+ Kxf8 46. Qh8+ Bg8 47. f4 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Rustam Kasimdzhanov − Ivan Sokolov, Pamplona 2002"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
{ We can reach the same position through our Berliner variation with   3...Nf6  4.d3  d6  5.O-O  Be7  6.c3  O-O }
4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 h6 10. d4 Re8 11.
Nbd2 Bf8 12. Nf1 Bd7 13. Ng3 Na5 14. Bc2 c5 15. d5 g6 16. b3 Bg7 17. Be3 Nh7
18. Qd2 h5 19. Ng5 Nb7
{ 19...Nxg5  20.Bxg5  Bf6  21.Be3  White was still better, when he would have prepared for f2-f4 @@StartBracket@@or followed Kasimdzhanov with the idea of Bd1xh5@@EndBracket@@. However, he faced the giant Efim Geller and lost finally.. Tseshkovsky,V @@StartBracket@@2560@@EndBracket@@ -Geller,E @@StartBracket@@2550@@EndBracket@@ Minsk 1979 0-1 @@StartBracket@@56@@EndBracket@@. }
20. Rf1 Nxg5 21. Bxg5 Qa5 22. Kh1 { 22.f4  exf4 } 22... Rf8
{ and as we have seen before, the sacrifices on h5 are very promising for White. }
23. Bd1
{ White is threatening to take on h5 with the bishop with a deadly attack on the black king. }
23... f6 24. Be3 Rae8 25. Bc2 Nd8 26. a4
{ White is fighting aa two-front war. Black directed all his pieces towards the kingside, hence the place to strike is the queenside! }
26... b4 27. cxb4 cxb4
{ 27...Qxb4  28.Qxb4  cxb4  29.Bd3  %csl Rd7,Rd8,Rg7  (when the black pawns on the queenside can't be rescued any longer.) }
28. Rac1 Nf7 29. Bd3
{ As a matter of fact, the game has been played yet. The pawns on b4 and a6 are too weak to be saved. }
29... Rc8 30. Rc4 Rxc4 31. Bxc4 h4 32. Ne2
{ With a final chord in the shape of a subtle knight manoeuvre, White decides the game. }
32... f5 33. f3 Bf6 34. Nc1
{ After Nc1-d3 the pawn on b4 is dropping of the board. } 34... Bd8
{ 34...Rb8  35.Nd3  f4  36.Bf2  Bd8  37.Be1  and b4 is really falling now. }
35. Nd3 Bb6 36. Bxb6 Qxb6 37. Nxb4 Rc8 38. Nc6 Kg7
{ 38...Bxc6  39.dxc6  Qxc6  40.Bd5  Qb6  41.Qh6  is winning for White. } 39. a5
Qc7 40. Bxa6 Ra8 41. Bc4 Bxc6 42. dxc6 Rxa5 43. b4 Ra4 44. Bb3 Ra3 45. Bd5 f4
46. b5 Qb6 47. Rc1 Ra7 48. Bxf7 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Peter Svidler  − Laurent Fressinet, Wch Rapid, Dubai 2014"]
[Result "*"]

{ Chessable Note: this is the only Model Game that isn't included in the video course. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 O-O 6. O-O d6 7. Nbd2 Ne7 8. Re1
c6 9. Ba4 Ng6 10. Nf1 Bb6 11. Ng3 h6 12. d4 exd4 13. cxd4 Bg4 14. h3 Bxf3 15.
gxf3 Nh7 16. f4 Qf6 17. f5 Nh4 18. e5 dxe5 19. dxe5 Qd8 20. Re4 Qxd1+ 21. Bxd1
Rad8 22. Bb3
{ Svidler not only rejoices his strong block of pawns on e5 and f5, but his bishop on b3 is also a nuisance for Black. }
22... Nf3+ 23. Kg2 Nd2
{ Thus, Black got rid of the bishop pair but not the massive b3-bishop. } 24.
Bxd2 Rxd2 25. Re2 { Firstly, White should regain control of the second rank. }
25... Rxe2 26. Nxe2 Re8 27. f4
{ Doubled pawns can be weak, but here, on the contrary, they are very compact meanwhile covering 'too' many important squares in and around the center. }
27... Kf8 28. Rd1 Rd8
{ Would Svidler have feared the exchange of rooks in his endeavour to win? }
29. Rxd8+
{ No, apparently not. The knight and king will find it hard to move out as the white block of pawns is so powerful. }
29... Bxd8 30. Kf3 { The white forces undertake joint action. } 30... Ke7
{ 30...Bb6  31.Bc2 } 31. Ng3 Bb6 32. h4
{ 32.Nh5!?  to lure the g-pawn forward.  32...g6  33.f6+!  this position should be lost as the pawns gain once more territory. }
32... Ke8 { What else? Black can barely move. } 33. Nh5 Kf8
{ Can you find the forced winning continuation for White? } 34. f6 gxf6 35. Bc2
{ The key idea behind the whole concept. The knight is trapped.. } 35... Kg8
{ Almost. } 36. Bxh7+
{ But now this exchange of pieces determines the outcome of the game. White is just gaining too much ground. }
36... Kxh7 37. Nxf6+ Kg7 38. h5 { Bad king..you stay in this booth! } 38... Bd8
39. Ne8+ Kg8 40. Nd6
{ The aim of White is to weaken the black pawns. In other words, force them on the same colour as the bishop. }
40... b6 41. f5
{ A strong move, as White is gradually moving forward.   41.Nf5!  Would be even more convincing. The king is forced to h7, and will not get the opportunity to get out of the corner for the rest of the game.  41...Kh7  42.Ke4  Bc7  43.Nd4  The knight paves the way for the king.  43...c5  The d5-square becomes accessible for the king.  44.Nf5  Black is defenseless against the king's invasion. }
41... Kf8 42. Ke4 { Joint action shatter all Black's chances on counterplay. }
42... Bc7 43. Nc4 Bd8
{ 43...f6  44.e6  Ke7  45.Ne3  would have merely been a postponement of Black's fate. }
44. f6 b5
{ Naturally, Black has a strong desire to move the pawns from the colour of his own bishop. The bishop can at least go somewhere @@StartBracket@@e.g. b6 or a5@@EndBracket@@. }
45. Nd6
{ But now that the pawns are moved forward, they become a prey for the knight. }
45... Ba5 { Can you find the easiest win for White? } 46. Nf5 Bd2 47. Nd4
{ And the curtain falls, as one of the 2 pawns will be taken. } *

